HULL SCORES 1,000th POINT IN VICTORY 
(For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MIKE HEIKA 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Brett Hull broke his silence, broke out of a brief
scoring slump and broke the collective back of the Boston Bruins
last night, leading the Stars to a 3-1 victory and scoring his
1,000th career point.
</P>
<P>
   Hull, who had not spoken to the news media for a week since he
commented about ice time in a game, addressed reporters on the
goal, the Stars' big victory and what he called ``unfair''
treatment.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah, it was a hard week, because it was so uncalled for. I
didn't do anything,'' he said. ``I didn't \Rgripe\S and moan about
ice time. I played 24 minutes two or three games earlier. I'm
playing as much as I did in St. Louis.''
</P>
<P>
   The news media frenzy got so bad that the Toronto Globe and Mail
speculated Friday that Hull would ask for a trade. Hull dismissed
the speculation.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm happy,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Hull added that sometimes ``when you think you want a bigger
piece of the pie, just go along with it.'' He said there has been
``an emotional adjustment'' in his game that he is becoming aware
of.
</P>
<P>
   But if weekends keep turning out as this one did, he won't have
a problem. The win against the Bruins completed a two-night road
trip in which the Stars not only won, but also played well. The
Stars, in beating the Detroit Red Wings, 5-1, Friday and coming up
with a hard-fought win against the Bruins, answered key questions
that had dogged them after a 2-0 loss to the Phoenix Coyotes on
Wednesday, Stars coach Ken Hitchcock said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have some of our better players playing well and we have
our role players starting to fill roles,'' Hitchcock said. ``We're
hopefully building a very functional group.''
</P>
<P>
   The Stars moved to 9-3-2 on the season and won their third
consecutive road game after starting the season 0-2-1 away from
home. Hull's performance added to that performance.
</P>
<P>
   The 34-year-old winger, who signed as a free agent in the
summer, scored his fifth and sixth goals of the season and is tied
with Mike Modano for the team scoring lead at 13 points. He is the
53rd NHL player to reach the plateau. He and his father, Bobby
Hull, are the only father-son combination to score 1,000 points
each.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was just talking to Johnny Bucyk,'' Hull said of the former
Bruins great. ``And I told him to have my name mentioned with guys
like that, it's a real honor.''
</P>
<P>
   Hull, who had one ``fluky'' goal in the previous four games,
broke out of his self-proclaimed slump with another goal on a
fluke. Down 1-0 in the first period, Hull drove hard to the net and
flicked a shot at Bruins goalie Byron Dafoe. Dafoe stopped the
shot, but Hull ran into him. In the collision, Bruins forward Jason
Allison deflected the puck into his goal.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe that's just what I needed to break this little slump,''
Hull said.
</P>
<P>
   The score remained tied throughout a fiercely contested game as
Modano and Bruins winger Sergei Samsonov each put on puck-handling
clinics and both sides threw their share of big hits.
</P>
<P>
   But it took another lucky bounce to change the game. After a
clearing pass bounced off an official, Modano stole the puck and
fed Hull moving in on Dafoe. Hull kept the puck an almost
impossible amount of time as he moved from the slot to deep on the
goal line to right of the net. Dafoe finally went down to block the
shot and Hull lifted a wrister over him from almost a 90-degree
angle.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had a solid foot to go,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Teammate Jamie Langenbrunner saw it another way.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have no idea how that puck went in the net,'' Langenbrunner
said. ``I guess that's how you score 1,000 points, with shots like
that.''
</P>
<P>
   That gave the Stars a 2-1 lead with 4:26 remaining in the game,
but the excitement wasn't over. Hull almost recorded his first hat
trick as a Stars player a few minutes later. However, his shot at
an empty net caromed off the post.
</P>
<P>
   Modano hustled to retrieve that puck and fed Hull behind the
net, who set up linemate Jere Lehtinen for the empty-net tap-in and
the 1,000th point.
</P>
<P>
   Was it a dream come true?
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think you dream of 1,000 points,'' Hull said. ``To be
honest, there's only one dream in my head, and that's winning the
Stanley Cup.''
</P>
</TEXT>
