<HEADLINE>
COYOTES GET UP, KICK SAND IN TAMPA BAY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB MCMANAMAN  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - The Coyotes have been kicking sand in people's faces
since the season started. Even the big boys of the NHL. But
Saturday night, they almost let a 98-pound weakling of a team push
them over.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, of course, it was the bumbling, stumbling Tampa Bay
Lightning that was the push over. The Coyotes eventually came to
their senses and delivered the knockout, humbling the Lightning,
4-1, in front of a sellout crowd at America West Arena.
</P>
<P>
   The victory pushed the Coyotes' undefeated streak to eight games
(6-0-2), tying them with the Buffalo Sabres for the longest active
streak in the league. It also put Phoenix (8-2-2) six games over
.500 for the first time since December, 1991, when the
then-Winnipeg Jets opened the season 15-9-7.
</P>
<P>
   Keith Tkachuk, Jeremy Roenick and rookie Daniel Briere each had
a goal and an assist. Rick Tocchet also scored.
</P>
<P>
   Tkachuk's goal was his team-leading ninth of the season. Briere
snared his first. Roenick's goal gave him 325 in his career, moving
into the NHL's top 100 goalscorers. Tocchet, meanwhile, moved
closer to getting No. 400. He now is just 10 goals away from the
milestone.
</P>
<P>
   Jimmy Waite, making his third straight start in goal, had a
relative easy night, facing 21 shots. He saw nine in the first two
periods combined.
</P>
<P>
   ``These are tough games for goalies, though,'' he said. ``The
goalie on the other end is playing well and making a lot of saves.
And you're not too busy, so you really have to keep your
concentration up. But the the guys really played well in front of
me.''
</P>
<P>
   The Coyotes jumped on Tampa early, but seemed to lose some
interest in the second period. Even after the Lightning got a goal
from Darcy Tucker to make it 2-1 and keep things interesting.
</P>
<P>
   But who could really blame the Coyotes for falling asleep? After
all, they were playing a team that was coming off two straight
disasterous performances. Tampa got whalloped by the New York
Rangers on Tuesday, 10-2. On Friday, the Lightning got zapped by
Colorado, 8-1.
</P>
<P>
   That's 18 goals against in two games _ two goals more than
Phoenix had allowed all season entering the game.
</P>
<P>
   For the eighth time in 12 games, the Coyotes grabbed the
first-period lead. And they've been incredibly succesful when they
do over the past couple years. Dating back to last season, they now
are 31-1-2 when holding the lead after the first 20 minutes of
play.
</P>
<P>
   Tkachuk and Roenick delivered the goods this time, with Roenick
taking a Jyrki Lumme pass and threading the puck to a cutting
Tkachuk for a big goal right after a faceoff. Only 1:54 remained in
the period, and the most surprising thing was that Phoenix only had
a 1-0 lead.
</P>
<P>
   Considering they outshot the Lightning, 17-3 _ their highest
output in a period thus far _ and had four power play
opportunities, it could have been a laugher from the outset.
</P>
<P>
   Darren Puppa wasn't laughing, though. Early in the second, the
Tampa Bay goalie faced a barrage of shots, including three straight
breakaways by Briere, Roenick and Dallas Drake. But you had the
sense the dam was going to break at any moment.
</P>
<P>
   With 6:19 left in the period, Briere made it 2-0 with his first
goal of the season, a nice slapshot of a Tocchet rebound while
getting pushed to the ice by Tampa rookie Vincent Lecavalier.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's pretty gratifying to finally score,'' Briere said. ``The
first line (of Tkchuk, Roenick and Dallas Drake) has really been
carrying us the last few games. Personally, I don't think I've been
playing all that well lately. I haven't been moving my legs very
well. But this was nice.''
</P>
<P>
   Briere hadn't registered a point in three games since getting an
assist and racking up several scoring chances during a 3-0 win in
Los Angeles _ his first game featured as the club's No. 2 center
following the Cliff Ronning trade to Nashville.
</P>
<P>
   He also didn't see much ice time in the third period of any of
the past three games. Schoenfeld, though, said Briere is
progressing along just fine.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you look at our past three opponents (Detroit, Colorado and
Dallas) and you look at their No.1 and No.2 centers, and then you
factor in they were all real close games, if you get a lead, you're
going to go with your guys who can nail it down for you,''
Schoenfeld said. ``That's a growing process young players go
through.
</P>
<P>
   ``Juha Ylonen, for example, the last couple games he's playing
great so his ice time is increasing. It's not that somebody else
isn't having a good game. It's just that you recognize this guy or
that guy is having a great game. Just like (Brad) Isbister the
other night (in Dallas). He was really on his game and we kept him
out there and he did the job.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
