<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-QUEST-TREK-RACE-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DESERT MISADVENTURE  
 MOST RACE OBSTACLES WERE OFF COURSE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By JEFF METCALFE  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Desert Quest sank long before Janeen Steffen stood on her Land
Rover, checking her watch with a flashlight, counting down from
five to start 261 mostly first-time adventure racers on an
ill-fated introduction to the sport.
</P>
<P>
   Ultimately, only 14 of the 87 three-person teams completed the
insufficiently staffed, poorly marked 100-mile course through the
Tonto National Forest on Oct. 23-24. But the event was simply the
end game of a venomous yearlong drama played out as much in the
courtroom and in cyber space as the wilderness.
</P>
<P>
   Steffen, an adventure racer who as a rookie race director hoped
to cash in on the sport's lucrative potential, overextended her
administrative abilities and mortgaged her future.
</P>
<P>
   Ill-equipped first-timers, paying a $1,000 entry fee per team,
overestimated their ability to handle a 17- to 24-hour test that
drew participants from all over the country.
</P>
<P>
   And disputes between the original partners in the venture and a
feud with a potential investor led, ultimately, to a chaotic
weekend and startlingly different futures for all involved.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not without blame, there's no doubt about it,'' said
Steffen, 35, of Phoenix. ``But these people, most of them were way
over their head. It was beyond any of our anticipation. This is not
a triathlon, this is not a 10K. This is an extreme sporting
event.''
</P>
<P>
   Adventure racing is a sport with a traceable history going back
barely a decade, and before that a sketchier lineage branching off
endurance triathlon. But with Discovery Channel sponsorship of the
Eco-Challenge giving adventure racing widespread recognition, the
chase is on to market the sport to the masses.
</P>
<P>
   The Phoenix area, with rugged, spectacular desert nearby, seemed
like a perfect locale. ``Voila,'' Desert Quest, was born. Steffen
advertised the event in 10 major markets during the April telecast
of the 1997 Eco-Challenge, held in Australia. Come to Arizona, the
commercial beckoned, for up to 24 hours of running, biking,
kayaking and climbing. Your chance to be an eco-guy/gal for a
bargain price in a sport where the entry fee for exotic expedition
events starts at $10,000.
</P>
<P>
   The slick, full-color Desert Quest entry form projected $100,000
in event awards and giveaways, a figure Steffen said she reached by
including such perks as running suits for the first 25 teams to
register.
</P>
<P>
   But the total cash awarded was $7,500 and the fourth-place team
received free entry into Desert Quest 1999, a prize that could be
worthless.
</P>
<P>
   What Steffen and her partners devised, the thrill-seeking
audience bought. By May, Desert Quest had reached its original
limit of 75 three-person teams and expanded to 105, larger than any
adventure race in the world involving overnight competition.
</P>
<P>
   By comparison, the fourth Eco-Challenge went off in Morocco last
month with 55 four-person teams.
</P>
<P>
   ``You've got big sponsors wanting big TV and big TV wanting big
sponsors,'' Steffen said before Desert Quest. ``So somebody's got
to put up. That happens to be me.'' &QL; 
Winners' check bounced &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Sponsors and TV mean nothing on race day when a few volunteers
at the finish are scrambling to transport gallons of water from
miles away in Mesa to the Tonto National Forest race site. And
sponsorship couldn't even pull together anything resembling a line
for the winners to cross after a 17{-hour effort.
</P>
<P>
   Long before the event, on adventure racing bulletin boards, the
likelihood of success was debated. The criticisms were echoed
afterward, in cyber space and in interviews with ``The Republic.''
</P>
<P>
   Not enough event staff.
</P>
<P>
   Problems with course markings that led to racers getting lost
and running out of water.
</P>
<P>
   A bottleneck at the difficult, if not unsafe, climb late in the
event.
</P>
<P>
   And it would have been nice if the winners' check hadn't
bounced.
</P>
<P>
   First-time adventure racers Clint Graham, Lisa Barnes and Rick
Wightman competed as Team Wilderness Adventure in Desert Quest.
Some four miles into the opening 6.5-mile run, in the light of a
quarter moon and headlamps, they negotiated the turn from Forest
Road 13 to 1863. Many others missed it, triggering a chain of
misfortune.
</P>
<P>
   One of the lead teams covered an estimated 20 miles instead of
6.5 before finding its way to the mountain bike stage. After a
36-mile ride, the team had to choose between taking unauthorized
water and disqualification or treking dehydrated and without water
for 15 miles to a transition area where water refill was allowed.
</P>
<P>
   ``We read the instructions,'' said Barnes of Glendale, whose
team finished second. ``That section was not marked, so the whole
time we were kind of questioning it, but it did say in the
instructions to go to 1863. We had doubts in the back of our mind,
but we went that way.''
</P>
<P>
   Steffen contends that the course was sabotaged by someone
removing ribbons that marked the course there and on the final leg
to the finish at Usery Mountain Park. Inexperience of many racers
compounded the problem.
</P>
<P>
   Because the two-way radios she expected were not delivered,
staff communication was restricted to cell phone in an area with
known dead zones.
</P>
<P>
   ``When Joe Bell (of first-place Trident Adventures) came in and
said, `Janeen, there are no ribbons,' I immediately fly into a
panic,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Steffen's thin resources, estimated by her to be 60-70
volunteers, were stretched by real, imagined and non-existent
emergencies.
</P>
<P>
   ``I should have stressed more the fact that if you quit
someplace in a race, you had to get down to a point where we could
get you out,'' Steffen said. ``You don't just stop and leave your
bikes and leave your gear and walk away and expect volunteers to
pick up after you.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I started shuttling people to try and prevent a major
medical situation, that's where I was cut short on the back side. I
was having to run from here to here to here to here. . . . What I
see now, to handle the inexperience level that was at this event, I
would have needed 200-plus volunteers.''
</P>
<P>
   Good luck, said one volunteer, all those working at his station
would not return if Desert Quest is held again. The volunteer cited
unkept promises (for example, volunteers had to pay for meals and
park entrance fees) and being left without sufficient backup or
communication.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was no way to know who was medical personnel,'' said the
volunteer, who asked for anonymity. ``There was no designated
person with (medical) clothing on. It was very stressful. Nothing
seemed to be organized as well as it could be. Every time we turned
around, we got knocked down another notch. She (Steffen) was very
lucky nobody got hurt.'' (There was one injury, a broken collarbone
in the bike portion of the trek.)
</P>
<P>
   Changing partners &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Many problems might have been averted if Steffen had partners
familiar with staging a race and more volunteer hands.
</P>
<P>
   But Steffen's relations with her original partners disintegrated
_ so much so that she took out restraining orders against them.
Another prospective partnership ended with another restraining
order. Other potential last-minute partnerships fell through.
</P>
<P>
   The dispute, predictably, follows the money _ more than $100,000
in entry fees. To understand where Desert Quest lost its way, you
need to track down Jack Dunn in Morocco.
</P>
<P>
   Dunn, one of the early collaborators, couldn't have been happier
to be in north Africa early last month, yanking on the reins on his
camel, instead of in Arizona trying to keep Desert Quest afloat.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm glad it worked out the way it did,'' said Dunn, 36, an
operating engineer from Scottsdale. ``Obviously I would have loved
to stay involved with putting the race on, but I didn't want to do
it with her (Steffen).
</P>
<P>
   ``She thinks she knows a lot more than she does, and that
bothers me.''
</P>
<P>
   Dunn and Nick Moore, 33, who owns a pool company in Palm
Springs, Calif., were in Morocco as half of Epinephrine Adventure
Racing, chosen in a lottery to be the 12th and final United States
entry in the Eco-Challenge.
</P>
<P>
   That opportunity came after a nasty split with Steffen and her
former racing teammates in mid-June that sucked much of the
organizing expertise out of Desert Quest.
</P>
<P>
   Dunn, Moore and another racer/partner, Louis Paciello, wanted an
accounting of entry fees and other funds that Steffen refused to
provide.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were never equal partners,'' she said. ``When I asked
them to do that back in September-October (1997), they wouldn't do
it. They never felt this would be the level it's at. They hoped
we'd have 30 teams. It was just too much for them.''
</P>
<P>
   Steffen said she left a job in computer sales to work full time
on Desert Quest, on which she said she spent $65,000 or more of her
own money.
</P>
<P>
   ``They wouldn't or couldn't do it. So what am I supposed to do?
Say `Race over' and fold up my tent? No, I begged, borrowed and
stole, as the saying goes, to make this race. I've cashed in my
401K, my stocks. Mortgaged my house. Everything to do this and also
make a living and pay my bills. They weren't willing to do that.''
</P>
<P>
   On her attorney's advice, Steffen took out restraining orders
June 17 against all three men, primarily based on a taped phone
conversation the day before with Dunn. ``Threatened to stop race,''
she wrote of Dunn in the injunction against harassment. ``(Said I)
need to watch my step. I will be unhappy girl in next couple
days.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I did leave a message on her recorder, and she took it as a
threat,'' Dunn said.
</P>
<P>
   Moore said: ``When she said we didn't have a right to look at
the books, we started to see some handwriting on the wall, to put
it nicely. We weren't second guessing, but we wanted to see what
was coming in and where it was going out.''
</P>
<P>
   Instead of a formal partnership agreement, which Steffen told
Moore her attorney was drafting, the restraining orders arrived,
putting Tonto National Forest and Upper Lake Mary in Flagstaff
off-limits to the men.
</P>
<P>
   ``Basically I can't step into the state of Arizona,'' said
Moore, who had been commuting on weekends to set the Desert Quest
course. ``But everything happens for a reason.''
</P>
<P>
   Enter Paul Romero, captain of Team Epinephrine.
</P>
<P>
   He met Dunn and Moore at the Met-Rx Adventure Race, June 13 at
Lake Perris (Calif.) State Park, where they were forced to pay
their own entry fee because Steffen canceled her check for them to
race as Team Quest. The next week, within days of the restraining
orders, came Romero's invitation to what Moore calls the big dance,
his third Eco-Challenge and Dunn's second.
</P>
<P>
   ``We just wanted to put on a good, clean race, and if there was
any money left over, divvy up the pie,'' Moore said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We know so many people, and they know Jack's reputation and my
reputation. That takes a while to build. We let actions speak for
themselves.'' &QL; 
Cliffs chaos &QL;
</P>
<P>
   All that went wrong with Desert Quest _ from the partnership
split, through Steffen's unanswered appeals for help in the final
pre-race weeks to the Maricopa County Sports Commission and Grand
Canyon State Games, to a rushed and cursory inspection of equipment
and climbing backgrounds during check-in _ culminated at the
Goldfield Cliffs.
</P>
<P>
   Because of loose rocks, inexperience and fatigue, teams stacked
up like Sky Harbor airplanes at Christmas trying to complete the
200-foot ascent and rappel. Steffen pulled the plug on the climb at
approximately 3 p.m., two hours ahead of the scheduled cutoff.
</P>
<P>
   ``I stopped most of the teams at the ropes,'' she said.
``Logistically, they could have finished by the mandatory (overall
24-hour) cutoff, but none of them took headlamps. There was no way
I was sending 20 teams (into the desert at dark).''
</P>
<P>
   Toni Mounts of Team Extreme Madness was fuming because she
couldn't retrieve her headlamp at the second transition after the
4.2-mile kayak stage on Saguaro Lake. ``They did not transport our
gear box (from the transition into the kayak) like promised,'' she
said. ``This had all our food, water, lights.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we were told we were DQ'ed, I felt like someone took a
part of me. I broke down and cried.''
</P>
<P>
   Keith Burdette of Desert Mountain Sports, whose performance on
race day drew respect from all sides, was in charge of the climb
and at the top of the cliff. He made the decision to shut down the
middle of three rope setups to reduce the risk of falling rock.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some of the loose rock could have been cleaned out,'' with
more volunteers, Burdette said. ``But nobody was hit, there were no
reports of (rock) injury.''
</P>
<P>
   Burdette is not sure the unqualified climbers could have been
weeded out during check-in or if any of the 18 teams that made it
to the top and back had an unsafe climbing system.
</P>
<P>
   ``I could do that ascent in five minutes,'' he said, ``but not
after 18 hours. It would have taken me a long time. You could have
been wildly qualified and still failed. We weren't catering to
people who had never ascended.''
</P>
<P>
   Steffen isn't so kind, saying had she been free to reach the
ropes section sooner she would have disqualified many teams for
improper equipment and/or insufficient skill.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't climb for them, I can't train for them, I can't run
for them,'' Steffen said. &QL; 
Plans fall through &QL;
</P>
<P>
   As race week end neared, Steffen's search for help became more
and more desperate.
</P>
<P>
   Her plans for national sponsorship/television and a blowout
entertainment expo at the finish area fell through.
</P>
<P>
   Most destructive, Steffen said, was a short-lived business
relationship with Tim McGill of Scottsdale.
</P>
<P>
   ``He came to me with a story and sucked me in on how he had
these national sponsors and was trying to do a race like mine,''
she said. ``From what we can determine, he saw big dollars, big
potential, single women, big entry fees and a chance to make some
money.''
</P>
<P>
   McGill, 35, who said he has business dealings that reach to
Africa, tells a different story. In July and August, he says, he
proposed a merger of his company, first called Treasure Quest and
now Extreme Sports Inc., with Steffen's and that she would not
provide her financial information.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wanted to make sure if I'm paying for a red apple, it's not
yellow,'' McGill said. ``I started talking to some other people
about her and decided to call it quits with her.''
</P>
<P>
   As their dealings melted down the Internet heated up.
</P>
<P>
   Through an on-line news group offered by the Adventure Racing
Association and the Desert Quest bulletin board, McGill began
posting his doubts about the event, questioning insurance, permits,
kayaks and Steffen.
</P>
<P>
   ``When this guy started posting all over the Internet, people
started getting edgy,'' said Chad Smith, who provided support for
Team Reebok/Sisyphus that traveled from Maryland for Desert Quest.
</P>
<P>
   Even Robert Nagle, a Harvard professor and a founder of the
Adventure Racing Association, , could not sift the truth out of the
charges and countercharges.
</P>
<P>
   ``People expect me to serve as Solomon, but there is only so
much you can do in life,'' said Nagle, whose team is a two-time
winner of the Eco-Challenge. But in a Solomon-like decision, he and
the ARA board put Steffen and McGill on probation, making their
submissions subject to his approval before being posted.
</P>
<P>
   ``After they had an opportunity to inform everyone on the e-mail
list of the potential problems at DQ, or lack thereof, the messages
became more animated than informative,'' violating the ARA policy
of no flaming (personal attacks), Nagle said.
</P>
<P>
   The damage to Desert Quest was substantial.
</P>
<P>
   ``He (McGill) stirred up a lot of trouble,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Steffen accused McGill of being the one who sabotaged the course
on race day. He denies it.
</P>
<P>
   More races planned &QL;
</P>
<P>
   McGill said he is in final negotiations for a $250,000, six-race
adventure series. He is offering free entry to his first Extreme
Sports Inc. event to all Desert Quest teams.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't cause her race to go (expletive),'' McGill said.
``She caused me to go goodbye. The difference between my first race
and hers? You'll all see.''
</P>
<P>
   He projects the first race of his series for February or perhaps
a month or two later, probably in the San Francisco Bay area. ``I
planned Northern Arizona,'' he said, ``but I can't start there
because of the bad taste.''
</P>
<P>
   Steffen lists two 1999 races, one in March and the other in
October, on her Desert Quest web site and said she is making a tape
of the 1998 race to peddle to ESPN.
</P>
<P>
   In reality, she is trying to sell what remains of her dream to
save her house from foreclosure. She told Bob Kite that her race
debts are $35,000 to $40,000, half of that for materials, and that
she has bounced some checks, including one for $3,500 to the Desert
Quest champions.
</P>
<P>
   Kite, the only one of Steffen's 1997 teammates not to have a
restraining order taken against him by her, is considering a
bailout purchase of Desert Quest. He then would turn the property
over to an established race director like Rob Wallack of
Phoenix-based Raceplace Events or Norm Klein of the Western States
100 to pick up the pieces.
</P>
<P>
   Wallack has a 20-year history of producing runs and triathlons
here and elsewhere, including national series and Arizona's largest
fitness event, Phoenix Race for the Cure (14,000).
</P>
<P>
   Except for Race for the Cure, which turns its profits over to
breast cancer research groups, he said he's had nothing close to a
$100,000-plus budget for an event. His typical budget for a
regional marathon would be $65,000.
</P>
<P>
   ``The racers should have every expectation of a high-quality
event (at Desert Quest),'' Wallack said. ``This is not a feather in
the cap of Arizona event production. The whole thing was
inexcusable.''
</P>
<P>
   Kite said he didn't pull any punches with Steffen. ``I told her
what you've got established is a bad reputation, and what value is
that? Maybe it can be salvaged under new ownership.''
</P>
<P>
   Steffen said a buyout is a possibility.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not going to give it away,'' she said. ``I've got to get a
job. I can't stay home and run this full time without some help.''
</P>
<P>
   Clearly, there is a market for the sport. About that, Steffen
was correct.
</P>
<P>
   ``Janeen did a lot of talking, which got her to a certain point,
but then when we had to back up her words, she didn't have it,''
Moore said. ``She thought we were replaceable, just grunts or dumb
jocks. We knew it was going to be a fiasco.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
Jeff Metcalfe can be reached at 602-444-8053 or at
jeff.metcalfe(at)pni.com via e-mail. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
