<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OUT-ARIZONA-BURKHART-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOREST SERVICE WANTS YOU 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BARRY BURKHART  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The U.S. Forest Service is completing revision of a strategic
plan for the use of its holdings.
</P>
<P>
   That's a good idea. Agreed, national forests should be multiuse
resources. Since we all hold ownership of these public lands, they
should be managed to accomodate as many public uses as possible.
</P>
<P>
   But historically, the Forest Service has been somewhat one-sided
in its management of the resources.
</P>
<P>
   Commodity users _ the timber industry and ranchers _ received
special considerations. Congress was of little help. It believed
the forests should make some money from timber and ranching
operations. After all, these industries contributed to the gross
national product. They should be encouraged.
</P>
<P>
   The only trouble became that these industries basically made
nothing for the Forest Service. They may have provided lumber and
food, but the Forest Service was expending too much of its
financial resources to provide the opportunities.
</P>
<P>
   The agency resisted change, but the pendulum and began swinging
the other way.
</P>
<P>
   Environmentalists, recreationists and wildlife conservationists,
who were growing in numbers, began to demand their fair share of
resources. At first, they fought together. The environmentalists,
especially, began winning their share of battles against
management. They often did it in court and still do. Witness the
battles over spotted owls and other endangered species.
</P>
<P>
   Then, the united groups began battling. Some environmentalists
and hiking groups believed other recreational groups were doing
more damage than good. As with the timber and ranching industries,
there were sweeping accusations that certainly didn't involve the
entire group.
</P>
<P>
   Off-highway-vehicle users were among those attacked. That
includes a large number of enthusiasts from those who drive 4x4
vehicles to those who operate all-terrain vehicles.
</P>
<P>
   There became an outcry to close some forest roads and keep these
blighters confined to controlled areas.
</P>
<P>
   There was some justification. Some OHV users are cowboys _
people looking only for a thrill, not conservation. But that
sweeping condemnation is akin so saying that most shooters are
gang-bangers. It's a statement so outlandish that it's laughable.
</P>
<P>
   Some groups have called for the elimination of large numbers of
back-country roads. It's true that some logging roads should be
eliminated, especially those that parallel or duplicate one another
or those that cause huge erosion problems.
</P>
<P>
   But it's obvious that some environmental groups just have a
problem with any OHV activities that aren't in confined areas.
Accepting that view would eliminate opportunities to explore that
only Arizona can offer.
</P>
<P>
   According to the Forest Service, the goals of the 1997 strategic
plan are as follows:
</P>
<P>
   Ensure sustainable ecosystems.
</P>
<P>
   Provide multiple benefits for people within the capabilities of
ecosystems. (No harm, no foul.)
</P>
<P>
   Ensure organizational effectiveness. (That's one that will be
debated a lot.)
</P>
<P>
   The Forest Service wants to know if these are the goals that
should be included in the revised strategic plan and if there are
others that should be added or substituted.
</P>
<P>
   Here are other questions, the Forest Service wants the public to
answer:
</P>
<P>
   What should the agency define as its long-term priorities or
objectives?
</P>
<P>
   Given these strategic goals and your sense of how long-term
priorities or objectives should be defined, what do you think
agency managers should focus on as the critical indicators of
success or failure?
</P>
<P>
   From your perspective, what are the most important outcomes or
future resource conditions on which you would like to see the
Agency focus?
</P>
<P>
   What other issues and concerns would you like the Forest Service
to know about and consider in the revision of its strategic plan?
</P>
<P>
   Any individual or organization may participate. Comments via
e-mail, letter or fax are welcome at any time.
</P>
<P>
   Here's where you send comments:
</P>
<P>
   By mail: USDA Forest Service &QL; 
ATTENTION: Kathryn P. Maloney, Director &QL; 
Strategic Planning and Resource Assessment Staff &QL; 
P.O. Box 96090 &QL; 
Washington, DC 20090-6090
</P>
<P>
   By e-mail: Resources.Program/wo(at)fs.fed.us
</P>
<P>
   By fax: (202) 205-1546
</P>
<P>
   For additional information, contact the Internet Forest Service
home page at www.fs.fed.us or the Strategic Planning and Resource
Assessment Staff home page at www.fs.fed.us/pl/rpa &QL; 
Barry Burkhart can be reached at 602-444-8454 or at
barry.burkhart(at)pni.com via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
