<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-15 00:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1356 &Cx1f; tic-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HKN-NOTEBOOK-MCMANAMA     11-15 1043
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-NOTEBOOK-MCMANAMAN-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INJURIES BECOME EPIDEMIC 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB MCMANAMAN  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   A New York Islanders prospect lost his right eye Friday.  &UR; Jeff
Libby had to have it surgically removed six days after being cut in
the face by a skate during an American Hockey League game.
</P>
<P>
   If you saw replays of Dallas defenseman  &UR; Darryl Sydor
dangerously running  &UR; Jeremy Roenick headfirst into a support beam
last week, you'd think the Coyotes center was lucky the same thing
didn't happen to him. It looked ghoulish, but JR escaped unharmed.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've seen it a few times already. No big deal,'' Roenick said
cooly. ``Hey, that's just part of the game. That's hockey.''
</P>
<P>
   But is it getting worse? There were nearly 100 concussions
suffered by NHL players last season. Some of them were bad enough
to force early retirements. The Coyotes, who led the league with
473 man-games lost to injury, have already had five different
players suffer concussions this season.
</P>
<P>
   Around the league, players are falling at an alarming rate.
Washington recently had as many as nine skaters on the shelf.
Colorado had eight. Los Angeles, Montreal and Ottawa had at least
seven each.
</P>
<P>
   Injuries are inevitable, but according to Coyotes Coach  &UR; Jim
 &UR; Schoenfeld, the problem has been compounded.
</P>
<P>
   ``The ice surface is the same size. The players are bigger,
faster and stronger, so there's less ice to maneuver on. The speed
at which they're confronting each other is greater. So when you get
these two big locomotives coming and there's no room to get out of
the way, something's got to give,'' Schoenfeld said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a tough game. We play three, four times a week and we
travel coast to coast. Football plays 16 games in a season and they
take a week to heal up. We can't do that. But it's a real grueling,
grueling way to make a living.''
</P>
<P>
   Schoenfeld, like many, also subscribes to the theory that there
is less respect among players in today's NHL. He blames improved
equipment for part of that.
</P>
<P>
   ``The more equipment you wear, the less regard there is,'' he
said. ``First of all, you think, `I've got to get through this
shield of armor to get to the flesh, and I can do almost anything
to get through this shield of armor.' I really do think that
players have less regard because of helmets, too.
</P>
<P>
   ``I played when a lot of guys didn't wear helmets, and our
sticks were carried lower. And you didn't bash a guy's head into
the glass. It was the odd time, but it wasn't the norm. A better
example is the kids who wear the cages. Now, instead of cuts and
getting teeth knocked out, you get spinal injuries. That's way more
severe. . . . But you think you're invincible and you can't hurt
the other guy.''
</P>
<P>
   The NHL is taking a more active stand this season on doling out
suspensions for flagrant and even borderline hits. But injuries and
accidents will keep coming. As Roenick said, ``That's hockey.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It makes you appreciate seeing a guy like  &UR; Danny Briere out
there,'' Roenick said of the Coyotes' 5-foot-9 rookie center.
``He's playing the toughest game in sports, and he's not afraid to
get hit. He's not afraid to go into the corners and take his lumps.
There's a lot of people in this game who don't sacrifice themselves
like that.
</P>
<P>
   ``That kid is amazing, though. I saw him on TV the other night,
and I swear to God, he looks like a freshman in high school.'' &QL; 
Don't be like Mike &QL; 
It's been a few months, but Florida Panthers General Manager
 &UR; Bryan &UR; Murray is still seething about the way goalie  &UR; Mike Richter
double-crossed him this summer during negotiations with the
then-unrestricted free agent.
</P>
<P>
   According to Murray, Richter agreed to a six-year, $31 million
overture from Murray during a phone conversation, but only used it
to drive up the price to re-sign with the New York Rangers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was assured when I made the offer that there was no right to
match as far as the Rangers were concerned,'' Murray said. ``But
the second I got off the phone, the first thing (Richter) did was
run to (Rangers GM)  &UR; Neil Smith with my offer. It was upsetting at
that time, and it's still upsetting.
</P>
<P>
   ``Like I told Mike afterward, I don't think he showed much
character or honor by doing that.''
</P>
<P>
   Richter reacted by saying, ``I could understand him being upset.
But I don't have any bones to pick with him at all. He's a good
man. He made me an offer and these are high stakes. But I was a
free agent and New York made me an offer. I considered it and I
took it. I don't think there's anything wrong with that.'' &QL; 
Kudos to Cullen &QL; 
He's battled back from cancer, and instead of accepting an offer
from Tampa Bay to retire and take a seat behind the Lightning bench
as an assistant,  &UR; John Cullen decided to stick it out and play in
the minors.
</P>
<P>
   Playing for Tampa's farm team in the International Hockey
League, Cullen tied a Cleveland Lumberjacks team record last
weekend by recording a seven-point night _ two goals, five assists
_ during a 7-3 win over the Chicago Wolves.
</P>
<P>
   ``The hockey gods are on my side,'' Cullen said. ``Every bounce
was going my way.''
</P>
<P>
   When  &UR; Dave Michayluk set the original record for Cleveland back
on Feb. 27, 1988, Cullen happened to be on the ice as a member of
the Flint Generals. &QL; 
Just plain ugly &QL; 
After the Coyotes ambushed the Stars, 2-0, last week in Dallas,
someone asked Coach  &UR; Ken Hitchcock if he was concerned about star
center  &UR; Mike Modano not scoring a goal in eight straight games.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes, I'm concerned,'' Hitchcock said, raising a few eyebrows.
``He's going to have to find out how far he's willing to dig in to
score. You don't score from the perimeter in this league. How many
shots has he had from the inside? Look where he's scored his three
goals earlier this year. All were inside.''
</P>
<P>
   Modano, who finally ended his slump during Friday's 5-1 win over
Detroit, said he plans to get his nose dirty.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have to hang around the net more,'' he said. ``You don't get
too many chances to score pretty goals. It's an ugly league. You
have to score ugly goals.'' &QL; 
Includes information from other media sources. Bob McManaman can be
reached at 602-444-8326 or at bob.mcmanaman(at)pni.com via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
