<SLUG> BC-BBO-NOTEBOOK-GOMEZ-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ATHLETICS OWNERS PERSONIFY GREED 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By PEDRO GOMEZ  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The late  &UR; Walter Haas, one of baseball's best friends during the
16 years he owned the Oakland Athletics, would be appalled to learn
what
 &UR; Steve Schott and  &UR; Ken Hofmann are up to with his beloved A's.
</P>
<P>
   The pair, which bought the club from Haas in his dying days for
a driven-down bargain price of $80 million or so, has the club for
sale at $155.3 million. The co-owners claim the club is worth $135
million (no way) and want an additional $20.3 million from the new
buyer to pay off deferred contracts and interest.
</P>
<P>
   Haas, who transformed Levi Strauss from a sleepy jeans company
into a worldwide heavyweight, never asked Schott (surprisingly, no
relation to  &UR; Marge) and Hofmann for deferred compensation. All Haas
sought was an owner who would keep the club in the Bay Area, also
the home of Levi's.
</P>
<P>
   From the beginning the co-owners began showing their intentions.
Before they even watched their first game as owners they drove
 &UR; Tony La
 &UR; Russa out of town, wondering how a manager could possibly be paid
$1.5 million per season.
</P>
<P>
   Forget that La Russa gave the A's credibility, money was all
that interested this pair from the start.
</P>
<P>
   Within months, the likes of  &UR; Todd Stottlemyre,  &UR; Dennis Eckersley
and
 &UR; Rick Honeycutt were former A's. It wouldn't be long before  &UR; Mark
 &UR; McGwire, who, at the time, wanted to remain in Oakland, had priced
himself out of the A's budget.
</P>
<P>
   The payroll last season was less than $20 million. Attendance
has not come near the levels it reached under Haas, and now Schott
and Hofmann have even made it one of their requirements that any
prospective owner pony up $15 million (10 percent of the sale
price) simply to review their books.
</P>
<P>
   Even sadder, the Oakland Coliseum Authority filed to take the
sale to arbitration. The Authority, which recruited Schott and
Hofmann to buy the club, wants the two to sell for the original $85
million plus 10 percent of that figure for each of the three years
they've owned the club and any capital they have put into the club
since taking over.
</P>
<P>
   ``They could have walked away with a profit of $40 million,''
Oakland City Council member  &UR; John Russo told the ``Oakland
Tribune.'' ``But it wasn't enough.''
</P>
<P>
   In short, this is nothing short of a white-collar crime. &QL; 
A near California collision &QL; 
Talk about a blockbuster. San Diego and Los Angeles nearly pulled
off a nine-player deal that would have sent Padres outfielder  &UR; Greg
Vaughn, pitcher  &UR; Joey Hamilton, second baseman  &UR; Quilvio Veras,
shortstop  &UR; Chris &UR; Gomez and reliever  &UR; Randy Myers to the Dodgers.
</P>
<P>
   In exchange, San Diego would have acquired outfielder  &UR; Gary
Sheffield, pitcher  &UR; Ismael Valdes, second baseman  &UR; Eric Young and
shortstop  &UR; Mark
 &UR; Grudzielanek.
</P>
<P>
   The deal was initiated and approved by the Padres. Los Angeles
thought hard before backing out, believing it wasn't receiving
enough. &QL; 
Just go away, already &QL; 
Former Florida Marlins owner/pariah  &UR; Wayne Huizenga couldn't depart
from Major League Baseball without one last laughable comment.
Huizenga insisted he sold the team at a ridiculously low price of
$158 million.
</P>
<P>
   When the Kansas City Royals, who have their own stadium, are on
the block for nearly $80 million, how can Huizenga make such an
absurd comment?
</P>
<P>
   He also said he turned down a $250 million offer from a group
that wanted to move the club to northern Virginia because he wanted
to keep the Marlins in south Florida.
</P>
<P>
   Yeah, right. This is a guy who once sent his attack-dog
attorneys to the corner pizza man because his business was named
Blockbuster Pizza, forcing the small businessman to change the
name. &QL; 
THE HIT LIST &QL; 
 &UR; Talk about covering a story: Two years ago  &UR; Andrea Pacione, a
Cleveland TV reporter, was sent to Jacobs Field to do a story on
the Indians. Last week she married first baseman  &UR; Jim Thome.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; This will surely go over well: Mets Manager  &UR; Bobby
 &UR; Valentine, assessing his newest player: ``I think  &UR; Bobby Bonilla is
a guy who comes with some risk who also comes with a lot of reward.
The risk is whether he catches the ball when it comes down.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Flashback: Pete Falcone.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Gee, that's awfully nice of you, Frank: White Sox designated
hitter (he no longer considers himself a first baseman)
 &UR; Frank Thomas last week said he was troubled with his name surfacing
in trade talk, especially after choosing ``to stay in Chicago and
settle for less.'' Thomas begins the first year of an eight-year
deal worth $78 million in 1999.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Suddenly, it's all the rage:  &UR; Al Martin joined Diamondbacks
outfielder  &UR; Bernard Gilkey in becoming another big-league player
who has opted for laser eye surgery in an effort to revitalize his
career. &QL; 
EXTRA BASES &QL; 
 &UR; Robin Ventura, the best free-agent third baseman available, has
made eyes at San Diego. Ventura, who could command $10 million a
year, has received little more than a blank stare in return.
</P>
<P>
   It seems that  &UR; John Smiley, who won at least 10 games in eight
of 10 seasons through 1997, may never pitch again. Smiley, who
broke a bone in his arm while warming up 14 months ago, recently
passed through waivers without being claimed. &QL; 
THE RUMOR MILL &QL; 
Once  &UR; Kevin Brown and  &UR; Randy Johnson, the two big fish among this
year's free agents, sign with new clubs, expect the clubs that lose
out to aggressively talk with Toronto about trading for  &UR; Roger
Clemens. The list of possible suitors: Houston, Los Angeles, Texas,
Anaheim, St. Louis, Atlanta and the Yankees. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Includes information from other media sources. Pedro Gomez can be
reached at 602-444-2364 or at pedro.gomez(at)pni.com via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
