<SLUG> BC-BBM-AZFALL-NOTEBOOK-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MINOR GAINS MAJOR ATTENTION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB COHN  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - When he turned his attention to professional baseball,
 &UR; Ryan Minor was best known as a prolific scorer for the Oklahoma
basketball team. He was even Big Eight Player of the Year in 1995.
But forget all that. Minor has an even greater claim to fame.
</P>
<P>
   On Sept. 21, less than two weeks after being called up from
Baltimore's Double-A affiliate in Bowie, Md., Minor started at
third base for the Orioles.
</P>
<P>
   In place of  &UR; Cal Ripken Jr.
</P>
<P>
   That ended Ripken's consecutive games streak at 2,632 and
certified Minor as the answer to a trivia question. But he wants to
be much more than that, which is why he is extending his season and
honing his skills as a member of the Grand Canyon Rafters.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, he will never be far from the memory.
</P>
<P>
   ``You think about it,'' said Minor, who was 8 when Ripken's
streak began on May 30, 1982. ``It's just one of those things that
I happened to be on the team that night and they just called my
name. It was a good experience. It was fun. It was something I'll
always remember.''
</P>
<P>
   Minor was sitting in the home team dugout at Camden Yards
sipping a cup of coffee before a game against the New York Yankees
when Manager
 &UR; Ray Miller pulled him into an adjacent bathroom to tell him he
would be starting in place of Ripken.
</P>
<P>
   Responded Minor, ``Does he know this?''
</P>
<P>
   Assured that Ripken was informed, Minor went 1 for 4 and played
flawlessly in the field. He even made a diving catch of a line
drive.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't try to do too much, not make any errors,'' said
Minor, who is one of baseball's tallest infielders at 6 feet 6{.
``It turns out I had a pretty good game.''
</P>
<P>
   As he took the field, Minor turned back and looked into the
dugout, ``to make sure everybody was with me and that it wasn't a
joke,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Afterward, he was the center of attention, but said his
experience as a Sooners basketball player helped him. A 33rd-round
pick in baseball's June 1996 draft, Minor was drafted by
Philadelphia in the second round of the '96 NBA draft. He was cut
and played in the Continental Basketball Association.
</P>
<P>
   This was just Minor's second full season of professional
baseball, and he hopes to make a good impression this spring. He
has been playing a lot of first base.
</P>
<P>
   ``If it takes being a utility guy or playing a position I'm not
used to playing, I'll do it ,'' he said. ``I just have to work hard
and see what happens.''
</P>
<P>
   Minor is considered a top prospect, and there is talk he is
being groomed as Ripken's replacement. But if it doesn't work out,
he can always return to basketball. Here are two words to remember:
 &UR; Danny
 &UR; Ainge. &QL; 
Another one &QL; 
Since the Fall League began in 1992, at least one its alumni has
been named Rookie of the Year every season. The streak continued
last week when Oakland Athletics outfielder  &UR; Ben Grieve won
American League honors.
</P>
<P>
   Grieve, who played for the Phoenix Desert Dogs in 1996, joins
 &UR; Mike
 &UR; Piazza (1993),  &UR; Bob Hamelin (1994),  &UR; Marty Cordova (1995),  &UR; Todd
 &UR; Hollandsworth (1996),  &UR; Derek Jeter (1996) and  &UR; Nomar Garciaparra
(1997).
</P>
<P>
   The second and third-place vote-getters in the AL, Tampa Bay
pitcher
 &UR; Rolando Arrojo and Chicago shortstop  &UR; Mike Caruso, also played in
the Fall League. So did Colorado first baseman  &UR; Todd Helton and
Diamondbacks first baseman  &UR; Travis Lee, runners-up to Cubs pitcher
 &UR; Kerry Wood in the National League.
</P>
<P>
   As a reminder that Fall League statistics often mislead, Grieve
hit a modest .277 with three home runs and 23 RBI in 40 games for
Phoenix. With the A's, Grieve hit .288, leading all major league
rookies in runs (94), hits (168), walks (85) and on-base percentage
(.386), and led all AL rookies in home runs (18) and RBI (89). &QL; 
Roster moves
</P>
<P>
   Congratulations to Toronto pitcher  &UR; Roy Halladay, who left the
Grand Canyon Rafters to go home to get married. In his second major
league game for the Blue Jays last season, Halladay came within one
out of a no-hitter. He was 4-0 with a 1.85 ERA for the Rafters. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
