<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-15 00:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1362 &Cx1f; tic-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-QUEST-SIDE-AZR &LR;      11-15 0839
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-QUEST-SIDE-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SCOTTSDALE IRONMAN FINDS ADVENTURE ON ROAD IN MOROCCO  
 CHALLENGE COMPETITION BRINGS RESPECT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By JEFF METCALFE  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Jack Dunn had never been on a camel until he arrived in
Essaouria, Morocco, the North Atlantic coastal town where the
Eco-Challenge began Oct. 6. That day dawned with camels to his
left. Camels to his right. The largest assembly of camels since
``Lawrence of Arabia'' was filmed more than 35 years earlier.
</P>
<P>
   ``At least they had Arabs riding on them (in the movie),'' Dunn
said. ``For this, they lined up 220 camels and said go, and there
were 220 camels going in 220 directions.'' The massive saddles
beneath many Eco-Challenge racers slipped under the camels'
bellies, making the animals unmanageable.
</P>
<P>
   Team Epinephrine _ captain Paul Romero of Big Bear Lake, Calif.;
Dunn, of Scottsdale; Nick Moore of Palm Springs and Karen Lundgren
of San Bernardino, Calif. _ has excelled since Dunn and Moore were
cut off from Desert Quest.
</P>
<P>
   Picked by lottery as the 12th and final U.S. team allowed in the
55-team Eco-Challenge, Epinephrine finished eighth in one of the
top adventure races in the world. It has lined up a lucrative
sponsor for the coming year and expects to get plenty of air time
when Discovery Channel's coverage of the Eco-Challenge is broadcast
to 144 countries in April.
</P>
<P>
   ``We found out after the race we were on their `A' list,'' Moore
said. ``In the 20-minute highlight video (to close Eco), we were
plastered all over the thing. We were just having a good time and
had a fun attitude.''
</P>
<P>
   On the weekend of Desert Quest, Team Epinephrine, just back from
Morocco, placed fourth at the Hi-Tec Adventure Race series finale
in Los Angeles. It also was first in Portland, Ore., second in
Sacramento and next year will be compete as Team Hi-Tec, a coveted
sponsorship.
</P>
<P>
   Morocco, said Dunn of his second Eco-Challenge, was
incomparable.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's fun to see human beings going through pain and torture
and wondering why,'' Dunn said. ``It's amazing to see what the
human body can endure and keep going. I know people who did Desert
Quest and said that took me 18 hours, I couldn't imagine getting up
three hours later and doing it again.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet that is the drill at Eco-Challenge and Raid Gauloises, day
after day of numbing treks, climbs and rappels, divided in Morocco
by a 30-mile ride on Arab Barbary horses. All by navigation,
finding the way with map and compass.
</P>
<P>
   ``All we saw for six days was rock,'' Dunn said, 175 miles worth
that with the up-and-down represented 80,000-90,000 feet of total
elevation gain. ``I didn't know Morocco had mountains like that.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was unbelievably cold, wind 40 miles per hour, water
freezing in the bottle. We were just praying we'd get to the next
checkpoint so we could get off the mountain.''
</P>
<P>
   After the nine-mile camel ride, the Eco-Challengers advanced
from three miles in full packs to a 48-mile kayak in the Atlantic.
</P>
<P>
   ``The water was unbelievable,'' Dunn said. ``Major, major
swells. The biggest water I've ever seen in any race.''
</P>
<P>
   Kayakers were forced to shore from 6 p.m. to 6 a.m., when the
ocean was ruled a dark zone.
</P>
<P>
   ``You could always see land, so there was this overwhelming
calm,'' Moore said. Right up until teams were given the option of
having one member swim to a checkpoint rather than fighting to
land. Moore, in a 10-second decision, accepted his duty as the
group's best swimmer to fight through waves rivaling those on
Hawaii's North Shore.
</P>
<P>
   Team Epinephrine completed the kayak in 24 hours and in 15th
place, up from 21st after the camel ride, and boarded a bus for the
nine-hour ride to the aptly named Atlas Mountains.
</P>
<P>
   About two-thirds of the way through, the team moved into sixth
place and then, briefly, into fifth.
</P>
<P>
   But Dunn developed an infected blister. Romero pulled a
quadricep muscle and injured the other while compensating. When the
110-mile mountain bike ride from Ali-n-Ito out of the mountains to
the finish at Marrakech began, Epinephrine was in ninth place and
on life support.
</P>
<P>
   ``I could walk faster than he (Romero) was moving (via bike),''
Dunn said.
</P>
<P>
   Rigging two bike tubes as a tow system, Moore, playing Superman,
started to pull Romero out the Moroccan equivalent of the Grand
Canyon. Then Dunn took a turn. They towed for four hours, covering
15 miles. ``I was ready to lay down and die,'' Dunn said.
</P>
<P>
   Then Romero, a paramedic and pioneer of snowboard patrolling,
found his legs and was able to ride the top half of the canyon and
what became an 80-mile express from the rim to Marrakech and an
eighth-place finish in eight days, 30 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are so many great teams and great athletes from all over
the world,'' said Moore, a 14th-place finisher in Eco Australia in
1997. ``To think about finishing in the top 10 is stupid.
</P>
<P>
   ``We went there with a great attitude and let the race come to
us. We didn't make any big mistakes.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
