<SLUG> BC-HKO-KRIKORIAN-COLUMN-LBPT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CZECH WILL BE MONEY PLAYER
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DOUG KRIKORIAN  
 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   He spoke not a word of English when he arrived in America last
Feb. 3 from the Czech Republic, a 17-year-old hockey player of vast
skills suddenly in a land of strange voices and customs.
</P>
<P>
   He admits he felt almost like an alien stranded on another
planet, an interloper unable to comprehend the labyrinth of roads
that pass for the L.A. freeway system.
</P>
<P>
   He couldn't believe the frenzied pace of life that was such a
contrast to the slow-motion tempo of the land of his upbringing.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everything so much faster here,'' says Patrik Stefan, the Long
Beach Ice Dogs' teen-age prodigy. ``The cars. The people. The
places you go. Better. Better than my country. More opportunity.
More to do. I like it here. Long Beach. Beautiful. Great weather.
Nice people. Yes, I like it here.''
</P>
<P>
   Patrik Stefan is seated across from me at a restaurant table on
a recent evening, smiling shyly, a trademark expression for an
endearing fellow who dropped out of high school at 15{ to pursue a
sport that soon will make him a millionaire.
</P>
<P>
   Despite his brief stay in this country, he has been able to
learn enough English to communicate his thoughts, and he does so in
a sincere manner bereft of the silly artificial poses favored by so
many of the U.S.-born athletes of his age category.
</P>
<P>
   Patrik Stefan just might be the warmest gate attraction in the
International Hockey League the Ice Dogs' center has been second in
the league in scoring and he figures to be among the first five
players chosen in the NHL entry draft next June.
</P>
<P>
   And, if that weren't enough to make one envious, Stefan also is
extraordinarily handsome with movie-star features on a face
highlighted by a strong jaw and Paul Newman blue eyes.
</P>
<P>
   He's become a terror on the ice who's inspired comparisons to
Pittsburgh Penguins' All-Star Jaromir Jagr, but off it he's a
modest, humble, self-effacing man who's handling his sudden
celebrity with calm discretion.
</P>
<P>
   ``I no change,'' says Stefan, who will perform with the Ice Dogs
in today's 4 p.m. match against the Las Vegas Thunder at the Long
Beach Arena. ``I got lot more to learn about hockey. I learn all
the time. I get better since I been in America, but I got long ways
to go. Long ways.''
</P>
<P>
   Stefan would have been eligible for the NHL draft this year had
he been born a day earlier than Sept. 16, but he has no complaints.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is good I play in IHL the entire season,'' he says.
``I'll be ready when times comes for me to play in the NHL. I still
have many things to learn.''
</P>
<P>
   He lives in an apartment on PCH near the Traffic Circle with
teammate Jan Nemecek, and spends his spare moments going to movies
and e-mailing friends in the Czech Republic.
</P>
<P>
   ``I go to movies all the time. ... that's where I learn to speak
English,'' he says. ``I like adventure movies, but also comedies. I
see `Waterboy.' Very funny.''
</P>
<P>
   His grandfather, an ex-hockey player himself, started teaching
him the fine points of the game when Stefan was a mere 7. And his
father Karel, who's in town for a month, took over supervising
Stefan's career when the grandfather moved to Greece.
</P>
<P>
   Patrik Stefan put up some impressive numbers during his career
in the Czech Republic, scoring 484 points (330 goals and 154
assists) in 327 games.
</P>
<P>
   He says there were strained feelings back home when he bolted
Sparta Praha earlier this year to play for the Ice Dogs.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's something I felt I must do to make it in the NHL,'' he
says. ``Hockey here is much different. The players are bigger and
stronger and faster. The game is so much faster.''
</P>
<P>
   His coach, John Van Boxmeer, envisions a bright NHL future for
Stefan.
</P>
<P>
   ``Patrik is very mature for his age and works extremely hard,''
says Van Boxmeer. ``He has all the physical tools, and is strong on
the puck. He's a very instinctive player, and isn't afraid to mix
it up. I said before the season that I think by the end of it he
will be the elite player in the IHL. I still think that way. He
just gets better and better.''
</P>
<P>
   At 6-foot-2 and 205 pounds, Patrik Stefan has the proper
physical equipment, but he also has the proper mental outlook.
</P>
<P>
   Oh, he's human. He admits he's finding it difficult to resist
all the temptations that go with being young, rich, handsome and
single.
</P>
<P>
   ``But no girlfriend yet,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   He plans to return to the classroom in the off-season to get the
equivalent of a high school degree, but college isn't on the
horizon for him.
</P>
<P>
   ``No time. ... I plan to play hockey for a long time,'' he
smiles.
</P>
<P>
   Suddenly, the restaurateur, Phil Trani, comes to the table and
beseeches Patrik Stefan to sign his famed Wall of Fame.
</P>
<P>
   Stefan walks into Trani's kitchen, and sees all the signatures
of athletic personalities on the walls and shakes his head softly
when he's informed who they are.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sure you want my name up there?'' he asks.
</P>
<P>
   ``Definitely,'' replies Trani, handing Stefan a pen. ``I think
one day you'll be as famous as anyone.''
</P>
<P>
   Grudgingly, Patrik Stefan writes in flawless English a few
commendatory words and affixes his signature.
</P>
<P>
   The kid, indeed, is precocious.
</P>
<P>
   Patrik Stefan has been in this country for only 10 months, and
his penmanship already is vastly superior to that of most American
citizens.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
