<SLUG> BC-FBC-ASU-CASSTEVENS-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DEVILS UNLIMITED FIRES BOTH BARRELS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 DAVID CASSTEVENS  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   EUGENE, Ore. - It has long been my belief that hunting would be
more sporting if the animals could shoot back.
</P>
<P>
   We have the right to bear arms. Why not arm bears?
</P>
<P>
   If you're unclear what any of this has to do with the Arizona
State football team maybe you didn't hear the latest. On a gray
chilly afternoon, amid's autumn's red-gold glow _ Duck hunting
weather _ the Oregon Ducks reversed the roles. The hunted became
the hunters, and vice versa.
</P>
<P>
   The Ducks, who had lost three in a row to the Sun Devils and
grown tired of being an easy target, came out blasting Saturday.
They let the visitors have it with both barrels. One barrel goes by
the name Akili; the other Smith.
</P>
<P>
   Akili Smith threw and threw and threw. Reloading, he kept firing
away until he had four touchdowns (to wide open receivers) and
almost 400 yards.
</P>
<P>
   Oregon's offense scored on its first four possessions. Smith was
accurate. Elusive. Relentless. It was as if, in Oregon's eyes, the
ASU secondary represented every sportsman who ever put on a plaid
flannel shirt and an Elmer Fudd cap and oiled the old 12-gauge.
</P>
<P>
   ASU had no cover. No place to hide. At times it looked as if the
Ducks had 12 players on offense. Someone, it seemed, was always
open.
</P>
<P>
   The Devils knew it was over late in the third quarter _ if not
long before _ when they fumbled their second kickoff return and a
Duck named Mallard _ honest _ recovered.
</P>
<P>
   The Ducks' supply of ammo seemed almost as inexhaustible as this
hunting analogy. Bottom line: Ducks Unlimited prevailed, 51-19. The
Devils, after winning three in a row, sank to 5-5. This overrated
team that began the season ranked among the nation's Top 10 won't
be going to a bowl unless the Devils beat rival Arizona in their
annual spleen-vent the day after Thanksgiving.
</P>
<P>
   If ASU's plan was to lull UA into a feeling of overconfidence
the Devils may have succeeded. ASU lost to Oregon by 32 points.
Oregon lost to Arizona by 35. The Wildcats won't be 67-point
favorites, but if they can beat their state brethren by that
margin, they will.
</P>
<P>
   Bruce Snyder called the UA game a ``one-game season.'' Sadly, it
has come to that. If the Devils find a way to win in Tucson they
can salvage a measure of respect and feel better about themselves.
</P>
<P>
   But they can't win without Ryan Kealy. They can't win without a
healthy J.R. Redmond. Kealy didn't play against the Ducks. After
sitting out two games, Redmond returned to the backfield and
sprinted 57 yards for a touchdown on his first carry.
</P>
<P>
   In the end zone J.R. playfully pointed to his suspect ankle as
if to tell the crowd, many of them tooting duck calls, that he is
fine, just fine, fully recovered from a sprain. Fact is, he still
isn't healthy.
</P>
<P>
   Senior Steve Campbell did an adequate job in only his second
start. At 6-foot-8, Campbell is America's tallest quarterback and
off the field he was the easiest player for the Oregon media to
identify. The drubbing over, a TV guy held up a microphone and
asked Campbell if he had ``fun.''
</P>
<P>
   Campbell fought the urge to wrap his hands around the
questioner's throat and lift him to eye level. ``Fun? It was
51-19,'' he said, as if that said it all, which it should. ``No, it
wasn't too much damn fun. I'd rather sit on the bench and us win
than play and get beat by thirty-something points . . .''
</P>
<P>
   Campbell felt embarrassed. So did the Devils defense. Cornerback
Courtney Jackson and his teammates spent the long day back on their
heels, in retreat. Members of the secondary may have felt as if
they were wearing ASU mascot Sparky's costume, the one with orange
flames licking up his pants legs. Smith burned them early, and
often. ASU gave up 493 yards. Jackson conceded that Smith created
``a little bit of chaos.''
</P>
<P>
   When the gun mercifully sounded, Snyder jogged to midfield,
shook Oregon coach Mike Bellotti's hand without breaking stride and
then looked for Smith. The ASU coach had nothing to say to
Bellotti, who earlier in the week suggested the Sun Devils are
guilty of intentionally chop blocking. This was akin to a doctor
going to the media and saying that a fellow physician is committing
medical malpractice.
</P>
<P>
   Snyder congratulated Smith. Wished him well. Then he retreated
to the inner sanctum of his locker room and told his team _ what?
</P>
<P>
   What does a coach say after a game like this? &QL; 
David Casstevens can be reached at 602-444-8635 or at
david.casstevens(at)pni.com via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
