<SLUG> BC-FBC-ASU-OREGON-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NO SUNSHINE FOR ASU IN OREGON  
 DRUBBING DROPS DEVILS TO .500 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By PAOLA BOIVIN  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   EUGENE, Ore. _ Like the foliage surrounding Auzten Stadium,
Arizona State showed its true colors Saturday. It wasn't pretty.
</P>
<P>
   Oregon manhandled ASU, 51-19, in front of 43,723. The Sun Devils
couldn't wait to make like a tree and leave.
</P>
<P>
   The implications of the loss were huge:
</P>
<P>
   The Sun Devils (5-5, 4-3 Pac-10) must beat Arizona in their
regular-season finale to be eligible for a bowl game. Keep in mind
this is a Wildcats team that destroyed Oregon, 38-3, two weeks ago.
</P>
<P>
   ASU is in danger of its first losing season since 1994.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we lose (against Arizona), we put the pads away and don't
take them out until spring,'' cornerback Courtney Jackson said.
``Who wants that?''
</P>
<P>
   The loss was ASU's worst since a 77-28 defeat by Nebraska in
1995 and Coach Bruce Snyder's second-worst at ASU. The 493 yards
were the most the Sun Devils have allowed this season.
</P>
<P>
   ASU played without quarterback Ryan Kealy and with a tailback,
J.R. Redmond, still limited because of an ankle injury. Had both
been 100 percent, it probably wouldn't have made a difference.
</P>
<P>
   Oregon still had quarterback Akili Smith, who was a one-man
wrecking crew. He completed 21 of 30 passes for 397 yards and four
touchdowns. He threw three in the first 10 minutes of the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't say enough about him,'' Snyder said. ``I really admire
him. This is clearly his football team.''
</P>
<P>
   The Sun Devils' defense wasn't up to the task, especially in the
first half. The line wasn't able to put any significant pressure on
Smith, and the rest of the defense appeared to have trouble
adjusting to Smith's play-making abilities.
</P>
<P>
   When he scrambled, look out.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes the worst thing you could do is cut him off,''
Jackson said. ``Because then he improvises and scrambles. It would
result in a little bit of chaos between the linebackers and
cornerbacks.''
</P>
<P>
   Snyder said, ``We're playing a lot of young guys, but it is the
10th game of the season. We have to play better.''
</P>
<P>
   The ineptness of ASU's defense was summed up in a fourth-quarter
drive, highlighted by a 55-yard pass play involving Oregon's
6-foot-4, 245-pound tight end Jed Weaver. He escaped the grasp of
four Sun Devils before being pulled down.
</P>
<P>
   Just when ASU appeared to get a handle on the drive, it was
tagged for two pass-interference plays in the end zone. Ultimately,
Herman Ho-Ching carried it in for a 2-yard touchdown.
</P>
<P>
   The game was billed as ``Chop-gate'' because of Oregon Coach
Mike Bellotti's comments early in the week accusing the Sun Devils'
offensive line of chop-blocking. But it was never an issue in the
game and other then a few flare-ups, emotions were kept in check.
</P>
<P>
   Snyder and Bellotti even briefly shook hands after the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``Overall, it was a pretty clean game,'' Oregon defensive tackle
Masi Heamish said. ``I had fun and I think those guys had fun,
except for losing.''
</P>
<P>
   ASU's offense couldn't do much either. Senior Steve Campbell,
starting in place of Kealy, was solid but not spectacular,
completing 11 of 24 passes for 217 yards and a touchdown. He seemed
poised for only his second career start.
</P>
<P>
   And confidence was clearly not a problem. At one point, with the
crowd roaring, he waved his arms to encourage fans to be louder,
then put his hand to his ear, suggesting he couldn't hear them.
</P>
<P>
   The game plan was to run the ball, but the Sun Devils rethought
their strategy at halftime because the Ducks' front seven was
effective at stopping them. They opened up the passing game in the
second half but it didn't make much difference.
</P>
<P>
   Redmond carried 10 times for 72 yards. Backup Davaren Hightower
managed just 29. Gerald Green didn't play because of a shoulder
injury.
</P>
<P>
   ``I went out about 80 percent,'' Redmond said. ``I didn't have
full range of motion.''
</P>
<P>
   It didn't look like that the first time he was handed the ball
after being sidelined for two games. He sprinted 57 yards upfield
and into the end zone and tied the score at 7.
</P>
<P>
   But Oregon bounced right back with touchdown passes of 22 and 35
yards to LaCorey Collins and Damon Griffin, respectively.
</P>
<P>
   The second was set up by Lenzie Jackson's fumble of a kickoff
return. Oregon took over at ASU's 35.
</P>
<P>
   ``The way we lost was a surprise,'' Campbell said. ``Any time
you get your butt handed to you, it's a surprise.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
