<SLUG> BC-FBC-KSTATE-NEBRASKA-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
K-STATE TRUMPS NEBRASKA  
 UNBEATEN WILDCATS END 29 YEARS OF FUTILITY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By KENT SOMERS  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   MANHATTAN, Kan. _ They started digging the hole for KSU Stadium
in the late 1960s, figuring, as one longtime resident of the
``Little Apple'' put it, that if this football deal didn't work
out, they could always fill the thing with silage.
</P>
<P>
   There are no such backup plans now.
</P>
<P>
   For those who still didn't believe that Kansas State has arrived
as a national power, the second-ranked Wildcats proved it Saturday
by defeating 11th-ranked Nebraska, 40-30.
</P>
<P>
   On a clear day that bathed the purple-clad crowd of 44,298 in
sunlight, the Wildcats (10-0) not only furthered their chance of
playing in the Fiesta Bowl for a national championship, but they
cleansed themselves of a demon that has haunted the program for 30
years.
</P>
<P>
   Kansas State hadn't beaten Nebraska (8-3) since 1968. The
futility streak since then had spanned 29 games and six presidents.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm humbled by it, honestly, just because of the amount of
time it's taken to do this,'' said Kansas State Coach Bill Snyder,
who has directed the biggest transformation since Dr. Frankenstein
took off his lab coat for good.
</P>
<P>
   It is unchartered territory for the fans of this school in the
Flint Hills two hours west of Kansas City.
</P>
<P>
   They didn't know how to react Saturday, and their attempts at
celebrating near the end of the game are sure to spawn numerous
Aggie jokes.
</P>
<P>
   When linebacker Jeff Kelly returned a fumble 23 yards for a
touchdown to give the Wildcats a 40-30 lead with three seconds
left, students flowed onto the field like spilled grape juice.
</P>
<P>
   They were ordered back to the sidelines by the public address
announcer, but after quarterback Michael Bishop's two-point
conversion attempt failed, the crowd rushed the field again,
thinking the game was over.
</P>
<P>
   Once more, the announcer ordered them off. When Nebraska was
stopped on the ensuing kickoff, the crowd poured onto the field for
good and began trying to remove the north goal post, and after
considerable effort, finally busted it off.
</P>
<P>
   The victory assures Kansas State of an appearance in the Big 12
title game Dec. 5 in St. Louis against Texas A&AMP;M. It would be the
Wildcats' first conference title since 1934, when they won the Big
Six championship.
</P>
<P>
   It also kept alive their hopes of a return trip to the Fiesta
Bowl, where they beat Syracuse last year. This season, the Fiesta
Bowl will match the two top teams in the country as determined by
the Bowl Championship Series formula, which has the Wildcats ranked
third behind fellow unbeaten teams Tennessee and UCLA.
</P>
<P>
   ``We knew that if we lost this game, people were going to call
us flukes and start disrespecting us,'' said defensive end Joe Bob
Clements, a senior from Emporia, Kan. ``I've watched Nebraska
pummel Kansas State for years and years. I'm glad I never had to
look back and say, `I wish I could have did this.' ''
</P>
<P>
   It was far from easy, however, and the final score is deceiving.
</P>
<P>
   At times, Kansas State appeared intent on bungling this chance,
too. Nebraska went 80 yards in eight plays on its opening drive to
take a 7-0 lead. Bishop fumbled five times in the first half,
losing three of them, two of which led to 10 points by Nebraska.
</P>
<P>
   The Cornhuskers took a 14-7 lead early in the second quarter
after freshman quarterback Eric Crouch threw a 45-yard touchdown
pass to receiver Kenny Cheatham, a senior from South Mountain High
School, who made an amazing one-handed grab.
</P>
<P>
   Bishop, however, brought the Wildcats back all day. He threw for
306 yards and two touchdowns and rushed for 140 yards and two more.
</P>
<P>
   When Kansas State took a 24-17 lead in the third quarter, it
looked as if the game had finally turned in its favor. The Wildcats
allowed Nebraska to gain just 15 yards in the third quarter, and
Kansas State's offense was moving at will.
</P>
<P>
   That changed quickly when Wildcats running back Frank Murphy,
playing for an injured Eric Hickson, fumbled, and Nebraska's Ralph
Brown returned it 74 yards for a touchdown to tie the score at 24
late in the third quarter.
</P>
<P>
   Nebraska scored to go ahead, 30-27, in the fourth quarter, but
Bishop brought the Wildcats back again.
</P>
<P>
   On his team's final scoring drive, Bishop entered the huddle
confidently.
</P>
<P>
   ``(Bishop) said, `We're going to go down and score, and then I'm
going to help the fans tear down the goal posts,' '' said receiver
Darnell McDonald, who caught 12 passes for 183 yards and two
touchdowns, including an 11-yarder that gave Kansas State a 34-30
lead.
</P>
<P>
   We don't know Bishop's version of the events because Snyder
hasn't allowed him to speak with the media for the last month, with
the exception of an ESPN interview earlier this week.
</P>
<P>
   Nebraska wasn't quite done. But in the closing minutes, Crouch
was sacked by linebacker Travis Ochs, who appeared to take Crouch
down by the face mask. There was no call.
</P>
<P>
   Crouch said he thought it was a penalty. Ochs probably did, too,
although he wasn't admitting it after the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``I looked around on the floor, didn't see a flag and went on my
merry way,`` he said.
</P>
<P>
   Nebraska got the ball back in time for one more play. But Crouch
was hit by Clements, and Kelly picked up the fumble, returning it
for the final score, placing an exclamation point on this piece of
history.
</P>
<P>
   ``Thirty years of history passed,'' said Kansas State tight end
Justin Swift. ``We swept it away.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
