r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-CARDS-BIG-GAMES-A     11-15 1516
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-CARDS-BIG-GAMES-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CAN'T BLAME FANS FOR FRENZY  
 BIG WINS A RARITY FOR CARDS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVE SCHOENFELD  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   TEMPE, ARIZ. - What the stiff-necked geeks in the NFL office _
the party patrol that's not phat and happy _ never understood about
the Cardinal fans' victory lap was that it was spontaneous.
</P>
<P>
   There were no clandestine meetings or huddles in the stands to
map out a parade route.
</P>
<P>
   This was spur-of-the-moment bedlam, years of bent-up frustration
of watching the Dallas Cowboys and their fans come into Sun Devil
Stadium, talk trash, back it up and leave stoked.
</P>
<P>
   The wild scene that ensued after the Cardinals ended a 13-game
losing streak against the Cowboys last season was understandable.
After all, can you name the last big victory in the Cardinals' 100
years before Kevin Butler banked a 20-yard field goal off the left
upright and through for a 25-22 overtime win?
</P>
<P>
   Don't give us the 1947 NFL title game, the last time the
Cardinals won in the playoffs. That was before MTV and sports-talk
radio.
</P>
<P>
   Forty years later, the Cardinals rallied from a 28-point deficit
to beat the Tampa Bay Buccaneers, 31-28, the biggest comeback in
team history. But who cares? It improved the Cardinals' record to
3-5.
</P>
<P>
   The next season, they moved to the desert and shocked the world.
Coach Gene Stallings called a fake field goal in the home opener
against Dallas, and a ``Monday Night Football'' audience watched in
disbelief as the first half ended on a feeble rushing attempt by
kicker Al Del Greco.
</P>
<P>
   From Del Greco's debacle to today's NFC East first-place
showdown against the Cowboys at Sun Devil Stadium, there have been
few BIG games in 11 seasons.
</P>
<P>
   So forgive the Cardinals and their fans if they get excited
about the Outback Steakhouse Madden Cruiser being parked in our
little burg this weekend. It doesn't happen very often.
</P>
<P>
   And if the Cardinals stun the Cowboys two years in a row, the
fuddy-duddies who get a kick out of fining players for too much
eye-black shouldn't spank the locals for bad behavior. Folks might
even run onto the field to see the freshly planted winter rye.
</P>
<P>
   They promise to stay a way from the $3,000-a-piece goal posts.
They have set their sights bigger this year. Remember fan Doug
Hustin of Mesa's proclamation after last year's win: ``Next year,
we're taking down the stadium.''
</P>
<P>
   Just try, say the Cowboys.
</P>
<P>
   ``This ain't the Fiesta Bowl,'' Cowboys offensive guard Nate
Newton said. &QL; 
Marching down Mill &QL; 
The post-game party could have been wilder after last year's Dallas
win.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of the fans hoisting the north goal post on their
shoulders, carrying it out of the stadium and down Tempe's Fifth
Street to Mill Avenue, where it was thrown off a bridge into the
Salt River bed, they could have celebrated the way Arizona State
fans did a year earlier.
</P>
<P>
   ASU students, giddy over beating Nebraska, tore down a goal
post, marched it across campus, through the student recreation
center and dropped it into a swimming pool.
</P>
<P>
   Cardinals rookie safety Pat Tillman, a seventh-round pick from
ASU, played in the victory over the Huskers and was on the field
when the fans climbed out of the stands.
</P>
<P>
   A year later, he had just finished a film session in ASU's
Intercollegiate Athletics Building, which overlooks Sun Devil
Stadium, when Butler's game-winner caused Cardinals' fans to go
berserk.
</P>
<P>
   ``It wasn't like when Kennedy was shot, where you remember
exactly where you were at the time,'' Tillman said, ``but it
obviously was a huge win.''
</P>
<P>
   The Cardinals trailed, 22-7, in the third quarter. But they
rallied for two touchdowns, including a 1-yard pass from Kent
Graham to tight end Pat Carter with 1:06 left in regulation. Graham
hit wide receiver Rob Moore for a two-point conversion to send the
game in overtime.
</P>
<P>
   Dallas recovered a fumble early in overtime, but then running
back Sherman Williams fumbled the ball back after a hit by middle
linebacker Ronald McKinnon. Cardinals outside linebacker Terry
Irving recovered.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was so hot, and I was under the pile cramping up,'' Irving
said. ``I wanted to get out of there.''
</P>
<P>
   Completions of 19 yards to Moore and 29 yards to fullback Larry
Centers set up Butler's kick.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a great feeling, exhilarating,'' linebacker Jamir
Miller said. ``But after that, we didn't win (another) game for six
weeks, so it defeated the whole purpose.''
</P>
<P>
   Miller said he watched the stands empty but never saw the goal
post come down.
</P>
<P>
   ``I ran off the field,'' he said. ``It was kind of rough out
there. It was a nice atmosphere, but not one for players to be
standing around.''
</P>
<P>
   Center Aaron Graham, a Denton, Texas, native, found his family
in the stands and waved to make sure everyone was OK. He celebrated
later.
</P>
<P>
   ``As a kid growing up (near) Dallas, being a Cowboys fan, having
the draft come around and having them pass on a hometown kid left a
bad taste in my mouth,'' said Graham, a fourth-round pick of the
Cardinals in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   NFL officials, seeing the goal post come tumbling down on
national TV, phoned Sun Devil Stadium director Tom Sadler the day
after the game. They weren't pleased.
</P>
<P>
   ``When it happens on Saturdays (in college games), the
prevailing mentality is that these are students,'' said Sadler, now
assistant athletic director at ASU. ``On Sundays, it's more of a
business. After talking to the league, we all agreed that it's
something that can't be tolerated. Can you imagine if it became a
habit?'' &QL; 
Beating the best &QL; 
The Cardinals' first big victory in the Valley of the Sun was one
of their unlikeliest.
</P>
<P>
   They trailed eventual Super Bowl-champion San Francisco, 23-0,
in the third quarter in November 1988.
</P>
<P>
   ``I remember a mass exodus going on in the third quarter,'' said
former Cardinals running back Ron Wolfley, now a talk-show host on
KMVP-AM (860) radio.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just out of total defiance, I was yelling at the crowd,
`You're going to miss the greatest comeback in NFL history.' I'll
be doggone if it didn't happen.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite giving up 17 unanswered points in the third and fourth
quarter, the 49ers still seemed to have the game in hand until
linebacker E.J. Junior stopped quarterback Steve Young inches short
of a first down with 1:27 left.
</P>
<P>
   Quarterback Neil Lomax directed the Cardinals, who had no
timeouts, 66 yards in seven plays, the game-tying score coming on a
9-yard pass to wide receiver Roy Green with three seconds left. Del
Greco's extra point gave the Cardinals a 24-23 win.
</P>
<P>
   ``The place went nuts and (49ers coach) Bill Walsh was just
crushed,'' Wolfley said. &QL; 
The victory left the Cardinals at 6-4. They beat the New York
Giants the next week to move into a tie for first place in the NFC
East, but they never won again that season.
</P>
<P>
   Lomax suffered a career-ending injury and the Cardinals lost
five straight. &QL; 
Holiday heartbreak &QL; 
Coach Buddy Ryan's Cardinals entered the 1994 season finale on
Christmas Eve in Atlanta knowing they needed the Cowboys to beat
the New York Giants for any chance of making the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   The Cardinals had beaten Cincinnati the previous week to go 8-7,
the first time they had been over .500 that late in the season
since 1984.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was so excited,'' said former Cardinals linebacker Garth
Jax, now a member of the team's front office. ``Never before in my
career had I experienced such an opportunity to go to the
playoffs.''
</P>
<P>
   But with about three minutes remaining, the players learned that
the Giants had won, 15-10.
</P>
<P>
   ``I tried not to watch the scoreboard,'' defensive tackle
Bernard Wilson said. ``I wasn't concerned about their game. There
was nothing I could do about somebody else winning or losing. But
late in the fourth quarter, the bad news came through that the
Giants had won.''
</P>
<P>
   All wasn't lost. The Cardinals still had a chance to post the
first winning record in Arizona.
</P>
<P>
   But three times they were inside Atlanta's 10-yard line and
didn't score, including a failed run by Ronald Moore from the
1-yard line on the game's final play. The Cardinals were held to
only two Greg Davis field goals and lost, 10-6.
</P>
<P>
   ``On that last play, Larry Centers was sitting on the
sideline,'' Jax said. ``They put in a guy (Moore) who wasn't the
best in the league, and he got stalemated at the goal line. I don't
know who was the play-caller of the day that day, but we had the
thing in the bag and didn't win.''
</P>
<P>
   Ryan's decision to have Moore, not known for his leaping
ability, to try to dive into the end zone was questioned by several
players and typified a season of offensive frustration.
</P>
<P>
   The day after the game, Ryan informed quarterback Steve
Beuerlein and wide receiver Ricky Proehl that they wouldn't be back
with the team next year. Beuerlein went to Jacksonville in the
expansion draft and Proehl was traded.
</P>
<P>
   ``On the flight home, we waited until Ronnie Jones, our
defensive coordinator, had a couple of `coffees,' and went up to
him to see if we would be part of the team next year,'' Jax said. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
