<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-NOTEBOOK-SCHOENFELD-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LEAF MAKING CARDS' DECISION LOOK GOOD 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVE SCHOENFELD  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   He could have been the Cardinals' headache, the rookie spitball
throwing quarterback who pours beer and makes obscene gestures at
former Washington State classmates.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, the Cardinals traded down one spot in last year's draft
and bypassed picking Ryan Leaf, benched by the San Diego Chargers
today for bad behavior, leaving his career in the balance.
</P>
<P>
   ``Growing up is hard to to do,'' said Bobby Beathard, Chargers
general manager. ``But he doesn't have any choice but to do it. A
whole career could be crumbling if he doesn't wise up and
understand he isn't handling things the right way.''
</P>
<P>
   The Cardinals didn't make the mammoth deal that brought them
rookie defensive end Andre Wadsworth, wide receiver Eric Metcalf,
linebacker Patrick Sapp and San Diego's first-round pick in 1999
because they feared Leaf was a boor. They did it because they
believed in then-rookie quarterback Jake Plummer.
</P>
<P>
   Some NFL officials thought the Cardinals blew it at the time,
questioning them for not taking a ``franchise quarterback.''
</P>
<P>
   Few are doubting the Cardinals now, not after Leaf's latest
night of terror in Pullman, Wash., 10 days ago.
</P>
<P>
   Several newspapers reported that Leaf threw beer on two
students, made obscene gestures at others, was thrown out of two
establishments and banned from a convenience store.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was pretty drunk when he came in,'' Washington State senior
Nicole Sanders said of the Coog Bar. ``I was at the window looking
at him when he was standing outside (after being asked to leave),
and he and his buddies were flipping us off and spitting at the
window. They were saying that we had no money.''
</P>
<P>
   Actually, what Leaf said to a friend was, ``Let's get out of
here. These guys aren't worth it. I can buy and sell all of them.''
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this season, Leaf cursed a TV cameraman and a newspaper
reporter in separate incidents and made an obscene gesture to a
reporter after the reporter said, ``Hello.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a term of endearment,'' Leaf said at the time, adding
that he didn't care ``what people think of me. I want respect from
the people I respect.''
</P>
<P>
   The Chargers have been so concerned about Leaf's behavior, they
talked to Leaf's family, to Washington State Coach Mike Price and
to Leaf's agent, Leigh Steinberg.
</P>
<P>
   Leaf doesn't think he has a problem. He thinks he just has the
type of personality that he doesn't make friends easily.
</P>
<P>
   ``You know that I'm not a (very likable guy),'' Leaf said. ``But
you don't have to be. When you run around and get beat up and beat
people up for a living, I don't think that's a very likable thing.
Not everyone is going to like you.''
</P>
<P>
   Mark Rypien, former Washington State and NFL quarterback, thinks
Leaf needs to take responsibility for his actions. ``He's in
denial,'' Rypien said. ``It's like some of my relatives who are
alcoholics, the hardest thing is getting them to admit `I need
help.' Maybe that's the hardest part for him. I'm in his corner. I
want to be in his corner.
</P>
<P>
   ``He needs someone who is gone through the same thing, and,
brother, I've been through it all 10 times worse. They were just
waiting to get rid of me in Washington two years after going to the
Super Bowl. They said I was the only guy who could overthrow
Noriega.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd like to help, and, maybe Ryan just needs someone to
listen. Whatever, I know this, how he handles the situation will
determine how long he lasts in the NFL.'' &QL; 
Preseason sorely missed &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Hall of Famer Gale Sayers thinks he knows why Bears rookie
Curtis Enis has joined ex-Cardinal Garrison Hearst, Ki-Jana Carter
and Tim Biakabatuka as the fourth running back taken in the top 10
of the draft to suffer a serious knee injury his rookie year.
</P>
<P>
   Enis tore his anterior cruciate ligament last week and will miss
the rest of the season.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really feel it all goes back to missing training camp,''
said Sayers, the former Bears running back. ``So many people say,
`I can play pro football. It's just like college football.' It is
not. Everybody's bigger and stronger and faster. Those linebackers
you ran over in college you can't do it in pro football.'' &QL; 
Hit for a loss &QL;
</P>
<P>
   How much havoc can one penalty cause?
</P>
<P>
   First, Washington's Patrice Alexander, making his first
appearance of the season, was cut after being called for holding 10
yards behind the play, nullifying kickoff returner Brian Mitchell's
touchdown against the Cardinals a week ago.
</P>
<P>
   Then, a Fredericksburg, Va., woman acknowledged she was going to
win a free car if Mitchell returned the opening kickoff for a score
as a the result of a contest sponsored by the Redskins radio
network.
</P>
<P>
   Alexander, by the way, was furious that he was released, feeling
he is a scapegoat. &QL; 
Surprise appearance &QL;
</P>
<P>
   An Indianapolis Colts teammate was so startled that third-string
quarterback Paul Justin was in the game last week against
Jacksonville, he asked Justin, ``What are you doing in here?''
</P>
<P>
   ``I told them I just ran out here and nobody told me to come
in,'' said Justin, the former Arizona State product.
</P>
<P>
   Justin was kidding, but he hadn't played since the preseason
finale on Aug. 28 at Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   He did well. He completed 7 of 10 throws for 107 yards and one
score in his fourth-quarter appearance. &QL; 
Ultimate long shot &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Jay Fiedler, the only healthy quarterback on the Minnesota
Vikings' roster, spent last fall coaching wide receivers at Hofstra
University.
</P>
<P>
   He was the No. 3 quarterback on the Philadelphia Eagles in 1994
and '95, released by Cincinnati in training camp in 1996 and a
member of the Amsterdam Admirals of the World League the following
spring.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been great and a lot of ups and downs. Right now, my
roller coaster is riding up to the top,'' Fiedler said. &QL; 
Short shots &QL; 
Dallas, 0-4 in NFC East road games last year, can complete a 4-0
division sweep by beating the Cardinals today at Sun Devil Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   Since Nov. 2, 1997, Atlanta has the same record as the 49ers at
13-4. The two teams play today for the division lead.
</P>
<P>
   Broncos defensive tackle Keith Traylor, an ex-Chief, thinks
Kansas City Coach Marty Schottenheimer, whose team is on a
four-game losing streak, is in trouble if he loses Monday to
Denver. ``I really think if we go in and beat 'em, then they'll
fold and that'll be the end of Marty,'' Traylor said. &QL; 
Includes information from other media sources. Steve Schoenfeld can
be reached at 602-444-8334 or at steve.schoenfeld(at)pni.com via
e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
