<HEADLINE>
MCALISTER, DOUGLAS SLUG IT OUT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By NORM FRAUENHEIM  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   BERKELEY, Calif. _ It was the heavyweight battle within the
game.
</P>
<P>
   Arizona cornerback  &UR; Chris McAlister versus California receiver
 &UR; Damaene
 &UR; Douglas.
</P>
<P>
   Douglas got three of his six receptions against McAlister. But
McAlister walked away feeling like the winner. And, in the most
important way, he was, by virtue of Arizona's 27-23 victory
Saturday at Cal's Memorial Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   ``I always expect a good receiver to catch a couple,'' said
McAlister, who blocked a punt that set up Arizona's initial TD in
the first quarter. ``I go into any game intending to shut a guy
out. But it doesn't usually happen that way.''
</P>
<P>
   There was clearly a lot of trash-talk between the two throughout
a game marked by personal fouls and a record number of penalties.
</P>
<P>
   ``I expect the talk,'' McAlister said. ``I enjoy it. It keeps me
on my toes. It makes me mentally tough.''
</P>
<P>
   McAlister had evident respect for Douglas, who set a Cal record
of 182 receptions, three shy of the Pac-10 record. But he would not
say that Douglas was the best receiver he has faced. &QL; 
Briefly &QL; 
The combined total for penalty yards was 307, breaking the
California record of 283. ``Both coaches probably wish some plays
could have been done over,'' Arizona coach  &UR; Dick Tomey said.
</P>
<P>
   Arizona defensive back coach  &UR; Duane Akina says he was told by a
Dallas Cowboys scout that McAlister is the best cornerback he's
seen this season.
</P>
<P>
   A reason  &UR; Ortege Jenkins likes to called OJ: A Bay Area
publication listed him as Cortege Junkins. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-15-98 0102EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
