<DOCNO> NYT19981115.0020 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-15 01:03 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1372 &Cx1f; tic-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBC-ARIZONA-CAL-AZR &LR;      11-15 0683
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-ARIZONA-CAL-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ARIZONA DODGES CALIFORNIA JINX 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By NORM FRAUENHEIM  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   BERKELEY, Calif. _ Arizona started playing football at the turn
of the century. The last one.
</P>
<P>
   The Wildcats didn't wear helmets or go 10-1 in those days. They
put on helmets sometime after the horse and buggy gave way to the
charter flight as the mode of transport to road games.
</P>
<P>
   A little bit of everything changed in nearly 100 years.
</P>
<P>
   But the biggest change of all happened Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   The Wildcats beat the millennium and California, 27-23, for
their first 10-1 record ever.
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't easy.
</P>
<P>
   At times, in fact, it was downright ugly as the Wildcats
struggled against a stubborn California defense, a yellow blizzard
of penalty flags and all the other assorted hobgoblins, hangnails
and hoodoos that always seem to await them at the Strawberry Canyon
setting for old Memorial Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   But in the end, Arizona (6-1 in the Pac-10) prevailed in what
could be their best season in this century and the last.
</P>
<P>
   After it was all over, Arizona Coach Dick Tomey was asked to
look ahead. He was asked how he might feel about his surprising
team one day while sitting in a rocking chair, presumably sometime
well into the next century.
</P>
<P>
   ``First off, I don't plan to ever be in a rocking chair,'' said
the characteristically understating Tomey, whose 1993 team also won
10 games but had two losses before it reached that mark. ``I'll
just think about what a tremendous group of kids these are.''
</P>
<P>
   Tremendous might be a little hard to define. Resilient is not.
Above all, that is what defines these Wildcats, who are No. 9 in
the Associated Press poll and still a Rose Bowl possibility.
</P>
<P>
   Cal repeatedly threatened in the late moments. It was as if the
Bears were setting the stage for an encore of their
quadruple-overtime victory on this same field in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wasn't going to celebrate,'' said Arizona quarterback Keith
Smith, who played throughout the second half as Tomey abandoned the
usual combination with Ortege Jenkins. ``There would be no
celebration until the last second came off that clock.''
</P>
<P>
   As it turned out, Smith's caution was wise.
</P>
<P>
   But Arizona took control by scoring early in the third quarter
and again in the fourth.
</P>
<P>
   In the fourth, it was running back Trung Canidate at his
explosive best. He raced for a 54-yard touchdown, his fourth of 45
yards or more over the last three games.
</P>
<P>
   In the third, Arizona's touchdown was set up by a penalty, one
en route to a dubious Cal record of 154 yards. On fourth down and
inches to a first at the Cal 22, Bears linebacker Albert Dorsey
jumped offside.
</P>
<P>
   On the next play, Smith tossed a 17-yard strike to Brad Brennan,
who was alone in a corner of the end zone. On the subsequent
conversion, Smith ran to the spot that Brennan had just vacated.
</P>
<P>
   The two-point conversion was important. It could been pivotal,
because Cal (5-5, 3-4 Pac 10) threatened.
</P>
<P>
   Early in the fourth, the Bears countered Canidate's touchdown
with with a 25-yard scoring strike from Justin Vedder to Marcus
Fields.
</P>
<P>
   Then receiver Damaene Douglas interrupted his trash-talking
exchange with Chris McAlister by taking a handoff on an apparent
reverse. He stopped, faked a pass and ran nine yards before leaping
into the end zone. But Ignacio Brache's kick for the extra point
was wide. The Wildcats held a four-point advantage with 3:16 left.
</P>
<P>
   Arizona emerged with a 12-10 lead from a first half that was
marked by stubborn defensive stands and 13 penalties.
</P>
<P>
   Wildcats place-kicker Mark McDonald provided the narrow
advantage with a career best 45-yard field goal during the half's
final 10 seconds. The beautiful kick came about 17 seconds after
Cal led, 10-9, on a 41-yard field goal by Brache.
</P>
<P>
   Defenders set up Arizona's only touchdown before halftime. Chris
McAlister blocked a punt that was picked up by A.J. Brown and
carried to the Cal 12. Three plays later, Arizona scored on an
8-yard pass from Smith to Jeremy McDaniel. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-15-98 0103EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
