<SLUG> BC-FBN-CARDS-BICKLEY-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TIME FOR THE LINE TO BE OFFENSIVE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By DAN BICKLEY  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   TEMPE, ARIZ. - The criticism has been endless.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've heard it until we're sick of it,'' guard Chris Dishman
said.
</P>
<P>
   They've been beaten up and beaten down.
</P>
<P>
   ``When an offense doesn't succeed, we're always the ones who get
a tongue-lashing,'' center Aaron Graham said.
</P>
<P>
   They've been targeted as the weak link, the unit most qualified
to sabotage the season.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think anything will put that to rest,'' tackle Lomas
Brown said. ``We're going to be like that for the rest of the
season.''
</P>
<P>
   Unless they stand up and fight. Unless they've swallowed enough
insults and are good enough to prove otherwise. And if the
Cardinals' offensive line wants to change the running perception,
this is a good time to start.
</P>
<P>
   Big games are always won here, in the trenches. And now they
have 60 minutes against the Cowboys. Sixty minutes from first place
and a large helping of redemption.
</P>
<P>
   Can they handle it? &QL; 
Message from Madden &QL;
</P>
<P>
   On Friday, as his bus idled in the parking lot of the Cardinals'
training facility, John Madden was asked a simple question. As a
coach, did he ever have a young, overmatched offensive line rise to
the occasion and win a game on emotion?
</P>
<P>
   ``No,'' Madden said.
</P>
<P>
   Madden listed plenty of reasons why it's nearly impossible. The
advent of zone blocking schemes, necessary to handle stunts,
blitzes and other forms of trickery, de-emphasize the one-on-one
battles. It tips the scales of confrontation back to things like
talent and intelligence. And more to the point . . .
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to get your offensive line set,'' Madden said. ``And
I would say they don't have their offensive line set.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, the offensive line is in flux. Lomas Brown is 35 years
old, in the last year of his contract. Lester Holmes is making too
much money to get benched for performance. The interior of the line
has been guilty of massive breakdowns. And they're relying on a
rehabilitating rookie _ Anthony Clement _ to make an impact before
the season is over.
</P>
<P>
   Football is like a pyramid. Any weaknesses in the line, on
either side of the ball, and the foundation suffers. The
repercussions are felt all the way to the top, and all over the
field.
</P>
<P>
   When the Cardinals have been able to run the football _ as they
did against the Eagles and the Redskins _ they look like a good
football team. When they can't, the offense has looked dreadful. &QL; 
What will it be? &QL;
</P>
<P>
   At some point, they must end the mystery. Either they can or
they can't.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the offensive line has a chance here,'' Madden said.
``This isn't a dominating front seven they're facing, other than
one guy, and that's Leon Lett.''
</P>
<P>
   So this isn't an impossible challenge. Merely a defining moment,
and a moment of truth.
</P>
<P>
   Is this a young offensive line getting better? Or a bad
offensive line in need of overhaul? One that will make things
difficult for the rest of the season?
</P>
<P>
   Sixty minutes to make their case.
</P>
<P>
   ``We watched film from the first game, and they didn't manhandle
us,'' Graham said. ``We self-destructed. A penalty here, an
interception there. Mistake after mistake. But I think you're going
to see great strides this week.
</P>
<P>
   ``We know we're capable of running the football on these guys.
It's not about them. It's not about the Dallas Cowboys. It's about
the Arizona Cardinals.''
</P>
<P>
   Exactly. And the offensive line knows it is under scrutiny. With
two first-round picks in 1999, they know the front office is
searching the college ranks for replacements. They know a few jobs
are on the line. &QL; 
Playoffs in picture
</P>
<P>
   They also know it's not too late. Ten weeks into the season,
despite heavy doses of ineptitude, the Cardinals are flirting with
the playoffs and the preposterous notion of a playoff game at Sun
Devil Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   A good offensive line can make the difference, and clearly, no
area of this football team has more room for improvement.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can hold our own against this football team,'' Dishman
said.
</P>
<P>
   Good. Now prove it.
</P>
<P>
   Stand up and fight. Run the Cowboys _ and the perception _ right
out of town.
</P>
<P>
   If you can handle it. &QL; 
Dan Bickley can be reached at 602-444-8253 or at
dan.bickley(at)pni.com. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-15-98 0106EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
