<SLUG> BC-FBN-COWBOYS-DEFENSE-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANOTHER `BIG D': DEFENSE  
 COWBOYS' SYSTEM REMAINS CONSISTENT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By TIM TYERS  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Mention the Dallas Cowboys, and thoughts of the Aikmans, Smiths
and Irvins pop into the minds of fans. Seldom do thoughts stray to
the other side of the ball _ save Deion Sanders, of course.
</P>
<P>
   It's the side that usually decides the outcome for the Cowboys.
</P>
<P>
   Think not? Since wheeling-dealing Jerry Jones purchased the team
in 1989, the Cowboys have had three coaches, Jimmy Johnson, Barry
Switzer and now Chan Gailey.
</P>
<P>
   Save for Johnson's first few seasons, when the Cowboys' talent
level was abysmal, the defense has remained rock solid throughout
the rapid turnover of head coaches and the departure of
coordinators Butch Davis and Dave Wannstedt.
</P>
<P>
   Even last year, when the Cowboys finished 6-10 with an offense
torn asunder by injury, free-agent defections, suspensions and
arrests, the Cowboys ranked second in the NFL in defense, allowing
282.3 yards per game while leading the league in pass defense at
156.2 yards per game.
</P>
<P>
   This, mind you, despite losing Leon Lett, Sanders, Darren
Woodson and Chad Hennings for a total of 23 games to injury.
</P>
<P>
   In 1996, the Dallas defense ranked No. 1 in the NFL for 11 of 16
weeks before finishing at third. In 1995, it ranked third, allowing
just 32 touchdowns en route to a Super Bowl win. In 1994, it was
No. 1. In 1993, another Super Bowl. Only Jones' mouth has worked
harder than the Dallas ``D.''
</P>
<P>
   The defense that the Cardinals will test today for a share of
the NFC East lead tops the league with an average yield of 13.4
points per game, and has allowed the second fewest touchdowns, 14,
in the NFL.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of it has to do with Dave Campo,'' said strong safety
Woodson, a former Arizona State star. ``He has been around here
since it all started and was here in 1992 when I got here.
</P>
<P>
   ``Coaches have come and gone, but they've stayed with the same
system. We have faith in what the system is doing and that it will
allow us to make plays.''
</P>
<P>
   Campo, who has been the Cowboys defensive coordinator since
1995, came to Dallas with Johnson from the University of Miami in
1989 as the secondary coach. He has been much more than the
caretaker, although to hear him speak might cause doubts.
</P>
<P>
   ``It all goes back to the way our program was set up
initially,'' Campo said. ``We took a hard-nosed approach with the
players from the beginning of not accepting anything less in
practice than the way we're going to play on Sunday. Maintaining it
isn't as difficult as it might be if you didn't have some character
guys and much of a tradition.''
</P>
<P>
   Campo breaks down the long-standing consistency into two
factors.
</P>
<P>
   ``First, we took the approach of there being no excuses,'' Campo
said. ``How you come across as a staff makes the players take on
that personality. We've always felt whatever cards we're dealt,
were dealt. When people ask how are you going to replace this guy,
or that guy, we don't talk about it.
</P>
<P>
   ``The next guy in line has to do it, and they kind of get a
succession mentality from it. We've lost a lot of players through
free agency, injury, retirement or whatever. But our guys have
accepted that tough-minded approach.''
</P>
<P>
   Second, and perhaps the best reason, according to Campo, is the
knowledge that the race usually goes to the swiftest.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've always had speed here,'' Campo said. ``Speed overcomes a
lot of mistakes and bad situations. We can run. Always have since
Jimmy came in. That is my mentality, and it was Butch Davis' and
Dave Wannstedt's before me.''
</P>
<P>
   Hennings, a seven-year veteran like Woodson, said common sense
was exercised throughout all the coaching turnovers.
</P>
<P>
   ``If it ain't broke, don't fix it,'' he said. ``We've pretty
much been in the top 10, if not the top five, all along. It starts
with the coaching staff and goes down to the personnel. To play
this defense, you need guys who have speed to fly around to the
ball and get after the passer.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not necessarily a defense of big-name stars. But it's
one that plays pretty good technique and gets after it.''
</P>
<P>
   Woodson added that competition between the players themselves
has been a catalyst.
</P>
<P>
   ``We do have great speed,'' Woodson said. ``We're not the
biggest guys in this league, but we're fast, and it's instilled in
us to get to the ball. When you have our type of speed, it's easier
to make plays and harder for other teams to make big plays.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-15-98 0106EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
