r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-PLUMMER-COMEBACKS     11-15 0553
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-PLUMMER-COMEBACKS-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PLUMMER CARVING COMEBACK NICHE  
 QB HAS RALLIED CARDS TO VICTORY IN 6 OF HIS 19 GAMES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB YOUNG  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   TEMPE, ARIZ. - Forget those comparisons between Jake Plummer and
Joe Montana. They're ridiculous.
</P>
<P>
   Heck, Joe just doesn't measure up.
</P>
<P>
   Neither do John Elway, Dan Marino or Jim Kelly, for that matter.
</P>
<P>
   OK, it's early. But in the first 19 games of Plummer's career he
has produced six fourth-quarter come-from-behind or ``game-saving''
victories.
</P>
<P>
   Game-saving is defined as a victory from a fourth-quarter tie.
Come-from-behind is, of course, a fourth-quarter rally to win.
Plummer also engineered a fourth-quarter comeback only to have the
Cardinals lose in overtime.
</P>
<P>
   Those other great comeback quarterbacks didn't match the magic
of Jake ``the Unrattled Snake'' early in their careers.
</P>
<P>
   Elway, who now has 46 comeback or game-saving victories, had
just one in his first 19 games and four in his first two seasons.
</P>
<P>
   Marino, who came into this season with 33, had two in his first
two seasons in a total of 25 games.
</P>
<P>
   In his first two seasons, including 32 games but only eight
starts, Montana generated only one comeback victory.
</P>
<P>
   And Kelly, who had 24 comebacks, had just two in his first two
NFL seasons while starting 28 games.
</P>
<P>
   ``You'd like to put teams away,'' Plummer said. ``But it keeps
it exciting. My mom and my family keep telling me it's getting
tough on them. My mom says she can't take it. It's too hard on her
heart.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I love it. It's do-or-die. You either succeed or lose
right there. There's nothing more exciting, but you don't want to
have to do it all the time.''
</P>
<P>
   It's that very knack for producing in the most pressure-packed
situations, which Plummer often exhibited at Arizona State, that
made him so attractive to the Cardinals and local fans.
</P>
<P>
   ``To win games, you've got to play strong defense, run the ball,
block and tackle, et cetera,'' said Cardinals Coach Vince Tobin.
``But there comes a point in any year when a game has been lost no
matter what you've done.
</P>
<P>
   ``A really great quarterback finds a way to win ballgames for
you after they've been lost. In the final analysis, that's how you
judge a quarterback.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you've done everything you can and you're still behind,
he can move you down the field and find a way to get you the points
to win the ballgame. That's something Jake has done for us.''
</P>
<P>
   Such comebacks require confidence from the quarterback, but also
confidence in him.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's a big part of it,'' Tobin said. ``But he still has to
do it. It takes a great presence of mind. In those two-minute
situations, everything speeds up. Some can see things clearly in
those chaotic situations and make plays when everything is falling
apart around them. Others see nothing.''
</P>
<P>
   Plummer has pulled off four comebacks this season alone,
including back-to-back games against the Eagles and the Rams and
back-to-back rallies again against Detroit and, last week, the
Washington Redskins.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like having that reputation because the guys are going to
believe in me,'' Plummer said. ``I think it helps that they know I
can get it done when the game is on the line if we do things
right.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-15-98 0107EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
