r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKC-PEPPERDINE-LADN     11-15 0462
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-PEPPERDINE-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PEPPERDINE RACES AWAY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JIM INGHRAM  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   MALIBU _ It took about, oh, two minutes for Pepperdine to assert
its dominance over UC Santa Barbara en route to a 71-51
season-opening thrashing of the Gauchos.
</P>
<P>
   Two minutes was how long it took the Waves (1-0) to build a 10-0
lead. And despite some offensive lulls, including a 8:26 stretch
when they scored just one point, the Waves were able to keep a
comfortable distance between themselves and the Gauchos (0-1)
before 1,915 at Firestone Fieldhouse on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really liked our energy at the beginning of the game and I
thought we defended well,'' Pepperdine coach Lorenzo Romar said.
``Our ability to defend is what helped us pull away.''
</P>
<P>
   Pepperdine suffered through some scoring droughts, including the
aforementioned dry spell in the first half and a 4:02 stretch in
the second half when they failed to score. But UC Santa Barbara
could never take advantage.
</P>
<P>
   The Gauchos shot 36 percent for the game and in several
instances failed to get a shot off, because of a shot clock
violation or some other miscue.
</P>
<P>
   B.J. Bunton led the Gauchos, who played their first game under
former Pepperdine assistant Bob Williams, with 16 points. Erick
Ashe added 11 points and former Pepperdine forward Josh Merrill had
10 points and 10 rebounds.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm glad we played them tonight instead of a month from now,''
Romar said. ``They'll be a much better after a few games, because
Bob Williams is a very good coach.''
</P>
<P>
   The same thing could be said about the Waves.
</P>
<P>
   Although Pepperdine cruised, the team still has work to do
fitting the newcomers in with the returning players.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm happy that we won,'' Romar said, ``because you never know
what to expect in openers. You can only speculate until you start
playing. For lack of a better term, were still finding ourselves.
We have a lot of new faces that were trying to mesh together.''
</P>
<P>
   A well-known face, Jelani Gardner, led the Waves with 19 points.
The senior also had a team-high six assists.
</P>
<P>
   David Lalazarian, a transfer from Notre Dame and of the team's
seven newcomers, had an impressive debut finishing with 14 points.
</P>
<P>
   Lalazarian, a redshirt-sophomore from Tustin, hit two 3-point
baskets in the first two minutes to help the Waves gain their early
lead.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was pretty exciting finally getting out there,'' Lalazarian
said. ``I though I played OK. I had some open looks that I should
have put down, but I lost a little rhythm after the first half.''
</P>
<P>
   Reserve Marc McDowell had 12 points and seven rebounds, while
Kelvin Gibbs and Louisiana State transfer, Nick Sheppard led with
eight rebounds each.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
