<SLUG> BC-HKN-KINGS-NOTES-LBPT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JOKE'S NOT ON JOKINEN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ROGER PHILLIPS  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; Long Beach Press-Telegram &LR;  &QC;
</P>
<P>
   INGLEWOOD _ For Olli Jokinen, disappointment came after the
morning skate Saturday, when he learned he wouldn't be playing that
night against the Carolina Hurricanes.
</P>
<P>
   Jokinen, Craig Johnson and Matt Johnson were the victims of
coach Larry Robinson's attempt to shake his team out of its slump
with lineup changes.
</P>
<P>
   It's been a week of ups and downs for Jokinen, who on Tuesday
scored his first NHL goal in a 5-4 overtime loss at Calgary, but
was a healthy scratch just four days later.
</P>
<P>
   ``Of course, I want to play,'' said Jokinen, who has four points
in five games. ``I don't want to sit in the press box and eat hot
dogs. I want to play.''
</P>
<P>
   Before the game, Matt Johnson sat in the press room and dined,
though he didn't have any hot dogs, which weren't on the menu. He
seemed at least as frustrated as Jokinen.
</P>
<P>
   ``They say they want big, young guys who can hit,'' said the
22-year-old Johnson, a physical player who is 6-foot-5, 232 pounds.
</P>
<P>
   Entering the lineup were Ray Ferraro, Nathan LaFayette and Sandy
Moger, who had been sidelined about 10 days with a strained back.
Moger is not known for his offensive skills, but began the game on
a line with Vladimir Tsyplakov and top center Jozef Stumpel, with
whom he played at times when the two were members of the Boston
Bruins.
</P>
<P>
   Of playing with Stumpel, Moger said: ``You think he's not going
to be able to get you the puck, and then all of a sudden, it's on
your stick. You've got to be ready.''
</P>
<P>
   Rosa out: Team physician Dr. Ronald Kvitne said Pavel Rosa, one
of the Kings' top prospects, will undergo an MRI this week to try
to determine the cause of headaches and light-headedness that have
sidelined the winger, who had been playing for the Long Beach Ice
Dogs.
</P>
<P>
   Rosa, 21, missed almost all of last season after suffering a
concussion during the preseason.
</P>
<P>
   Kvitne said an inner-ear condition related to the concussion is
believed to be at the root of Rosa's problems, as it was last
season. He saw an ear specialist several days ago, and will do so
again this week.
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, Rosa will not be permitted to skate, but how he
responds to riding an exercise bike and lifting weights will be
monitored.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to be cautious,'' Kvitne said. ``His whole career is
in front of him. ... We're not sure when we'll let him play
again.''
</P>
<P>
   Loose pucks: The Kings activated defenseman Mark Visheau, who
had been sidelined with injuries, and he replaced Jan Nemecek in
the lineup.... New York Rangers general manager Neil Smith was in
attendance and ate dinner before the game with Kings GM Dave
Taylor. The Rangers don't play again until Wednesday, when they
visit the Mighty Ducks, and Thursday, when they visit the Kings....
The Kings have re-assigned center Jason Morgan from the Ice Dogs to
Springfield of the AHL.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
