<SLUG> BC-BOX-JONES-GRANT-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JONES BATTERS GRANT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RON BORGES  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MASHANTUCKET, Conn. _ It was over in the first round.
</P>
<P>
   Technically, Roy Jones Jr. needed 10 rounds to beat back the
challenge of Otis Grant Saturday night at Foxwoods, but, after
three minutes, the issue was settled. By then the World Boxing
Organization middleweight champion had been drilled in the face
repeatedly by fists he did not see and was powerless to stop. After
that it was simply target practice for the light heavyweight
champion, as he battered Grant's face and body until he could take
no more.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew he couldn't take my body shots,'' Jones said. ``I'm the
man, I'm the best. I do whatever I have to do to win.''
</P>
<P>
   That was pretty much whatever Jones (38-1) wanted, when he
wanted. The game special education teacher from Montreal had the
word ``MAGIC'' stitched across the front of his trunks and that is
what he needed Saturday night. He needed something that could make
Jones disappear. Instead, Jones made him disappear, although not
soon enough to prevent him from taking a terrible pounding.
</P>
<P>
   At the end of the fourth round, Jones rocked Grant and after the
bell sounded the challenger looked over at him as he walked back to
his corner like a man eying an alley he didn't want to walk down.
By then Grant had an ugly welt under his left eye and no chance of
winning, but he kept coming, realizing with every step he was going
into a neighborhood where bad things would happen.
</P>
<P>
   They finally did in the sixth round, when Jones dropped Grant
with a short right uppercut that landed so solidly he collapsed on
his back, his feet rolling up over his head. Grant got up at the
count of nine, but his face was a mask of discomfort.
</P>
<P>
   Although his courage was admirable, Grant was merely a canvas on
which Jones was painting a horrible face until he finally ended the
night with a leaping right hand that dropped Grant at 1:08 of the
10th round. Again Grant's feet rolled over his head and, when he
got up, he was walking in dark shadows.
</P>
<P>
   Grant's trainer, Russ Anber, realized it immediately and tried
to throw in the towel, but the corner cannot end a fight in
Connecticut, so referee Arthur Mercante Jr. threw it back out. That
didn't dissuade Anber, who leaped into the ring as Grant tottered
backward and Jones looked on until Mercante was convinced Anber's
suggestion was a wise one.
</P>
<P>
   ``I been with this guy since I was 13 and he wasn't going to let
me get hurt,'' Grant (31-2-1) said, like a young man who knew it's
nice to have a friend in your corner.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier in the evening, International Boxing Federation
lightweight champion James Leija learned too much Sugar is bad for
your health.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sugar'' Shane Mosley made that obvious by pounding the former
World Boxing Council super featherweight champion for nine rounds
before Leija's corner decided their man had had enough as well and
surrendered with their fighter slumped in his corner. By then
Mosley had dropped Leija three times, cut his left eyebrow, and
dominated him so completely that when a point was taken away from
him in one round the champion still did enough to win it.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-15-98 0145EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
