<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-BRUINS-STARS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRUINS FALL TO EARTH 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By NANCY L. MARRAPESE  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ The barometer by which teams measure their success is
how well they fare against the cream of the crop. Play well against
the best and it usually means you're on the right track. Get blown
out and, well, it may mean back to the drawing board.
</P>
<P>
   The Bruins had just such a test Saturday night at the
FleetCenter as they hosted the Western Conference-leading Dallas
Stars, who are widely believed to be the favorite to win the 1999
Stanley Cup.
</P>
<P>
   They lost, 3-1, which ended their unbeaten streak at four games
(2-0-2). Despite playing the Stars even for nearly the entire game
(for 55 minutes 34 seconds the Bruins were either ahead or tied),
the bottom line was the club's old bugaboo _ a lack of finish _
proved the difference.
</P>
<P>
   ``(Against the Rangers Friday) that was a game we could've
had,'' said Bruins captain Ray Bourque. ``And tonight was the same
thing. We get one point out of four. I don't think that's good. We
can play better and we will.''
</P>
<P>
   Boston managed a short-lived lead a little more than two minutes
into the game. Steve Heinze took out pesky forward Mike Keane along
the left-wing boards. The puck was freed up for Anson Carter in the
left circle and he dished it to Joe Thornton. Thornton didn't get
much on his shot from the inside edge of the left circle but it was
enough to trickle through goalie Roman Turek's legs, giving the
Bruins a 1-0 edge at 2:23.
</P>
<P>
   That advantage lasted 1:57 until Stars sniper Brett Hull took
advantage of a fortuitous bounce. Hull navigated his way through
the left circle, maneuvering past big Bruins defenseman Hal Gill.
He lost the puck, Bourque slid across, hit goalie Byron Dafoe and
knocked the puck out, where it caromed off Bruins center Jason
Allison's skate and into the net at 4:20.
</P>
<P>
   ``The rebound came at me and I didn't want it to go by because
there were trailers coming and it would've been an empty net, so I
turned my foot at the last second to try to contain it and it
bounced off me,'' said Allison.
</P>
<P>
   Bourque was unhappy with that particular play.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know what I was doing,'' he said. ``I came back and
kind of just slid and thought I was going to knock the puck into
the corner and I'm not sure exactly what happened. I guess I
knocked it toward Ally and it hit his skate and came back and went
in. There was no reason to do that.''
</P>
<P>
   Heinze had a great chance at 17:16 of the second when Carter
grabbed an errant Stars drop pass. He relayed it to Heinze, skated
through the left circle, cut right to the net, and tried to squeeze
a backhand shot past Turek at the left post. The goalie stopped it
with his left pad, keeping it in front just shy of the goal line.
Heinze, who had four shots on net, was frustrated.
</P>
<P>
   ``I put my couple chances home and we're all smiling,'' he said
ruefully. ``It's a different outcome. Personally, I should have put
a couple of pucks home.''
</P>
<P>
   Hull tallied the winner on a remarkable play that started with a
lucky bounce. Bourque tried to clear the puck out of the Boston
zone at the blue line near the left boards but the puck bounced off
referee Richard Trottier and right to center Mike Modano. Modano
sent a lead pass to Hull down the right side and Hull skated the
puck toward the right goal line. When Dafoe looked to be in
control, Hull fired a high shot from a nearly impossible angle that
hit the goalie's mask and went in at 15:34. Forward Jere Lehtinen,
set up by Hull, closed it out with an empty-net goal with 33.1
seconds remaining.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think I could've pushed him more to the goal line,''
said Dafoe, incredulous that the puck found its way into the net.
``I thought he was pretty much shut off. He just tipped it off the
tip of my head. Maybe if I'd had a bigger head, I would've stopped
him. I was very surprised it went in. He's a goal scorer, there's
no question about it. You give him an inch, he'll take it. That was
kind of a devastating way to lose a game.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
