<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-STARS-HULL-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HULL A CHIP OFF OLD BLOCK 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOHN VELLANTE  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Brett Hull joined a very exclusive group Saturday night
with his two goals and one assist against the Bruins in a 3-1
Dallas win at the FleetCenter.
</P>
<P>
   He joined guys named Wayne Gretzky and Gordie Howe, Marcel
Dionne and Mario Lemieux, Johnny Bucyk and Phil Esposito.
</P>
<P>
   And, even more important, he joined a guy named Bobby Hull, his
NHL Hall of Fame father.
</P>
<P>
   Hull's three points were the 998th, 999th, and 1,000th of his
career, just enough to join his father, making them the only
father-son combination in NHL history to each reach 1,000 points.
</P>
<P>
   Bobby Hull finished a 1,063-game career with Chicago, Winnipeg,
and Hartford with 610 goals and 560 assists for 1,170 points. Brett
now has 560 goals and 440 assists in 815 games played over 12
seasons with Calgary, St. Louis, and Dallas.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a weird feeling,'' said Hull. ``You start out in this
league just hoping you get a chance to make it and play and to be
able to say I was an NHLer and then all of a sudden the success
comes.
</P>
<P>
   ``You know I just did an interview with Johnny Bucyk and now I
can say that my name can be put alongside some people like that.
It's a tremendous honor.''
</P>
<P>
   Hull's first goal, in the first period, may have been among the
easiest of any of his previous goals or assists. He was the last
player to touch the puck before it glanced off Jason Allison's
skate and past Bruins goalie Byron Dafoe.
</P>
<P>
   He worked for the second goal. He picked up a loose puck at the
blue line, skated far to the left of Dafoe, and then, from an
almost impossible angle behind the net, put the puck behind Dafoe.
Dafoe said the puck glanced off his mask.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was just one of those plays,'' said Hull. ``Unfortunately
for the Bruins, they're just clearing the puck and I think it hits
the referee and goes right to Mike (Modano) and he sees me. I think
(Dafoe) has to believe I'm going to shoot it from there. He forced
me wide and I got lucky. It's a good thing I'm not a lefthanded
shot.''
</P>
<P>
   Point No. 1,000 came with Dafoe on the bench for an extra skater
and the Bruins pressing for the tying goal.
</P>
<P>
   Hull blasted a shot from just inside the blue line and the puck
hit the post and went behind the net. He went in after it and
centered it to Jere Lehtinen, who potted the empty-netter with 34
seconds left.
</P>
<P>
   Hull, who signed this past summer with the Stars as a free
agent, said it's been a struggle for him to get going in his new
surroundings. He went into Saturday night's game with just four
goals.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've had so many great chances to score and the puck hasn't
been going in,'' he said. ``When I was credited with that first
goal, I thought to myself maybe something like that's exactly what
I need to break this little hex, or whatever it is, that I'm under.
It's been an emotional change.''
</P>
<P>
   Hull said when he broke into the NHL he never dreamed of
challenging his father's scoring marks.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think 1,000 points is something you really think
about,'' he said. ``You might think of 4 or 500, and what that
might be like, but 1,000? I don't think so.
</P>
<P>
   ``To be honest, the only thing I dream about is the Stanley Cup.
Games like this and marks like this are nice, but winning the
Stanley Cup is what it's all about.''
</P>
</TEXT>
