<HEADLINE>
KANSAS STATE ENDS NEBRASKA HEX 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARK BLAUDSCHUN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MANHATTAN, Kan. _ Bill Snyder made a concession Saturday night.
He was happy, which for the emotionally-challenged (at least in
public) Kansas State coach was a major concession.
</P>
<P>
   For the thousands of Kansas State fans who stormed Wagner Field
Saturday afternoon, happy couldn't begin to describe the feeling
that accompanied the posting of a final score that some people
around here thought they'd never live to see.
</P>
<P>
   Nebraska 30, Kansas State 40.
</P>
<P>
   What was just one more pit stop in a journey that Snyder has
penciled into his day planner as not ending until Jan. 4 in the
national championship game in the Fiesta Bowl was a victory for the
ages for long-suffering Wildcat fans.
</P>
<P>
   For the first time in 30 years, Kansas State beat Nebraska. For
the first time since 1959, Kansas State fans celebrated a home win
over the Huskers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm happy, I assure you that,'' said Snyder, who stuck to his
plan of seclusion for some of his players by making sure no media
members could chronicle the reaction of victorious quarterback
Michael Bishop. ``I feel very good about this win.''
</P>
<P>
   But then again, there wasn't much Bishop could say that could
top his effort Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   The 6-foot-1-inch senior who has been muzzled by Snyder since
October _ except for an ESPN dispensation this past week _ overcame
lots of things in leading Kansas State to its 10th straight
victory.
</P>
<P>
   He survived a first half in which he ran for two touchdowns,
fumbled the ball away three times, and was so emotionally revved up
that even Snyder had to gently wave him away after he had fumbled
away a scoring opportunity at the Nebraska 1.
</P>
<P>
   ``Michael always fits into our plans each game,'' said Snyder,
who watched Bishop recover in the second half to throw two
touchdown passes to wide receiver Darnell McDonald (12 catches, 183
yards), including the winner, an 11-yard score with 5:25 left that
turned a 30-27 Nebraska lead into a 34-30 Wildcat edge that was
expanded in the final seconds when linebacker Jeff Kelly rumbled 23
yards into the end zone off a Nebraska fumble.
</P>
<P>
   If Kansas State was going to take control of the Big 12 _ the
Wildcats clinched the Northern Division spot in the championship
game Dec. 5 in St. Louis _ it was not going to come easily.
</P>
<P>
   The Huskers (8-3), led by freshman quarterback Eric Crouch, took
the opening kickoff and went 80 yards and scored, putting Kansas
State, which has feasted on secondary opponents all season, in the
rare position of trailing.
</P>
<P>
   By the second quarter, Nebraska had a 17-7 lead and some of the
faithful who had gone through two generations of waiting to see
Nebraska lose here must have been wondering what kind of magic it
would take.
</P>
<P>
   Ultimately, it was Bishop. Whether it was running the ball or
throwing it, Bishop had solutions for Nebraska's defensive puzzles.
</P>
<P>
   ``He made the plays when he had to make them,'' said Nebraska
coach Frank Solich, who watched Bishop take apart his secondary and
run like a tailback all afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   In 30 minutes of back-and-fourth second-half action, Kansas
State and Nebraska turned this into a heavyweight fight.
</P>
<P>
   Kansas State seemed to pick up the tempo on defense after
intermission, limiting the Huskers to 5 yards on their first nine
plays. Aided by that and Bishop's play, Kansas State took a 24-17
lead with 5:03 remaining in the third quarter and that looked like
it might be good enough, considering Nebraska's problems on
offense.
</P>
<P>
   No problem. The Huskers came up with a defensive game-turner of
their own as cornerback Ralph Brown went 74 yards for a touchdown
off a fumble by backup Wildcats running back Frank Murphy.
</P>
<P>
   Suddenly it was 24-24 and the game had a
last-team-to-touch-the-ball-will-win feel.
</P>
<P>
   More give and take. A 21-yard field goal by Kansas State's
Martin Gramatica. A 9-yard touchdown pass from Crouch to tight end
Sheldon Jackson. The TD pass from Bishop to McDonald.
</P>
<P>
   With five minutes left, Nebraska had one last good chance to
spoil another Kansas State fall, winter, spring, and summer. Down
to their last play, on fourth and 8 from his 32, Crouch went back
one last time and was sacked by the Wildcats' Travis Ochs.
</P>
<P>
   Replays showed it was more like a mugging as Ochs pulled down
Crouch by his face mask.
</P>
<P>
   ``I got face-masked,'' said Crouch. ``I thought it was a
penalty.''
</P>
<P>
   So did referee John Lewis, who put his hand in his back pocket
for an instant, but never pulled out the yellow flag.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't see a flag,'' said Ochs, with a smile on his face.
``So I went on my merry way.''
</P>
<P>
   So did the Wildcats, although they had to hold their celebration
dance for a few breathless seconds following the final touchdown as
fans kept charging onto the field before the clock had expired.
</P>
<P>
   No matter.
</P>
<P>
   The Wildcats and their fans had waited 30 years, a few extra
minutes weren't going to make a bit of difference.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
