<HEADLINE>
MARQUETTE MAULS BC 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOE BURRIS  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ To give an example of how awful the game was, and how
much partisan fans clamored for something, anything, to get excited
about, consider this: With 5:12 remaining in Saturday night's
Boston College-Marquette game, BC guard Willie Deane stole the ball
in the backcourt and scored on a breakaway dunk that sent the crowd
into a raucous, high-fiving frenzy.
</P>
<P>
   It also cut BC's deficit to 25 points.
</P>
<P>
   This promises to be a very long season for Boston College
basketball. After one game, it's safe to draw that conclusion,
because Marquette is marginal at best yet it handed BC a 70-49
home-opening shellacking despite turning the ball over 19 times in
the second half and playing with as much rhythm and fluidity as
traffic on the Southeast Expressway.
</P>
<P>
   Marquette snapped BC's 25-game Conte Forum winning streak in
non-conference contests, dating to a 75-58 loss to Providence in
the quarterfinals of the 1993 National Invitation Tournament. It
also snapped BC's 24-game season-opening win streak.
</P>
<P>
   You knew those marks were in jeopardy almost midway through the
first half. BC, a team with seven newcomers and a starting point
guard (junior Dwyane Pina) who began his career as a walk-on,
converted on 5 of 17 shots from the floor over the first eight
minutes of the game.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, many of Marquette's attempts were uncontested, as on
the Golden Eagles' first possession, when forward John Polonowski's
top-of-the-key attempt caromed off the left side of the backboard.
</P>
<P>
   At the time, BC was fortunate to trail, 12-11, but Marquette,
which hit 4 of 14 shots from the floor over the first eight
minutes, found its range and outscored BC, 29-13, the remainder of
the half for a 41-24 advantage at the break.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is an indication what can happen on some nights for us,''
said second-year BC coach Al Skinner, whose team finished shooting
28 percent from the floor and was outrebounded, 46-33. ``Part of
our problem was we got impatient on offense as frustration set in
and I think we kind of bailed out.''
</P>
<P>
   BC outscored Marquette, 8-4, to start the second half to pull to
45-32 with 15:42 left. But BC had several self-inflicted wounds
that kept it from making a serious rally.
</P>
<P>
   The Eagles would go the next four minutes without scoring.
Marquette added an occasional basket or free throw, and its
horrible second-half performance went virtually unnoticed. With
10:54 remaining, Kenny Walls scored to give Marquette a 50-34
advantage.
</P>
<P>
   With eight minutes left, Mike Bargen drained a 3-point basket to
give the Golden Eagles a 57-36 advantage. Marquette's final trey of
the contest, by Jarrod Lovett with 6:15 left, gave the Golden
Eagles their biggest lead of the game, 66-36. By then, some of the
BC fans had gone from criticizing officials and Marquette players
to heckling their team.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was obviously two very young teams on the floor,'' said
Marquette coach Mike Deane.
</P>
<P>
   ``If this was a senior- or junior-oriented group, I would be
pulling out what few hairs I have left,'' said Skinner, who went
through a similar beginning at the University of Rhode Island.
</P>
<P>
   ``Guys like Tyson Wheeler and Cuttino Mobley (who took URI to
the Midwest Regional Final last season) were 7-20 in their first
season. This is going to be a learning experience for us. I don't
know what our record will be, but I know we won't be 20-7.''
</P>
<P>
   Kenny Harley had a game-high 19 points for BC, which hosts
Harvard Wednesday night at 7:30.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
