<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-KINGS-WRITETHRU-LBPT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KINGS LOSE 5-3
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ROGER PHILLIPS  
 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   INGLEWOOD _ If there has been a play epitomizing the rocky first
five weeks of the Kings' season, it came late in the second period
of Saturday night's game against the Carolina Hurricanes, a goal
off the stick of defenseman Steve Duchesne.
</P>
<P>
   The problem was, the puck ended up in the Kings' net _ a
centering pass from Ron Francis to Martin Gelinas inadvertently
deflected past goalie Manny Legace to a collective groan from the
announced crowd of 10,990 at the Forum.
</P>
<P>
   Before the season began, Duchesne was expected to help put pucks
in opposing nets, but it hasn't worked out that way so far, and
Francis' deflating goal helped send the Kings to a 5-3 loss.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew he was passing it across,'' Duchesne said. ``I figured
I'd try to tip it in the corner. Of course, it was a good shot by
me. I roofed it.... We're taking the laces off our skates _ suicide
watch.''
</P>
<P>
   Coach Larry Robinson said, ``He makes a great play, a diving
stop, and it's right in the top corner. It's like a black cloud is
over everybody's heads.''
</P>
<P>
   To the Kings' credit, they battled back all night, even after
Francis' goal. But that doesn't change the fact the Kings (5-9-3)
are 1-6-1 in their past eight games, have lost three straight, and
are 1-5-2 at the Forum this season.
</P>
<P>
   Robinson's long-threatened lineup changes failed to produce a
victory for the Kings, who were 0 for 7 on the power play and have
not scored in their past 22 chances with the man advantage.
</P>
<P>
   Robinson put Sandy Moger (returning from a strained back),
Nathan LaFayette and Ray Ferraro into the lineup, removing Craig
Johnson, Matt Johnson and rookie Olli Jokinen. He also played
defenseman Mark Visheau (who returned from a broken hand) in place
of rookie Jan Nemecek, who has been reassigned to the Long Beach
Ice Dogs.
</P>
<P>
   Moger began the game on the No.1 line with Jozef Stumpel and
Vladimir Tsyplakov (who left the game in the third period with a
mild concussion and is listed as day to day), but Robinson shuffled
his combinations as the night progressed and as things went
haywire.
</P>
<P>
   They went haywire in a hurry, with the Kings falling behind 2-0
on goals by Ray Sheppard and Robert Kron in the first 10:33.
Sheppard's goal came when he was allowed to skate untouched into
the slot and blast a quick shot past goalie Manny Legace.
</P>
<P>
   To their credit, the Kings didn't panic despite the early
deficit, which they cut to one midway through the second period on
Ian Laperriere's first goal this season. Laperriere _ who played on
a wing, out of his customary center's position _ received a pass
from Luc Robitaille in front of the Carolina net, shook loose from
the Hurricanes' Keith Primeau, and backhanded the puck past goalie
Arturs Irbe.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately for the Kings, this began a cycle that would be
repeated for the rest of the night. The Kings would draw within a
goal, then allow one and have to battle again from a two-goal
deficit.
</P>
<P>
   Francis' goal off Duchesne's stick made it 3-1, but Stumpel
tipped Glen Murray's pass into the net for his first goal of the
season, at 4:34 of the third.
</P>
<P>
   Less than a minute later, Primeau restored the Hurricanes'
two-goal lead, but with 11 minutes left, LaFayette's first goal of
the season _ shorthanded _ cut the margin to 4-3. The Kings have
scored seven shorthanded goals this season, and just five on the
power play.
</P>
<P>
   The Kings could not tie the score, however, and with 44 seconds
to play, Murray's ill-advised slashing penalty killed the Kings'
last hopes of tying the score. Primeau's empty-net goal with 8.6
seconds to play sealed the Hurricanes' victory.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a great effort,'' Robinson said. ``How do you get mad
at guys who give everything they've got. Everything that can go
wrong does go wrong.''
</P>
</TEXT>
