<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-TCU-ORAL-ROBERTS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GAINOUS' PLAY RESCUES FROGS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By T.R. SULLIVAN 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH _ TCU forward Lee Nailon has been nominated for some
of the highest individual awards in college basketball.
</P>
<P>
   Last night, the Horned Frogs won a thriller in a game in which
their star player showed few of the characteristics needed to win
those awards.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, junior forward Marquise Gainous rode to the rescue,
putting back his own missed shot with three seconds remaining to
give the Frogs a 94-93 victory against the Oral Roberts Golden
Eagles at Daniel-Meyer Coliseum.
</P>
<P>
   ``When Lee fouled out, my goal was to come in and take over,''
said Gainous, a junior-college transfer from Jacksonville (Fla.)
College.
</P>
<P>
   He scored 27 points and grabbed 16 rebounds and Ryan Carroll
added 17 points to help the Frogs improve to 2-1. Each of the three
games have been decided in the final seconds.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was too much of a struggle,'' Carroll said. ``We came out
fired up, but we just didn't make enough plays on defense.''
</P>
<P>
   Coach Billy Tubbs, whose team is likely to drop out of the
Associated Press Top 25 after starting the season ranked 25th,
said, ``You have to give ORU credit. They shot the ball well
tonight, although we had a lot to do with it. Basically, they took
it to us and outplayed us.''
</P>
<P>
   Nailon finished with 24 points but was 6-for-23 from the field,
a 26.1 shooting percentage that was the second-worst of his TCU
career and a far cry from the 55.4 percent that led the Western
Athletic Conference last season. He fouled out with 6:08 remaining.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our big guy hasn't had a big night yet,'' Tubbs said. ``But
he's getting a lot of attention and getting beat up around the
basket. I thought he got hammered two or three times underneath,
and we didn't come out of there with any \Rfree\S throws. He's got
to play better, but he's getting a lot of attention.''
</P>
<P>
   With Nailon struggling, the Frogs had trouble pulling away from
the Eagles. TCU's biggest lead was 74-67 with 10:55 remaining.
</P>
<P>
   But the Eagles stormed back, taking an 81-78 lead with 7:28 to
play, then matched the Frogs basket for basket down the stretch,
while Nailon watched from the bench.
</P>
<P>
   An upset loomed with 14 seconds remaining when Oral Roberts
guard Chad Wilkerson of Grand Prairie got inside the Frogs' defense
for a layup, giving the Eagles a 93-92 lead.
</P>
<P>
   After a timeout, the Frogs got the ball to Gainous, whose short
jumper missed off the front rim. But he got his own rebound and
softly laid it back in with three seconds remaining.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew it was coming off,'' Gainous said. ``I just got it back
and hurried it up.''
</P>
<P>
   The offensive rebound was the Frogs' 21st of the game, a total
that Oral Roberts coach Barry Hinson said was the difference.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were slippery as snakes; we couldn't get a body on
them,'' Hinson said. ``That was \Rpart\S of our emphasis in
practice the past two weeks, but that's what they do good.''
</P>
<P>
   The offensive rebounding made up for the Frogs' defensive
shortcomings. The Golden Eagles shot 53 percent from the field and
had little trouble breaking the Frogs' full-court press. The Golden
Eagles were 7-of-10 from 3-point range in the first half, then
pounded the ball effectively inside in the second half when TCU
tried to adjust.
</P>
<P>
   ``They did a better job inside on Lee Nailon than we did on
their inside men,'' Tubbs said. ``Offensively we can live with what
we're doing, but defensively we have to get a lot better. Our
inexperience shows up at some positions. We have a lot to learn,
but I've said that all along.'' Briefly Carroll, who suffered an
injury to the arch in his right foot before the season, has
essentially decided against redshirting. ``I'm playing with pain,
but hopefully it will go away.'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Nailon took a TCU career-high 18 free throws, hitting 12 of
them.
</P>
<P>
   Former Cowboys announcer Dave Garrett is doing radio
play-by-play for Oral Roberts.
</P>
</TEXT>
