<HEADLINE>
TECH VICTORY ELIMINATES TEXAS FROM TITLE CONTENTION
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JIMMY BURCH 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LUBBOCK, Texas _ Two defenses steeled themselves to stop someone
named Ricky Williams.
</P>
<P>
   But a lot of other names proved to be more telling down the
stretch last night at Jones Stadium, as Texas Tech (7-3, 4-3)
rallied for a 42-35 upset of No. 18 Texas that eliminated the
Longhorns (7-3, 5-2) from title contention in the Big 12 South
Division.
</P>
<P>
   Tech's victory broke a three-game losing streak and assured
Texas A&AMP;M (10-1, 7-0) of a second consecutive trip to the Big 12
title game, where the Aggies, No. 6 in The Associated Press poll,
will face Kansas State (10-0, 7-0) on Dec. 5 in St. Louis.
</P>
<P>
   For clearing up their postseason travel plans before a Nov. 27
trip to Austin, the Aggies can thank Tech players Rob Peters, Derek
Dorris, Chris Birkholz, Kyle Allamon and Tim Baker. All had season-
or career-best nights in an offensive blitz that saw the Red
Raiders score on eight of 16 possessions, including touchdowns on
their final three drives.
</P>
<P>
   The biggest plays in crunch time belonged to Peters, who threw
for a career-high 322 yards, and Allamon, whose leaping, 35-yard
catch set up Peters' game-winning quarterback sneak with 25 seconds
remaining. Peters' 3-yard touchdown sneak completed a comeback in
which the Raiders overcame three deficits and broke two
fourth-quarter ties.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is why you never quit,'' said Tech coach Spike Dykes, who
tied former coach Pete Cawthon (1930-40) atop the school's career
victory list with his 76th win. ``If you had one like this every
Saturday, there wouldn't be anything left.''
</P>
<P>
   Tech fired the game's most telling shots during a nine-play,
82-yard march that broke a 35-35 tie created when Texas receiver
Wane McGarity (six catches, 174 yards) hauled in his fourth
touchdown strike of the night from Major Applewhite with 2:18
remaining.
</P>
<P>
   When the Tech offense took the field, Peters laid down the law
to his teammates.
</P>
<P>
   ``He looked us in the eyes and said, `No matter what, we're not
coming off this field until we score a touchdown,' '' said Tech
tailback Ricky Williams, who rushed for 148 yards on 32 carries and
outgained his Texas counterpart (30 carries, 141 yards) for the
second consecutive year in a head-to-head setting.
</P>
<P>
   Peters, who threw for 150 yards and a touchdown in the final
quarter, made good on his vow by scrambling 12 yards for a first
down. On third-and-nine from the Tech 48-yard line, he found Baker
for 10 yards. His next third-down strike went to a leaping Allamon,
who rumbled to the Texas 3-yard line to complete a 35-yard
connection.
</P>
<P>
   ``I reached for the sky, and the ball hit my hands,'' said
Allamon, who entered the game with only 10 catches this season.
``When I turned around and saw no one was covering me, I couldn't
believe it. I just wished I was faster.''
</P>
<P>
   Peters scored the game-winner on Tech's next snap. It provided
the capper on a night when the Red Raiders reached the 42-point
mark against Texas for the first time in school history.
</P>
<P>
   Tech got there with a career night from Dorris, the former Azle
High School standout who grabbed three passes for 93 yards,
including his first two touchdowns. Kicker Birkholz booted a
career-best four field goals, including a career-long of 53 yards
to start the scoring. Baker and Allamon both grabbed two-point
conversion passes, and Peters ran for a score and threw for two
others.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were playing me loose and I don't know why,'' said
Dorris, who had touchdown catches of 44 and 17 yards. ``I guess
it's because they were worried about stopping Ricky. I'll take it.
It couldn't be a better night.''
</P>
<P>
   Texas coach Mack Brown said inconsistency killed the Longhorns
and their title hopes, especially on defense in the second half.
</P>
<P>
   ``We didn't make the plays, and the blame is on me,'' Brown
said. ``This was a great college football game, if you didn't care
who won. We played hard but we just ran out of time.''
Ricky watch
</P>
<P>
   Texas tailback Ricky Williams had 30 carries for 141 yards,
giving him 6,020 in his career. Williams needs 63 yards in his
final regular-season game, Nov. 27 against Texas A&AMP;M, to surpass
Tony Dorsett's NCAA career record of 6,082 yards.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
