r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBC-REEVES-COLUMN-TEX     11-15 0659
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-REEVES-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TECH SENDS UT DREAMS SOUTH
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JIM REEVES 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LUBBOCK, Texas _ Those wearing burnt orange who kept waiting for
Ricky Williams to deliver the miracle that would save the Longhorns
last night at Jones Stadium went away sadly disappointed.
</P>
<P>
   Texas coach Mack Brown never put Williams in on defense.
</P>
<P>
   Playing cornerback _ somebody needed to _ would have been the
only way the soon-to-be Heisman Trophy winner could have kept the
Longhorns from coming out on the short end of a 42-35 shootout with
Texas Tech on the high plains.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a great college football game,'' Brown said, sighing,
``if you didn't care who won. In Austin, any time you lose to
anybody, it's really bad.''
</P>
<P>
   Williams, who began the game needing 204 yards to break Tony
Dorsett's all-time NCAA career rushing record, carved that number
down to an easily makable 63 when Texas and Texas A&AMP;M have brunch
together the day after Thanksgiving in the regular-season finale
for both teams.
</P>
<P>
   That's about all the drama the game has after the Red Raiders
knocked the Longhorns out of the Big 12 South race with the upset
last night.
</P>
<P>
   ``It makes you sick,'' Brown said after watching Tech's Rob
Peters scramble in from the 3-yard line to score the winning
touchdown with 25 seconds left. ``Winning the Big 12 South was one
of our goals all year.''
</P>
<P>
   The loss dropped the Longhorns (7-3, 5-2) two games behind the
Aggies (10-1, 7-0), who beat Missouri yesterday.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the second half we big-played them. but we didn't stay on
the field long enough,'' Brown said. ``And we didn't make the plays
defensively. At one point we were up 28-20 with 12 minutes to play,
and we let them overcome three third-down situations.''
</P>
<P>
   The offensive slugfest almost made an afterthought of Williams
and his pursuit of Dorsett's record.
</P>
<P>
   For the second consecutive season, Tech's ``Little Ricky''
Williams won the head-to-head battle with Texas' more famous runner
of the same name. ``Big Ricky'' finished with 141 yards on 30
carries. ``Little Ricky'' lugged it 32 times for 148 yards.
</P>
<P>
   Call it irrelevant, if you must. Just don't do it in front of
``Little Ricky.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I get a big charge out of that,'' Tech's Williams said. ``It
lets me know our defense played well and that I played well. \RUT's
Williams\S is an awesome running back. I know he'll go far.''
</P>
<P>
   That's assuming ``Big Ricky'' made the team bus after the game.
Most scribes, waiting with bated breath to hear him put his assault
on Dorsett's record into perspective for the huddled masses,
finally huffed off to the press box as disappointed as the Texas
fans who were waiting for a Williams miracle to save the 'Horns.
</P>
<P>
   It appears that while Williams has been praised far and wide for
his talent, kind spirit and charitable nature, he has apparently
yet to grasp the concept of newspaper deadlines.
</P>
<P>
   While admitting a somewhat narrow-minded disposition on the
subject, I find this to be a serious, if correctable, flaw.
</P>
<P>
   So we leave it to Brown to speak for his tardy star.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a true credit to our Ricky that \RTech\S was giving up
112 yards a game rushing and he got 140-something,'' Brown said.
</P>
<P>
   Tech stacked its defense to stop Williams, which allowed
quarterback Major Applewhite and wide receiver Wane McGarity to
click for four touchdown passes, and that wasn't enough to hold off
the Raiders.
</P>
<P>
   Williams is almost certain to break the record in his final
regular-season game, at home, in front of the Texas fans, a fitting
curtain call for a remarkable player.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the A&AMP;M game,'' Applewhite said, knowing that says it
all. ``You can throw out the rankings, you can throw out the
numbers, you can throw out who won and who lost last year. It's
A&AMP;M.''
</P>
<P>
   It's brunch at Memorial Stadium. Just so Ricky understands that
for this one, deadlines shouldn't be a problem.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
