r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ATHELTES-RETIREMENT-T     11-15 2019
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ATHELTES-RETIREMENT-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ENOUGH TO MAKE A GROWN MAN CRY: ATHLETES DON'T QUIT EASILY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By GIL LEBRETON 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
There is terror behind the dream of being a professional
ballplayer. It comes as a slow realization of finality and of the
frightening unknowns which the end brings. When the playing is
over, one can sense that one's youth has been spent playing a game
and now both the game and youth are gone...He approaches the end of
his playing days the way old people approach death. He puts his
finances in order. He reminisces easily. He offers advice to the
young. But, the athlete differs from an old person in that he must
continue living. Behind all the years of practice and all the hours
of glory waits that inexorable terror of living without the game.
From ``Life on the Run'' by Bill Bradley
<TEXT>
<P>
   In the end, his Cowboys teammates say, Tony Tolbert could barely
jog in practice. His knees, already operated upon five times, were
getting worse.
</P>
<P>
   And though owner Jerry Jones told the media on the day the
Cowboys released him, ``This is a decision that has been reached in
a mutual fashion,'' Tolbert did not leave willingly.
</P>
<P>
   Whether it was for pride or for his scheduled $2.5-million
salary, the 30-year-old defensive end wanted to return.
</P>
<P>
   On the week of this year's season opener, four months after
Tolbert again had surgery on both knees, the Cowboys invited their
former lineman to the annual Kickoff Luncheon to receive the Ed
Block Courage Award, the training room's equivalent of the Purple
Heart.
</P>
<P>
   Tolbert didn't show.
</P>
<P>
   The end of the road does not always come with a tickertape
parade and a champagne shower for a professional athlete.
</P>
<P>
   Some, like Tolbert and Cowboys teammate Charles Haley, defy the
doctor and yearn to try again. Some, like former
Cowboy-turned-coach Jim Jeffcoat, allow their bodies to tell them
it's time.
</P>
<P>
   Others, like the Rangers' Mickey Tettleton and the Cowboys' Bill
Bates, find themselves overtaken by emotion. There are still more,
notably the Chicago Bulls' Michael Jordan, who seem torn between
the eternal comeback and the final goodbye.
</P>
<P>
   ``In my case, I knew it was time,'' said Jeffcoat, who retired
in 1997 after 12 seasons with the Cowboys and 15 in the NFL. ``I
had injured my knee, and I knew I couldn't do some of the things
that I had been doing for so many years. I couldn't picture myself
going out there at half-speed.''
</P>
<P>
   Jeffcoat left willingly. His fellow first-year coach on the
Cowboys staff, Bill Bates, took a more reluctant path.
</P>
<P>
   ``Is this an easy decision? Of course not,'' Bates said through
tears back in July. ``Do I want to play? I think you know I do.''
</P>
<P>
   Bates, at least, left with his health intact. Haley's retirement
was supposed to be prompted by a lingering back injury that had
reduced him to a part-time player in 1996, his last season with the
Cowboys.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, Jones was stunned to receive a phone call from Haley during
the summer, asking the Cowboys for a release so that he could try
out with the San Francisco 49ers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Different kinds of athletes respond to the end in different
kinds of ways,'' said sports psychologist Dr. Don Beck, who heads
the National Values Center in Denton.
</P>
<P>
   ``For some, the huge salaries you see today become a pair of
golden handcuffs and probably contain athletes for longer than they
have to. For others, the issue is missing the camaraderie of the
`male' thing _ the locker room _ and there's a fear of being
ushered out into a world without structure.
</P>
<P>
   ``From the time they were in the little leagues, sports has
provided a rhythm to their entire lifestyle. To these athletes,
facing the end, that's a lonesome world, and it's fearful.''
</P>
<P>
   The ``terror'' former Knicks player Bill Bradley spoke about in
``Life on the Run'' is real.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fear is of never playing again,'' said former Cowboys
quarterback Danny White. ``Guys just can't see themselves _ or see
life _ without the game of football.
</P>
<P>
   ``I remember making the decision and going home that day and
sitting there, thinking, `Now what do I do?' It's almost as if life
stopped. Ended. And in a lot of ways, it does.
</P>
<P>
   ``You pass through the veil, if you will, from a dream world
into reality. And it can be a scary thing.''
</P>
<P>
   For the retiring athlete, there is also the reality that the end
doesn't come with an adoring arena. What do they do when the
cheering stops?
</P>
<P>
   ``There are guys who thrive on that. That's the reason they play
the game _ for the attention and being in the spotlight,'' White
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It wasn't for me, but even I missed it when it was gone. Very
quickly, you become yesterday's news. And it can jolt you.''
</P>
<P>
   There is no question that the athletes of prior generations
likely lingered a bit longer for the growing financial rewards that
their sports offered. In Tolbert's case, he faced losing more than
$5 million in salary for the 1998 and '99 seasons.
</P>
<P>
   Jeffcoat thinks the golden handcuffs issue is overrated. ``I
think players stay around because of the thrill of it _ their
competitive nature.
</P>
<P>
   ``The hardest thing for an athlete is finding something to fill
that void,'' he added. ``It's something that gets inside of you, a
fire that burns bright, and it's hard to channel that energy into
something else.''
</P>
<P>
   Other retired athletes, including former Rangers Pete O'Brien
and Jim Sundberg, also dispute the notion of being shackled by
financial chains. Money isn't what keeps a veteran player in the
game, they said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I almost think it's the reverse,'' Sundberg said, ``because in
professional sports, you can make so much money in a short period
of time, if you're a decent player, that you put yourself in a
position where you're financially flexible for probably the rest of
your life.
</P>
<P>
   ``To me, I always thought the large increases in salaries would
mean shortened careers.''
</P>
<P>
   Besides, O'Brien added, the pressure to produce mandates a
certain level of performance in professional athletics.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't `hang on' at the big-league level,'' he said. ``I
don't think the game keeps you around if you're not performing.''
</P>
<P>
   At 6-foot-2 and 215 pounds, Tettleton was a symbol of strength
when he was with the Rangers. Rugged and intense. The ultimate
Marlboro Man.
</P>
<P>
   But on the day in 1997 he announced his retirement at The
Ballpark, Tettleton couldn't hold back the tears.
</P>
<P>
   ``For me, getting to play the game had been a dream come true,''
Tettleton said. ``You go all the way back to the hours you spent
throwing balls off the side of the house in the backyard, to
playing games with your friends and pretending you were somebody.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you leave something like that, something that you really
enjoy doing, you go through some pretty crazy emotions. In the two
days leading up to that, I don't know how many times I cried at
home.''
</P>
<P>
   Limping on and off the disabled list, trying to recover from his
sixth surgery, Tettleton batted only 44 times in 1997 before, at
36, he called it quits.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you're hobbling up and down the stairs in your own
home,'' he said, ``it's not a whole lot of fun.''
</P>
<P>
   In that regard, Tettleton was one of the lucky ones. He accepted
the finality. But sports history is lined with the dim snapshots of
athletes who tried to hang on.
</P>
<P>
   The great Willie Mays, for instance, hit 52 home runs in 1965
when he was 34. It was his last great season. But Mays continued to
hang on, hitting only 13 home runs in 1969 and then, at age 41,
being traded from the Giants where he had played his entire career
to the New York Mets. In his final hurrah, Mays, who hit 660
big-league home runs and had a career average of .302, batted .211
in his last season with the 1973 Mets.
</P>
<P>
   The Cowboys' Bates was one who left with a bittersweet feeling.
Unable to fit the veteran safety under the salary cap or onto the
depth chart, the Cowboys named Bates an assistant coach during last
summer's training camp.
</P>
<P>
   Bates and running back Herschel Walker were squeezed by salary
cap rules that would have required Jones to pay them the veteran
salary minimum of $325,000. Jones reasoned that he could pay two
young players for the price of one old (36 years) Herschel.
</P>
<P>
   Bates' announcement, like Tettleton's, was emotional.
</P>
<P>
   ``The hardest thing for a player is to realize it's over,'' he
said. ``You think, `How can I walk away from the game? How can I
totally forget something that I've done my whole life?'''
</P>
<P>
   The sigh of resignation in Bates' voice, however, betrays him.
If owner Jones asked, Bates would suit up in a minute.
</P>
<P>
   Jim Sundberg wouldn't. When his years as an All-Star catcher and
16-year major-leaguer were done, he found a comforting punctuation
to it all _ a Jim Sundberg Day, staged by the Rangers.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a nice finale,'' said Sundberg, who retired in 1989.
``There are a lot of fond memories attached to that.''
</P>
<P>
   After a career that saw him make three All-Star teams and earn
six Gold Glove Awards, Sundberg said he knew it was ``time to move
on.'' After 13 years as a starting catcher, he was the backup
catcher for three seasons.
</P>
<P>
   ``And I was never comfortable with that,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Still, it isn't easy to tell the game you love goodbye.
</P>
<P>
   On a Sunday in 1993, the Rangers bid goodbye to Arlington
Stadium. By the next year, the club had moved to The Ballpark in
Arlington and the former stadium would be on its way to becoming a
parking lot. An impressive ceremony formally bid adieu to the old
place.
</P>
<P>
   With the sun setting and the stands empty, a few remaining
writers in the press box noticed a solitary figure walk out. He
carried a paper cup in his hand.
</P>
<P>
   Jim Sundberg stopped at home plate, where he had worked for
seven Rangers seasons, and crouching over, he began to quietly fill
the cup with dirt.
</P>
<P>
   The memories linger. The athlete can't.
</P>
<P>
   They left too soon
</P>
<P>
   Jim Brown, football: Ran for 1,544 yards and 17 touchdowns in
1965 and, at age 29, took his ball and headed for Hollywood.
</P>
<P>
   Sandy Koufax, baseball: Was only 30 years old when he struck out
317, won fifth consecutive ERA title and retired, citing arthritic
elbow.
</P>
<P>
   Don Meredith, football: Tired of the Morton-Meredith QB
controversy, he turned out the lights and declared the party over
at age 30.
</P>
<P>
   Bobby Orr, hockey: Hailed as the greatest defenseman ever to
play the game when bad knees forced him to quit at age 32.
</P>
<P>
   Willis Reed, basketball: After only 10 years, but with two NBA
titles, Willis surrendered to injuries and retired at age 32.
</P>
<P>
   Left too late
</P>
<P>
   Babe Ruth, baseball: Released by Yanks and fading, he signed on
with the Boston Braves and batted only .181 in final hurrah.
</P>
<P>
   Muhammad Ali, boxing: Finally ran out of comebacks and greatness
in 1981 at age 39. No one knows what physical toll his final bouts
took.
</P>
<P>
   Gordie Howe, hockey: Hockey's greatest, still scoring goals in
Houston at age 52, but why? He even played a shift in the IHL last
season at _ what? _ 69!
</P>
<P>
   Adrian Dantley, basketball: Played on seven teams, helped sink
Mavericks in late '80s, and then, at 35, signed a contract to play
in Italy.
</P>
<P>
   Johnny Unitas, football: After glorious 17-year run in
Baltimore, he headed to San Diego, of all places, and a 40.0 QB
rating.
</P>
<P>
   Left at right time
</P>
<P>
   Bill Russell, basketball: Became Red Auerbach's player-coach at
age 33, but was still pulling down 19 rebounds a game when he hung
up his sneakers two years later.
</P>
<P>
   Florence Griffith Joyner, track: With three gold medals, two
mighty world records and nothing more to prove, she retired after
the Seoul Olympics to start a family.
</P>
<P>
   Rocky Marciano, boxing: Whisked through his heavyweight career
undefeated, 49-0, and left a champion, vacating the title at age
33.
</P>
<P>
   Roger Staubach, football: Fearful of another concussion, he left
at age 37, throwing a career-high 27 TD passes in his final season
and still able to find Drew Pearson.
</P>
<P>
   Ted Williams, baseball: He was 42 and still batting .316 when he
hit a home run in Fenway Park on his final at-bat.
</P>
