<HEADER>
A1479 &Cx1f; tad-z
r w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RONPAUL-TEX-1116-COX     11-15 0320
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RONPAUL-TEX-1116-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    EDs: For Texas clients only.
 &HT;    REP. PAUL SAYS HOUSE GRIDLOCK NOT BAD IDEA
 &HT;    For Use Monday, Nov. 16 And Thereafter.
 &HT;    By CHRISTI HARLAN 
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ A would-be House leader called Rep. Ron Paul,
R-Surfside, last week and asked for Paul's vote, promising that he
would ``make the trains run on time'' if elected this week.
</P>
<P>
   Oops. Wrong number.
</P>
<P>
   In Congress-speak, ``making the trains run on time'' means
moving legislation, particularly the federal spending bills, to the
House floor and passage as smoothly as possible. The chugging of
those trains is not necessarily a pleasant sound to Paul, a former
Libertarian presidential candidate who believes the Constitution
places strict limits on what Congress can do.
</P>
<P>
   ``Are `on-time trains' such a good thing if they carry off more
of our money and freedoms while delivering more regulations?'' Paul
asked in his weekly column. ``It may be that our leaders should
demand that we stop the trains entirely.''
</P>
<P>
   Paul may get his wish next year: with Republicans holding 223
seats and Democrats 211, a mere six votes will decide whether the
House passes legislation or grinds to a halt.
</P>
<P>
   ``The frustration and gridlock may not be all that bad for those
of us who want to slow the growth of the federal government,'' said
Paul, who was re-elected Nov. 3 to represent parts of Travis,
Williamson and Hays counties in Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Paul's column didn't mention any leadership candidates by name,
but House Majority Leader Dick Armey, R-Irving, who campaigned for
Paul last summer, is fighting to keep his job and has mentioned his
expertise with legislative trains. As of Friday, seven Texans were
among the 37 Republicans who had publicly endorsed Armey's
re-election. Paul wasn't on the list.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-15-98 1331EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981115.0046 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-15 13:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1488 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SUNKEN16-COX     11-15 0988
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SUNKEN16-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Developer offers bare proposition for Florida's Sunken Gardens
 &HT;    By Mike Williams
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ST. PETERSBURG, Fla. _ For more than 60 years, tourists have
gazed in wonder at the exotic trees, gorgeous flowers and rare
animals gathered at Sunken Gardens, one of Florida's oldest
roadside attractions.
</P>
<P>
   Soon, the pink that tourists glimpse may not be flamingos.
</P>
<P>
   A developer has proposed buying the once-grand but now
dilapidated attraction and converting it into a posh resort filled
with jacuzzis, conversation pools, saunas, masseuses _ and naked
patrons.
</P>
<P>
   The proposal for an upscale, European-style naturist resort is
raising goose-bumps on some neighbors, but not from pleasure.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's a disgrace,'' said M.L. Nance, who owns a nearby
motel on Fourth Avenue, one of the main arteries leading into
downtown St. Petersburg. ``All we'll get is a bunch of slime over
there. Decent people wouldn't go there.''
</P>
<P>
   Not so, argues the developer.
</P>
<P>
   ``Naturists are the nicest, most decent people I've ever met,''
said Galen Ballard, who has signed a deal to pay $2 million for the
4.5-acre property and wants to sink another $3 million into
renovations. ``They tend to be much more affluent than the average
person. Just north of St. Petersburg, there are four naturists
resorts and officials there love them. No crime, no trash, no
problems. It's clean, passive recreation and will generate a lot of
tax dollars.''
</P>
<P>
   City officials have said a cursory review turned up no apparent
problems with the proposal, but they've yet to issue final
approval.
</P>
<P>
   The deal would be an interesting twist in the history of what
was once one of Florida's premier tourist attractions.
</P>
<P>
   Long before there was a Walt Disney World or Universal Studios,
the state was dotted with small, mom-and-pop roadside attractions
that catered to the steady stream of sun-seeking tourists who
motored down for winter vacations.
</P>
<P>
   Sunken Gardens was one of the first. The gardens were actually
started in 1903 by George Turner Sr., a plumber who drained a
sinkhole and started raising fruit and flowers in the rich, mucky
soil left behind.
</P>
<P>
   During the Depression, Turner opened his gardens to the public
at the modest fee of 25 cents for two. Soon he was selling juice
and fruit, along with Florida crafts and curiosities, said his
grandson, Tom Turner.
</P>
<P>
   Word of Turner's handiwork spread, and by the 1950s, Sunken
Gardens rated as one of Florida's top-10 tourist attractions,
drawing hundreds of visitors each day in the summer and thousands
in the winter.
</P>
<P>
   Along with beds of brightly-colored flowers, small waterfalls
and rock gardens, a mile-long path led through a stunning array of
tropical vines, trees and ferns.
</P>
<P>
   There were also rare animals, including pygmy goats, scarlet
macaws and pink flamingos. One trained bird actually played cards
with visitors.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was 7 or 8 when my family went there on a vacation from
Wisconsin,'' said Ballard, now 54. ``I was absolutely in awe. I had
never seen anything like that in my life. I got to handle a baby
alligator and saw those pink flamingos. Before that I thought they
were only made out of plastic.''
</P>
<P>
   But Florida tourism began changing in the 1960s and 1970s with
the arrival of corporate giants like Disney and Busch. Competition
increased and the small mom-and-pop attractions started losing
business as tourists bypassed old favorites on their way to the new
mega-attractions.
</P>
<P>
   The Turners added a ``King of Kings'' wax museum exhibition
chronicling Jesus' life, as well as an alligator-wrestling show.
But the bigger attractions kept drawing away customers.
</P>
<P>
   In the late 1980s, the Turners put the attraction on the market,
but by then, once-bustling Fourth Avenue was a rundown stretch of
cheap motels and liquor stores drawing drifters and prostitutes.
</P>
<P>
   The family offered to sell to the city, but wary commissioners
declined, fearing they would be saddled with a money-losing
facility.
</P>
<P>
   A year ago, the Turners had a buyer who wanted to put in upscale
condominiums, but residents of a rejuvenated neighborhood to the
east rose up in opposition. Deluged with irate calls, city
officials turned down the condo proposal's zoning and also
designated the gardens as a historic landmark _ a move aimed at
discouraging development.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're just really frustrated,'' Tom Turner said. ``The city
doesn't seem to want to let us sell it, but they don't want to do
anything to help us keep it alive.''
</P>
<P>
   Ballard, who lives about an hour north of St. Petersburg, heard
about the family's troubles through his work as a resort consultant
and developer. He recalled his fascination with the gardens as a
boy, and mulled over possibilities.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew it could no longer stand on its own as an attraction,''
he said. ``But then the light bulb came on. I realized naturists
would pay $15 to $20 a day to relax in a private, natural
setting.''
</P>
<P>
   Ballard plans to make the nudist resort a day-only operation,
with an upscale restaurant _ for clothed patrons _ to operate at
night after the naturists have departed.
</P>
<P>
   He plans to offer diners tours of the gardens, hoping that might
attract more business for the day-time, clothing-optional
operation.
</P>
<P>
   He hopes the city won't try to block him by treating his
naturist resort like an x-rated adult business. If they do, he
plans to go to court.
</P>
<P>
   ``This isn't a topless bar,'' he said. ``In Europe, they raise
their children not to be ashamed of their bodies. There's nothing
erotic about a nudist resort. It's for families.''
</P>
<P>
   As for residents who think nudism is indecent, he thinks they
should give it a try.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you try it one day you'll never be the same again,'' he
said. ``You'll feel so relaxed you won't even remember you're
nude.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
