<HEADER>
A1495 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ALAMO-DIARY16-COX     11-15 1825
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ALAMO-DIARY16-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Auction of Alamo diary causing consternation
 &HT;    WITH ALAMO-TEXT, ALAMO-MYTH
 &HT;    By Don McLeese
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ When asked about the imminent auction in Los
Angeles of the controversial manuscript commonly called the ``Alamo
diary,'' Don Carleton began to laugh. He had to laugh, admitted the
director of the Center for American History at the University of
Texas, for it would hurt too much to cry.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just all so unfortunate,'' he said. ``This just shouldn't
have happened.''
</P>
<P>
   According to Carleton, it never should have come to this _ a
public auction for a document of priceless historical value that UT
previously felt it would hold for perpetuity. What makes the memoir
particularly provocative is its assertion that Davy Crockett was
captured and executed at the Alamo, contrary to the popular myth
that has him going down fighting.
</P>
<P>
   For a quarter-century, this memoir from the Mexican side of the
Texas Revolution _ purportedly written by Jose Enrique de la Pena,
a junior officer in the army of Antonio Lopez de Santa Anna _ has
been the cornerstone of the John Peace Collection of the John Peace
Library at UT-San Antonio. The late John Peace II was the UT regent
largely responsible for establishing a campus in his native San
Antonio, and he was one of the collectors through the 1960s and
early 1970s whose passion for Texana established a high-priced
market.
</P>
<P>
   Foremost among his prized purchases was the diary, which he
acquired in Mexico from the widow of a book dealer in 1973. Peace
died the next year. It was his wish that the Alamo diary and the
rest of his Texana collection remain forever at the university
library bearing his name.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes, it was,'' agreed John Peace III, a rare-book dealer in
San Antonio who transferred the manuscript from the library to the
Butterfield &AMP; Butterfield auction house in Los Angeles earlier this
year. ``But I think my father, if he were alive today, would have a
different opinion. The times have changed, the people involved with
the university have changed and the politics of colleges are much
more transparent these days. ... If people were aware of how
libraries treat their donations, they'd think twice. My father gave
a lot more to UT than just this diary. He gave his life.''
</P>
<P>
   Until bidding commences Wednesday (Nov. 18), it's hard to
estimate what the manuscript might bring. Peace previously put a
$250,000 price tag on it at the Cheever Books in San Antonio, which
he manages, and received no offers. Since then, however, the
auction has generated publicity ranging from an article in The Wall
Street Journal to a feature on ``The Today Show,'' eliciting
inquiries from all sorts of public institutions, private collectors
and folks who, said Peace, ``just like interesting things.'' It
remains to be seen how much of that interest is serious, and at
what price.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have been amazed at the response that we have gotten,''
said Greg Shaw, director of Butterfield &AMP; Butterfield's book and
manuscript department. ``I don't want to scare anybody off, but it
could go for a million dollars.''
</P>
<P>
   ``In his dreams,'' scoffed Carleton. ``There could be some
person with more money than sense who would spend a million dollars
for that, but I think that's absurd, and I just don't believe it's
going to happen. It has value in the realm of historical
scholarship, but there's not really any monetary value attached to
that. Babe Ruth didn't sign it, much less Mark McGwire.''
</P>
<P>
   Price aside, the manuscript has been a source of contention
throughout its stay in San Antonio. Though there's plenty of
historical revelation in its 400-plus pages, all the furor has
focused on a few lines from a single page: The assertion that David
Crockett was one of seven at the battle who surrendered to Santa
Anna and were executed. This contradicts one of the most beloved
tales in all of Texas history, which has Davy fighting to his death
against overwhelming odds. Though de la Pena's account doesn't
disparage Crockett's heroism _ ``these unfortunates died without
complaining and without humiliating themselves before their
torturers,'' he writes _ it contradicts the larger-than-life myth
that has been Walt Disneyed, John Wayned and indelibly Imaxed into
the American consciousness.
</P>
<P>
   De la Pena was no sycophantic apologist for Santa Anna. To the
contrary, he charged the Mexican military leadership with cruelty
and incompetence, asserting that the failings of Santa Anna were
largely responsible for losing the Texas campaign that was Mexico's
to win. In the early 1840s, de la Pena died as a political prisoner
in a Mexico City cell, where he had revised his diary into a
memoir.
</P>
<P>
   His account stirred little U.S. interest when it was published
more than a century later in Mexico in 1955 (ironically, just as
Disney was transforming Crockett into an all-American icon). But
after Peace brought it across the border, the diary ignited a furor
with its American publication in 1975 as ``With Santa Anna in
Texas: A Personal Narrative of the Revolution.'' Translated by
Carmen Perry, director of the Daughters of the Republic of Texas
Library at the Alamo, the work was revised into an expanded edition
that was published last year by Texas A&AMP;M University Press.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is virtually no disagreement among historians of any
stripe that there were executions at the Alamo,'' said James E.
Crisp, a history professor at North Carolina State University who
has established himself as the foremost authority on the de la Pena
document. (His introduction to last year's edition details the
controversy.)
</P>
<P>
   ``The idea that every last man died in combat is not taken
seriously, except by tourists, chauvinists and people who believe
in fairy tales. The furor comes from people who don't want that
myth tampered with _ this highly structured story that is told over
and over again, and which is intended to inculcate certain values
and give some sense of what the Texas identity is. And part of that
Texas identity is that you don't surrender.''
</P>
<P>
   Such notoriety has escalated the price of the manuscript,
particularly since Crisp's research and the verification of the
paper's age by Butterfield &AMP; Butterfield have all but conclusively
confirmed its authenticity. The controversies also gave James Peace
III some sense of the diary's increasing value and some concern
that UT-San Antonio wasn't giving the document its due. Though
everything else in his father's collection had been donated to the
university in a series of tax write-offs, the Alamo diary was the
last piece (along with some associated research documents) still on
loan to the library. When he read a newspaper report last year that
the library was considering moving the Peace Collection to the
Institute of Texan Cultures for space purposes, he felt that the
university was taking the Peace legacy for granted, and he decided
to take back the manuscript.
</P>
<P>
   ``If my father had been alive to see that they were thinking of
transferring what he had donated, he'd sue 'em,'' said Peace. ``I
don't intend to go in and sue 'em, but I'm doing the one thing I
can. ... UT just wasn't utilizing it properly. It's been there for
25 years, and it had been neglected. So this has been a good
stimulus to get it out of UT and move on.''
</P>
<P>
   ``You can take all those explanations that he gives you with
whatever you think they are worth,'' said Michael Kelly, director
of UT-San Antonio's John Peace Library, who said that the
collection will remain within an expanded archive there. ``The
document has received very intensive scrutiny here. I don't know
what he thinks should have been done with it, and I don't know if
he really thinks those are the reasons for doing what he did. He
complained about it being kept in a box. Well, that's what you do
with documents. You keep them in document boxes.
</P>
<P>
   ``We regard it as a major loss, but I'm not going to cry about
it being gone, because that's a decision I had no control over,''
Kelly said. ``You can draw your own conclusions as to why somebody
would want to sell a document for $200,000.'' (Peace said that the
beneficiary of the sale would be his mother, with the son receiving
a 6 percent finder's fee.)
</P>
<P>
   ``The money's a factor, buy my motivation certainly isn't the
money,'' said Peace. ``I just think that it deserves a better shot
than it has had. Only a third of it has been translated, the final
draft, so that the rough draft, all his notes, his footnotes and
references have not been translated. Having all this publicity has
been good for the document, and it's good to get it out there.''
</P>
<P>
   At 200 grand, UT might well be in the running, with Kelly and
Carleton agreeing that the UT System would need to make the
purchase since the San Antonio library lacks sufficient resources.
But with all the rumors flying around, it's hard to know whether
such a price represents the finish line or merely the starting
point.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every auction is an unknown,'' said Texas auctioneer Dorothy
Sloane, who specializes in rare books and manuscripts. ``When you
get the right-sized egos in the same room, who knows what might
happen? This is a research manuscript that has a lot of scholarly
potential, but that's a totally different thing from a trophy piece
you hang on a wall. It's a wonderful document for an institution;
in fact, where it was, was about the perfect place for it.''
</P>
<P>
   The auction catalogue lists an estimated value of $200,000 to
$300,000, which Shaw maintains is ``very conservative.'' He says
that some wealthy Texas ranchers have expressed interest. Other
possible parties include Yale University and the University of
California at Berkeley, institutions that could consider the diary
a prize among their extensive Texas holdings. There was even talk
of a Hollywood production company using the diary to remake ``The
Alamo.''
</P>
<P>
   For the record, UT is ``monitoring the situation very closely,''
said Carleton, without confirming that the institution would be
among the bidders. ``I just wish we were dealing directly with the
donor and could work something out. ... It's an icon, an artifact,
and I think the preservation of these things in the original is
absolutely essential. Yes, the information has been published and
so forth, but there's really nothing like the original as a link to
the past.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm hoping very much that a philanthropist, benefactor or
foundation will buy it and donate it eventually to an archive,''
said Crisp. ``What would be a terrible tragedy is if it ended up in
the hands of private collectors who didn't make it available to
scholars. The ultimate tragedy would be if somebody who really
hates this diary buys it and tosses it into the fire.''
</P>
<P>
   Even the staunchest defenders of Davy Crockett wouldn't do that.
Would they?
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
