<DOCNO> NYT19981115.0063 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-15 15:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1567 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CALL-SUBSTITUTE-TEACH     11-15 0502
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CALL-SUBSTITUTE-TEACHERS16-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Computer does the calling to contact substitute teachers
 &HT;    By Malissa Kash
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   SPRINGFIELD, Ohio _ A $20,000 computer system is helping
Springfield City Schools alleviate a substitute teacher shortage.
</P>
<P>
   Called Substitute Employee Management System, or SEMS, the
program has been in place since Sept. 21 and can call six
substitutes at one time.
</P>
<P>
   It works much like an automated banking line that gives out
checking and savings account information with a personal
identification number and a Social Security number.
</P>
<P>
   When teachers, aides or secretaries call off, they enters the
date and a code for the reason, like personal business or illness.
The system then calls a list of qualified substitutes up to 60 days
in advance; the substitutes enter PIN numbers assigned by the
district and accept or decline the job.
</P>
<P>
   Before the system, Linda Paul, administrative secretary of
substitute services, had to call and find about 60 substitute
teachers a day. Now the computer does it for her, or substitutes
can call in and find jobs on days they are free.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've always had a problem with a shortage of subs,'' she
said. ``Now they can tailor this to their needs. If they are
proactive, they can work as much as they want. I'm finding a lot of
people are sitting down with calendar and calling in.''
</P>
<P>
   This year, the district was in such need for subs that it
accepted anyone with a four-year college degree who was interested
in work as a substitute.
</P>
<P>
   Paul's office is Mission Control for the system; so she has to
monitor it closely each day and work out any glitches. She says she
still makes the calls to find substitutes for principals or those
for long absences.
</P>
<P>
   Paul said the system calls people as late as 10 p.m. or as early
as 6 a.m. for a job that day. The system now serves 900 employees
in the district. It will have all 1,200 employees on it by next
school year.
</P>
<P>
   Cheryl Beard, building secretary at Hayward Middle School, was
responsible for training the building staff members on how to use
the system. She likes this system because she knows at 7:45 a.m. if
there are any unfilled positions in the buildings; teachers have to
cover classes that don't have substitutes, and she needs to notify
them.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought it would be difficult, but it was easier than I
expected,'' she said. ``I can call in and know exactly who will be
in the building and if I have a sub or not. It's easier to plan the
day if you know who is going to show up.''
</P>
<P>
   The system has another advantage _ it can track ``unusual''
absences, she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Really, it improves the level of accountability,'' she said.
``Someone is going to abuse available leave regardless of whether
you're talking with a person or computer. There's a date and time
stamp. We may see emerging patterns for someone consistently off
Mondays and Fridays.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
