<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ART-DIGEST-AUCTION-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
READER'S DIGEST ART AUCTION EXPECTED TO BRING $100 MILLION 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Includes two sidebars   at end)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARK FEENEY  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PLEASANTVILLE, N.Y. _ The eyes of the art world are trained on
the Upper East Side of Manhattan, 35 miles south of this leafy
Westchester suburb. That's where Sotheby's will conduct what's
likely to be one of the richest auctions of corporate art in its
history.
</P>
<P>
   Up for bid Monday will be 38 works of art_ among them, paintings
by Cezanne, Monet, Renoir, Modigliani, Matisse, and van Gogh _ that
are expected to bring close to $100 million to their owner, the
Reader's Digest Association. One other work of art will be sold
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   It's hard to say which comes as more of a surprise: that
America's favorite source of homespun wisdom and human interest,
Reader's Digest (located where else but in a town called
Pleasantville), should find itself the center of attention at
high-cultural ground zero; or that its parent company, owner of the
world's most popular publication, with 100 million readers of its
48 editions in 19 languages, needs to liquidate assets as part of a
major corporate restructuring.
</P>
<P>
   Until recently, the Digest had enjoyed almost constant
circulation increases and astonishing profitability during its 76
years of existence. The Wall Street Journal once called it ``the
top publishing success since the Bible.'' And, like the magazine
itself, such Digest features as ``Life in These United States'' and
``It Pays to Enrich Your Word Power'' long ago entered the common
currency of American culture, ``part of the air people breathe,''
in the words of the magazine's editor-in-chief, Christopher
Willcox.
</P>
<P>
   Yet this monument to steady-state publishing in the Big Bang
world of '90s media has had a rocky past few years. ``The recent
history has been rather painful,'' says John Mack Carter, director
of new magazine development for Hearst Corporation and a longtime
friend of DeWitt and Lila Acheson Wallace, the legendary couple who
founded the Digest and ran it for nearly 60 years.
</P>
<P>
   In September, the company announced it would reduce its dividend
by 75 percent and lay off several hundred staffers from its
5,600-member work force. This followed such previous cost-cutting
measures as sale of its corporate jet. Reader's Digest Association
stock, an investor favorite when the company went public in 1990,
has gone from a high of $56.375 in December 1992 to a low earlier
this year of $16.25. On Friday, shares closed at $23.75. Writing in
this year's annual report, chairman and chief executive officer
Thomas O. Ryder describes the Digest as ``a world-class company
grappling with world-class challenges.''
</P>
<P>
   The magazine, which provides roughly a quarter of corporate
revenues, has fared better than some other parts of the company.
But it, too, is making changes. Next year its circulation rate base
will fall by 2.5 million copies, to 12.5 million. In May, the
magazine unveiled a new design most notable for putting a
photograph on the cover (a first for the Digest). Less visibly,
Willcox has been working to give the magazine a more contemporary
feel. A feature on computer humor, Virtual Hilarity, was introduced
last year. Laughter, the Best Medicine can offer a dose of David
Letterman's Top 10 list.
</P>
<P>
   Changing a magazine with such a long tradition and successful
formula is ``extremely tricky,'' admits Willcox. ``We have to
connect with the younger generation coming up. But we have to be
careful to keep the core audience who value us for the `reads.'''
</P>
<P>
   In a media world whose two most sacred words are ``Tina'' and
``Brown,'' the Digest _ resolutely unhip and cheerfully retrograde
_ can seem like the ultimate editorial throwback. ``Reader's Digest
stands for the good guys,'' Willcox says. ``We try not to do that
in a Pollyanna way or to avoid controversy. Still, our basic
purpose is to encourage people, inspire them, give them hope.''
</P>
<P>
   That same purpose motivated the Wallaces when they founded the
Digest in a basement under a Greenwich Village speakeasy in 1922.
Back then, the magazine didn't seem stolid and staid but almost
revolutionary, and the Wallaces played their part in the post-World
War I transformation of media culture. As much as Time (founded in
1923), H.L. Mencken's American Mercury (founded in 1924), or The
New Yorker (founded in 1925), the Digest marked a radical departure
for American magazines.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are living in a fast-paced world,'' DeWitt Wallace said in
1919, words that sound even more pertinent today than then,
perhaps. ``People are anxious to get at the nub of things. I intend
to search it out for them.'' And so he did, taking the bus each
morning to the periodicals room of the New York Public Library on
42d Street to copy out articles he thought suitable for his new
magazine, condensing them on the spot.
</P>
<P>
   The first issue had a print run of 5,000 copies and promised
subscribers ``thirty-one articles each month from leading
magazines. Each article of enduring value and interest, in
condensed and compact form.'' What search engines are to the
Worldwide Web, a means of quickly navigating the information
landscape, and what USA Today is to daily journalism, a vigorously
upbeat and tightly edited distillation of the world around us,
Reader's Digest was three-quarters of a century ago. It proved an
immediate success, and allowed the Wallaces to move the Digest to
Pleasantville.
</P>
<P>
   The innovations did not stop there. The Digest, which
practically invented direct-mail marketing, was creating synergies
long before anyone knew what the word meant. ``Remember when you
look at Reader's Digest, the magazine is a relatively small part of
the whole thing,'' says Dennis McAlpine, a media analyst at the New
York investment firm of Josephthal, Lyon &AMP; Ross. ``The magazine is
really an entree, in many respects, to get people into the books
and home-entertainment, direct-marketing stuff.'' Though the
magazine remains the company flagship, almost two-thirds of
revenues now come from direct-mail offerings of books, music, and
videos.
</P>
<P>
   As important as innovation was to the Digest's success was an
almost 19th-century brand of idealism. ``The Digest always stood
above,'' says Carter. It strove to earn not just the loyalty of its
readers, but also their trust. The magazine didn't accept
advertising until 1955, for example, and didn't raise its original
cover price of 25 cents until 1957. The Digest was also a famously
generous employer. (Until a few years ago, all employees received a
complimentary turkey at Thanksgiving.)
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a whole different way of thinking about things,'' says
Peter Canning, author of ``American Dreamers: The Wallaces and
Reader's Digest'' and a former Digest managing editor. ``You really
did feel that the value of the magazine, of putting together the
best of popular media into a form that average people could read
and take value from, was an important function.''
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the only comparable media enterprise is the Walt Disney
Company: another icon of American culture, committed to traditional
family values, and very much the product of a visionary founder.
Yet where Disney now stands as a model of media-empire success _ a
globally recognized brand name with holdings in television, film,
publishing, and theme parks _ the Digest struggles. Thirty years
ago, the situation was reversed, with Disney seemingly in decline
after the death of its namesake founder, and the Digest
flourishing.
</P>
<P>
   Willcox, for one, finds the divergence in the two companies'
paths instructive. ``Disney has made some bets that have paid off
for them in a big way, and in areas where we have not made bets.
Probably, if you were to say the Reader's Digest needs to make some
bets, to move forward and grow the company, I'd say yes.''
</P>
<P>
   The question then becomes will they pay off? Can the company
come back? ``It is a very strong brand name, even among
non-readers,'' notes McAlpine. ``It's recognized. It has a high
degree of respectability and integrity behind the brand name.''
</P>
<P>
   It remains unclear, though, whether that very strength of the
brand name is more blessing or curse. ``That special status is the
spine of the magazine,'' says John Mack Carter, ``and without that
strength, without that history of cultural impact, I'd hesitate to
say what (Reader's Digest) might be. On the other hand, the very
phrase `had a cultural impact' suggests something musty, something
that belongs in a frame.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
AN OFFICE FOR THE ART LOVER &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   PLEASANTVILLE, N.Y. _ The 38 works of art that Sotheby's will
auction are the cream of an 8,000-work art collection that,
literally, covers much of the walls at Reader's Digest Global
Headquarters here.
</P>
<P>
   A visitor walking down a corridor or into a conference room
might encounter a Roy Lichtenstein or Alex Katz lithograph, a
Fairfield Porter oil, or a photograph by Diane Arbus or Robert
Mapplethorpe (neither a name normally associated with the Digest).
</P>
<P>
   ``Every employee gets to choose two works for his or her
office,'' explains Marianne Brunson Frisch, curator of the Digest's
corporate art collection. ``The policy is a legacy of Mrs.
Wallace's concern for the staff and her feeling that art brightened
the work environment.''
</P>
<P>
   Lila Acheson Wallace's taste in art reflected the consistently
optimistic tone of the magazine she helped to found. Alexander
Apsis, cochairman of Sotheby's Impressionist and Modern Art
Department, describes the paintings at auction as ``happy, pleasing
pictures, full of joie de vivre,'' words that might apply to her
acquisitions generally.
</P>
<P>
   The magazine not only funded Wallace's purchases but also helped
to inspire them. ``All those fancy New Yorkers think of us as this
tacky little magazine in the stupid suburbs,'' she once told a
friend. ``That's why I buy these paintings _ to show these snobs
we're not so dumb.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
READER'S DIGEST THROUGH THE YEARS
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   1922: First edition of magazine, with print run of 5,000 copies,
sold by subscription
</P>
<P>
   1929: First newsstand sales
</P>
<P>
   1938: First international edition (Great Britain)
</P>
<P>
   1950: Reader's Digest Condensed Books introduced
</P>
<P>
   1955: Magazine starts to include advertising
</P>
<P>
   1959: Direct-mail sales of recordings introduced
</P>
<P>
   1962: Reader's Digest Sweepstakes launched
</P>
<P>
   1981: Cofounder DeWitt Wallace dies at 91
</P>
<P>
   1984: Cofounder Lila Acheson Wallace dies at 94
</P>
<P>
   1986: Direct-mail sales of videos introduced
</P>
<P>
   1990: Reader's Digest Association stock publicly traded
</P>
<P>
   1996: Web site introduced
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-15-98 1627EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
