<SLUG> BC-PATENTS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PATENTS: STERILIZING FLOSS; KEEPING TRACK OF MEDICAL RECORDS 
</HEADLINE>
  (nk) 
 By SABRA CHARTRAND   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Most people dislike flossing their teeth, and would probably
have to admit that they do so irregularly. Flossing has such a bad
image that people tend to floss erratically even when they
understand that it is the only way to really clean below the gum
line. Recent research linking periodontal disease to heart attacks
probably will not change that.
</P>
<P>
   But Sean Dix is hoping that those people who do use dental floss
will prefer a sterile product. Dix is a former diamond cutter
turned inventor who won a patent a few years ago for inexpensive
plastic rings that aid flossing. He had trouble flossing himself
because of a skin condition: wrapping thin floss around his
fingertips further irritated them. So he designed the rings, won a
patent and got his product into drugstores across the country, quit
his diamond cutting job and became a full-time floss entrepreneur.
</P>
<P>
   Now Dix, who lives in New York, is expanding his business to
include his newly patented sterile dental floss. His latest
invention started when he was looking for a way to produce precut
segments of floss that would fit between his rings. That is when he
learned how floss is traditionally manufactured.
</P>
<P>
   ``Currently, floss is produced in spool form using machinery
slightly altered from the sewing thread industry,'' Dix explained.
``Thus, the spools are spun out into a bin six inches from the
floor.'' The spools are then assembled into individual packages by
hand, he added.
</P>
<P>
   ``The problem with hand assembly is that even though workers
wear gloves they still have the probability of dropping the spool
on the floor or scratching their face and then handling the
spools,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Some manufacturers also coat floss with beeswax, Dix said, which
``as an organic compound, naturally decays and promotes the growth
of mold.''
</P>
<P>
   The resulting product, Dix said, meets the Food and Drug
Administration's requirements of what is known as a 10-3 sterility
assurance level. Dix said that meant floss manufacturers had to
practice ``good manufacturing procedures.''
</P>
<P>
   ``An interesting comparison would be that Band-Aids are held by
FDA regulation to a 10-6, meaning zero microbes,'' he said. ``The
reason being that Band-Aids come into contact with the blood
through compromised tissue, much like floss comes into contact with
blood in the soft tissues beneath the gum line.''
</P>
<P>
   Not surprisingly, Dix said his market research had found that
``100 percent of those surveyed said they would choose a sterilized
floss over a nonsterilized floss if given the option.'' But he also
acknowledged that the National Institute of Dental Research had not
studied the possibility that floss can transmit bacteria.
</P>
<P>
   Under Dix's patent, floss assembly is automated. Parallel
strands of floss are stretched from master spools ``such that the
strands resemble a web coming off a loom,'' Dix writes in his
patent. The floss is laminated with two layers of a glassine
substrate that can be sterilized. Beads of melted adhesive are
dabbed on the floss at intervals, and then the web is cut at those
spots to create floss segments with sealed tips.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no human contact with the floss,'' so it stays clean,
he said. The master spool of floss and the paper used to package it
are loaded onto the machine at the same time, so that it can
produce packages containing 100 floss segments each. Dix received
patent 5,819,767.
</P>
<P>
   Keeping Track Of Medical Data
</P>
<P>
   In 1995, Stuart Bowie was visiting Laramie, Wyo., when a car hit
his vehicle broadside. The crash killed his two dogs, who were
riding in the back seat, but Bowie escaped with four broken ribs.
At the hospital emergency room, however, his blood pressure dropped
dangerously and a surgeon thought he might have internal bleeding.
</P>
<P>
   ``Aside from my Pennsylvania driver's license and Blue Cross
card, the physicians were treating me blind,'' Bowie, who lives in
Wallingford, Pa., remembered. ``I was in semishock, and they had no
way of knowing I have hypertension or any other factors which could
modify, preclude or obviate the need for a given procedure.''
</P>
<P>
   Thus the doctors had to order an array of tests that might not
have been necessary had they known his medical history. After
recovering, Bowie realized that in an emergency, time is often lost
to basic tests as doctors struggle to reach a diagnosis. Even
people who are familiar with their own medical history might end up
unconscious in an emergency room.
</P>
<P>
   That lead him to acquire a patent for a computer system that
uses a ``medical data smartcard'' bearing a person's entire medical
history.
</P>
<P>
   ``The U.S.A. has the finest medical technology, hospitals and
physicians, but an antique paper system of medical history
record-keeping,'' he said. ``Since the medical history is 90
percent of the diagnostic ball-game, the lack of a workable system
is dangerous, deprives indigent persons of care and adds
tremendously to the cost of care.''
</P>
<P>
   Bowie hopes an invention created by Sylvio Eberhardt, a
professor at Swarthmore College, will change that. Bowie financed
development of the research behind the patent, and then bought the
rights to the invention from Eberhardt.
</P>
<P>
   The system uses a network of computers and a credit card-sized
data storage device. Information is loaded, updated and maintained
on the card via a magnetic strip or through the kind of laser
embossing used to make compact discs. The smartcard would carry
information about medical conditions like diabetes,
hospitalizations or other treatments, surgeries, prescription
drugs, allergies or any other part of a medical history.
</P>
<P>
   A doctor, nurse or emergency technician would slip the card into
a computer terminal, and the data would be displayed on a monitor,
printed or transmitted to other computers. Information that
identified the patient could be encrypted to protect privacy in the
event that the data were downloaded to a hospital hard-drive or
transmitted via modem to another computer.
</P>
<P>
   The invention, which Bowie intends to market, received patent
5,832,488.
</P>
<P>
   Patents are available by number for $3 from the Patent and
Trademark Office, Washington, D.C. 20231. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
