<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IRAQ-RUSSIA-1116-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    IN PROTECTING IRAQ, RUSSIA WANTS WORLD ROLE, RENEWED ECONOMIC
TIES
 &HT;    EDs: Optional add begins at 250 words.
 &HT;    With US-IRAQ-1116.
 &HT;    By CHARLES W. HOLMES 
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW _ Since the end of the Persian Gulf War, Russia has
resolutely opposed U.S. and British efforts to punish Iraqi
President Saddam Hussein for his failure to cooperate with U.N.
weapons inspectors.
</P>
<P>
   Of the three permanent members of the U.N. Security Council that
have taken this position -- the others being China and France --
Russia has been among the most stalwart of Iraq's allies and a
diplomatic middleman between Washington and Baghdad.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts say Moscow is motivated global political stature and
domestic economics.
</P>
<P>
   In pushing Iraq's agenda, and opposing the United States, Russia
is able to flex its diplomatic muscle -- among the few strengths
the faded superpower has left.
</P>
<P>
   Russia also looks to the day when United Nations sanctions are
lifted. Its own economy in crisis, Russia sees urgently needed
economic potential in relations with Iraq as a partner in oil
production and a buyer of Russian arms.
</P>
<P>
   Before the economic crisis hit Russian in August, Russian oil
companies reportedly had signed an estimated $10 billion in
preliminary contracts with Iraq for the day when sanctions are
lifted.
</P>
<P>
   Furthermore, Iraq owes Russia about $7 billion for arms
purchases dating back to the Iran-Iraq war during the 1980s, when
the Soviet Union was a major arms supplier. Iraq cannot begin to
repay those debts until it can again export the bulk of its oil,
now forbidden under the U.N. sanctions.
</P>
<P>
   In the current crisis, over the weekend Russia played an active
role in seeking to clarify Iraq's intentions to the five-member
Security Council after Saddam announced that U.N. weapons
inspectors could reenter Iraq.
</P>
<P>
   (Story can end here. Optional add follows.)
</P>
<P>
   Russian officials in Moscow said Iraq's letter to the Security
Council was unambiguous.
</P>
<P>
   ``Baghdad's unequivocal reply provides the sound basis for a
political settlement over Iraq,'' Russian Deputy Foreign Minister
Viktor Posuvalyuk said on the Ekho Moskvy radio station Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   ``Grasping the meaning of the text that (Iraqi deputy prime
minister) Tariq Aziz turned over is like reading a legal, calm and
impartial document,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   In Kuala Lumpur, Malaysia, Russian Foreign Minister Igor Ivanov
warned that diplomacy must succeed. ``All other actions,
particularly unilateral, will only complicate the implementation of
the U.N. Security Council's resolution on Iraq,'' Ivanov said.
</P>
<P>
   After a meeting with U.S. Secretary of State Madeline Albright,
Ivanov said the U.S. and Russia have ``common final goals'' in
policy toward Iraq.
</P>
<P>
   The United States and Russia agree that Iraq should abide by
U.N. sanctions -- put in place before and after the 1991 Gulf War
-- that require inspections to guarantee that Saddam Hussein is not
rebuilding a weapons stockpile that could threaten the oil-rich
region.
</P>
<P>
   But with a sympathetic tenor, Russia also has called for a
timetable to ease the sanctions and has played a prominent role in
defusing previous stand-offs.
</P>
<P>
   In a similar round of tension between Iraq and the U.N, last
February, Russian President Boris Yeltsin went so far as to warn
that U.S. strikes against Iraq could lead to another world war. And
Defense Minister Igor Sergeyev warned that their differences over
Iraq could harm U.S.-Russian relations.
</P>
<P>
   Russian officials have toned down their talk this time.
</P>
<P>
   Yeltsin sent a letter to President Clinton on Saturday
expressing confidence that a diplomatic solution could be found to
ease the current stand-off, but placing wholly the blame for the
current tensions on Iraq.
</P>
<P>
   In Damascus on Sunday for meetings with Syrian officials,
Sergeyev told Russian reporters that the use of force contemplated
by the United States and its allies ``will be counter-productive.''
</P>
<P>
   Last November, Russian diplomats negotiated an end to a previous
dispute over weapons inspections in Iraq. For Russia, the
achievement provided a measure of international regard it once
enjoyed as a superpower. Russia is eager to repeat the success, but
seems unwilling in the current stand-off to confront the United
States with the same confrontation tone.
</P>
<P>
   Apparently uncertain whether the United States would act
unilaterally, Russia evacuated the families of its Iraq-based
diplomats from Baghdad on Sunday, the emergencies ministry said.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
