<HEADLINE>
A GORE'S FORAY INTO SECRET SERVICE  
 CONFESSION OF CANNIBALISM  
 STANDOFF IN CHARLOTTE  
 LUDLUM'S SWITCH 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Conn., N.C.)  (mk) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The second child of Vice President Al Gore has written an essay
for The Harvard Lampoon in which she satirizes the type of person
who might be drawn to the life of a Secret Service agent.
</P>
<P>
   In the October issue of the humor magazine, a six-paragraph
essay is signed by K.C.G. The writer, Kristin C. Gore, a senior at
Harvard University, is listed on the masthead. Matt Murray,
president of The Harvard Lampoon, confirmed that Ms. Gore wrote the
piece.
</P>
<P>
   The essay is told from the perspective of someone so mentally
unbalanced that he pretends he is a Secret Service agent, chasing
people down streets and offering to protect them.
</P>
<P>
   ``I decided early on that I had to either be a Secret Service
agent or live a life devoid of meaning,'' the article begins. It
goes on: ``My baby pictures depicted a gurgling young maverick clad
in dark sunglasses and an unwieldy earpiece. Strangers pitied me
for my debilitating cataracts and partial deafness, but you should
never talk to strangers. They usually don't understand cleft
tongues, and they also talk too softly and are blurry.''
</P>
<P>
   Referring to a Clint Eastwood movie about a secret agent, the
narrator says, ``On better days, I'd recite `In the Line of Fire'
in 25 minutes flat, augment my artillery arsenal with more shiny
objects and swear words, acquire extra-sensory perception, refuse
to testify, develop a clenched jawline, hit Taco Bell and choose my
protectee of the week.''
</P>
<P>
   ``These days,'' the narrator says, ``I spend my time driving
around the President of the United States in a camouflage golf-cart
with a bullet-proof attitude. I stop at every second light to run
background checks on foreign passersby, reload my paint-ball gun,
and make sure the Pres is strapped in tight.''
</P>
<P>
   Why would Ms. Gore write an essay in which an agent _ even
someone pretending to be one _ is portrayed as mentally defective
and dangerous? It was all in good fun, she says.
</P>
<P>
   ``I not only have the highest possible regard for the Secret
Service, I am extremely grateful to them for the work they do and
the professional way in which do it,'' she says. ``This piece was
intended as a spoof in a college humor magazine. I would never
express any disrespect for the Secret Service, and I regret if
anyone misinterpreted it that way.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Alex Kuczynski &QR;
</P>
<P>
   Art Criticism Recycled in Time
</P>
<P>
   The nation's highest-profile art critic confessing to ...
cannibalism?
</P>
<P>
   Well, kind of. In last week's issue of Time, Robert Hughes, the
magazine's star art critic and author of ``American Visions''
(Knopf, 1997), a top-selling survey of American art that grew out
of a popular TV series, apologized to readers for plagiarizing
material.
</P>
<P>
   Time's issue two weeks before had contained Hughes' review of a
show of American and Australian landscapes at the Wadsworth
Atheneum, the nation's oldest public art museum, in Hartford, Conn.
The opening sentences turned out to be embarrassingly close to
those of a review in July in the magazine ``Australian Art
Collector'' by a Boston art writer, Patricia Macdonald.
</P>
<P>
   She started her piece: ``If you started digging on the banks of
the Hudson River _ birthplace of American landscape painting where
Thomas Cole, his most famous pupil Frederick Church and Albert
Bierstadt all lived and worked _ and kept going on through the
centre of the earth you would emerge a little to the northeast of
Tasmania right about where John Glover arrived in Australia.''
</P>
<P>
   Hughes' Time article began: ``Suppose you started digging a hole
on the bank of the Hudson River, the cradle of American 19th
century landscape as painted by Thomas Cole, Frederick Church, and
others. Suppose you kept digging straight down through the center
of the earth and came out on the other side. The hole would open up
just off Tasmania, the island state of Australia, painted in the
19th century by, among others, John Glover and W.C. Piguenit.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Macdonald wrote Hughes and in Time's last issue he
apologized: ``To my embarrassment I seem to have cannibalized it,
but it was entirely unconscious.''
</P>
<P>
   As it turned out, Ms. Macdonald said, Hughes had recited her
same material earlier in a talk at the Atheneum on Oct. 23. She
arrived late and missed it. But she made light of it, praising
Hughes. ``The taller the poppy, the more people want to cut it
down,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Hughes called the matter closed. ``If I made my career as a
cannibal I wouldn't have had a career,'' he said. Christopher
Porterfield, executive editor of Time, which is owned by
Time-Warner Inc., said he was satisfied the borrowing was
inadvertent. ``Bob is hardly in need of somebody else's words,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   But with several other art scholars claiming their insights and
arguments have cropped up without credit in ``American Visions,''
the College Art Association, which represents 14,000 academics and
2,000 institutions, has scheduled a panel at its annual meeting in
February on ``American Revisions: Evaluating Robert Hughes' Media
Blitz.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Ralph Blumenthal &QR;
</P>
<P>
   An Endorsement That Wasn't
</P>
<P>
   The Charlotte (N.C.) Observer's publisher added one more
surprise to this fall's election season when he scuttled his
paper's endorsement of North Carolina's Democratic Senate candidate
just before the election. Then, more than 40 journalists in the
Observer's newsroom surprised him with passionate objections to the
decision.
</P>
<P>
   Peter Ridder had wanted his newspaper to endorse the Republican
incumbent, Lauch Faircloth, but found himself at odds with his two
top editors and all the editorial writers, who supported the
Democratic candidate and eventual victor, John Edwards.
</P>
<P>
   The immediate result of the standoff was an editorial that was
the newspaper's first nonendorsement in a Senate race in 20 years.
That, in turn, generated a strongly worded round-robin open letter
from the editors and reporters, most of whom argued that the
newspaper, which is owned by Knight Ridder, failed its readers.
</P>
<P>
   ``No one disputes that it is a publisher's prerogative to
overrule an editorial board, or that differences of opinion will _
and should _ surface,'' the authors wrote in the declaration
circulated around the newsroom. ``Yet when a publisher overturns
the judgment of skilled journalists, we wonder whether that has
implications for the journalistic integrity of the newspaper.''
</P>
<P>
   Among those who added his comments was Taylor Batten, recently
promoted to an editing job, who wrote ``the paper, which should
love this community, abdicated its role by failing to take a stand
one way or the other.'' Batten's name has resonance beyond his own
newsroom; he is the son of Knight Ridder's longtime chief
executive, James Batten, who died in 1995. Ridder, the publisher,
is the brother of the company's current chief executive, Anthony
Ridder.
</P>
<P>
   Ridder, who came to Charlotte in September 1997, said: ``I think
you'll find that publishers and editorial boards will never agree
on every issue. Do they compromise? I would hope so.'' Of the
staff's reaction, he said, ``I want them to understand that I have
the same values as they do.''
</P>
<P>
   Ed Williams, editor of the editorial pages at The Observer, said
of the dispute: ``We compromised by not firing the publisher. And
he didn't fire us.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Felicity Barringer &QR;
</P>
<P>
   Robert Ludlum Signs With St. Martin's
</P>
<P>
   Robert Ludlum, master of international intrigue and weaver of
grand-scale conspiracy plots, is departing his paperback publisher
of more than two decades. But the reason seems rather dull for an
author whose spies are constantly foiling world takeovers.
</P>
<P>
   Is he leaving because a vast, sprawling global conglomerate,
Bertelsmann AG, has merged his longtime publisher, Bantam Books,
with Random House?
</P>
<P>
   No. At age 70, Ludlum, author of novels like ``The Matarese
Circle'' and ``The Bourne Identity,'' said he moved to St. Martin's
Press because it would give him more time to work on his books. His
eight-figure contract _ which one publishing executive estimated at
about $4 million for each hardcover book _ calls for him to write
three hardcover books and four paperback originals that will have a
co-author.
</P>
<P>
   Ludlum's agent, Henry Morrison, said the move was also
precipitated by a need for a ``fresh'' publishing approach, a
desire that has taken hold with other authors like Stephen King who
speak of publishing relationships as if they are grading the
quality of stem roses.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are things that they were talking to us about that
seemed very fresh, very enthusiastic, and hopefully this will bring
us to a new plateau,'' Morrison said of the appeal of St. Martin's,
which is owned by Holtzbrinck GmbH. Ludlum's sales had settled to a
level of about 450,000 copies for the last few years, said one
publishing executive, who spoke on condition of anonymity. But
Morrison noted that ``even some of the biggest names have seen
erosion in the market.''
</P>
<P>
   Matthew Shear, publisher of St. Martin's mass-market division,
said he intended to publish Ludlum's books more regularly. ``What
happens is that the publication of these authors can often become
rote, but you need to have fresh ideas come out of it, fresh ideas
on how to package,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   _ Doreen Carvajal &QR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
