   NATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   ANATOMY OF A CRASH
</P>
<P>
   Award-winning Atlanta Journal-Constitution reporter Gary M.
Pomerantz trekked thousands of miles _ from Georgia to Maine to
Texas to Alaska _ to track down and interview survivors of ASA
Flight 529, a small propeller-driven plane that crashed in a
hayfield in West Georgia killing 10 of the 29 people aboard. In a
seven-part series, Pomerantz vividly describes the 9 minutes and 20
seconds of horror aboard the doomed aircraft and how the tragedy
has reshaped lives. Photos and illustrations for the series and
layouts from Parts One, Two and Three will be posted in a folder
slugged ASA-CRASH in the National folder on the Cox server. Here is
the budget line for Part Two:
</P>
<P>
   DAY 2 _ Nov. 16
</P>
<P>
   CRASH-THEFIRE _ The little propeller-driven plane with 29 people
aboard fell out of the sky at 140 miles per hour. It sliced through
treetops and bore down on a hayfield in Carrollton, Ga. The left
wing tip gouged the earth first. The wing ripped away from the body
of the plane as dirt clods and rocks flew. The plane's nose next
skidded on its underside. Then the one-winged plane went airborne
again, bouncing up a ridge about 100 feet, the first killing steps
in a macabre dance of physics. The plane was in pieces, connected
only by a common fate. (Pomerantz, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
WITH PHOTOS. MOVED
</P>
<P>
   SOUTH-SUMMIT _ BIRMINGHAM, Ala. _ Spot coverage of the
``Unfinished Business'' summit on Southern social progress.
(Shepard, Cox News Service). EDs: ETA 6:30 p.m. EST.
</P>
<P>
   RONPAUL-TEX _ WASHINGTON _ A would-be House leader called Rep.
Ron Paul, R-Surfside, last week and asked for Paul's vote,
promising that he would ``make the trains run on time'' if elected
this week. Oops. Wrong number. In Congress-speak, ``making the
trains run on time'' means moving legislation, particularly the
federal spending bills, to the House floor and passage as smoothly
as possible. The chugging of those trains is not necessarily a
pleasant sound to Paul, a former Libertarian presidential candidate
who believes the Constitution places strict limits on what Congress
can do. (Harlan, Cox News Service) MOVED
</P>
<P>
   CALL-TEACHER-SUBSTITUTES _ SPRINGFIELD, Ohio _ A $20,000
computer system is helping Springfield City Schools alleviate a
substitute teacher shortage. Called Substitute Employee Management
System, or SEMS, the program has been in place since Sept. 21 and
can call six substitutes at one time. (Kash, Springfield News-Sun)
MOVED
</P>
<P>
   INTERNATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   US-IRAQ _ WASHINGTON _ For the second time in nine months,
President Clinton has taken a massive strike force to the brink of
an attack against Iraq, only to draw back in the face of
last-minute concessions from Saddam Hussein. Both men dutifully
demonstrated their now familiar abilities to engage, then withdraw,
from a dangerous, and costly, contest pitting the will of the
world's mightiest military power against the wiles of its most
menacing dictator. Moving forward, Clinton and Saddam are in much
the same position as they were when the year began. The long-term
solution, a weary Clinton said Sunday, is for Saddam to step down _
willingly or not. Developing. LEDE-ALL. (Deans, Cox News Service).
EDs: ETA 6:30 p.m. EST.
</P>
<P>
   w/IRAQ-OPPOSITION _ AMMAN, Jordan _ Moauth Abdul Raheem used to
be Saddam Hussein's mouthpiece before he fled Iraq and defected.
Though the United States did not strike Iraq in this latest round
of cat-and-mouse over weapons inspections, this avuncular
66-year-old thinks the time will come. ``I am not disappointed. If
this opportunity was missed, there will be lots of other
opportunities,'' said Raheem. Raheem's Iraqi National Accord is one
of the groups that could stand the most to gain from the latest
stand off with Saddam Hussein. As ``Saddam Fatigue'' _ as one Arab
diplomat calls it _ builds, Saddam faces less support from his
traditional allies and, possibly, more active opposition. (Kaplow,
Cox News Service). EDs: ETA 6:30 p.m. EST.
</P>
<P>
   w/IRAQ-RUSSIA _ MOSCOW _ Since the end of the Gulf War, Russia
has resolutely opposed U.S. and British efforts to punish Saddam
Hussein for his failure to cooperate with U.N. weapons inspectors.
Of the three permanent members of the U.N. National Security
Council that have done so, Russia has been among the most stalwart
of Iraq's allies and a diplomatic middleman between Washington and
Baghdad. Analysts say Moscow is motivated global political stature
and domestic economics. (Holmes, Cox News Service) MOVED
</P>
<P>
   BRITAIN-THANKS _ LONDON _ Plymouth, ``the cradle of New
England'' will become a little America this November, when it hosts
its first Thanksgiving Festival. Hoping to attract the tens of
thousands of Americans living in the United Kingdom and Europe, the
festival will last Nov. 26 to Nov. 29. Events will include a Big
Band Thanksgiving Dinner, and the arrival in Plymouth docks of the
NATO Standing Naval Force Atlantic, led by the US Warship USS
Stark. (Roughton, Cox News Service). EDs: ETA 6:30 p.m. EST.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
