<SLUG> BC-BIZGLANCE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSINESS AT A GLANCE 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEAGRAM EXPECTED TO OUST HEAD OF UNIVERSAL STUDIOS
</P>
<P>
   ``Meet Joe Black,'' the lavish three-hour film made by Universal
Studios, opened over the weekend to poor reviews and a
disappointing box office, increasing the expectations in the movie
industry that Seagram, the studio's owner, planned to oust Frank
Biondi Jr., Universal's chairman and chief executive.
</P>
<P>
   Entertainment industry executives close to Edgar Bronfman Jr.,
Seagram's chairman, predicted that he would dismiss Biondi within
the next few weeks, possibly earlier. At the same time, these
executives said, Bronfman plans to revamp the corporate set-up so
that various divisions like movies and music report directly to
him.
</P>
<P>
   ORACLE TAKES ON OPERATING SYSTEMS
</P>
<P>
   As the Comdex computer industry trade show opens in Las Vegas,
the chairman of Oracle plans to introduce a new version of his
company's database program that he hopes will do away almost
entirely with the operating system on computer servers.
</P>
<P>
   ANYBODY HAVE AN OLD $20?
</P>
<P>
   When the Treasury Department issued a redesigned $20 bill in
September, officials said that the new notes would help thwart
counterfeiting by keeping ahead of digital printing technology. But
virtually no vending machines that take twenties accept the new
bills. And it will be well into next year before they do. About
100,000 merchandise vending machines accept $20 bills, as do many
change makers and digital vending machines.
</P>
<P>
   DEAL FOR FIBER OPTIC LINES
</P>
<P>
   Cable and Wireless PLC of Britain has agreed to buy roughly $400
million worth of fiber optic lines from Global Crossing, a small
international communications carrier.
</P>
<P>
   UNFETTERED OPTIMISM FOR INTERNET
</P>
<P>
   The stocks of two newly public companies _ Theglobe.com and
Earthweb _ soared last week as investors once again rushed to buy
up the promise of the Internet. Small investors pushed the prices
of many Internet stocks to levels that not only seemed to defy
gravity but also common sense.
</P>
<P>
   NEWS ORGANIZATIONS PUSH INTO CUBA
</P>
<P>
   At a time when the volume of foreign news is dwindling, networks
are eliminating foreign news bureaus and newspapers are playing
down reports from overseas, a dozen news organizations are making a
considerable effort to open news bureaus in Cuba.
</P>
<P>
   BERKSHIRE ASSETS DROP 15 PERCENT
</P>
<P>
   Berkshire Hathaway, the investment and insurance company led by
the billionaire Warren Buffett, had a 15 percent drop in assets in
the third quarter.
</P>
<P>
   VALUE OF `ER' DEPRECIATES
</P>
<P>
   When NBC decided to pay $13 million for each new episode of
``ER,'' it made history: no one had ever paid more for a show. But
the show's high ratings are at least giving the network value for
price. The cable channel TNT paid a record $1 million an episode
for four years of repeats. Judging by the ratings so far, the
return is a bit more risky.
</P>
</TEXT>
