   BOEING-SST (Seattle) _ At an evangelical church not far from
Disney World, services were held in the shadow of its massive
variable-sweep wings and five-story tail. Several times it was
nearly sold for scrap metal. And for the past eight years, it
deteriorated in the rain and Florida humidity at a junkyard near
Cape Canaveral, covered by weeds and all but forgotten, the last
artifact of America's efforts to build a supersonic passenger
plane. Now, the full-scale, $11 million mock-up of The Boeing Co.'s
supersonic transport has finally found a permanent home, thanks to
a California aviation pioneer who had help from friends at Boeing.
</P>
