<HEADER>
A1652 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IRAQ-OPPOSITION-1116-     11-15 0820
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IRAQ-OPPOSITION-1116-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    IRAQI OPPOSITION GETS BOOST IN CLINTON SPEECH, BUT ARE THEY
READY?
 &HT;    EDs: Optional add begins at 550 words.
 &HT;    With US-IRAQ-1116.
 &HT;    By LARRY KAPLOW 
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   AMMAN, Jordan _ President Bill Clinton's pledge Sunday to
increase support for Iraqi leader Saddam Hussein's opponents
involves a massive challenge in organizing rival groups and
reversing a history of American-backed failures.
</P>
<P>
   It also signals an important shift to a policy that Clinton's
own administration recently derided.
</P>
<P>
   But, it was good news to a former top official in the Iraqi
information ministry, who has gone from being Saddam Hussein's
mouthpiece to representing a group that aims to unseat his old
boss.
</P>
<P>
   In his sparsely-furnished home in exile in Jordan's capital,
Moath(CQ) Abdul Raheem said that, even though this crisis ended in
diplomacy, there will be others that could bring military strikes
against Saddam.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am not disappointed. If this opportunity was missed, there
will be lots of other opportunities,'' Raheem, spokesman for the
Iraqi National Accord opposition group, said.
</P>
<P>
   Raheem's group has received limited backing from the United
States for years. He said Clinton's pledge Sunday, ``moves us
faster toward a long term solution for the problem of the Iraqi
people.''
</P>
<P>
   But, even within the Clinton administration there has long been
doubt about whether Raheem's groups or others can do the job.
</P>
<P>
   On Oct. 31, Clinton reluctantly signed a Congressional plan
letting the administration give opposition groups access to $97
million in military training. The plan also includes $38 million to
start beaming Radio Free Iraq into Saddam's state.
</P>
<P>
   A few days before, the man who heads the military's central
command that oversees U.S. operations in the Persian Gulf
criticized the concept.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think this has been very well thought out,'' Gen.
Anthony Zinni said at the time. ``A Saddam in place and contained
is better than promoting something that causes Iraq to explode,
implode, fragment into pieces, cause turmoil in the region; which
could happen if he comes down in the wrong way.''
</P>
<P>
   The opposition is divided into some 70 groups that are often
rivals. They include two Kurdish groups that have fiercely opposed
each other. Hussein opponents within the Shiite Muslim minority in
southern Iraq suffer severe repression. Then, there is Raheem's INA
and the most prominent group, the Iraqi National Congress.
</P>
<P>
   Amatzia Baram, an Israeli specialist on Iraq, said the United
States would have to consolidate the 10 most prominent groups. That
will involve getting religious fundamentalists to cooperate with
secular groups, communists with elitists. He said the INA,
meanwhile, has a track record for being anti-American.
</P>
<P>
   Then, they would need a strategy and a place in Iraq to base the
movement. That may require protection from U.S. ground forces,
which could anger Arabs in the region and endanger troops. This
process could take five years.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton said the U.S. effort has been increasing already.
</P>
<P>
   ``Over the past year we have deepened our engagement with the
forces of change in Iraq, reconciling the two largest Kurdish
opposition groups, beginning broadcasts of a Radio Free Iraq
throughout the country,'' Clinton said. ``We will intensify that
effort.''
</P>
<P>
   (EDs: Story can end here. Optional add follows.)
</P>
<P>
   But, American policy has been scarcely better organized than the
opposition groups themselves. Former President George Bush
encouraged a rebellion shortly after the 1991 Gulf War. But, when
an uprising started, Saddam used helicopter gunships -- allowed to
fly by the American-brokered ceasfire -- to snuff out the
rebellion.
</P>
<P>
   There have been other gory failures. The U.S. encouraged a
rebellion in 1995, then called it off. But, it was still attempted
and got crushed. In 1996, Saddam crushed the CIA-backed efforts of
the INA and INC when he executed about 100 people, reportedly army
officers, who he believed were planning a coup.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Congress and the White House have fought about
whether the U.S. should back coups from within Saddam's government
or strengthen outside movements, whether the toppling of Saddam
would empower Iran next door, or whether the United States will
have to commit air power or ground forces to assist the opposition
-- who have no stronghold in Iraq from which to launch its efforts.
</P>
<P>
   Through it all, the 61-year-old Saddam Hussein has survived
several assassination attempts. Though his army has been weakened
by eight years of weapons inspections and sanctions, his security
apparatus is extensive and feared.
</P>
<P>
   Saddam has held nearly absolute power in his country more than
20 years and used chemical weapons against the opposition.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
