<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-15 18:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1654 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-US-IRAQ-1116-COX     11-15 1220
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-US-IRAQ-1116-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    CLINTON CALLS OFF DOGS OF WAR, CALLS FOR IRAQI OPPOSITION TO
SADDAM
 &HT;    EDs: Optional add begins at 850 words.
 &HT;    With IRAQ-OPPOSITION-1116; IRAQ-RUSSIA-1116.
 &HT;    By BOB DEANS 
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Twice in nine months, President Clinton has ordered
a massive U.S. strike force to the brink of war against Iraq, only
to draw back in the face of last-minute concessions by Saddam
Hussein.
</P>
<P>
   While he declared victory Sunday after the latest crisis eased,
Clinton also voiced frustration with an eight-year-old containment
policy and the costly and dangerous pattern of brinkmanship it has
engendered.
</P>
<P>
   While he vowed to continue that policy, Clinton stressed that it
was no substitute for a permanent solution to one of his greatest
foreign policy headaches. What's needed, he said, are stepped-up
U.S. efforts to help opposition groups that seek to oust Saddam and
replace his regime with a new government.
</P>
<P>
   ''Saddam Hussein remains an impediment to the well-being of his
people and a threat to the peace of his region and the security of
the world,'' Clinton told reporters at a hastily-called White House
news conference.
</P>
<P>
   ''We will continue to contain the threat he poses,'' Clinton
said. ''However, over the long term, the best way to address that
threat is through a government in Baghdad, a new government that is
committed to represent and respect its people, not repress them;
that is committed to peace in the region,'' said Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   ''Over the past year we have deepened our engagement with the
forces of change in Iraq,'' he said. ''We will intensify that
effort.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Deputy Prime Minister Tariq Aziz criticized Clinton's vow that
the American government is committed to replacing Saddam's regime
in Iraq.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have to condemn strongly the statement of Mr. Clinton, the
plans of his government to overthrow the government of Iraq,'''
Aziz said in an interview on CNN. ``This is a flagrant violation of
the Security Council resolutions as well as international law.''
</P>
<P>
   After ordering a massive attack of cruise missiles and smart
bombs against Iraq on Saturday, Clinton rescinded the command later
in the day to give his security team time to assess an 11th-hour
offer by Iraq to allow United Nations teams to inspect its alleged
chemical, biological and nuclear weapons programs.
</P>
<P>
   Asked how close Iraq came to being attacked on Saturday, U.S.
Defense Secretary William Cohen told reporters ''very close.''
</P>
<P>
   Late Saturday, Clinton rejected Iraq's offer, claiming that it
was laden with conditions.
</P>
<P>
   Iraq denied the charge, but sent two letters to the United
Nations by early Sunday stating specifically that it intended to
permit the inspections, without conditions.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton declared victory for diplomacy backed by the threat of
force, just as he did last February when, after a massive military
build-up in the Persian Gulf, Saddam reversed an earlier decision
to end the U.N. inspections.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our willingness to strike, together with the overwhelming
weight of world opinion, produced the outcome we preferred: Saddam
Hussein reversing course, letting the inspectors go back to work
without restrictions or conditions,'' said Clinton. ''They have
been, and they remain, the most effective tool to uncover, destroy
and prevent Iraq from rebuilding its weapons of mass destruction
and the missiles to deliver them.''
</P>
<P>
   In Baghdad, however, Iraq declared itself the victor in the
dispute, with Vice President Taha Yassin Ramadan telling state-run
television that Iraq had been able ``to prove to the whole world
that our views are correct'' and that the Americans were misguided.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the foundation and the basis of our victory,'' he
declared in the first official reaction to the weekend's tumultuous
events.
</P>
<P>
   And, as he did in February, Clinton said Saddam would be judged
by his actions, not his words, and that the United States would
remain vigilant and prepared to act should Iraq go back on its
word.
</P>
<P>
   ''This is not a question of faith, this is a question of
action,'' Clinton said, adding that ''Iraq must live up to its
obligations,'' by granting U.N. inspectors ''unfettered access to
inspect and to monitor all sites they choose with no restrictions
or qualifications.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton made clear, however, that efforts to contain Iraq will
be unsatisfying, so long as Saddam remains in power.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton stopped short of calling for Saddam's overthrow, and it
wasn't clear whether his comments reflected the start of an
aggressive campaign to unseat the Iraqi dictator, or merely a
calibrated increase in what have been acknowledged as anemic
efforts to date to counter Saddam's regime by backing his
opponents.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton said, however, that efforts to replace Saddam must be
part of an overall U.S. strategy and suggested that, otherwise,
Saddam would continue to menace his oil-rich Persian Gulf neighbors
and harry the United States.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was not calling for the overthrow of Saddam Hussein,''
Cohen said. ''What he was saying is that we are prepared, and we
will work with opposition forces or groups to try to bring about in
some future time a more democratic type of regime that is more
responsive to its people, and not to engage in the harsh and brutal
repression of them.''
</P>
<P>
   (EDs: Story can end here. Optional add follows.)
</P>
<P>
   Without endorsing any specific initiative, Sen. John McCain,
R-Ariz., agreed with Clinton that Saddam is the problem, and air
strikes, much less the threat of them, won't resolve it.
</P>
<P>
   ''Again, we have allowed Saddam Hussein to set the agenda and
put us on this roller coaster, which doesn't seem to end,'' McCain
told the ABC television network. ''We have to change this
equation.''
</P>
<P>
   Talk of trying to oust Saddam, 61, raises chilling memories of
the weeks following the end of the Gulf War, when, after President
Bush suggested that Iraqis might overthrow Saddam, he launched a
ruthless crackdown on his Kurdish opponents in northern Iraq and
other opposition groups in the south.
</P>
<P>
   Two years ago Saddam routed Kurdish opposition groups that had
been backed by the United States, killing hundreds and backing
others into remote mountains before a core of some 2,000 could be
evacuated by the United States.
</P>
<P>
   The United States operates Radio Free Iraq, an Arabic-language
radio broadcast beamed across most of the country, and has worked
on a modest level with expatriate Iraqis opposed to Saddam.
</P>
<P>
   After roughly two decades in office, though, Saddam has built a
potent security apparatus that has either murdered, imprisoned, run
out of the country or otherwise stifled any meaningful, open
dissent.
</P>
<P>
   That has helped Saddam retain his grip on power in a country
that has been ravaged by his rule.
</P>
<P>
   McCain said the time had come for more aggressive U.S. support
for building opposition groups within Iraq.
</P>
<P>
   ''There is a growing consensus, not only in the United States,
but around the world, that Saddam Hussein poses an unacceptable
threat and he should be removed,'' said McCain.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's a very difficult operation. It's fraught with difficulty.
But we have to set up a resistance organization within Iraq.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
