<SLUG> BC-BOX-NOTEBOOK-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JONES' LESSON MAKES AN IMPRESSION ON A TEACHER 
DELAY FOR TYSON
</HEADLINE>
  (ms) 
 By TIMOTHY W. SMITH   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   JONES' LESSON MAKES AN IMPRESSION ON A TEACHER
</P>
<P>
   MASHANTUCKET, Conn. _ Everyone thought Roy Jones Jr. was the
superior fighter when his light-heavyweight title bout against Otis
Grant, a middleweight moving up in weight, was announced.
</P>
<P>
   That fact became evident Saturday night in the bout's sixth
round when Jones landed a right uppercut that sent Grant crashing
to the canvas, flat on his back with his heels going over his head.
After that, Jones, clearly aware of his vast superiority and not
wishing to punish Grant further, pulled back. His inactivity in the
seventh round was so great that Referee Arthur Mercante Jr. had to
admonish him to fight.
</P>
<P>
   That he did. A straight right that landed flush on Grant's face
in the 10th round sat him on the seat of his pants. That prompted
Grant's manager, Russ Anber, to throw in the towel and follow it
into the ring to save his battered fighter. Jones (38-1) won on a
knockout when Mercante agreed to stop the fight at 1 minute 18
seconds of the round.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not going to punish a guy if I don't have to,'' Jones
said. ``I'll try to hit him every now and then to knock him out.
But to go out and brutalize a guy, why do it?''
</P>
<P>
   So, Jones sought to land a knockout punch, but could not. So,
instead, the courageous Grant took a battering.
</P>
<P>
   Jones has created his boxing conundrum. He only selects
opponents whom he likes and respects. He respects them because they
have heart and courage and they are good boxers. Once he gets them
into the ring, he finds it difficult to administer the types of
beatings required to take out a highly trained boxer with heart and
courage.
</P>
<P>
   Such was the case with Grant (31-2-1), whose corner had warned
him after the first knockdown that if he took another shot like
that they would stop the fight.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think he needed to put on a Rocky Balboa showing to
show how great and tough he is and go out of the ring with his face
all mangled,'' Anber said.
</P>
<P>
   Grant, a special-education teacher in Montreal, said he had
nothing to be embarrassed about. ``I gave it my best shot,'' said
Grant, who earned $450,000 and will return to his teaching job on
Monday morning. ``I came up short. Life goes on.''
</P>
<P>
   As for Jones, who knows? He selects his own opponents. He has
some mandatory bouts to defend the World Boxing Association and
World Boxing Council light-heavyweight titles, but no one is
holding his breath waiting for him to fight any of them. Jones said
he had no interest in going to Germany to defend against Graciano
Rocchigiani.
</P>
<P>
   In the co-feature Saturday night, Sugar Shane Mosley also
benefited from a compassionate corner. Mosley scored a knockout
against Jesse James Leija when Referee Eddie Cotton stopped the
fight at the end of the ninth round. As in Grant's case, Leija's
corner did not want him to continue to take a beating from the
speedy Mosley.
</P>
<P>
   Mosley (30-0) kept his International Boxing Federation
lightweight title and walked away with sore hands. It was a product
of bouncing his fists off the top of Leija's hard head. Mosley said
Leija would come in with his head lowered, and it provided Mosley
with an easy target.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the fifth round I noticed that my left hand was hurting, so
I quit throwing the jab so much and started working the body,''
Mosley said. ``In the sixth round my right hand started to hurt.
But I kept working the body. I think that's what did it for me.''
</P>
<P>
   Leija (37-4-2) is a tough former two-time world champion who
previously had only been stopped by Oscar De La Hoya and Azumah
Nelson.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've fought on HBO three times, and I've lost three times,
because every time they put me in with someone like Godzilla,''
Leija said.
</P>
<P>
   HBO announced it had signed Mosley to a long-term contract that
would allow him to eventually move up to the 140-pound class, where
there are some intriguing matchups for a boxer who is beginning to
display matchless skills. Mosley's next fight will be in February
or March and there are many good opponents. Among those in the
lightweight division are Cesar Bazan and Ivan Robinson. When Mosley
moves up to the 140-pound division, he could face Miguel Angel
Gonzalez, Kostya Tszyu and Vince Phillips.
</P>
<P>
   DELAY FOR TYSON
</P>
<P>
   A news conference scheduled for Tuesday in New York City to
announce Mike Tyson's return to boxing has been postponed by
Showtime, which will broadcast the bout, because contracts with
Francois Botha, Tyson's opponent, and with the MGM Grand hotel in
Las Vegas, Nev., the site of the Jan. 16 fight, have not been
signed. No new date for the news conference has been set, but the
fight itself is not in jeopardy.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-15-98 1851EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
