<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-15 18:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1658 &Cx1f; tth-z
r w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DUNN-GOP-SPI &LR;      11-15 1113
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DUNN-GOP-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DUNN'S FUND-RAISING COULD PRODUCE VOTES IN LEADERSHIP CONTEST 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By MICHAEL PAULSON  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Late last summer, Rep. Jennifer Dunn took a quick
trip to Southern California to help out one of her most endangered
colleagues, Rep. Brian Bilbray, a Republican from La Jolla.
</P>
<P>
   Now, as Dunn, R-Wash., wages an uphill campaign to become House
majority leader, Bilbray is returning the favor, supporting Dunn as
she takes on the incumbent, Dick Armey of Texas, and the insurgent,
former Seattle Seahawk Steve Largent of Oklahoma.
</P>
<P>
   Dunn's labors on behalf of her fellow Republicans, which began
more than two decades ago when Dunn was a foot soldier in the 1976
Ronald Reagan presidential campaign, are a major selling point as
she campaigns to become the first woman to hold a top job in the
House.
</P>
<P>
   It remains unclear whether Dunn's party-building work, combined
with her gender and her communications skills, will be enough to
overcome GOP reservations about her support for abortion rights and
a voting record that is a hair less conservative than that of her
two opponents.
</P>
<P>
   But if she does eke out a surprise victory, the sometime
gardener will owe her victory in no small part to her
oft-demonstrated willingness to do the spade work of politics:
raising money.
</P>
<P>
   A staunch opponent of campaign finance reform, Dunn raised money
at a furious pace over the past two years. According to the most
recent documents on file with the Federal Election Commission, Dunn
raised $1.3 million for her personal campaign treasury, and another
$100,000 for a so-called ``leadership'' political action committee
used as a legal means of circumventing campaign finance limits. She
also raised $54,000 for a second leadership PAC she uses to help
GOP candidates for the Washington state Legislature.
</P>
<P>
   Dunn, whose congressional district is considered safely
Republican and who faced an articulate but underfunded challenger
this year, gave generously to other Republican candidates. From her
personal campaign treasury she doled out $57,500 to the National
Republican Congressional Committee, the main campaign arm of House
Republicans, and $31,000 directly to the campaigns of 28 Republican
House candidates. And from her leadership PAC she gave $67,500 to
35 Republican candidates for the House.
</P>
<P>
   Dunn's efforts this year cap a long career of activity on behalf
of other Republicans. She claims to have raised $13 million while
chairwoman of the state Republican Party. As a freshman in
Congress, she was one of the top four fund-raisers for the National
Republican Congressional Committee, bringing in $270,000. In
Washington state, she used her own mailing list to raise money for
other Republican candidates for Congress, and she hosted a
reception at the state GOP convention at which the price of
admission was a donation to any Republican running for Congress.
</P>
<P>
   She often walks the half block from her office to the National
Republican Congressional Committee, where she can use special
telephones to make fund-raising calls. In 1996, she was the
co-chairwoman of the House-Senate Republican dinner, an annual
fund-raiser to which she sold tickets worth $350,000.
</P>
<P>
   Also in 1996, she gave $75,000 from her own campaign treasury to
82 Republicans and $47,000 from her Washington Fund to 28
Republican candidates, and in 1997 she was elected vice-chairwoman
of the House Republican Conference, the highest post ever held by a
woman.
</P>
<P>
   Dunn's efforts pale in comparison to those of the established
top party leadership _ outgoing House Speaker Newt Gingrich raised
$7.5 million through his personal campaign and his leadership PAC,
while Armey raised $2.9 million. But Dunn's efforts were impressive
for a junior member of leadership. She was just behind Majority
Whip Tom Delay's $1.6 million effort, and slightly ahead of House
Republican Conference Chairman John Boehner's $1.2 million pace.
</P>
<P>
   Her efforts this year to help Republicans around the country may
be partly to blame for a price paid back home. Voters in Dunn's
district re-elected her with 59 percent of the vote. That's a
result that would be enviable in many districts around the country,
but one that raised eyebrows in Washington state, even among Dunn
partisans, because it was the congresswoman's worst performance
ever.
</P>
<P>
   ``She will never have an easy ride again if I have anything to
say about it,'' said state Democratic Party Chairman Paul Berendt.
</P>
<P>
   The Republican Party also suffered some of its worst losses this
year in Dunn's backyard.
</P>
<P>
   In Washington state the Republicans lost two of the six
congressional seats they had held, lost control of the state
Senate, and, depending on the final count of absentee ballots, will
likely be forced to share control of a state House evenly divided
between Republican and Democratic lawmakers. Among the GOP's likely
losses were three state House seats located in Dunn's congressional
district.
</P>
<P>
   ``She spent all this time running around the country,
campaigning for these Republicans, gathering chits for this
leadership battle, and what happens but we're the only state in the
Union that had more than one seat (in Congress) turn over,''
Berendt said. ``If she had wanted to make a contribution to her
caucus, she probably should have just stayed home and helped
Republicans here, instead of gallivanting around the United
States.''
</P>
<P>
   Dunn and her loyalists reject that assertion, blaming this
year's loss on a national tide, on a weak Republican candidate atop
the state ballot, and on an unusually artful get-out-the-vote and
absentee voter program by the Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jennifer has done more for Republican candidates in Washington
state than nearly any other officeholder, has consistently aided
state, federal and local Republicans, and will continue to do so,''
said Rob Nichols, a former Dunn spokesman who has returned to help
with her majority leader campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Her travels, which brought her to 30 congressional districts
around the country this year, are clearly a boon to her current
campaign. She claims the support of more than half of the 17 new
Republicans elected to the House, and many of the people she has
helped are backing her.
</P>
<P>
   ``The issue is, who can really grow our base and grow our
majority,'' said Bilbray, who was narrowly re-elected earlier this
month. ``Jennifer comes with a lot of experience leading the party
in her state. And frankly, I think the Democrats would hate to see
her elected, because it would destroy the big lie that Democrats
tell about Republicans.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-15-98 1852EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
