r d &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FOOD-COLUMN-OWEN-SPI &LR;      11-15 0838
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOOD-COLUMN-OWEN-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A HAM LOAF FOR ALL SEASONS AND HOLIDAYS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JOHN OWEN  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   I'm not suggesting that Santa Claus is a witch, a goblin or Newt
Gingrich in disguise. All I know is that the Jolly Old Elf was
campaigning in our neighborhood at least two weeks before Halloween
and Election Day. His premature appearance in store windows
suggests that by Dec. 26 he will have worn out his welcome and
probably couldn't get elected chief sweeper in a reindeer corral.
</P>
<P>
   Granted, the Gnome from Nome generates a lot of retail sales.
But the Christmas celebration is already running longer than the
baseball season and St. Nick has almost as many commercials as
Michael Jordan.
</P>
<P>
   If our national holidays are essential in keeping our economy
boiling, then admit it. But we shouldn't dump the entire
responsibility on the back of S. Claus, Esq.
</P>
<P>
   We don't need a three-month Christmas season. What we need are
more holidays, promoting unbridled feasting and lavish giving of
gifts.
</P>
<P>
   For example, we honor our late presidents but so far have done
nothing for CEOs. How about celebrating Bill Gates' birthday, for
starters?
</P>
<P>
   We've got an unofficial holiday on May 1, but it doesn't work.
How much revenue are we going to generate from May baskets? We need
a Soviet-style May Day parade, which means the military gets to buy
a whole lot more new tanks. We can always use them to keep out the
Canadians. The U.S. Customs agents at Blaine are doing a pretty
good job, but every once in a while a grandmother from Moose Jaw
slips through the dragnet with a six-pack of Molson.
</P>
<P>
   Use your imagination! We have Mother's Day, Father's Day,
Secretary's Day and Valentine's Day. How about recognizing the most
important members of our households with holidays honoring dogs,
cats, goldfish and pet whales?
</P>
<P>
   We could celebrate Mark McGwire's birthday and add on
celebrations honoring Sammy Sosa, Roger Maris and Babe Ruth. What
gifts would be appropriate on the days devoted to baseball's
greatest stars? Obviously, Beanie Babies.
</P>
<P>
   I just happen to have a ham loaf recipe appropriate for all
holidays. It could easily be baked in the shape of a heart
(Valentine's Day), a tank (May Day) or a Mariner Moose (Ken Griffey
Day.)
</P>
<P>
   I bake it in an oblong shape to annually commemorate Jerome
Kern's birthday. With cherries and pineapple on top, the ham loaf
looks sort of like a showboat.
</P>
<P>
   Showboat Loaf
</P>
<P>
   1 pound ground ham
</P>
<P>
   One-and-one-quarter pounds ground turkey
</P>
<P>
   2 eggs, lightly beaten
</P>
<P>
   1 cup cracker crumbs
</P>
<P>
   1 cup milk
</P>
<P>
   One-half teaspoon salt
</P>
<P>
   One-eighth teaspoon black pepper
</P>
<P>
   4 slices pineapple
</P>
<P>
   7 maraschino cherries
</P>
<P>
   Three-quarters cup brown sugar, packed
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon dry mustard
</P>
<P>
   One-quarter cup vinegar
</P>
<P>
   It's best to buy lean ham and put it through a grinder or food
processor. Use a lean grind of turkey.
</P>
<P>
   In a large bowl moosh together the ham, turkey, eggs, cracker
crumbs, milk, salt and pepper.
</P>
<P>
   In a small bowl combine the brown sugar, mustard and vinegar.
</P>
<P>
   Grease well the bottom and sides of a loaf pan. Lay three slices
of pineapple on the bottom of the pan. Cut the fourth slice in half
and arrange halves between the whole slices. Fill in the gaps with
the cherries.
</P>
<P>
   Spoon half the brown sugar mixture over the fruit, then pack in
the meat. Smooth out the top, then cover with the remainder of the
sugar mixture.
</P>
<P>
   Bake at 400 degrees for two hours.
</P>
<P>
   Serve with this side dish commemorating the anniversary of
Idaho's admission to the union.
</P>
<P>
   Famous Potatoes
</P>
<P>
   2 cups half-and-half (or low-fat evaporated milk)
</P>
<P>
   1 large clove garlic, minced
</P>
<P>
   Three-quarters cup freshly grated Parmesan, divided
</P>
<P>
   One-half cup grated Swiss cheese, divided
</P>
<P>
   Two-and-one-half pounds baking potatoes
</P>
<P>
   Freshly grated nutmeg
</P>
<P>
   In a saucepan combine the half-and-half with the garlic,
one-half cup of Parmesan and one-quarter cup of Swiss cheese and
stir-cook until the cheese begins to melt. Do not boil.
</P>
<P>
   Peel the potatoes and thinly slice. Toss the spud slices with
nutmeg, plus salt and pepper to taste.
</P>
<P>
   Spread the potato slices in an oven-proof dish. Slop the milk
mixture over the top and sprinkle with the remaining cheeses. Bake
in a 400-degree oven until tender and brown on top, probably one
hour.
</P>
<P>
   This serves four but if you have leftover ham and potatoes, lay
them out in an oven-proof skillet for breakfast and top with beaten
and seasoned eggs (or egg substitute.)
</P>
<P>
   Cook this omelet on top of the stove for 3 minutes, then shove
under an oven broiler, a couple of inches from the heat, until the
top is set. Serve for breakfast in wedges.
</P>
<P>
   Come to think of it, why doesn't Congress establish a national
Leftover Day in the United States? It may conflict with Dog Day,
but politicians are paid to make these hard choices.
</P>
<P>
   John Owen writes ``The Intermediate Eater'' weekly for the P-I.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
