<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    No. 21 Jackets point to strong finish
 &HT;    By Carroll Rogers
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ With Wake Forest and Georgia left to complete the
regular season, Georgia Tech couldn't be much more satisfied with
what has taken place and what remains at stake. In their final home
game against Wake Forest on Saturday, the Yellow Jackets will play
for a share of the ACC championship and a likely invitation to the
Gator Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   The Jackets (7-2, 6-1), who moved up two spots to No. 21 in both
the Associated Press and ESPN/USA Today polls after their 24-21 win
over Clemson on Thursday, would get their first ACC title since
1990 and second ever in 16 seasons of ACC football.
</P>
<P>
   Tech, which has reached seven wins for the fourth time in the
1990s, got there the quickest since the 1990 season.
</P>
<P>
   After losing to Florida State, Georgia Tech needed wins over
Maryland, Clemson and Wake to keep pace with the Seminoles for a
share of the ACC title. With two of those three wins now in hand,
the Jackets have kept their focus and have two reasons not to look
past the Demon Deacons to rival Georgia, which it hasn't beat since
1990.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
