<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-INSIDE16-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    `Lucky' Vols didn't rate drop
 &HT;    By Tony Barnhart
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Random thoughts as we head down the regular-season
stretch:
</P>
<P>
   _ Some will call Tennessee lucky after its 28-24 win over
Arkansas on Saturday. Yes, Razorbacks quarterback Clint Stoerner
did give the Volunteers a last chance to win when he fumbled with
1:43 left. But Tennessee took advantage of the opportunity. Good
teams do.
</P>
<P>
   Tennessee's fortunate finish is probably why the coaches dropped
the Vols to No. 2 in their poll after being tied with Kansas State
at No. 1 last week. Tennessee is still No. 1 in the Associated
Press media poll and should hang on to the top spot in today's BCS
Standings.
</P>
<P>
   To those who voted Tennessee down after beating the No. 10 team,
we say this: Most national championship teams usually have some
luck along the way. Remember Nebraska and the tipped pass at
Missouri last year? Remember Colorado's fifth down in 1990?
Remember Georgia's Buck Belue-to-Lindsay Scott miracle in 1980?
</P>
<P>
   Championship teams usually make their luck by not giving up.
</P>
<P>
   _ Having said all those nice things about Tennessee, do you
think Kentucky's Tim Couch is licking his chops as he looks forward
to throwing against the Volunteers secondary Saturday? That group
made Stoerner-to-Anthony Lucas look like Montana-to-Rice. This a
dangerous game for Tennessee after Saturday's emotional win._ Poor
John Cooper. The Buckeyes could beat Michigan Saturday and still
not go to the Rose Bowl. If Wisconsin beats Penn State and Ohio
State beats Michigan, there would be a three-way tie atop Big Ten.
Wisconsin would go to the Rose because it hasn't been since 1995.
If Michigan beats Ohio State, the Wolverines go to Pasadena.
</P>
<P>
   Fantastic finishes
</P>
<P>
   If you went to bed early Saturday night, you missed two of the
most dramatic finishes of the season:
</P>
<P>
   _ At the Carrier Dome in Syracuse, N.Y., Donovan McNabb hit
tight end Stephen Brominski with a 13-yard touchdown pass on the
last play of the game as the Orangemen rallied to beat Virginia
Tech 28-26. The win keeps Syracuse alive for the Big East
championship. The Orangemen must win their last two games with
Temple and Miami to win the Big East and a trip to either the
Orange or the Sugar Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   _ At Lubbock, Texas, Rob Peters scored on a 3-yard touchdown run
with 25 seconds left as Texas Tech upset Texas 42-35. Ricky
Williams of Texas ran for 141 yards and needs only 63 yards to
break Tony Dorsett's Division I career rushing record. He'll try to
get those final yards Nov. 27 against Texas A&AMP;M. Williams, however,
was outgained on Saturday by the ``other'' Ricky Williams. He plays
for Texas Tech and had 148 yards.
</P>
<P>
   Worth noting
</P>
<P>
   _ It is now official. The Jan. 2 Orange Bowl will move back to
the old Orange Bowl Stadium for one year. The game was scheduled
for Pro Player Stadium, home of the Miami Dolphins, but the change
was made because of a potential scheduling conflict with the NFL
playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   _ The Chick-fil-A Peach Bowl has finalized an agreement with the
ACC that will put an ACC team into the game for the next four
seasons. Earlier this year the SEC signed a similar agreement to
provide the other team. The Peach Bowl will be Dec. 31 at 5 p.m. at
the Georgia Dome.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
