<HEADER>
A1685 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-FALCONS-BISHER16-     11-15 0695
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-FALCONS-BISHER16-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    49ers get theirs with a little help from ``bigtime'' plays
 &HT;    By Furman Bisher
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Across the playing field of the Georga Dome, a red
banner had been hung on the gray wall with care, harking back to a
glorious moment. ``1980 NFC West Champions,'' it read, a single
sad, lonely pennant highlighting the one time the Atlanta Falcons
had won any kind of prize in the National Football League. It would
look a little sickly beside the Celtics and the Yankees, and all
those pennants that decorate their premises, but it seemed just the
time to break it out, as the Falcons played for one to match it.
</P>
<P>
   You had to giggle at the audacity of it. Here they were playing
the San Francisco 49ers, who have owned them over the years. No Dan
Reeves team had beaten them since he came here. In the last 15
seasons, the Falcons had beaten them only five times. What grounds
were there to expect any great reformation? The bookmakers favored
the 49ers by three points, even playing in their home parlor.
</P>
<P>
   If you caught the picture on the first page of the sports
section Sunday morning, you saw Chris Chandler sitting on the
ground, sacked, looking up at the taunting Roy Barker, a scene from
their first match of the season, when the 49ers had devoured the
Falcons. There was cold derision in Chandler's eyes, delivering a
quiet message to Barker: ``You turkey, you'll get yours down the
road.''
</P>
<P>
   Well, it was over. Barker and associates had indeed ``gotten
theirs.'' The Falcons were removing their sweat-sogged armor,
revealing red welts and angry bruises. They blurted the story of
their happiness into microphones thrust in their faces, glistening
in the strobe lights. Outside, wives waited, as they do, proudly
wearing their husbands' numbers on their backs. Of such happiness,
few Atlanta Falcons and Falcons followers have ever known.
</P>
<P>
   The Falcons had given the lofty 49ers a good old-fashioned
butt-kicking. They spent the dwindling time looking at a mirror
image of themselves in the downtrodden days of yore, except these
images wore red and white and bore the names of Young, Rice, Hearst
and Doleman, the vincible (cq)49ers. Here they were, in arrears,
fighting to come back, the Falcons in control. Rarely has it ever
been thus.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bigtime players make bigtime plays,'' Reeves would say later.
</P>
<P>
   It was not as easy as the simple score indicated, 31-19, and
that was what the coach spoke of. Just when it seemed the Falcons
had it put away, here came Steve Young, who had been buffeted about
like a losing heavyweight, and his cast of acrobatic catchers with
another bomb. First, to Terrell Owens from Tenn-Chattanooga, 54
yards over Randy Fuller. Then to the incredible Jerry Rice, who
suddenly shows up at the most distressful moment, 65 yards over
William White. From 24-6, the 49ers had closed the margin to 24-19.
Just as suddenly, a pall fell over the dome, like theater lights
going dim.
</P>
<P>
   Then came the big play. Terance Mathis had been the quiet one
all day, while Bob Christian and Tony Martin had been Chander's
favored catchers. (O.J. Santiago might have been, but he had a
serious case of ``board hands.'') Mathis slipped down the sideline
behind R.W. McQuarters, a rookie from Oklahoma State, and Chandler
nailed him. In one 78-yard touchdown strike, Mathis became the
Falcons' leading receiver of the day.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was huge. Our backs were to the wall. We just had to score.
We couldn't let them have the ball again,'' Reeves said. ``Terance
is a bigtime player.''
</P>
<P>
   It was like a day at the circus outside. Traffic, pedestrians,
scalpers, groupies, hustlers of all kinds were drawn as if by a
some powerful magnet. The bandwagon had pulled up and everybody was
jumping on. The house was sold out. Now the Falcons lead the NFC
West, 8-2, best record any Falcon team has ever had.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wish the season was over,'' Reeves said, ``but we have six
more games to play. We could lose either one of them, but I'll go
to war with the men I have in that room there any time.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
