<SLUG> BC-LEAH-PERSONALS-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANOTHER PRESIDENTIAL HONOR
</HEADLINE>
  
 By LEAH GARCHIK  
 (c) SF CHRONICLE
<TEXT>
<P>
   At a party in Washington last week,  &UR; Bill  &LR; and  &UR; Hillary Clinton &LR; 
were named godparents of 6-week-old  &UR; Melanne Rose Dozoretz &LR; , whose
parents are Democratic fund-raisers. Among the guests at &UR; Beth  &LR; and
 &UR; Ron Dozoretz &LR; 's house were  &UR; Glenn Close &LR; , &UR; Kathleen Kennedy
Townsend &LR; , Housing Secretary
 &UR; Andrew Cuomo &LR; , Agriculture Secretary  &UR; Dan Glickman &LR;  and
Representative  &UR; John &LR;   &UR; Dingell &LR; , D-Mich. Rabbi  &UR; Jeffrey Wohlberg &LR; 
officiated, joined by an Indian swami who said prayers in English
and Hindi, and a Japanese nun.
</P>
<P>
   Rabbi Wohlberg explained to a Washington Post reporter that the
concept of godparents is largely ceremonial in Jewish tradition.
``A person of such prestige,'' he said of the parents' regard for
President Clinton, ``they wanted to give him a feeling of being
honored significantly.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know whether in the back of their minds is the idea
that, God forbid, anything happens to them he would take over the
moral education of the child.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WHOLE PERSONALS GIFT CATALOG &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Several toilet-guitar items having encouraged a flood of
potty-related suggestions to the Personals holiday gift guide, it's
time to clean up the act with an item that refers to the sacred act
of the holiday season: buying.
</P>
<P>
   From the Flax catalog,  &UR; Kathleen Seaman  &LR; forwards notice of a
miniature shopping cart, ``with all the benefits of a real shopping
cart with none of the drawbacks. Even the wheels work poorly, just
like in the supermarket.''
</P>
<P>
   The ``benefits of'' a real cart being mostly limited to its
ability to carry big loads, it takes imagination to see how this
71/2-inch tall item, which costs $25, fills the bill.
</P>
<P>
   &LR;   &LR;   &UR; FLASH &LR;
</P>
<P>
   - Director &UR; Tony Kaye &LR; , who was so angry over the editing of
``American History X'' that he demanded his name be taken off the
film, is described in the latest issue of Premiere as a rookie
director ``testing the limits of Hollywood's patience.'' In the
course of conflict with New Line Cinema, the company financing his
movie, Kaye showed up for one meeting ``with a rabbi, a priest and
a Tibetan monk in tow.''
</P>
<P>
   - At Portland International Jetport,  &UR; Mark Hetts  &LR; heard the
intercom announcement: ``Ladies and gentlemen, if you have not done
so, would you please do so now? Thank you for your cooperation.''
</P>
<P>
   - In Milan at the MTV European Musics Awards ceremony on
Thursday, the  &UR; Duchess of York &LR;  was brushed off by members of the
the British group Massive Attack, who refused to shake her hand
when she gave them an award for Best Video. ``P- off,' band member
3D told her backstage, explaining later to the London Evening
Standard, ``What the f- does she got to do with music?''
</P>
<P>
   - Tips for everyday life: &UR; Bill Williams &LR;  received a charming
phone bill from Pacific Bell, detailing minimal charges on one
side, and on the reverse, the simple printed declaration: ``Blank
Page.'' And the latest issue of Self magazine includes among its
``tips for dry-mouth sufferers'' the astonishing Item No.1: ``Take
frequent sips of water.''
</P>
<P>
   &LR;   &LR;   &UR; HERO WORSHIP &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Esquire magazine focuses on 10 famous men and the heroes they
worship. Among them is  &UR; Al Sharpton &LR; , who talks about the qualities
that make  &UR; James Brown &LR;  a hero to him: ``Unwavering inner strength,
unshakable equilibrium and perseverance. ...''
</P>
<P>
   ``I have been by James Brown's side at the highest highs and the
lowest lows,'' writes Sharpton. ``I have never seen him frightened
and I have never seen him panic.
</P>
<P>
   ``I saw him when he was in prison, and he walked into the
visitors' room like he was walking onstage at the Apollo. He asked
me how I was doing, and I said, `How do you think I'm doing? This
is a terrible situation.' And he said, `It's just business, Al,
just business.' ''
</P>
<P>
   &LR;   &LR;   &UR; WHO SAID WHAT &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ``I take my work seriously, but I don't take Eartha Kitt &LR; 
 &UR; seriously. I know the difference between Eartha Kitt the &LR; 
 &UR; character onstage and that which is me at home. I'm not walking &LR; 
 &UR; around all the time with high makeup on and eyelashes on and my &LR; 
 &UR; hair all done up and wearing the wigs. I go out as me, and I'm &LR; 
 &UR; not interested in looking like Vogue unless I go to an affair.'' &LR;
</P>
<P>
   -  &UR; Eartha Kitt  &LR; in Egg magazine.
</P>
</TEXT>
