<HEADLINE>
FOR THE RECORD, YOU CAN'T TRY THESE AT HOME
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By TOM HOFFARTH  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Go back to that ``Brady Bunch'' episode when Bobby and Cindy
decided they needed to break the world teeter-totter record in
their backyard, but they ended up too tuckered to teeter after a
few nauseating hours.
</P>
<P>
   Remember, at least they got their pictures in the paper.
</P>
<P>
   Guaranteed, if you accomplish one of the following feats listed
in the ``Guinness Book of World Records 1998'' ($24.95, Guinness
Publications, 320 pages), someone from a newspaper will take your
picture and there's a chance one of the local TV goofs will come
poking around with a microphone, too:
</P>
<P>
   BOWLING
</P>
<P>
   __ Oldest to record a 300 game: The American Bowling Congress
reports that Joe Norris of San Diego was 86 years, 10 months and 6
days when he did it on Dec. 14, 1994. The oldest woman was Myrt
Kressin of Bremerton, Wash., who was 71 years, 5 months and 7 days
on Feb. 8, 1997.
</P>
<P>
   GOLF
</P>
<P>
   __ Lowest score, throwing a golf ball around an 18-hole course
(more than 6,000 yards): 82, by Joe Flynn, age 21, at the
6,228-yard Port Royal course in Bermuda on March 27, 1975.
</P>
<P>
   __ Fastest round: 27 minutes, 9 seconds by James Carvil at
Warrenpoint Golf Course in Northern Ireland (6,154 yards) on June
18, 1997. The ball has to come to a rest between each new stroke.
</P>
<P>
   __ Most holes in 24 hours, on foot: 401 (22 rounds, plus five
holes) by Ian Colston at the Bendingo Golf Club in Australia (par
73, 6,061 yards), Nov. 27-28, 1971.
</P>
<P>
   __ One club, lowest score: 70, by Thad Daber using a 6-iron at
the 6,037-yard Lochmore Golf Club course in Cary, N.C. to win the
World One-Club Championship in 1987.
</P>
<P>
   Oldest player to shoot his age:!of! 103, by C. Arthur Thompson
in 1973 on the Uplands course (6,215 yards) in Victoria, B.C.,
Canada.
</P>
<P>
   WALKING BACKWARD
</P>
<P>
   Greatest distance: 8,000 miles (est.) by Plennie L. Wingo, who
did it from Santa Monica to Istanbul, Turkey, between April 15,
1931 and Oct. 24, 1932.
</P>
<P>
   HORSE RACING
</P>
<P>
   __ Biggest payout: $1,627,084.40 at Santa Anita on April 19,
1987. Anthony Speelman and Nicholas Cowan, both of Great Britian,
put $64 down on a pick-9 ticket for a jackpot that had been
building for 24 days.
</P>
<P>
   FYI: The IRS withheld $406,768.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe you wouldn't want your picture taken for this record. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-15-98 2007EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
