<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOUTH-FUTURE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LOOKING TO NEW CENTURY, SOUTH REFOCUSES EYES ON THE PRIZE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CURTIS WILKIE  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BIRMINGHAM, Ala. _ Painful memories from a generation ago
collided this weekend with calls for action in the coming century,
to complete the South's ``Unfinished Business'' at a conference on
race, poverty, and inequality.
</P>
<P>
   Although the meeting took place in a city that bears little
resemblance to the segregated stronghold of 1960s, most of the
participants advocated further steps against discrimination, rather
than rest on the accomplishments of the civil rights movement.
</P>
<P>
   Organizers of the regional conference hope to hammer out by
Monday's closing session an agenda for the 21st century that
emphasizes the importance of public schools, decent housing, and
respectable jobs in a racially-diverse society.
</P>
<P>
   It is an opportunity, said John Egerton, a civil rights
historian from Nashville who was the conference director, to issue
a new ``Southern Manifesto'' that flies in the face of the original
1956 document, signed by almost every Southerner then in Congress,
defying a Supreme Court decision to strike down segregated schools.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we don't have a program to identify ourselves,'' Egerton
said in an interview Sunday, ``we leave it to the neo-Confederates
and the Christian right, who speak with a Southern accent, to say
they are what the South stands for.''
</P>
<P>
   The conference was held less than two weeks after voters
rejected far-right candidates in Alabama, Georgia, North Carolina,
and South Carolina, while Jeb Bush and George W. Bush, espousing
``conservatism with compassion,'' won in Florida and Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the political results, which were viewed as progress by
the delegates here, the meeting took place in the long shadows of
Birmingham's troubled history. Sixty years ago, a racially mixed
Southern Conference for Human Welfare, convened to consider the
region's social and economic problems, was interrupted by a police
commissioner named Eugene ``Bull'' Connor, who demanded that the
group hold segregated sessions or face arrest. A quarter-century
later, in a more memorable outburst, Connor unleashed police dogs
and fire hoses on black demonstrators.
</P>
<P>
   To acknowledge the city's past, the ``Unfinished Business''
conference held its first session at the 16th Street Baptist
Church, where the peace of a Sunday morning in 1963 was shattered
by a bomb that killed four schoolchildren.
</P>
<P>
   ``Remembrances _ there are so many,'' said Alpha Robertson,
whose daughter died in the bombing. ``I remember the signs: Colored
Only. White Only.''
</P>
<P>
   US Representative John Lewis of Georgia recalled the segregated
strife, too. As a youthful demonstrator, he was beaten by Alabama
troopers during the ``Bloody Sunday'' attack on the Edmund Pettus
Bridge at Selma in 1965. But speaking to younger blacks who
complain that little has changed in the South, Lewis preferred to
accentuate the positive developments.
</P>
<P>
   ``We lived in a tremendous amount of fear. People couldn't
register to vote. The fear is gone. The signs are gone. That's
changed,'' Lewis said. ``We're on our way toward laying down the
burden of race.''
</P>
<P>
   William F. Winter, a member of President Clinton's advisory
board on race and an exponent of public education when he was
governor of Mississippi, said it is essential ``to have our
children go to school together.'' Addressing another thorny
subject, Winter said: ``There is still room for affirmative action
because there is still a network that rotates people to
opportunity. Blacks have got to have access to that network.''
</P>
<P>
   Although the South has enjoyed explosive economic growth in
recent years, statistics were cited from a new report by MDC Inc.,
a North Carolina research organization, finding that the median
family income for Southern blacks stood at 55 percent of the median
for whites. More than 7 million Southerners who worked full-time
last year made less than a poverty-level income of $12,500 a year.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are not enough jobs for the uneducated, and they are not
getting themselves educated,'' said George Autry, MDC's president.
</P>
<P>
   In a spirited debate Sunday afternoon, questions were raised
about the region's old public policies of tax incentives to attract
industry, and a growing Hispanic population that may be perceived
as a threat by blacks still fighting for equity.
</P>
<P>
   ``Leadership positions continue to be dominated by white
males,'' said Wendy Jones, executive director of the Southern
Regional Council, an Atlanta-based civil rights organization. She
recommended a ``systematic campaign'' for the South to adapt to ``a
Technicolor community.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-15-98 2010EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
