</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HONDURAS-DISASTER-2TAKES-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PEOPLE IN U.S. WITH TIES TO HONDURAS WORRY ABOUT THEIR LOVED ONES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By OSCAR AVILA AND MARY SANCHEZ  
 c. 1998 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN PEDRO SULA, Honduras _ For days after Hurricane Mitch
struck, the Martinez brothers of Kansas City, Mo., heard nothing
from their family in Honduras. So they packed up a truck and drove
south.
</P>
<P>
   They could wait no longer.
</P>
<P>
   Jesus Castellanos of Lenexa couldn't wait either. He flew to
Honduras, trying to get supplies in time to save the lives of his
countrymen.
</P>
<P>
   Honduras is on life support, and the next few weeks will
determine how many in the country will survive.
</P>
<P>
   The president of Honduras said Hurricane Mitch wiped out 50
years of progress in 72 hours, knocking out three-fourths of the
country's bridges and roads. One in four residents is homeless. The
entire banana crop is gone. More than 6,500 people have died.
Almost twice as many are missing.
</P>
<P>
   Some say disease could double the death toll. Malaria and
cholera are spreading, and there is little medicine. The water is
contaminated with waste and pesticides. Entire regions are cut off
from help.
</P>
<P>
   Saturday brought a familiar sight: three children in San Pedro
Sula squatting by a pool of water. They splashed in the stagnant
water, using it to wash mud from their legs and arms. Social
workers fear the water is full of parasites.
</P>
<P>
   In Kansas City and all over the world, people with ties to
Honduras have no idea whether their loved ones are even alive. Many
are rushing to Honduras by air, sea and car. They travel with hope
and with dread.
</P>
<P>
   Along with them are Kansas City area relief organizations, such
as Heart to Heart International, Children International and La
Buena Fe, which have answered a worldwide 911 call. They are
sending food, medicine and water as fast as their cargo planes can
get there.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is the hope that the worst is already gone,'' Castellanos
said Friday night from the capital, Tegucigalpa, where he is
helping Heart to Heart distribute aid. ``But the hardest part is
still to come. We think there are still some major complications in
the next few weeks.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a real urgency here,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   When Castellanos moved to Lenexa, Kan., this year, the memories
he kept of Tegucigalpa were of a 400-year-old colonial city with
narrow streets. Modern skyscrapers shared the landscape with small
shanties on the hills.
</P>
<P>
   When he returned this month, he found buildings collapsed and
those narrow streets blocked with debris. The military patrolled
the streets at night. There was a 9 p.m. curfew, a far cry from the
bustling nightlife he recalled.
</P>
<P>
   And he knew the worst was outside the city.
</P>
<P>
   One thought cheered him up, though.
</P>
<P>
   ``Thank God it's still the same people,'' he said. ``People who
are friendly, patient and have been enduring as much as they can.''
</P>
<P>
   The mountains that surround Tegucigalpa and the industrial city
of San Pedro Sula played a big part in the destruction. The steep
terrain caused rainwater to flow downhill with fury, leaving little
hope for the villages in the valleys.
</P>
<P>
   Before the storm, Francisco Sagastume Pereira had a banana
plantation. It was a lush piece of property beside the Chamelecon
River. The river is muddy and fast-moving, much like the Missouri
River, but narrower.
</P>
<P>
   It has receded to its original size now. But it is easy to see
how the rains widened the river to three times its normal width.
The waters deposited a sandy beach of sediment on what used to be
land abundantly covered with trees, grass and flowers.
</P>
<P>
   On Saturday, Pereira shoveled the sandy sediment that covered
his land. The banana trees and their fruit are gone, washed away in
the storm.
</P>
<P>
   Beginning Oct. 28, Mitch pounded Honduras with winds of up to
180 mph. The storm brought an inch of rain an hour for several
days.
</P>
<P>
   Mitch was one of the four most-powerful hurricanes in history
and the deadliest storm to hit the Caribbean in 200 years.
</P>
<P>
   Other countries felt the storm's wrath. More than 2,000 died in
Nicaragua, and hundreds more perished in El Salvador and Guatemala.
</P>
<P>
   But Honduras was squarely in the storm's crosshairs from the
start.
</P>
<P>
   The hurricane wiped entire communities off the map. Eight-foot
bushmaster snakes, among the deadliest in the world, shared high
ground with survivors. Children now drink water contaminated by
corpses or pesticides.
</P>
<P>
   For many there is no alternative.
</P>
<P>
   Driving rains collapsed buildings and buried hundreds of people
under debris and mud. Others drowned as rains turned villages into
lakes. The rain cut off thousands from the world _ no phones, no
roads and no food.
</P>
<P>
   Pereira dug to uncover a tree for firewood. Like many people
here, Pereira precedes his comments with ``By the grace of God.''
</P>
<P>
   As in, ``It is by the grace of God'' that his six children and
his wife are safe. God also kept his home solidly planted in the
earth.
</P>
<P>
   He says he is also lucky because he does not rely on the bananas
as his sole source of income. He has another job, as a tax
collector for the government. But like the plantation land, that
job is now obsolete.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why bring debts to people who have nothing?'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   After the storm, Honduran natives all over the world tried to
find out whether loved ones had survived. It was almost impossible
to get through.
</P>
<P>
   Telephone lines are down in many parts of the country. Some
people have worn Honduran telephone books ragged, searching for a
number that will connect to a voice from home. One man reached a
message last week that said all telephone numbers in Honduras had
been changed.
</P>
<P>
   Some pleaded with relief workers to check on their family.
Others withstood days of torturous waiting.
</P>
<P>
   With no hope of contact, some in Kansas City have chosen
dangerous, desperate measures.
</P>
<P>
   To drive to Honduras, Kansas City residents must travel more
than 2,000 miles through the United States, Mexico and Guatemala.
The journey is on dangerous roads through uncertain political
terrain. MORE
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
