<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981115.0150 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-15 20:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1731 &Cx1f; kan-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HONDURAS-DISASTER-2ND     11-15 0939
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HONDURAS-DISASTER-2NDTAKE-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
   
 c. 1998 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN PEDRO SULA, Honduras _ uncertain political terrain.
</P>
<P>
   About 40 persons left Kansas City earlier in the week. Eliazar
Martinez said he thought the trip would take eight days.
</P>
<P>
   He left Kansas City on Thursday morning with his brother,
Aristides.
</P>
<P>
   Last week the Martinez brothers and other friends struggled to
hitch together two Toyota trucks for the trip. The brothers are
driving one truck, towing the second. If the first truck breaks
down, they will switch to the second truck, making repairs at a
stop later down the road.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have money only for the gas and some food for ourselves,''
Eliazar Martinez said.
</P>
<P>
   A month has passed since they last spoke to their mother, Bertha
Martinez. She is 72 years old and lives alone in Sonaguera, Colon.
</P>
<P>
   Bridges are out near the town. The men plan to link up with
other Hondurans from Kansas City in the town of El Progreso. From
there they will travel by bus as far as the roads will take them.
</P>
<P>
   They think they will end up having to reach the town by boat.
</P>
<P>
   Nicolas Rodriguez Banegas of Independence, Mo., hasn't heard
from his mother, two sisters, six brothers and two daughters living
in the El Progreso area.
</P>
<P>
   Some reports say the hurricane wiped out El Progreso.
</P>
<P>
   So Banegas is driving, too.
</P>
<P>
   Banegas was a concrete worker in Honduras. He wonders what
happened to the structures he helped build, including a hospital in
San Pedro Sula.
</P>
<P>
   More important, Banegas wonders what happened to his family.
</P>
<P>
   Many of these travelers do not have the money for vaccinations
to guard them against feared epidemics of malaria, dengue and
hepatitis.
</P>
<P>
   Edgardo Diaz Rodriguez, the Honduran ambassador to the United
States, was stunned when he heard of the driving trips from Kansas
City to Honduras.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would tell them not to go. Stay here and let us help them
get information,'' Rodriguez said Friday while on a visit to St.
Joseph. ``The risk is too great. They won't be able to make it.''
</P>
<P>
   But Larry Florence of Claycomo, Mo., understands what is pulling
them home. He plans to drive to Texas, put his truck on a boat to
Honduras and try to make contact with his wife's relatives.
</P>
<P>
   ``Only God can stop these people,'' Florence explained. ``They
have no choice. They have to go.''
</P>
<P>
   Almost every hour, cargo planes land at Tegucigalpa's airport.
Inside are donations of food, medicine, water and clothes.
</P>
<P>
   These aircraft, which Castellanos helps unload, are a lifeline.
</P>
<P>
   Hurricane Mitch is yet another chapter in Honduras' uneasy
relationship with the United States. This time Americans are
welcome angels of mercy.
</P>
<P>
   That hasn't always been the case.
</P>
<P>
   In the early 20th century, American gunboats patrolled the
waters to protect corporate interests. In the 1980s, Honduras was a
staging ground for the U.S.-backed contras fighting in neighboring
Nicaragua.
</P>
<P>
   Even now, Ambassador Rodriguez complains that aid from the
American government was ``very, very slow'' at the beginning.
</P>
<P>
   That has changed somewhat. Honduras has received about $80
million in aid from the American government. American soldiers are
rebuilding bridges, administering medical clinics and delivering
goods.
</P>
<P>
   Other countries, especially Mexico, Japan and Spain, have
helped, too.
</P>
<P>
   ``We hope we can do the best we can do in response to this show
of human solidarity,'' Rodriguez said.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Rodriguez and others say ordinary people _ from Honduras
and all over the world _ will be most important to the country's
recovery.
</P>
<P>
   Kansas City's strong links to Honduras started in 1958, when a
Sugar Creek doctor sold his practice and took his family there.
John Blumenschein set up a clinic and school that has grown into La
Buena Fe, an association that works throughout Central America. La
Buena Fe translates to ``the Good Faith.''
</P>
<P>
   Today at least three major Kansas City-based relief
organizations are in Honduras to help the country rebuild. La Buena
Fe has sent doctors. Heart to Heart is loading cargo planes.
Children International is helping Honduran children who have been
matched with American and Canadian sponsors.
</P>
<P>
   In Kansas City, dozens of other groups are soliciting aid: from
students at Winnetonka High School to local Starbucks Coffee shops
to the Girl Scouts at Holy Trinity School in Lenexa.
</P>
<P>
   Even with the global relief, however, the Honduran ambassador
says the country's recovery ultimately will depend on his own
people.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need to stand together as a country in a spirit of unity,''
Rodriguez said. ``We need to work together because the major
burden, in the end, will be on our shoulders.''
</P>
<P>
   They will have to rebuild deserted villages in the countryside
that hearken back to the eighth century, when some Mayan cities
were inexplicably abandoned. The buildings stood untouched, but
their inhabitants had disappeared.
</P>
<P>
   Many theories abound, but some speculate that a natural threat _
perhaps heavy rains _ drove the Mayans away.
</P>
<P>
   The cruelty of nature often appeared in the mythology of the
Mayans, the ancestors to many in Honduras and the rest of Central
America.
</P>
<P>
   The Mayans believed that the world ended and was reborn over and
over. One story said the world would end in a deluge. The Milky
Way, in the form of a serpentlike creature, would open its jaws and
release water onto the earth. The waters would come for days and
days until they swept away humanity.
</P>
<P>
   But, the Mayans believed, the land that washed away would be
replaced by a new and better world.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-15-98 2018EST &QL; 
