<HEADLINE>
FINANCIAL ANALYSTS, ON THE WHOLE, OFFER ASSURANCES FOR MARKETS IN
'99 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JERRY HEASTER  
 c. 1998 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNDATED: How do the experts feel the economy and stock market
will fare between now and 2000?
</P>
<P>
   That was the question posed Tuesday during a get-together with
members of the Kansas City Society of Financial Analysts. My
feeling was that if you're holding that much informed brainpower
hostage in one place, why not do some serious brain-picking?
</P>
<P>
   The range of responses from those who earn their livings
pondering the economic future reflected the uncertainty of the
present. When asked to characterize their outlook through next
year, 43 percent were pessimistic, 38 were optimistic and 19
percent were neutral.
</P>
<P>
   As for the stock market, the estimates of where the Dow Jones
industrial average will end this year ranged from 9,500 to 7,500.
When asked to predict where the Dow will be at the end of 1999, the
forecast range widened, from 11,500 to 7,500. On balance, however,
the predictions for the Dow industrials a year down the road were
fairly upbeat. Fully one-third of the analysts expected the Dow to
be at 10,000 or higher at 2000's dawning.
</P>
<P>
   The average prognostication for the blue-chip indicator's 1999
close was 9,450, for a gain of about 7 percent between now and
then. While this average appears conservative compared with the
gains of the major stock indexes over the past few years, it
apparently factors in the analysts' outlook for profits.
</P>
<P>
   When asked to estimate earnings for Standard &AMP; Poor's 500, most
predicted year-over-year growth in the range of 3 percent to 6
percent. The good news is, only a couple of respondents forecast a
decline. The bad news is, they believe the double-digit
profit-growth party is over.
</P>
<P>
   Given the prospects for domestic economic growth and the
multitude of world trouble spots, though, the slowing earnings
momentum is likely to get even slower. The most optimistic of the
analysts' forecasts for gross domestic product was an annual rate
of growth of 3 percent through 1999. The most pessimistic was zero
growth. The average of all forecasts called for the economy to
expand by 1.9 percent during this period.
</P>
<P>
   If the forecast is on target, it wouldn't constitute an economic
downturn, but it would be what some economists characterize as a
growth recession. This occurs when the economy isn't expanding fast
enough to create enough jobs to keep the jobless rate from rising.
Given the tightness of the labor markets at this point in the
cycle, some observers probably would see this as a good thing for
the economy.
</P>
<P>
   When Kansas City's market mavens were asked to predict the most
significant market development of 1999, the answers were all over
the place. They included the market's anticipation of Y2K computer
problems, Social Security privatization initiatives, Middle East
terrorism and problems with Iraq, improvement in the Japan-Asia
situation, the emergence of cyclical companies as the stock
market's leaders, the crash of the ``nifty 50'' stock group, the
resurgence of small-cap stocks, the continuing integration of the
European economies, and the impeachment of President Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   On balance, their outlook could be interpreted as reasonably
reassuring, given the maturity of the economic expansion at home
and potential for geopolitical instability abroad.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-15-98 2020EST &QL; 
