<SLUG> BC-FBN-PARCELLS-PROBE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NFL QUESTIONS PARCELLS ABOUT CALLING BLEDSOE
</HEADLINE>
  (ms) 
 By GERALD ESKENAZI   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   INDIANAPOLIS _ New York Jets Coach Bill Parcells is being
investigated for possible tampering by the National Football League
over a telephone call he made to quarterback Drew Bledsoe of the
New England Patriots, whom Parcells once coached. But Parcells said
after Sunday's game that he had made the call merely ``to thank
him.''
</P>
<P>
   Parcells denied Sunday's CBS-TV report that suggested he had
telephoned Miami Dolphins Coach Jimmy Johnson to provide him with
information about the Patriots that Bledsoe had given him.
</P>
<P>
   An NFL spokesman, Greg Aiello, said, ``We have made an inquiry
into the reported telephone conversation with Drew Bledsoe and Bill
Parcells.'' Aiello added that the league had written to the Jets
early last week and asked Parcells about the conversation.
</P>
<P>
   Parcells, who is believed to have already replied to the
league's questions, said Sunday, ``Let's take the depositions and
see who did what.''
</P>
<P>
   League rules describe as potential tampering ``any contact
between members of one organization and another that could
potentially interfere with employer-employee relationships. Clubs
that do so do so at their own risk and could risk forfeiture of a
draft choice.''
</P>
<P>
   However, Parcells described the talk as an innocent outgrowth of
an emotional reunion. Bledsoe had a problematic run under Parcells,
who left New England after the 1996 season. Bledsoe was quoted
several times since as denigrating Parcells. But after the Jets
defeated the Patriots, 24-14, last month at Foxboro, Mass., Bledsoe
sought out Parcells to shake his hand. Parcells said Bledsoe's
action led him to call Bledsoe the next day.
</P>
<P>
   CBS reported Sunday that Bledsoe told Parcells that wide
receiver Terry Glenn was injured and unlikely to play against the
Dolphins, and that Parcells then passed on that information to
Johnson.
</P>
<P>
   ``I haven't called Jimmy Johnson,'' Parcells said.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, the league conducted a similar review when Bill
Belichick, the Jets' assistant head coach, spoke with one or two
players for the Baltimore Ravens days before a game between the
teams. No disciplinary action was taken against the Jets, but they
were warned by the league not to repeat the action.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-15-98 2023EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981115.0156 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-15 20:26 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1749 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-ASTROS-CAMINITI-H     11-15 0645
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-ASTROS-CAMINITI-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CARLTON THOMPSON  
 c. 1998, Houston Chronicle  
It was just a matter of time before Ken Caminiti became an Astro
again, but no one knew that time would come in the wee hours of
Sunday morning.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Just hours after Caminiti and his wife, Nancy, celebrated their
wedding anniversary, Astros fans received the gift they had been
anticipating for days when the club reached an agreement with the
free-agent third baseman at approximately 1:30 a.m.
</P>
<P>
   Caminiti agreed to a deal that could be worth $15 million over
the next three years. The 35-year-old switch hitter is guaranteed
$4.5 million in 1999 and the same amount in 2000, and he could make
$5.5 million if the Astros exercise their club option in 2001.
</P>
<P>
   Caminiti also could make an extra $500,000 in incentives based
on plate appearances in 2001. If the club chooses not to pick up
the option, Caminiti will be paid $500,000 in the form of a buyout.
</P>
<P>
   The agreement is contingent on Caminiti's passing a physical
examination, which could take place as early as Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``We feel like his most serious injuries are behind him,''
Astros general manager Gerry Hunsicker said. ``If we keep him
healthy, this adds another All-Star-caliber player to our lineup.
Ken is right out of the Craig Biggio/Jeff Bagwell/Moises Alou/Derek
Bell mold.
</P>
<P>
   ``He leads by example. He's the ultimate gamer. One of the
things our club seemed to be missing was that spark, and maybe
Caminiti is the guy who can ignite this club. I think it would be
hard not to get fired up with Ken Caminiti as your teammate. When
he's healthy, he's among the elite in the game.''
</P>
<P>
   The acquisition of Caminiti provides the Astros with a run
producer who can swing from the left side of the plate, something
the club had hoped to add over the offseason. The former National
League Most Valuable Player (1996) has averaged 30 homers and 99
RBIs over the past four seasons. Caminiti likely will bat cleanup
behind Bagwell in a lineup that already was the most feared in the
NL.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm so happy to be here that I don't care where Dierk (Astros
manager Larry Dierker) hits me,'' said Caminiti, who on Sunday
departed for a hunting trip to South Texas. ``I'm going to be happy
wherever he puts me. The main thing for me is just getting a chance
to play at home and be an Astro again.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wanted to come back in a bad way. I wasn't going to take no
for an answer. I'm just fortunate everything worked out and I
didn't have to go somewhere else.''
</P>
<P>
   It became a foregone conclusion that Caminiti would choose the
Astros after he turned down a three-year, $21.5 million offer from
the Detroit Tigers last week. From that point, it was obvious money
wasn't as important to Caminiti as being close to his wife and
three daughters and their home in Richmond.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm sure a lot of the big-time ballplayers are going to be
laughing at me and saying I messed up the market,'' Caminiti said.
``But you can take a look at the market; I didn't mess it up. I'm
not going to worry about what anyone else has to say. I only worry
about my own happiness and what's best for me and my family.''
</P>
<P>
   Caminiti, the Astros' third-round draft pick in 1984, made his
major-league debut in Houston in 1987. He played with the Astros
through the 1994 season before being traded to San Diego.
</P>
<P>
   The Astros dealt Caminiti, Steve Finley, Andujar Cedeo, Roberto
Petagine and Brian Williams to the Padres for Derek Bell, Ricky
Gutierrez, Doug Brocail, Phil Plantier, Craig Shipley and Pedro
Martinez, not to be confused with the current Red Sox pitcher.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're elated to begin our offseason this way,'' Hunsicker
said. ``This is a homecoming of sorts. It's special when a player
who develops and grows up in your system can finish his career
where it started.''
</P>
</TEXT>
