<SLUG> BC-AIDS-TREATMENT-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RESEARCHERS `FLUSH OUT' AIDS VIRUS, ATTACK WITH DRUGS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD A. KNOX  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Researchers have virtually eradicated the AIDS virus from the
immune cells of several patients by flushing the virus out of
hiding and then cutting it down with antiviral drugs, they
announced Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   It remains to be seen whether ``virtually'' means ``totally,''
and also whether the elusive virus could emerge from other hiding
places in the body, such as the brain, when the researchers
discontinue the patients' antiviral drugs entirely, as they plan to
do soon.
</P>
<P>
   Still, this marks the first time any experimental maneuver has
come so close to eliminating the human immunodeficiency virus (HIV)
from its favorite lair _ the genetic inner sanctum of so-called
``resting'' CD4 immune cells.
</P>
<P>
   Even though the experiment did not work in all the participants,
the researchers hope they have opened a new front in the effort to
vanquish HIV. They announced the results at a meeting of the
Infectious Diseases Society of America in Denver.
</P>
<P>
   The strategy, which Dr. Anthony S. Fauci of the National
Institute of Allergy and Infectious Diseases put forward last
February, is worthy of an action-movie script. The ``bad guy''
virus, holed up in a remote mountain cabin, is lured out of hiding,
only to be massacred by the big guns of antiviral drugs that hit it
from several different angles.
</P>
<P>
   In this case, the agent that smokes HIV out of its hiding places
is interleukin-2, or IL-2, an immune system chemical that sounds
the alarm to awaken resting CD4 cells. Antiviral drugs, while
remarkably successful in eradicating HIV from the bloodstream,
cannot kill HIV within resting CD4s.
</P>
<P>
   Even patients on antiviral drugs who have no detectable HIV
circulating in their bloodstream for months and years invariably
have viral genes secreted in the DNA of their resting CD4 cells.
The quiescent virus can spring forth when the immune cells it
infects are awakened to battle an ordinary infection.
</P>
<P>
   ``We know the virus is present in basically everybody on
antiviral therapy,'' said Dr. Robert Siliciano of Johns Hopkins
University, a leading HIV researcher. ``So this sanctuary is going
to have to be dealt with.''
</P>
<P>
   It may not be necessary to flush out every HIV particle, or
every set of HIV genes lurking in any of the body's billions of
cells. One current hypothesis is that some patients' immune systems
can keep the virus in check once it is reduced to a low-enough
level; some individuals are known to have survived for years
despite some HIV in their systems.
</P>
<P>
   Fauci cautioned against declaring premature victory. Until
patients show no evidence of HIV's reemergence for a considerable
time off antiviral therapy, ``we shouldn't even use the word
`cure,''' said Fauci.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can't say, ``Aha, we've gotten rid of all the virus,''
Fauci said in an interview. ``We can't make the statement that
there's no virus in the body, just that there is no virus in the
`compartment' we've looked at,'' referring to the CD4 immune cells.
</P>
<P>
   However, the researchers' inability to find HIV in some
patients' CD4 cells is important, because Fauci said his group has
``never run across anybody on antiviral therapy alone'' who didn't
have HIV lurking in resting immune cells. ``We've cultured scores
and scores of them,'' Fauci added, referring to the practice of
growing millions of patients' activated CD4 cells in laboratory
dishes to see if they produce virus.
</P>
<P>
   Normally researchers grow 10 million to 20 million CD4 cells
from each patient to determine if HIV still resides in any, and
Siliciano sometimes cultures up to 100 million cells.
</P>
<P>
   To be as sure as they could in the new experiment that no HIV
was still present, Tae-Wook Chun, a researcher in Fauci's lab, took
330 million CD4 cells from each of the six patients who had no
evidence of remaining HIV at lower levels of detection.
</P>
<P>
   Three patients who had undergone the ``flushing'' strategy had
no detectable virus at the 330 million-cell level. Tissue taken
from the lymph node of one patient likewise showed no evidence of
remaining HIV, also suggesting that the virus may have been
eliminated from every last resting CD4 cell.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, Chun found HIV in three other subjects who had
appeared virus-free when he cultured 10 million to 20 million of
their CD4 cells. Another eight patients who participated in the
``flushing'' experiment for an average of 39 months still had
traces of HIV in their CD4 cells at the 20 million-cell level _
although not as much as a dozen other patients who had only
conventional combination antiviral therapy for the same length of
time.
</P>
<P>
   There is currently no way to distinguish patients whose HIV was
apparently cleared by the new strategy from others in whom the
approach did not work, Fauci said in an interview. For instance,
successful patients were not HIV-infected for shorter periods of
time before treatment, nor did they have notably different types of
prior drug therapy.
</P>
<P>
   Despite only partial success, Fauci is encouraged by the results
because they strongly suggest it is possible to clear HIV from a
major, highly persistent ``reservoir'' within the body, something
not shown before now.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have been assuming that the pool of latently infected CD4
cells is the reservoir from which the virus reignites when you take
people off therapy,'' Fauci said.
</P>
<P>
   The federal researchers are planning to extend the experiment to
additional patients and to withdraw antiviral therapy from patients
with undetectable CD4-cell infections to see if HIV reemerges.
</P>
<P>
   Until that experiment is done and patients are followed for a
considerable length of time without resurgence of the virus, AIDS
researchers will not conclude it is possible to eliminate the virus
from anyone's system once it is established.
</P>
<P>
   ``Clearly these patients have very little virus,'' Siliciano
said of the three patients reported Sunday. ``But you won't know
for sure if the strategy works until you stop therapy and see what
happens.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
