<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GEN-WALL-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OFF THE WALL: WHAT ARE GARV'S PRIMARY COLORS?
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By TOM HOFFARTH  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The guys at Porky's baseball card shop in the North Hollywood
section of L.A. had a constant stream of customers Saturday to see
the irrepressible Steve Garvey sign his name on whatever stuff they
put in front of him.
</P>
<P>
   Garv was also astute enough to offer a handshake and smile with
every hello. Ever the politician.
</P>
<P>
   And what of his latest political aspirations? Could Porky's be
headquarters for Garv's revenge?
</P>
<P>
   Maybe former pro wrestler Jesse ``The Body'' Ventura blazed a
new trail, winning the governorship of Minnesota, but Garvey has a
boxer in mind. The Republican candidate said he thought recently
re-elected Senator Barbara Boxer ``could have been had.''
</P>
<P>
   And he said he (and his people) ``are keeping an eye'' on the
state's other senator, Dianne Feinstein. Her six-year term comes up
in 2000 and she's a potential running mate for Democratic prez
hopeful Al Gore.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever Garvey does _ and the U.S. Senate is definitely his
target _ he won't wait too much longer.
</P>
<P>
   ``You know, I'm going to be 50 in December,'' the former Dodgers
All-Star first baseman admitted.
</P>
<P>
   Say it ain't so. . .
</P>
<P>
   __ By the way, guess who's the proud papa of a 2-week-old son?.
. .
</P>
<P>
   __ The votes were tabulated weeks ago and the should-be winners
of this week's contest are, starting with today's AL Cy: David
Wells, Trevor Hoffman, Nomar Garciapara, and, 'cause remember it's
a team sport, Sammy Sosa. . .
</P>
<P>
   __ One of the newest Beanie Babies is a blue jay named
``Rocket.'' We'll see which is retired first. . .
</P>
<P>
   __ Boston Globe sportswriter Dan Shaughnessy spent a day at
Santa Monica's Third Street Promenade last week. His primary
function was to ask a bunch of typical So Cal natives _ freaks to
the untrained eye _ if they recognized the name Mo Vaughn, who
could sign a $72 million, six-year deal with the Angels any day
now. Shaughnessy estimated just 20 percent of the folks he asked
knew of Vaughn, and a quarter of them knew nothing of his possible
relocation plans. . .
</P>
<P>
   __ Shaughnessy seemed most impressed that James Worthy could
wade through the street performers, animal-shaped shrubs and
homeless residents without being hounded. Maybe it's because out
here, there are fewer parochial, pasty-skinned, bean-eating,
chowder-smelling, Green Monster-mashing, Fleet self-Centered,
flailing-over-Flutie, McDonnough-doughy drooling fans falling over
themselves when there's a celeb in their presence. . .
</P>
<P>
   __ Here's an upside-down cake to celebrate David Stern's 15th
anniversary of being named the NBA commissioner. Blow out the
candles after you turn out the lights on 1998-99. . .
</P>
<P>
   __ Trendspotting: KIRO-AM in Seattle has given an hour of
airtime to former Sonics and current Bucks coach George Karl,
starting tonight at 7. That's 60 minutes per week, by the way. . .
</P>
<P>
   __ Karl Malone might be a no-show again for his own radio show
today. Sellout sidekick Vic ``The Prop'' Jacobs explained Malone's
absence Friday by spinning that the Mailman ``is paying the
emotional price for liberation'' and ``experiencing the rampant
backlash'' from his off-the-wall, get-me-outta-Utah comments last
week. . .
</P>
