A1764 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-49ERS-SECOND16-CO     11-15 0568
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-49ERS-SECOND16-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    49ers get new view from on 2nd floor
 &HT;    By Len Pasquarelli
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Having trailed by double digits in three of their
previous four games entering Sunday's NFC West showdown at the
Georgia Dome, the haughty San Francisco 49ers already have
demonstrated in 1998 that they can play from behind on the
scoreboard.
</P>
<P>
   Starting with next Sunday's game with New Orleans, however, the
Niners face a rare and much more daunting challenge _ proving they
can play from behind in the division. Now one game behind the
Atlanta Falcons following a 31-19 defeat, even some veteran Niners
conceded they are anxious to see how the club reacts to its latest
adversity.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're a team that isn't accustomed to being in this
position,'' linebacker Ken Norton Jr. said. ``Second place, right?
It doesn't even sound good. Some guys were saying this is a wake-up
call. Well, we're going to find out if we all heard the alarm go
off. We have to answer the challenge we're facing.''
</P>
<P>
   To overtake a Falcons team playing with palpable confidence, the
49ers will need more gumption than they showed on Sunday. For
years, the Niners were miscast as an outfit that could only play a
finesse game, and typically they responded by quietly bludgeoning
their opponents.
</P>
<P>
   But on Sunday, the Falcons enjoyed the physical advantage
throughout, so much so that Atlanta linebacker Cornelius Bennett
even hinted the great Jerry Rice might have been a bit intimidated.
Bennett referred to Rice having ``alligator arms,'' an allusion to
a pair of dropped passes, including one in the end zone near the
end of the first half.
</P>
<P>
   ``They talk a lot every time we play them, and this time they
went out and backed it up,'' strong safety Tim McDonald said. Added
cornerback Darnell Walker: ``There was a kind of swagger to (the
Falcons), and we're the ones supposed to have that.''
</P>
<P>
   Unlike the first meeting on Sept. 27, when several Atlanta
players were critical of a game plan long on gimmicks and with too
much respect for the suspect San Francisco secondary, coach Dan
Reeves constructed a model around his team's strengths.
</P>
<P>
   If anything, the Falcons were too conservative at times, and
didn't test rookie cornerback R.W. McQuarters nearly enough. But
one thing Atlanta never lacked was the feeling it was the better
team, and that it could claim the division lead simply playing
things straight. The bully-boys of the division for nearly two
decades, the 49ers exited the Dome on Sunday evening with their
noses bloodied.
</P>
<P>
   Stopping the hemorrhaging might require more than a tourniquet.
</P>
<P>
   The 49ers listed eight players as injured in the game, and four
of them were starting offensive linemen. Against a Saints defense
that has a blitz ratioamong the league's highest, San Francisco
could have problems in protecting already-battered quarterback
Steve Young next week.
</P>
<P>
   Clearly pressing to make some plays, Young appeared to be
suffering far more than club officials have conceded. Although
recovering from an abdominal strain, there still are rumors Young
is also nursing a rib injury, and some of his passes looked like
it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every game,'' Young said, ``is like a train wreck.''
</P>
<P>
   Time will tell if this was the one that derailed the 49ers for
good in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
