A1765 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-FALCONS-MAIN16-CO     11-15 0724
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-FALCONS-MAIN16-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Birds rule roost
 &HT;    By Matt Winkeljohn
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Falcons coach Dan Reeves is not by nature a
happy-go-lucky man, but when he walked into a small room in the
Georgia Dome after Sunday's game against the San Francisco 49ers,
he couldn't wipe the silly grin off his face.
</P>
<P>
   These are high times for the local NFL team, and after the
Falcons pounded San Francisco 31-19 Sunday in front of a sellout
crowd of 69,828 to take possession of first place in the NFC West,
there was much to smile about.
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta is 8-2 for the first time, and has won 14 of its last
18. This is the latest in the season the Falcons have been in first
place since Week 15 of the 1991 season. And they reached these
heights by beating the dreaded 49ers (7-3) handily to gain a
franchise-record seventh straight victory at home.
</P>
<P>
   Until Sunday, San Francisco had owned the Falcons, winning five
straight and 11 of 13.
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta used a big-play defense, which created two touchdowns in
a span of 56 seconds in the final quarter, to take a 24-6 lead,
then needed a 78-yard touchdown pass in the final three minutes to
seal the victory.
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta settled the matter with 2:51 remaining, when Chris
Chandler (21-of-21, 198 yards) hit wide receiver Terance Mathis
with a perfect pass on a 78-yard scoring play. The play erased all
doubts that had been created on two previous 49ers possessions,
when Steve Young completed long touchdown passes to Terrell Owens
and Jerry Rice to close the gap to 24-19.
</P>
<P>
   When Mathis scored, the Dome went nuts.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope everybody got their money's worth because that was an
exciting game,'' Reeves said. ``What can you say about the pass
Chris threw to Terance? That's what happens in these games.
Big-time players make big-time plays.''
</P>
<P>
   The Falcons were shockingly physical while winning the battle on
both lines of scrimmage. They held San Francisco to 76 rushing
yards, and Jamal Anderson rushed 31 times for 100 yards (his
seventh 100-yard game in the last eight).
</P>
<P>
   ``They played very hard,'' San Francisco linebacker Ken Norton
Jr. said. ``They outplayed us.''
</P>
<P>
   Anderson's 10-yard run off left tackle with 2:56 left in the
first half gave Atlanta a 7-0 lead.
</P>
<P>
   San Francisco countered by driving 75 yards in 13 plays in just
2:37. But the 49ers, which led the NFL in red-zone touchdown
percentage (20 of 29) were forced by the Atlanta defense to settle
for a 24-yard field goal from Wade Richey.
</P>
<P>
   Each team had added field goals in the third quarter, which set
the stage for Atlanta's defensive heroics. Atlanta cornerback Ray
Buchanan intercepted a fluttering pass by Steve Young and returned
it to the 1 to set up the Falcons' second touchdown. Jamal Anderson
scored from the 2 two plays later.
</P>
<P>
   On the next possession, Falcons defensive tackle Shane Dronett
forced Young to fumble, and middle linebacker Jessie Tuggle
recovered at the 2 and rolled into the end zone for a 24-6 lead.
</P>
<P>
   The Falcons premature celebration ended moments later, when the
49ers countered with a 54-yard touchdown pass to Owens, who beat
nickel back Randy Fuller, and a 65-yard pass to Rice, who beat
strong safety William White with 3:09 left.
</P>
<P>
   The late scores made Reeves make a critical call.
</P>
<P>
   ``(The 49ers) have got a rookie corner,'' Reeves said. ``I just
felt like we had to score; we couldn't give them the ball back.''
</P>
<P>
   So on second-and-8, he had Chandler look for Mathis, who beat
rookie cornerback R.W. McQuarters. The end result -- a 78-yard
clincher -- has Atlanta thinking big.
</P>
<P>
   Only Minnesota (9-1) has a better record in the NFC, and Atlanta
has only one game remaining against a team with a winning record, a
home game on Dec. 27 against the Dolphins.
</P>
<P>
   ``From now on, every game is extremely important,'' White said.
``It's not just about getting in the playoffs; it's about getting
homefield advantage.''
</P>
<P>
   Reeves likes his team's chances.
</P>
<P>
   ``This has gotten us into a position to where it's in our
control, but if we don't do the same things that we've done to this
point, we're setting ourselves up,'' he said. ``I'll go to war with
the men I've got . . . any time because they're going to give you
everything they've got.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
