<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-15 20:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1766 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-FALCONS-NEXT16-CO     11-15 1036
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-FALCONS-NEXT16-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Stunting 49ers rush yards gives Falcons edge
 &HT;    By Matt Winkeljohn
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ WHAT WENT RIGHT
</P>
<P>
   The Falcons were dominant on both lines of scrimmage, running
for 114 yards and limiting the 49ers to 76 yards rushing. Although
Atlanta averaged just 3.2 yards per rush, Jamal Anderson had enough
plus-yardage plays to provide first downs. Atlanta had the edge in
time of possession (34:30 to 25:30) for the eighth time this year _
and has won all eight. The defense gave up three big pass plays (42
yards in the third quarter, and touchdown receptions of 54 and 65
yards in the fourth quarter), but made more than enough big plays
to win. Atlanta sacked 49ers quarterback Steve Young four times,
once causing a fumble that linebacker Jessie Tuggle recovered for a
touchdown _ tying the franchise record (1991) for five defensive
scores in a season. Also, cornerback Ray Buchanan's third-quarter
interception set up a touchdown. The secondary did a better job
than in the first matchup by not giving San Francisco receivers
room over the middle.
</P>
<P>
   WHAT WENT WRONG
</P>
<P>
   The three big pass plays made it scary in a game that shouldn't
have been. ... Atlanta finally took advantage of 49ers rookie
corner R.W. McQuarters when Terance Mathis scored on a 78-yard pass
with 2:51 left. Why not pick on the guy sooner?
</P>
<P>
   FLYING HIGH
</P>
<P>
   Buchanan spent more than half the game covering Jerry Rice,
especially in the first half when Atlanta played mostly man-to-man.
Although Rice finished with 10 catches for 169 yards and a
touchdown (his 29th against Atlanta), few of the big plays came
when Buchanan was covering him. ... Anderson had 100 yards and two
touchdowns on 31 carries, the seventh time in eight games he's had
100 or more. Anderson has a career-high 11 touchdowns, 10 rushing.
... Tight ends O.J. Santiago and Brian Kozlowski and fullback Bob
Christian did an outstanding job blocking on running plays. All
three were involved in both Anderson's scoring plays. ... Christian
was excellent as a receiver, too, catching four passes for 48
yards. Sometimes, he and Anderson were split wide. ... Punter Dan
Stryzinski (five punts, 42.4 yards) averaged better than 40 yards a
kick for the fifth straight game. Four of his punts were returned,
but for minus-3 yards. ... Linebacker Craig Sauer was a demon on
special teams, with four tackles. ... Defensive tackle Shane
Dronett tied Tuggle for the team lead with six tackles. He also had
1.5 sacks and forced the Young fumble that Tuggle recovered for a
score. ... Tuggle has five fumble recoveries for TDs in his 12-year
career, an NFL record.
</P>
<P>
   FLYING LOW
</P>
<P>
   Rookie corner Elijah Williams, who earlier this season gave up
touchdown catches of 39 and 82 yards, got beat while in the
``dime'' defense by wide receiver Mark Harris for a 42-yard pass in
the third quarter. ... SS William White bit on a Rice fake in the
fourth quarter, and the Niners ended up with a 65-yard TD play.
</P>
<P>
   BEST HIT
</P>
<P>
   Early in the second half, Dronett dropped into pass coverage on
a zone blitz, and when Young threw, Dronett drilled Rice as the
ball arrived, knocking it loose and sending Rice to the turf in a
heap.
</P>
<P>
   BEST PLAY
</P>
<P>
   Buchanan's interception and 34-yard return to the 49ers' 1 in
the third quarter was special, but the 78-yard touchdown pass from
Chandler to Mathis with 2:51 left in the game was the biggest play
of the season.
</P>
<P>
   WORST PLAY
</P>
<P>
   Rice's 65-yard scoring reception with 3:09 caught Atlanta
flat-footed. The Falcons were in base defense (a decision defensive
coordinator Rich Brooks said was dictated by the 49ers' personnel
of two backs, one tight end and two wide receivers). Rice was
released by the cornerback, and White ran straight to the sideline
as Rice streaked right past him. ``I blew it,'' White said. ``I was
supposed to roll over the top, and I saw (Rice) slow down. I looked
back to see if there was a sack or something, and he took off. In
11 years (in the NFL), that was probably the worst play I've ever
had. That was bone-headed.''
</P>
<P>
   GOOD CALL
</P>
<P>
   The play to Mathis. Instead of trying to eat clock, the Falcons
went for the jugular.
</P>
<P>
   BAD CALL
</P>
<P>
   Facing third-and-6 from the Atlanta 43 in the middle of the
third quarter, Young threw down the left sideline for Rice, who
caught the ball for a apparent 38-yard gain to the Atlanta 5. But
after a lengthy conference, officials ruled pass interference on
both Rice and Buchanan, negating the play. It looked like the pass
play should have stood because contact was minimal.
</P>
<P>
   SIGNS OF THE TIMES
</P>
<P>
   For a change, there were multiple signs and banners in the
Georgia Dome. They weren't very imaginative, though. One said ``90
No play in this Chucky's House,'' a reference to Falcons defensive
end Chuck Smith. ... Another: ``We be Jamin ... We hope you be
Jamin, too. Go Jamal (Anderson) 32.''
</P>
<P>
   ETC.
</P>
<P>
   San Francisco defensive end Chris Doleman, a former Falcons
('95-96) whose family still lives in Atlanta, left the Dome upon
learning that his mother, Mary, was taken from the stands to
Piedmont Hospital after experiencing chest pains and high blood
pressure. She was listed in stable condition, and will stay
overnight for observation. ... The Falcons deactivated running back
Harold Green, defensive tackle Shawn Swayda and cornerback Darren
Anderson before the game. Cornerback Ronnie Bradford (knee) dressed
out for the first time in three games, but didn't play.
</P>
<P>
   INJURY UPDATE
</P>
<P>
   The Falcons came out of Sunday's game healthier than any game in
recent memory; ankle sprains to RB Jamal Anderson, DE Lester
Archambeau and LB Craig Sauer were the only reported injuries. None
appear to be serious.
</P>
<P>
   LOOKING AHEAD
</P>
<P>
   The Falcons will try to hold on to sole possession of first in
the NFC West on Sunday, when the Chicago Bears visit Atlanta for
the first time since 1990. The series is tied 9-9, but the Bears
have won five straight, including a 6-0 victory in Chicago in 1993
in the teams' last meeting.
</P>
<P>
   Staff writer Curtis Bunn contributed to this story.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
