</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-FALCONS-CROWD16-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Crowd catches victory fever from Falcons' unexpected win
 &HT;    By Al Levine
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ That noise coming from the Georgia Dome Sunday was the
Falcons bandwagon fully packed and careening out of control.
</P>
<P>
   With less than three minutes left in the NFC West showdown and
with the 49ers closing, 24-19, Atlanta receiver Terence Mathis
raced past a falling San Francisco cornerback R.W. McQuarters for a
78-yard touchdown catch and a 31-19 lead.
</P>
<P>
   For the first time all day, the believers may have outnumbered
the cynics. The sellout crowd nearly stretched the teflon roof with
its noisy appreciation.
</P>
<P>
   ``Before this game, I was skeptical,'' Brince Woods said. ``I
thought they'd play well, but not like this. They may make the
Super Bowl now.''
</P>
<P>
   Woods was sounding like a long-suffering Falcons follower.
``Actually, I just jumped on the bandwagon,'' said Woods, who was
wearing a Falcons cap. ``Nobody wants to root for a losing team.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't expect this,'' Reginald Carter said. ``San Francisco
hadn't been playing well, and this was a fantastic opportunity for
the Falcons. I think they've got a chance to go all the way. But to
be honest with you, I'm a Cowboys fan. This is my second-best
team.''
</P>
<P>
   A big crowd for the Falcons-Niners game is nothing new. Four
times this decade, Atlanta's division nemesis from the West Coast
has helped produce the biggest gate of the season for the Falcons.
</P>
<P>
   But Sunday's sellout was the home team's first since 1995, and a
city looking for something to cheer about, since the Braves' bust
in the National League championship series, was happy to learn it
had an NFL franchise, after all. This game was for first place, an
8-2 record and credibility.
</P>
<P>
   Marietta's Terry Gantt was among those getting his ticket
punched for the bandwagon.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is what Atlanta does,'' Gantt said. ``We get a winner and
we get interested. It's what happened with the Braves. Now, they're
an old story. This is the next new bandwagon.''
</P>
<P>
   Gantt was happy to be one of the new passengers. ``It's my first
game this year,'' he admitted. He did it up right, tailgating
before the game on a metal bench outside the Dome with a number of
friends.
</P>
<P>
   Some Falcons diehards got a fresh coat of paint for the
occasion. Craig Keith and Jim Ross each sported a silver face with
red goatee and black painted mask. ``Takes 20 minutes to create;
we're getting good at it,'' Keith said. ``And when you wash it off,
it takes the blackheads right off your face,'' Ross said.
</P>
<P>
   They carried a hand-painted sign: ``Super Bowl Is For The
Birds.''
</P>
<P>
   Huge crowds walked through the fan pavilion known as the Falcons
Nest outside the Dome, where children played games and adults
listened to music.
</P>
<P>
   Michael and Karla Ward brought their banner to a contest that
was judged by a radio station giving away two trips to New Orleans.
</P>
<P>
   Scalpers were getting $100 for end zone seats. One person, who,
who identified himself as Stan Ticket from Kansas City, stood near
Gate C and called out, ``need an end zone or a nosebleed single.''
He had sold $750 worth of tickets at the Georgia-Auburn game
Saturday night. ``But this place is too hot (with police),'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just want one ticket to see a little of the game; I've got
to catch a plane at 3:30,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Patricia Hein, a 49ers fan living in Marietta, wasn't having the
time of her life celebrating a birthday at the game. ``I can't
believe,'' she said, ``how quickly the Falcons have gotten a good
team.''
</P>
<P>
   It only took 32 years.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
