<SLUG> BC-FBN-FALCONS-ANDERSON16-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Anderson meets challenge, giving Falcons breathing room
 &HT;    By Jeff Schultz
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Hundred-yard games are becoming commonplace; franchise
records are starting to tumble, and he has been a centerpiece of
NFL coverage for the national media in the past week. So what was
Jamal Anderson's biggest concern as he prepared for Sunday's
showcase game against San Francisco?
</P>
<P>
   ``I wanted to make sure my curls looked good,'' the Falcons'
running back joked as he patted his quaff. ``I couldn't let anybody
see me if my hair didn't look good.''
</P>
<P>
   So much for withering in the spotlight. On stage Sunday in the
Georgia Dome, Anderson failed to disappoint himself, teammates,
fans or the blur of family members who flew in from California to
attend the game. He rushed for 100 yards _ the seventh time in the
last eight weeks he has reached or achieved that mark _ and scored
two touchdowns for the third straight week in the Falcons' 31-19
victory against San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a situation now where I expect this,'' said Anderson.
``You want to be one of the best players. You want to get
recognized. It was kind of a challenge for me this week (because of
the attention), but I just had to go out and do what I know Jamal
Anderson can do. Everything else will take care of itself.''
</P>
<P>
   Anderson has rushed for 1,066 yards. His seven 100-yard games
are two short of the franchise record. He tied Gerald Riggs' club
record for the fastest to 1,000 yards, hitting it in the second
quarter of the 10th game. He also joined Riggs (1984-86) and
William Andrews (1979-81) as the only Falcons to rush for more than
1,000 yards in three straight seasons. He is on a pace to finish
with 1,706 yards, which would fall just short of Riggs' mark of
1,719.
</P>
<P>
   Success was not immediate against the 49ers. Anderson's
first-quarter fumble ended a scoring threat on the Falcons' second
possession, and after one quarter he had netted only 23 yards on
nine carries (2.3 average). But midway through the second, the
Falcons' offensive line started opening some holes, and Anderson
ran seven times in an 11-play drive, eventually scoring from 10
yards out to make it 7-0.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I got through the line and I saw (49ers free safety)
Merton Hanks standing there at the goal line waiting for me, I was
thinking, 'TD. TD. TD.' I mean, he didn't have a chance. I was
coming at full speed, 235 pounds. I had to score,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Anderson's 2-yard plunge early in the fourth quarter gave the
Falcons some breathing room at 17-6.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
