A1769 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-FALCONS-HUMMER16-     11-15 0578
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-FALCONS-HUMMER16-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Mathis slays monster with one big blow
 &HT;    By Steve Hummer
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The 49er killer _ ``You mean the 40-Monster killer,''
he corrects _ had been laying in the weeds all day. This is
especially difficult on artificial turf, but Terance Mathis is
nothing if not wiley.
</P>
<P>
   The 60-minute receiver had nary a catch for the first 56:57 of
Sunday's engagement with San Francisco. And the monster was
stirring. Jerry Rice had outflanked the Atlanta secondary again,
running free for a 65-yard touchdown reception that brought the
49ers back to within five.
</P>
<P>
   Mathis will do the grunt work required in Dan Reeves's
Protestant gameplan. And his teammates were being nicely
supportive. ``Just keep blocking, keep blocking,'' linebacker and
foreshadower Cornelius Bennett had told Mathis at the half.
``You'll catch one pass and it will be for a touchdown, and it will
be the winning touchdown.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, this was getting a little ridiculous for a leading
receiver such as himself. ``I was saying that I can't get shutout
in this game. That was on my mind,'' Mathis admitted.
</P>
<P>
   Not to worry, because under the new rules of Falcons football,
all concerns are met, all prayers are answered.
</P>
<P>
   The plan was hatched to let Mathis do something with San Fran
rookie cornerback R.W. McQuarters. Better get him while he's still
green. As soon as McQuarters came up for some intensely personal
bump-and-run, the big-play machinery went into motion. Mathis would
take his route down the left sideline, and the Falcons would go for
it all. ``Why not take a shot? He was pressed with a rookie. I felt
pretty good about it,'' said quarterback Chris Chandler.
</P>
<P>
   Mathis streaked, Chander delivered and 78 yards later the
Falcons had themselves a touchdown and a victory worth display in
their very small Hall of Precious Memories. Actually, it's more an
efficiency apartment, but the team may be outgrowing it.
</P>
<P>
   Thus was the final stake driven into the heart of the team known
to Mathis as the 40-Monsters.
</P>
<P>
   Other images came to mind. That of a tired, aging king swept out
by an ambitious heir. Or of the long-time bully getting his
backside booted by the kid with skinny arms and bad skin.
</P>
<P>
   On a rare afternoon when Atlanta resembled a true NFL town, one
of its truest NFL players made a difference. Maybe the Falcons
haven't beaten San Francisco enough to have an official 49er
killer. But Mathis is close enough for our purposes. The two
longest receptions of his career (81 yards and Sunday's 78), and
three of his five longest, have come off the 'Niners. Three years
ago, Mathis willed himself into the end zone to beat San Francisco
at season's end to qualify the Falcons for the playoffs. That one
allowed a flighty team one more game. This one hinted at a more
permanent shift in power.
</P>
<P>
   ``As I had been saying all along, it (the 49ers dominance) has
to stop. Today, it stopped,'' Mathis said.
</P>
<P>
   It was telling that the Falcons won the day with the big play
instead of with caution. Not enough to bleed the clock against the
49ers. Got to make them bleed as well. It's a message that plays
well with the long-suffering. Said Jessie Tuggle, the longest
sufferer, ``That play set the tempo. It said we're not going to try
to sit on leads. We're going to try to win.''
</P>
<P>
   Monsters are not timidly slain.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
