<SLUG> BC-FBN-FALCONSFANS-ATBAR16-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    It's `Dirty Bird' dancing at 1st &AMP; 10 bar
 &HT;    By Michael Lee
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Edward Smith and Morris Wyatt drink beer and eat wings
at 1st &AMP; 10 Sports &AMP; Wings on Old National Highway almost every
Sunday they're not in the Georgia Dome to see the Falcons.
</P>
<P>
   But for the first time in three seasons, neither paid to see the
Falcons at home. They watched the Falcons-49ers on the big screen
at their favorite pub.
</P>
<P>
   ``In my opinion, it's hard to sell out 70,000,'' Wyatt said.
``Some stadiums have a capacity of 52,000. If we have 52,000 we
can't see it. We're penalized 'cause we have a big stadium.''
</P>
<P>
   Not Sunday. The NFL's local blackout rule was lifted because the
Georgia Dome was filled to capacity for the first time since a
28-13 loss to Dallas on Oct. 29, 1995. Bobby Ruff had a simple
answer to that.
</P>
<P>
   ``Coach (Dan) Reeves said we don't support them. Now he's got to
put up or shut up,'' Ruff said. ``People don't show up till you
win.''
</P>
<P>
   Well, the Falcons are winning, and it was evident that this was
no ordinary afternoon at 1st &AMP; 10.
</P>
<P>
   While people in Pittsburgh Steelers jerseys and Dallas Cowboys
sweatshirts were in large numbers, as usual, there arguably were
more Falcons fans at the small sports bar, owned by former NFL and
Georgia Tech cornerback Najee Mustafaa.
</P>
<P>
   Before opening kickoff, 1st &AMP; 10 waitress Karen Tann blew her
whistle and yelled, ``Crank it up. Time for the Falcons.''
</P>
<P>
   After every big play, her whistle triggered Falcons fans to
their feet. Some did weak renditions of ``The Dirty Bird'' dance.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't care if they're bandwagon or closet fans. This feels
good,'' Smith said after Ray Buchanan's third-quarter interception.
``It's 72,000 fans in the Georgia Dome, and we're probably making
more noise right now. It's been like this before, but not from
Atlanta fans.''
</P>
<P>
   When Jamal Anderson gave Atlanta a 17-6 lead, the attention fell
on regular Kecia Lyman. Fans surrounding the bar began yelling,
``Take it off! Take it off!''
</P>
<P>
   Now, it wasn't that kind of party. She was one of handful of
people with audacity to wear a 49ers T-shirt.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm a sports fanatic. I love a challenge,'' said Lyman, who
attended Mississippi Valley State with 49ers receiver Jerry Rice.
</P>
<P>
   One customer got in a heated argument with an adamant Falcons
detractor. ``Big man,'' he yelled. ``Big man! We're used to losing.
We're for real this year.''
</P>
<P>
   A round of high-fives followed.
</P>
<P>
   With the Falcons grasping a huge fourth-quarter lead, Smith
paced and grinned. ``The next best thing to being there is being
here,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
