<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-FALCONS-BUCHANAN-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Buchanan's big play gives him, fellow Falcons reason to crow
 &HT;    By Jeff Schultz
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Although he was tackled on his interception return 1
yard from the end zone, Ray Buchanan felt the ``biggest play of the
game'' (he won the vote, 1-0) was worthy of the dance.
</P>
<P>
   ``That right there _ that was the bird,'' said Buchanan, the
Falcons' cornerback, of his post-interception rumba. ``Everybody
has their own bird. We saw a crow out there today. I even saw a
drunk ostrich.''
</P>
<P>
   The Falcons' defense surrendered 307 net passing yards Sunday
against San Francisco, but it had reason to, well, crow. A San
Francisco offense that typically has shredded Atlanta coverage was
limited to two field goals until two busted coverages in the fourth
quarter provided some momentary suspense.
</P>
<P>
   ``It seems like that happens every game,'' said safety Eugene
Robinson. ``We have those lapses that lets the other team get one
or two plays. That's something you can't let happen when you get
into the playoffs.''
</P>
<P>
   Well, there's a switch: the Falcons showing concern about
defects before the postseason. But with an 8-2 record, the focus
should change.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't think I was going to be around here for this,''
linebacker Cornelius Bennett said. ``But I'm here and I'm enjoying
it.''
</P>
<P>
   The focus of the Falcons' defense was to pressure quarterback
Steve Young, who is still ailing from a strained muscle near his
groin, be physical with San Francisco receivers, and if at all
possible, not let Jerry Rice turn 5-yard slants into a 55-yard
gains. With the exception of two fourth-quarter scores by Terrell
Owens (54 yards, blown coverage by Randy Fuller) and Rice (65
yards, the fault of safety William White), the Niners' appeared to
be a frustrated lot.
</P>
<P>
   Falcons defensive coordinator Rich Brooks said, ``I don't think
we saw a healthy Steve Young today,'' but he wasn't weeping.
Several Atlanta defenders remarked that Young seemed to shy away
from throwing back across his body because of his injury.
</P>
<P>
   Young looked anemic on Buchanan's interception, which came late
in the third quarter. With the Falcons leading 10-6, Young blooped
a pass intended for tight end Greg Clark, but Buchanan leaped it
front for the interception and headed back up field. Just before
being tackled at the 1-yard-line, he turned to look for a teammate
to lateral to, then thought better of it. (Brooks: ``I damned near
jumped out of the pressbox.'') Buchanan then broke into his dance,
leaving Jamal Anderson to score _ and dance _ seconds later.
</P>
<P>
   On San Francisco's ensuing drive, the defense struck again when
Young was sacked by Shane Dronett and fumbled, and linebacker
Jessie Tuggle fell on the ball in the end zone for a touchdown and
a 24-6 lead.
</P>
<P>
   Buchanan said he's certain Young, Rice and other 49ers came into
the Georgia Dome thinking they would be able to roll up points with
ease.
</P>
<P>
   ``Of course _ they've been doing it,'' he said. ``History has
shown they've beaten down the Falcons. That's how they get their
stats. That's how they get in the Pro Bowl a lot of the times,
because of how they play against the Falcons.''
</P>
<P>
   Not this time.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
