<SLUG> BC-FBN-FALCONS-DEFENSE16-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Calling Falcons defense? It's busy
 &HT;    By Curtis Bunn
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ In the past, the Falcons defense served as a mere prop
in San Francisco's offensive onslaughts. Big plays by the 49ers
usually left the Falcons' heads spinning and shaking in dismay.
</P>
<P>
   There was a reversal of sorts Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   In less than two minutes spanning the third and fourth quarters,
the Falcons defense turned a four-point game into a 24-6 cushion
that proved significant in a benchmark victory over the Niners.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you score some touchdowns by the defense,'' coach Dan
Reeves said, ``you usually don't lose.''
</P>
<P>
   In other words, you win.
</P>
<P>
   And the Falcons catapulted to the top of the NFC West when the
defense got busy. First, cornerback Ray Buchanan, whose nickname is
``Big Play,'' intercepted a Steve Young pass and made an exciting
34-yard return to the San Francisco 1-yard line with 28 seconds
left in the third period.
</P>
<P>
   ``Huge play,'' Reeves said.
</P>
<P>
   Two plays later, at the start of the fourth quarter, Jamal
Anderson plunged in for a touchdown and a 17-6 lead.
</P>
<P>
   On the next possession, defensive tackle Shane Dronett sacked
Young and forced a fumble that was recovered by Jessie Tuggle, who
rolled into the end zone for the touchdown.
</P>
<P>
   ``We let them know they were going to be in for a dogfight,''
Dronett said. ``I came out of a double team, and Young rolled my
way. He squared to throw, and I got a pretty good lick on him.
Jessie did the rest.''
</P>
<P>
   Tuggle's score established an NFL record of five career
touchdowns on fumble recoveries.
</P>
<P>
   ``It couldn't have come at a better time,'' he said. ``I'm
pretty proud of myself and the whole unit. We mixed up defenses and
we rallied to the ball.
</P>
<P>
   ``And most important _ against a team that usually makes big
plays on us _ we made big plays on them. And it feels great.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
