<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-APEC-TRADE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ASIAN NATIONS ENDORSE LIMITED MEASURES TO OPEN MARKETS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By INDIRA A.R. LAKSHMANAN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   KUALA LUMPUR, Malaysia _ After days of bitter negotiations that
degenerated into public name-calling, the United States and other
Asian and Pacific economies Sunday salvaged a compromise trade
liberalization deal that squelched Japanese efforts to protect
markets at a time of financial crisis.
</P>
<P>
   Still, several officials at the Asia-Pacific Economic
Cooperation summit bemoaned the accord as a half-measure that
failed to live up to APEC's goals _ raising questions about the
ability of key nations to scuttle deals, and doubts about the
effectiveness of the self-styled free trade club.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, domestic political discord here in Malaysia
distracted from the economic agenda of the 21 governments. Police
Sunday arrested and fired tear gas at a few hundred demonstrators
demanding that their prime minister step down, and US Secretary of
State Madeleine K. Albright defied her hosts by meeting the wife of
a jailed government critic and engaging in a war of words over it
with a Malaysian Cabinet minister.
</P>
<P>
   Officials tried, however, to keep the spotlight on an accord
worth $1.5 trillion in trade that may prove to be the key agreement
at this year's APEC summit. The hangup in the deal came when Japan,
Asia's largest economy, said it could not approve proposed tariff
cuts in forest and fish products, two industries that are key
supporters of Japan's ruling party.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, 16 of APEC's 21 nations, including Japan, agreed to
keep the commitment to voluntary liberalization intact, but to
submit the plan to the World Trade Organization for negotiation and
approval by other nations.
</P>
<P>
   The deal covers fish, medical equipment, environmental goods and
services and energy sector goods and services, as well as
chemicals, forest products, gems and jewelry, toys and
telecommunications equipment.
</P>
<P>
   The United States is eager to open markets to help halt the nose
dive in US exports to Asia, which have taken a beating since the
regional crisis began 17 months ago. The US trade deficit with Asia
is expected to balloon to $177 billion this year, up 30 percent
from last year. The downturn has cost America thousands of
manufacturing jobs, but resisting domestic pressure to protect
affected industries, the Clinton administration has tried to force
other countries to open markets and import more US goods.
</P>
<P>
   Sunday the United States put the best possible face on the deal,
saying the free trade consensus among members, despite the
financial crisis that has slashed growth in several nations,
prevented Japan from reverting to protectionism or persuading its
neighbors to do the same. In that alone, US Trade Representative
Charlene Barshefsky said, APEC had achieved a victory and could now
be the catalyst for a broader effort to reduce tariffs worldwide.
</P>
<P>
   ``A year ago we had nothing, zero. Two days ago we thought there
was a very high degree of likelihood the whole thing would
collapse. Particularly given the financial situation of these
countries, it's remarkable this initiative has held together,'' she
said last night.
</P>
<P>
   ``These countries could have used Japan's intransigence on
forests and fish to retreat. ... Instead, exactly the reverse
occurred,'' she said, praising Indonesia, Thailand, the Philippines
and South Korea for expanding, rather than reducing, their offers
to cut trade barriers, despite Japanese pressure.
</P>
<P>
   APEC members ``decided that market opening is not the cause of
the crisis and was not going to become a victim of the crisis. It
was going to be used'' as a way out of the crisis.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday, Barshefsky had angrily accused Japan of offering
financial aid to countries willing to scrap the trade deal, and
Japan retorted that the United States was ``mean'' and saw the
world in ``an evil way.''
</P>
<P>
   In a brief interview last night, Japanese Trade and Industry
Minister Kaoru Yosano said domestic pressures had made it
impossible for him to secure tariff cuts in sensitive sectors, but
insisted Japan was trying its best.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Japanese government had been trying for a pretty long time
... to enable Japan to participate. ... However, our effort was not
quite in time for this meeting,'' he said, asserting that Japan
would support, not obstruct the deal at the trade organization.
``Don't confuse what's happening in APEC with what will happen in
WTO.''
</P>
<P>
   Barshefsky also acknowledged that with or without Japan's
cooperation, under US law, Washington could not implement tariff
cuts until a ``critical mass'' of countries worldwide have signed
on under the World Trade Organization.
</P>
<P>
   Comparing the process to an information technology agreement
that APEC negotiated a few years ago, Barshefsky noted that only
eight APEC members initially signed onto that deal. But within
eight months of its being taken to the trade organization, 23
countries signed, and another 22 signed a year later.
</P>
<P>
   Despite that positive spin, others expressed disappointment the
deal was not fully adopted Sunday by APEC nations.
</P>
<P>
   ``Canada certainly would have preferred a quicker pace,'' said
Canadian Trade Minister Sergio Marchi. ``Instead of plan A, we
opted for plan B _ to move the package entirely to WTO. ... Plan B
is not as good as plan A, but it's better than no plan at all.''
</P>
<P>
   Robert Lees, secretary general of the Pacific Basin Economic
Council, which represents 1,100 Pacific Rim corporations, last
night questioned APEC's credibility, given that it could not make
good on a pledge made a year ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``I suppose we should be happy. ... At least the process is
alive,'' he said. But ``it's an opportunity lost to APEC. ... Is it
a family of 21 economies? It's a shame we can't get an initiative
through that really delivers tangible results that APEC needs to
deliver to business.''
</P>
<P>
   Politics was also a point of conflict Sunday, when Albright was
forced to defend her decision to meet the wife of Anwar Ibrahim,
the Malaysian deputy prime minister who was fired and arrested on
charges of sodomy and abuse of power after clashing with Prime
Minister Mahathir Mohamad.
</P>
<P>
   ``The United States has made clear a number of times that Anwar
Ibrahim is a highly respected leader. We believe he is entitled to
due process and a fair trial,'' Albright said at a forum of Cabinet
ministers and journalists.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can assure the international community that anybody in this
country will get a fair trial,'' Malaysian Trade Minister Rafidah
Aziz snapped back. ``Perhaps when I go to the US, I would like to
meet Ken Starr.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He is not in prison,'' a visibly angered Albright responded.
</P>
<P>
   ``But to find out what is happening _ curious,'' retorted
Rafidah.
</P>
<P>
   State Department spokesman James Rubin called the comparison
between Anwar and Starr ``pathetic. ... It says more about the
difference between them and us than anything else I've heard.''
</P>
<P>
   Mahathir expressed dismay at President Clinton's decision not to
attend APEC because of the Iraqi crisis. ``If the US is not
represented at the highest level'' at APEC ``other countries will
have a bigger say,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Also Sunday, sporadic protests that began after Anwar's ouster
continued, with about 200 demonstrators calling for Mahathir to
step down. Police sprayed them with water, tear gas, and dye, and
according to the Bloomberg news service made seven arrests.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
