<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Stinchcomb won't play vs. Ole Miss
 &HT;    By Mark Schlabach
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATHENS, Ga. _ Georgia's 28-17 win over Auburn on Saturday proved
costly as the Bulldogs may have lost All-America offensive tackle
Matt Stinchcomb for the remaining two regular-season games.
</P>
<P>
   Stinchcomb, a 6-foot-6, 291-pound senior from Lilburn's Parkview
High, separated his left shoulder in the third quarter. Coach Jim
Donnan said the left tackle will miss Saturday's game against
Mississippi, but could return for the Nov. 28 game against Georgia
Tech.
</P>
<P>
   Stinchcomb, who underwent an MRI exam Sunday, would likely play
in a postseason bowl game for Georgia (7-2, 5-2), which moved up
three spots to No. 14 in the Associated Press poll and No. 15 in
the USA Today/ESPN coaches' poll.
</P>
<P>
   ``Stinchcomb will be out this week,'' Donnan said. ``We think he
has got a chance to play against Georgia Tech, but we'll be very
careful because of his pending NFL career.''
</P>
<P>
   Receiver Tony Small (knee) and linebacker Adrian Hollingshed
(ankle), who both missed the second half against Auburn, are
probable for the Mississippi game.
</P>
<P>
   Stinchcomb, a finalist for the Outland Trophy, has been
Georgia's most durable player, starting 32 consecutive games. His
blocking grade has been 90 percent or better in every game this
season.
</P>
<P>
   Georgia has a few options in replacing Stinchcomb. Right tackle
Chris Terry could move to the left side to protect quarterback
Quincy Carter's blind side, with backup Kelvin Williams starting at
right tackle. Sophomore Jonas Jennings, the starting right guard,
could move to tackle, with sophomore Reggie Stargill of LaGrange
starting at guard.
</P>
<P>
   Williams, a 6-5, 290-pound transfer from Georgia Military
College, played the final quarter against the Tigers.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
