<SLUG> BC-IRAQ-ANALYSIS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RAPID EVENTS LEAVE A HAZY OUTCOME 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (a and i coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID L. MARCUS   AND COLUM LYNCH  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Three days after declaring that the world was
united against Saddam Hussein, the Clinton administration found
that the truth was not so simple.
</P>
<P>
   The coalition of Arab and European governments that had tacitly
supported the US buildup in the Persian Gulf had crumbled by
Sunday. A day after rejecting Hussein's ambiguous offer to
capitulate, President Clinton accepted it. And even as he made a
deal with Hussein, Clinton took the unorthodox step of calling for
the Iraqi leader's overthrow.
</P>
<P>
   For his part, Hussein avoided a full-bore military assault,
apparently at the last minute. But it is far from clear that he
will achieve one of his most important goals: ending UN economic
sanctions on Iraq.
</P>
<P>
   The traditional definitions of winner and loser do not apply
this time. The United States has paid a heavy price in diplomatic
capital as it has undergone a billion-dollar military buildup, but
it has avoided a war that could have cost far more.
</P>
<P>
   Hussein won his fifth attempt to thwart Clinton, but he has
tried the patience of his halfhearted defenders, Russia and France.
</P>
<P>
   And as the rhetoric dies down, UNSCOM, the beleaguered UN arms
monitoring agency, probably will return to Iraq with agents who are
demoralized and a mission that is far from clear.
</P>
<P>
   ``We didn't have a lot of good choices,'' said Jeswold Salacuse,
an international law specialist at the Fletcher School of Law and
Diplomacy at Tufts University. ``Could we go in and attack when
Iraq showed flexibility? Even if we did, could we have driven him
from power? That would have taken an invasion, and I can't see the
American people going for that once they learned the costs in
manpower and possible casualties.''
</P>
<P>
   Just last Thursday, this hazy outcome seemed improbable. Eight
Arab countries issued a statement saying Hussein had only himself
to blame for his conflicts with the UN and the United States. No
other country stepped forward to support Hussein _ not even Russia,
a traditional defender. The State Department said that absence of
criticism amounted to international support for a US military
attack.
</P>
<P>
   Late Thursday, President Boris N. Yeltsin and Prime Minister
Yevgeny M. Primakov of Russia wrote to Hussein, telling him to step
down. Hussein remained defiant, saying that he would consider any
initiative but that it must take into account Iraq's rights.
</P>
<P>
   The following morning, the alliance started to splinter,
diplomats say. As they tell it, the UN representatives of France,
Russia, and China made the first concerted effort to foil a US
attack and find a diplomatic solution, urging UN Secretary General
Kofi Annan to write a letter asking Hussein to admit weapons
inspectors back to Iraq.
</P>
<P>
   According to the diplomats, Annan showed interest but said he
needed ``airtight'' assurance that Iraq would allow in the nearly
100 inspectors without conditions. He also wanted US support for
the idea.
</P>
<P>
   At the time, senior aides said Annan did not want to repeat
negotiations he had held with Hussein but would consider going to
Baghdad if asked by the Security Council, which is made up of the
most powerful countries. ``It would probably make him sick,'' said
a senior UN aide.
</P>
<P>
   The United States squelched the initiative and demanded that
Annan send a letter to the Iraqi leadership repeating Annan's
previous demands that the Iraqis back down.
</P>
<P>
   During the diplomatic back-and-forth, Annan's advisers said they
had been tipped off that a massive US airstrike on Iraq was likely.
Several Arab reporters, after chatting with Iraq's ambassador to
the United Nations, Nizar Hamdoon, in the Security Council lounge,
spread rumors about an upcoming airstrike.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday, Annan sent a last-ditch appeal to Baghdad, but told
reporters that prospects for a diplomatic solution were fading. A
day later, as US officials tell it, the Pentagon was about to
strike when Iraq's deputy foreign minister, Tariq Aziz, pledged to
let the inspectors back but confused matters by demanding an end to
inspections and a relaxing of sanctions.
</P>
<P>
   Annan and his senior envoy in Baghdad, Prakash Shah, said that
the letter meets the Security Council demands. Annan's spokesman
Fred Eckhard said UN humanitarian workers would return to the
country, infuriating American officials. According to Annan's
aides, Clinton's national security adviser, Samuel R. Berger,
called the UN chief on Saturday morning to say that bombers were
already in the air.
</P>
<P>
   Annan dropped his plan to send the humanitarian workers back,
but by that time the United States had to reckon with divided
allies and friends. Russia and China immediately hailed Iraq's
promises as a breakthrough. The president of France, Jacques
Chirac, urged the UN to ``test'' the offer by sending inspectors
back, a move that would make a US strike impossible.
</P>
<P>
   On Saturday night, Russia's deputy ambassador, Yuri Fedotov,
emerged from a Security Council meeting to say that the United
States was being ``unpleasant.'' Other members, even Britain,
argued against a military strike.
</P>
<P>
   In an address Sunday, Clinton proclaimed that ``the world spoke
with one voice'' against Iraq. And that was so, if only for a brief
moment before the harmony was lost.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
