<SLUG> BC-EDIT-BUDGET-OFFICE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: HONEST NUMBERS ON CAPITOL HILL 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 &HT;     
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial on Monday, Nov. 16:
</P>
<P>
   When Congress debates taxes and spending decisions, it is the
Congressional Budget Office that sets the terms of the debate, with
its estimates of just how much each provision will cost or bring in
to the Treasury. That office has developed a reputation for
impartial professionalism that must be preserved.
</P>
<P>
   With June O'Neill, the director of the office, stepping down at
the end of the year, the appointment of her successor will provide
an early indication of whether the new Republican leadership in the
House will continue on the same disastrous course begun by Speaker
Newt Gingrich and his colleagues last summer.
</P>
<P>
   Frustrated by Ms. O'Neill's refusal to bend the numbers to make
huge tax cuts appear to cost little in the way of revenues, the
speaker and the rest of the outgoing House Republican leadership
sent a letter threatening to ``review the structure and funding''
of the office if it did not start making more congenial
assessments.
</P>
<P>
   Now, some Republicans are arguing that the new director should
be a Republican partisan who will run the office in a blatantly
political way. It is up to the chairmen of the Budget Committees,
Rep. John Kasich and Sen. Pete Domenici, to assure that does not
happen. The incoming speaker, Robert Livingston, should make it
clear that he wants professionalism, not rigged numbers.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
