<HEADLINE>
DEFUSING CRISIS, CLINTON ACCEPTS IRAQI RETREAT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By COLUM LYNCH   AND DAVID MARCUS  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNITED NATIONS _ President Clinton pulled back Sunday from the
brink of a bombing campaign in Iraq, while vowing to embark on a
long-term campaign to remove Iraqi leader Saddam Hussein from
power.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  He accepted Hussein's latest offer to reopen Iraq to UN arms
inspections, but said that US troops remain poised to strike if
Baghdad breaks its pledge.
</P>
<P>
   The president's decision followed by hours Baghdad's
capitulation in the face of US demands that it provide public and
written assurances that it will stop interfering with UN arms
inspectors seeking to rid Iraq of its chemical, biological and
nuclear weapons.
</P>
<P>
   The diplomatic victory was tempered, however, by concerns among
US officials that the Iraqi leader will provoke another
confrontation down the road. The chief UN weapons inspector,
Richard Butler, said Sunday he would send the UN arms team back to
Iraq on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``Let me be clear that Saddam Hussein has backed down, but that
is not enough. Now Iraq must live up to its obligations,'' Clinton
said. ``Iraq isolated itself from world opinion ... more than at
any time since the Gulf War'' in 1991.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton expanded the US commitment by outlining a mission to
undermine the leadership in Baghdad and install ``a government in
Iraq that represents and respects its people _ not represses
them.''
</P>
<P>
   The plan, which involves supporting Iraq's ineffectual exile
opposition movement and propaganda radio into Iraq, emerged last
October when the administration authorized $97 million to finance a
``democratic'' alternative to Hussein.
</P>
<P>
   ``Over the past year we have deepened our engagement with the
forces of change in Iraq,'' he said. ``We will intensify that
effort.''
</P>
<P>
   Following a UN Security Council debate Sunday night, the UN
humanitarian aid coordinator, Benon Sevan, announced that he would
send 151 relief workers back to Iraq as early as Monday. An
additional 92 UN weapons inspectors are expected to return to
Baghdad Tuesday to begin testing Iraq's pledge, according to Ewen
Buchanan, a spokesman for the UN Special Commission charged with
eliminating Iraq's weapons of mass destruction.
</P>
<P>
   The current crisis has its roots in the 1991 cease-fire
agreement ending the Gulf War. Under the terms of the accord, Iraq
is required to prove to the United Nations that it has destroyed
all of its long-range missiles and obliterate its chemical,
biological and nuclear weapons programs.
</P>
<P>
   The Special Commission has obliterated more weapons than were
destroyed by the US-led Gulf War alliance, according to Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   But the commission maintains that Iraq is still hiding evidence
of a secret weapons program.
</P>
<P>
   Prevented by the Iraqi authorities from working, the UN
inspectors, along with UN relief workers, were pulled out of the
country last Wednesday amid expectations that the United States and
Britain were on the verge of striking Baghdad.
</P>
<P>
   US and British officials said Baghdad escaped a military strike
by hours.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton ordered US warplanes into action Saturday only to recall
them when Washington learned of Baghdad's retreat. The president's
national security adviser, Samuel R. Berger, said Sunday the
military would remain in the region to respond to potential acts of
defiance.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, for example, three EC-130 planes with electronic
jammers, are set to leave from an Air Force base in Arizona.
</P>
<P>
   The Pentagon said it had halted a major buildup of military
forces in the Gulf, a deployment that began last week in
expectation of strikes against Iraq, Reuters reported.
</P>
<P>
   The United States already has a powerful force of more than 180
warplanes and 15 ships, including the aircraft carrier Eisenhower,
in the Gulf. Seven of those ships and a submarine are capable of
firing long-range Tomahawk cruise missiles.
</P>
<P>
   There was considerable anger in Washington that Hussein had once
again avoided punishing strikes after forcing the United States to
mount an expensive military build up in the Gulf. Former senator
Sam Nunn said on NBC Sunday morning that the United States would
have been far better off ``had we bombed before'' Baghdad had a
chance to step down.
</P>
<P>
   But many congressional figures said the plan to oust Hussein has
merit.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's easier said than done,'' Senator Arlen Specter,
Republican of Pennsylvania, told CNN Sunday. ``But I think that's,
candidly, the next objective and I'm glad to hear the president
talk about it openly and forcefully.''
</P>
<P>
   The president's decision to suspend the threat of military force
was made as international acceptance that American military action
was inevitable began to dry up Saturday when Hussein sent a
conciliatory message to the United Nations.
</P>
<P>
   Faced with clear signs that Baghdad was looking to reverse
course, France, Russia and China, all members of the Security
Council, found it increasingly untenable to back US military
action.
</P>
<P>
   Arab countries that had earlier blamed Baghdad for provoking
Washington made it clear Sunday that they were satisfied that Iraq
no longer deserved to be targeted by US cruise missiles and
warplanes. ``Now we are not talking about military strikes,'' said
Egyptian Foreign Minister Amr Moussa. ``The problem we hope will be
defused.''
</P>
<P>
   Even Britain, the closest US ally, began looking for a
diplomatic exit from the crisis as early as Saturday night,
signaling that it was time to test Iraq's word. Senior UN sources
said that British Prime Minister Tony Blair phoned Clinton late
Saturday night and appealed to him to give the Iraqis another a
chance.
</P>
<P>
   Blair said Sunday that British and American forces still
``remain on alert'' to bomb Hussein. ``Saddam is now trapped,'' he
told reporters outside his office at 10 Downing Street. ``One false
move and he can be hit legitimately.''
</P>
<P>
   ``There will be no further warning whatsoever,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Many analysts said the Clinton administration should have
expected Hussein's last-minute diplomatic entreaty. Laurie Mylroie,
the publisher of the Iraq News bulletin and a critic of the Clinton
administration, said she listened in disbelief Sunday to the
president's announcement that the crisis was ending.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's pathetic,'' Mylroie said. ``The administration should
have been prepared for Saddam to back down. They should have had a
list of steps he had to take within 48 hours to show he really is
complying with his promises'' to let weapons inspectors back to
work. ``They should have had punishment for not complying.''
</P>
<P>
   But UN Secretary General Kofi Annan joined many other world
leaders in praising Clinton's decision.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm grateful to President Clinton for the courageous and
difficult decisions, which he announced earlier today. ... This is
a victory for diplomacy,'' Annan said. ``Iraq must move swiftly to
insure complete and unconditional compliance.''
</P>
</TEXT>
