<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-15 21:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1822 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-IRAQ-HNS &LR;      11-15 1283
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-IRAQ-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
CLINTON SAYS US WILL WORK TO OUST SADDAM
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   By GREG McDONALD &QL; 
 &QL; 
c. 1998
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Houston Chronicle
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
WASHINGTON _ President Clinton upped the ante Sunday in the deadly
game being played out with Iraqi President Saddam Hussein, saying
he plans to intensify efforts to remove him from power in the
aftermath of the latest crisis that moved right to the brink of
war.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton called off a Saturday U.S. airstrike against Iraq after
Saddam sent an urgent series of letters to the United Nations
promising to comply unconditionally with demands that he allow
weapons inspections to resume.
</P>
<P>
   But Clinton, who came under fire for not ``pulling the trigger''
on Saddam, as one member of Congress put it, said the United States
and its allies would ``remain vigilant, keep up the pressure and be
ready to act'' immediately if Iraq shows any signs of reneging on
its latest commitment.
</P>
<P>
   ``Iraq has backed down, but that is not enough. Now Iraq must
live up to its obligations,'' Clinton told reporters Sunday at the
White House.
</P>
<P>
   Flanked by Defense Secretary William Cohen and other members of
his national security team, Clinton stopped short of calling for
Saddam's overthrow. But he made it clear that the United States
will follow through with financial support and other efforts aimed
at stirring up opposition to Saddam from within Iraq.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton said the latest crisis ``demonstrates, unfortunately,
that Iraqi President Saddam Hussein remains an impediment to the
well-being of his people and a threat to the peace of the region
and the security of the world.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Over the long term,'' Clinton added, ``the best way to address
that threat is through a government in Baghdad _ a new government _
that is committed to represent and respect its people, not repress
them, that is committed to peace in the region.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's comments were echoed by British Prime Minister Tony
Blair, who said that he would keep British forces in the Persian
Gulf region on alert to provide support to U.S. forces if military
action is eventually called for.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to be sure that what the Iraqis are saying they will
do ... This is not over yet,'' he cautioned, adding that every
promise Iraq has made this time must be ``bolted down'' before U.S.
and British forces are withdrawn from the immediate area.
</P>
<P>
   ``We remain ready, willing and able to strike at any point in
time,'' Blair said.
</P>
<P>
   United Nations officials said they expect to have international
inspectors, who were pulled out of Iraq completely last week, back
in Baghdad within the next two days. Richard Butler, who is in
charge of the U.N. inspection effort, said he was ordering the
inspectors to return to Iraq on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   But Butler said he believed it would take longer than that to
get enough personnel and equipment in place again to carry out the
kind of surprise inspections that have already uncovered and led to
the destruction of various elements in Iraq's chemical, biological
and nuclear weapons programs.
</P>
<P>
   The latest crisis began on Oct. 31 when Saddam said he would no
longer allow inspections to continue and called on the U.N. to end
economic and other sanctions imposed against his country. Saddam
claimed again that he was not producing weapons of mass
destruction.
</P>
<P>
   Butler said on NBC's Meet the Press Sunday that there is no
doubt, however, that Iraq is continuing to manufacture biological
weapons like VX nerve gas and missiles capable of delivering them
to nearby nations. He said inspectors have also found plenty of
evidence that Iraq is continuing an aggressive biological and
nuclear procurement effort abroad in violation of the agreement it
signed in 1991 ending the Persian Gulf War.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton aborted an airstrike against Iraq Saturday as U.S.
bombers were on their way to selected targets and fighter planes
aboard the aircraft carrier USS Eisenhower in the Persian Gulf were
being prepared for takeoff.
</P>
<P>
   Cohen confirmed to reporters that the order to strike had
already been given early Saturday and the planned attack was nearly
played out ``right up to the end'' when Iraq sent its first letter
to the U.N. promising to back down. But the initial letter was
unacceptable, he said, and Iraq was forced to send to follow-up
statement pledging unconditional cooperation before Clinton issued
a final order for U.S. forces to stand down.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was close, very close,'' Cohen said.
</P>
<P>
   As insurance to help guarantee Saddam's latest promise of
compliance, Cohen said the buildup of American forces in the region
would continue through the Thanksgiving holiday in case military
action becomes necessary. By Thanksgiving, some 22 U.S. Navy ships
will be in the Persian Gulf along with the Eisenhower. Altogether,
some 45,000 U.S. military personnel will be on station in the
region.
</P>
<P>
   At the United Nations, Iraqi ambassador Nizar Hamdoon claimed a
partial victory for Saddam, saying that his leader had at least
``succeeded in getting a good hearing'' about his frustration with
continued international sanctions that were put in place after the
war.
</P>
<P>
   But Hamdoon acknowledged that inspectors would be allowed to go
``anywhere they want.'' Asked what forced Iraq to back down this
time, Hamdoon said, ``We have decided to give it a chance because
peace, stability, preventing war, I think, is a noble goal.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to get out of this crisis. We are not interested in
getting into another one,'' Hamdoon said later as the U.N. Security
Council began a meeting on Iraq.
</P>
<P>
   While Clinton's decision to call off military strikes was
welcomed by U.N. Secretary General Kofi Annan as ``courageous'' and
``statesmanlike,'' it was strongly criticized by some Republican
senators who have long advocated using force against Saddam to
remove him from power.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Richard Lugar, R-Ind., a member of the Senate Foreign
Relations Committee, said he thought it was a mistake to reverse
course on the brink of airstrikes and called on Clinton to push
ahead with destruction of sites known to be part of Saddam's
weapons programs. He also called for strikes against Saddam's
military forces.
</P>
<P>
   ``While we have the forces moving there now, we ought to use
them,'' Lugar said, adding that diplomacy with Saddam has been a
failure.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now, we're in the dodge and weave period again,'' he said on
NBC's Meet the Press. ``We've been embarrassed.''
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Arlen Specter, R-Pa., also called for assassination to be
considered as an option to get rid of Saddam, even though it is
outlawed by U.S. law.
</P>
<P>
   Reacting to the criticism, Clinton agreed that military action
would ``significantly degrade the capability of Saddam Hussein to
develop weapons of mass destruction.'' But he said it would also
mark the end of the U.N. presence in Iraq.
</P>
<P>
   ``We would delay it, but we would have no oversight, no insight,
no involvement in what is going on within Iraq,'' Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The return of the inspectors, if they can act in an unfettered
way, is the best outcome because they have been and they remain the
most effective tool to uncover, destroy and prevent Iraq from
rebuilding its weapons of mass destruction and the missiles to
deliver them.''
</P>
<P>
   Following the U.N. Security Council meeting Sunday, Annan said
that member nations were satisfied that Iraq had agreed
unconditionally to allow inspections to continue. But he conceded
that he could not guarantee that the new agreement will work.
</P>
<P>
   ``I cannot tell you that there will not be a next time,'' he
said. ``But if there is a next time, I'm not sure there will be
enough time for diplomatic appeals.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
