<HEADER>
A1830 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-APEC-MALAYSIA-HNS &LR;      11-15 1034
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-APEC-MALAYSIA-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
US LEADERS KEEP AN EYE ON ASIAN ECONOMIC SITUATION AS FORUM BEGINS
<TEXT>
<P>
   By CRAGG HINES &QL; 
c. 1998
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Houston Chronicle &QL;
</P>
<P>
   KUALA LUMPUR, Malaysia _ While most Americans don't know a
ringgit from a rupiah, U.S. voters are hypersensitive to the value
of their own money and are quickly troubled when a dollar won't buy
as much as they think it should.
</P>
<P>
   That's why both U.S. political parties are keeping a wary eye on
the Asian economic crisis and this week's Asia-Pacific Economic
Cooperation forum, where Vice President Al Gore will join leaders
from 20 other Pacific Rim nations.
</P>
<P>
   The trouble began 16 months ago with a run on Thailand's
currency, the baht, then spread quickly to other southeast Asian
monetary units, including the Malaysian ringgit and the Indonesian
rupiah.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. political leaders are equally cautious about international
financial turbulence beyond the Pacific region, especially in
Russia and Latin America, and particularly about what any of these
foreign crises mean to the domestic economy.
</P>
<P>
   For woe be unto the American politician, especially a
presidential candidate, whom voters tie to economic bad news.
</P>
<P>
   Ask Gerald Ford, Jimmy Carter and George Bush _ three of the
last five U.S. presidents _ who each failed to hang on to the White
House at least in part because voters thought the U.S. economy had
headed south.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you've got to put money on one variable'' in the political
equation, said Michael Lewis-Beck, a University of Iowa political
scientist, ``just look at how the economy's doing. That's going to
take you farther than anything else.''
</P>
<P>
   Voter satisfaction with the U.S. economy and President Clinton's
stewardship of it over the last six years was found in exit polls
to be a factor in his Democrats' better-than-expected showing in
congressional elections earlier this month.
</P>
<P>
   But it's not clear sailing for Democrats, especially Gore,
Clinton's close ally and the leading contender for his party's
nomination in 2000.
</P>
<P>
   For the fourth month in a row, consumer confidence fell in
October _ to its lowest level in two years, according to the
Conference Board's closely followed index of how Americans are
feeling about their economic future. But the measure is still
firmly in positive territory after hitting a record high in June.
</P>
<P>
   ``People are a little less optimistic about the future, but it
hasn't had a major impact yet,'' said Alan Abramowitz, a political
scientist at Emory University in Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   The concern, however, is real for Democrats in general and Gore
in particular.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the meltdown that began in Asia and has been moving in our
direction leaves our economy weakened or even stalled in the year
before the 2000 election, the probability of the Republicans
recapturing the White House increases dramatically,'' said Thomas
Mann of the Brookings Institution in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   Some analysts believe that even without pronounced spillover
from the Asian crisis, some issues arising from the globalization
of the economy will enter the domestic political dialogue.
</P>
<P>
   Chief among the points emphasized by liberal economists and
social policy advocates is the stark difference between what the
move to a borderless financial world has meant to workers and
investors.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've had a 20 percent increase in productivity, (and) the
typical worker has nothing to show for it,'' Dean Baker of the
Washington-based Economic Policy Institute told a recent forum.
</P>
<P>
   Another participant, Mark Weisbrot of the Preamble Center, said
later that the decline in real wages is ``the most outrageous''
consequence of the headlong drive to a global economy. He predicts
it is an issue that could play a major role in the next
presidential campaign.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guarantee you it will be there in 2000,'' Weisbrot said. ``I
think even the establishment candidates are going to have to deal
with this. The whole spectrum is moving.''
</P>
<P>
   And beneath the residual overall public approval of Clinton's
handling of the economy, already there are some heavy clouds on the
horizon.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton has lost for the foreseeable future his free hand in
international trade negotiations because of Congress' refusal to
grant him ``fast track'' authority. The power, routinely accorded
to administrations over the last several decades, was withheld
because of a ``strange bedfellows'' coalition of liberal Democrats
who want worker and environmental protections incorporated into
trade deals and conservative Republicans who see an erosion of
sovereignty in the massive pacts.
</P>
<P>
   Only with the greatest difficulty did Clinton secure additional
U.S. cash for the International Monetary Fund, which he said was
needed to guarantee bailout deals in case the Asian economic flu
spread, particularly to the Americas.
</P>
<P>
   Some liberal and conservative economists have taken heart in
Congress' recalcitrance.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is finally the well-justified backlash against a global
process that has really kind of put people last,'' Weisbrot said.
``I think it keeps building, especially if the economy slows down,
which it inevitably will.''
</P>
<P>
   Some economists, such as Lawrence Lau of Stanford's Hoover
Institution, discount any relationship between Asia's slide or
other international financial problems and U.S. politics.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. exports are 12 percent of the nation's gross domestic
product, Lau said, and exports to Asia have been running 30 percent
of that, or 3.6 percent of GDP.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the aggregate, that's not going to make a big difference,''
Lau said.
</P>
<P>
   Also, many political scientists believe economic problems have
to hit very close to home before discomfort is felt at the polls.
But at that point it can be very direct and compelling. Carter was
denied a second term in 1980 partly because the second Arab oil
shock was being felt by average Americans in a dose of short gas
supplies and long lines at filling stations.
</P>
<P>
   ``Clearly there are very real impacts if people see the economy
not doing well,'' said Bruce Oppenheimer, a political scientist at
Vanderbilt University. ``But clearly a bigger effect is if they're
not doing well.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
