<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-15 22:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1881 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TOBACCO-COX16     11-15 0516
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TOBACCO-COX16 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    As states agonize over tobacco deal, industry backs good bet
 &HT;    By Chris Burritt
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   GREENSBORO, N.C. _ The tobacco industry is embracing a proposed
$206 billion settlement of states' health-related lawsuits as a way
to avoid potentially devastating jury verdicts, Lorillard Tobacco
Co.'s chief executive said Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   ''It greatly reduces the risk of a large class-action award,''
Lorillard Chairman and CEO Alex Spears said in an interview, as the
attorneys general of eight states prepared today to unveil details
of the proposed 25-year settlement.
</P>
<P>
   Over the next several days, states across the country will
consider whether to join in the landmark settlement. Besides the
eight states negotiating with the industry, 30 others, including
Georgia, are plaintiffs in the litigation. Georgia would receive an
estimated $2 billion to $3 billion in the settlement. The state
could reject the settlement and pursue a separate lawsuit, which
could result in billions of dollars more, or nothing at all.
Georgia officials are expected to decide this week.
</P>
<P>
   Spears' remarks early Sunday were believed to be the first
public comments by an executive of any of the four tobacco
companies involved in the intense negotiations with attorneys
general from Washington, North Carolina, California, Colorado, New
York, Oklahoma, North Dakota and Pennsylvania.
</P>
<P>
   Greensboro-based Lorillard, which produces Newport, Kent and
True cigarettes, agreed Saturday to the proposed settlement along
with the other major cigarette makers, Philip Morris, RJR Nabisco
and Brown &AMP; Williamson. Without a settlement, Spears said, the
industry is vulnerable to awards that could reach tens of billions
of dollars for each state. And if the industry wanted to appeal a
verdict, a judge could require cigarette makers to post an
immediate bond, which could exceed the amount of the verdict by
many times. ''That could be huge,'' Spears said.
</P>
<P>
   The proposal to be announced today would salvage parts of a
broader tobacco settlement that died in Congress last summer. The
major tobacco companies had agreed in June 1997 to settle for
$368.5 billion over 25 years, but the industry withdrew its support
after legislation to enact the settlement raised the price tag to
$516 billion.
</P>
<P>
   The new proposal, negotiated over five months, is less
attractive to the tobacco industry because it does not put an end
to class-action lawsuits, as the earlier proposed settlement would
have done, Spears said.
</P>
<P>
   A class-action lawsuit involves a group of plaintiffs, such as
the estimated 500,000 Floridians represented in the first
class-action lawsuit against the industry to go to trial. Legal
observers estimated the plaintiffs in that trial in Miami could
receive $200 billion. ''You are still going to have such suits
against you,'' Spears said. He added the industry still faces legal
threats from individuals and from municipalities, such as city and
county governments.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
