<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-DBACKS-REYNOSO-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DIAMONDBACKS TARGET REYNOSO 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By DON KETCHUM  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - By week's end, the Diamondbacks could have another man
in their starting rotation.
</P>
<P>
   He's free-agent right-hander Armando Reynoso, who was 7-3 in 11
starts for the New York Mets in 1998, including a 5-4 victory over
Arizona at Bank One Ballpark on Aug. 15.
</P>
<P>
   Reynoso's agent, Oscar Suarez, met with Diamondbacks General
Manager Joe Garagiola Jr. and Assistant General Manager Sandy
Johnson on Sunday and came away optimistic that a deal can be
completed.
</P>
<P>
   Suarez said although the Boston Red Sox, Philadelphia Phillies
and San Diego Padres also have expressed interest in the
32-year-old Reynoso, the pitcher's first choice is to come to
Arizona.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a good meeting. The interest is very strong,'' Suarez
said.
</P>
<P>
   Reynoso is a native of Mexico and has numerous friends and
relatives in this region, according to Suarez.
</P>
<P>
   Suarez said Reynoso also could be instrumental in improving the
comfort level of outfielder Karim Garcia, also a native of Mexico.
Garcia, 23, and Reynoso were teammates for a brief period for the
Obregon ballclub in the Mexican League.
</P>
<P>
   ``What better way for Armando to help the club than to take
Karim under his wing,'' Suarez said.
</P>
<P>
   Reynoso was selected by the Colorado Rockies from Atlanta in the
1992 expansion draft and was the club's Pitcher of the Year (12-11)
after beginning the season at Triple-A.
</P>
<P>
   In 1994, he was 3-4 in nine starts before an elbow injury cut
short his season. He underwent ``Tommy John'' surgery, in which a
ligament from the left wrist was transplanted into the right elbow.
</P>
<P>
   He was 7-7 with 18 starts in 1995 and 8-9 in 30 starts in 1996
before being traded to New York for pitcher Jerry Dipoto. Reynoso
was 6-3 in 16 starts for the Mets in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Reynoso has been plagued by nagging shoulder difficulties over
the last few seasons, including the start of the 1998 season. Once
healthy, however, he provided the Mets with a solid presence on the
mound. He is not an overpowering pitcher but has excellent control.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's fair to say that there's a great deal of interest
there,'' Garagiola said. ``We're hopeful that something can get
done by the end of this week.''
</P>
<P>
   Reynoso would join a rotation that includes right-hander Andy
Benes and left-handers Brian Anderson and Omar Daal.
</P>
<P>
   The Diamondbacks are hoping the rotation also will include
left-hander Randy Johnson, with whom they have had repeated contact
over the last few weeks, or right-hander Todd Stottlemyre.
</P>
<P>
   The 33-year-old Stottlemyre will visit with Arizona officials
Tuesday at Bank One Ballpark. He began the 1998 season with St.
Louis, beating the Diamondbacks twice, then was traded to the Texas
Rangers and finished with a combined record of 14-13. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
