Brennan discussing one of his paintings with visitors to his studio
as part of Artwalk NY, a series of tours through artists' studios
and a three-part fund-raiser. The event is run by the Coalition for
the Homeless, which raised an estimated $400,000 for its nine
programs, including food distribution and a summer camp. (Edward
Keating/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT7) WASHINGTON -- Nov. 15, 1998 -- HOUSE-FRESHMEN, 11-15 --
The House freshman class gathered on the steps of the Capitol on
Friday for an official portrait by the House photographer Dwight
Comedy, in foreground. Few expected the changes in the House
brought about since the election. (Stephen Crowley/New York Times
Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT6) XCACEL, Mexico -- Nov. 15, 1998 -- MEXICO-TURTLES-2,
11-15 -- This pristine Caribbean beach at Xcacel is one of the
world's most important nesting areas for sea turtles, and Mexican
environmentalists view its ivory sands and emerald waters as sacred
terrain. The state government's sale of the beach to a Spanish
corporation, Sol Melia, which intends to build a hotel on the
beach, has been condemned by Mexican and international
environmental groups. (Keith Dannemiller/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT5) XCACEL, Mexico -- Nov. 15, 1998 -- MEXICO-TURTLES-1,
11-15 -- An Atlantic green turtle making its way toward the sea
from the beach at Xcacel. The state government's sale of the beach
to a Spanish corporation, Sol Melia, which intends to build a hotel
on the beach, has been condemned by Mexican and international
environmental groups. A Sol Melia executive insists that
environmental protection will be a factor in the new hotel's
design. (Keith Dannemiller/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT4) JERUSALEM -- Nov. 15, 1998 -- JEWS-IDENTITY, 11-15 --
Maya Hagege, 20, a student from Los Angeles, Calif., at the Western
Wall. In an attempt to rebuild religious identity among young Jews,
who are marrying non-Jews and abandoning the faith in large
numbers, Jewish organizations are starting a program, Birthright
Israel, that will pay for any Jew in the world between age 15 and
26 to travel to Israel for 10 days. (Rina Castelnuovo/New York
Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT3) MIAMI -- Nov. 15, 1998 -- SUB-CRUISE-SHIP-CRIME-2, 11-15
-- The fun began in full force recently, as a cruise ship left
Miami. As the cruise business has boomed to more than 5 million
passengers a year, sexual assaults are just one of several new
among the concerns as the industry has expanded, and become more
focused on partying. (Paul Hosefros/New York Times Photo) Eds:
Subbing for photo selection not caption content.
</P>
<P>
   (NYT2) MIAMI -- Nov. 15, 1998 -- CRUISE-SHIP-CRIME-1, 11-15 --
As the cruise ship industry has boomed, it has presented new
concerns for passengers, in part because of the size of its giant
liners, in part because the cruise lines operate largely outside
the laws of any one country. One particular problem is the
allegations of sexual assaults committed by crew members. In Miami,
the country's busiest cruise port, the FBI say they are called out
to investigate a shipboard sexual assault about every other week.
(Paul Hosefros/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT1) RAWLINS, Wyo. -- Nov. 15, 1998 -- WYO-COYOTE-HUNTERS,
11-15 -- At the annual National Coyote Calling Contest in Rawlins,
Wyo., hunters came from as far away as South Africa and as near as
Colorado to compete for a purse of several thousand dollars, won by
a man who killed nine coyotes. Using only a specialized ``call'' to
lure the coyotes, the hunters killed 200 of the 545 coyotes they
had spotted. Hunting contests, primarily in Western states, have
environmentalists facing off against farmers and ranchers. (Kevin
Moloney/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   The New York Times News Service
</P>
