<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-15 22:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1897 &Cx1f; tic-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-CARDS-OFFENSE-AZR     11-15 0644
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-CARDS-OFFENSE-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SECOND-HALF OFFENSIVE EXPLOSION NOT ENOUGH FOR CARDINALS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 ATTN: Dallas Morning News  
 By LEE SHAPPELL  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   TEMPE, ARIZ. - The scoreboard doesn't lie. Long after an
emotion-charged showdown ended Sunday, it still showed that the
Cardinals had defeated the Dallas Cowboys, 21-7.
</P>
<P>
   In the second half.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately for the Cardinals, their latest late-game heroics
could not erase mistakes made earlier in what proved to be a 35-28
setback that dropped them to 5-5.
</P>
<P>
   ``Good job'' from well-wishers just didn't cut it with
quarterback Jake Plummer, not even after he took the Cardinals from
a 28-0 deficit to the brink of overtime with 465 passing yards,
third-most ever by a Cardinal.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm bummed out,'' Plummer said. ``I've never accepted losing.
I hate losing. People come up and say, `Good job,' and I wonder
what they're saying that for. We lost. The job is to go out and
win.''
</P>
<P>
   The Cardinals offensive players could say they didn't lose, they
just ran out of time.
</P>
<P>
   They could say the officials didn't have the spine to throw a
flag in the end zone on the final play where Cardinals receiver Rob
Moore was wearing not only a red jersey but also Cowboys cornerback
Kevin Smith on his chest.
</P>
<P>
   They could say there was more to be encouraged than discouraged
about.
</P>
<P>
   All of the above would be correct.
</P>
<P>
   What could have made all of the above moot, though,is a stronger
start. That's a recurring theme that did not escape the attention
of offensive coordinator Marc Trestman.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a process, and that's just where we're at right now,''
Trestman said. ``You go back to the Detroit game and we came out
very shaky in the first half. It was the same against the Redskins.
We've used the first half as a feeling-out process, and then all of
a sudden the game gets our attention and we play.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't get the sense that we need to go no-huddle to start
the game, but we have to find something that allows us to play the
way we've played in the second halves when we're letting go and
playing relaxed. That's going to be a point of emphasis. We have to
play a lot better in the first 30 minutes.''
</P>
<P>
   The Cardinals trailed 28-0 with 3:29 left in the second quarter
before, as Trestman put it, the game got their attention.
</P>
<P>
   ``We do need to start the first half faster, get some big plays
in the first half, get some points, get ahead, get a lead,''
Plummer said. ``We kept it interesting. I don't think anyone left
on us.''
</P>
<P>
   In the second half, a combination of the Cardinals' no-huddle
offense, the Cowboys playing softer with a big lead, and the line
giving Plummer time to fire put them Cardinals into a position of
having two shots from the Dallas 5 to send the game into overtime.
</P>
<P>
   The first was a pass that Frank Sanders couldn't haul in.
``That's me, it just went through my hands,'' Sanders said.
</P>
<P>
   Then on the final play, Plummer lobbed a fade-pattern pass to
Moore that was broken up by Smith.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know he wasn't looking at the ball,'' Moore said. ``It
looked like one ref wanted to throw his flag and then didn't.
That's a play for me to make. I had both hands on it. When I pulled
it down I hit his shoulder pads and knocked it loose.''
</P>
<P>
   So it ended, after a closing two quarters in which Plummer
completed 18 of 35 passes for 304 yards and two touchdowns without
an interception. His 465 passing yards in the game were one yard
short of the record by a Cowboys opponent.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jake played a phenomenal game,'' Coach Vince Tobin said.
</P>
<P>
   The Cardinals can only wonder how phenomenal it might have been
had they started sooner.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't play just the second half,'' said Moore. ``That's
what we've been doing for three weeks. I wish we could play the
third quarter first.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
