<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-15 22:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1902 &Cx1f; tic-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-CARDS-EMOTION-AZR     11-15 0491
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-CARDS-EMOTION-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CARDS PLAN TO CARRY THIS LOSS WITH THEM 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 Attn: Dallas Morning News  
 By TIM TYERS  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   TEMPE, Ariz. - Cardinals guard Chris Dishman wasn't moping.
Instead he was scribbling a message on his game gloves: ``Dallas
35, Cardinals 28.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm going to put these in my locker as a little reminder,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Dishman's mood typified the attitude of the Cardinals in the
aftermath of Sunday's gut-wrenching 35-28 loss to the Dallas
Cowboys. A frenzied comeback from 28-0 fell five yards short of
overtime and ended momentary hopes of a share of first place in the
NFC East.
</P>
<P>
   The mood in the locker room wasn't one of despondence. It was a
feeling of determination and anger.
</P>
<P>
   ``No, I don't think it will be hard to bounce back from this,
but it's hard right now,'' Dishman said. ``It's like losing a wife
or a kid. It's hard to explain to somebody who hasn't faced a big
loss. But we have to do our job and get after Washington next week.
</P>
<P>
   ``The way we finished up the second half is how we want our
offense to work. If we had done some of those things in the first
half, we wouldn't be in this position.''
</P>
<P>
   The Cardinals play Washington and Kansas City on the road in
their next two games, then finish the season with three of their
final four at home. Coach Vince Tobin's postgame message was to
keep getting the job done and their probable first-round playoff
opponent would be the Cowboys.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not out of it,'' center Aaron Graham said. ``We're still
5-5. We just have to handle our business and chances are we'll play
them again. We not going to hang our heads about this, that's for
sure.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Larry Centers and Aeneas Williams said it's the role of the
veterans to keep the team on track.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have the character to bounce back from this,'' Centers
said. ``It's up to the older guys to show we're not going to give
up. We didn't exactly shoot par, but we finished the hole strong.
</P>
<P>
   ``We waited a bit too long to get started but showed character
coming back when most people thought it was over. We've been behind
at halftime in our last three games, and we've come back strong.
Our quarterback (Jake Plummer) had a coming out today and showed
the heart we want to exemplify on this team. He is a great
leader.''
</P>
<P>
   Williams added, ``In the past, if we were down, 28-0, we could
easily pack our bags and forget it. But this team believes it can
always win. Regardless of the score going into the fourth quarter,
we know we can win. We know it because we've shown we can do it.''
</P>
<P>
   Safety Tommy Bennett said the loss has merely stoked the fire.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a tough loss, but I think we'll feed off this,'' he said.
``We had a chance to win and got a few unfortunate calls. But we
know now we can play with these top teams. It's something we can
feed off and take with us to Washington.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
