<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-15 22:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1905 &Cx1f; tic-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-COWBOYS-OFFENSE-A     11-15 0634
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-COWBOYS-OFFENSE-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COWBOYS FIND 2 OF 3 NOT BAD  
 SMITH, AIKMAN CARRY LOAD WHEN IRVIN SHUT DOWN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB YOUNG  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   TEMPE, Ariz. -On a day when Dallas receiver Michael Irvin had
his 117-game streak of consecutive games with at least one
reception snapped by the Cardinals and cornerback Aeneas Williams,
one would figure the Cowboys' offense would be in for a long day.
</P>
<P>
   One would figure wrong.
</P>
<P>
   It turned out that two of the Cowboys' ``Big Three'' on offense
were enough to get the job done in a 35-28 victory Sunday at Sun
Devil Stadium. The result is a two-game lead for Dallas over the
Cardinals in the NFC East race, with the Cowboys also holding the
tiebreaker should Arizona pull even in the last six games.
</P>
<P>
   Despite Williams' shutout of Irvin, the Cowboys churned to 354
yards and romped to a 28-0 lead before the Cardinals rallied in the
second half.
</P>
<P>
   The other two offensive stars, quarterback Troy Aikman and
running back Emmitt Smith, shredded the Cardinals, and they did it
playing behind a banged up offensive line.
</P>
<P>
   Smith, with 118 yards and three touchdowns on 26 carries, moved
past Walter Payton and Jim Brown on the NFL's all-time rushing list
and left the Cardinals' defense standing almost as still as those
old-timers.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Aikman completed 14 of 18 passes, including a string
of 13 straight that began on the first play of the Cowboys' second
possession of the game and continued until Mark Smith batted down
an attempt with just over 10 minutes to play.
</P>
<P>
   But he never found Irvin.
</P>
<P>
   ``I walked off and they gave me stats, and Michael didn't have a
catch,'' said Dallas Coach Chan Gailey. ``I was shocked. We threw
it to a lot of people, and I couldn't 2believe Michael didn't have
a catch. That's unusual to score that many points and throw to that
many different receivers and him not have one.
</P>
<P>
   ``They did a good job of (double-teaming) and creating problems
on that side. I don't know how long that will last, but until
people realize we can go to other places with it, they'll keep
doing it.''
</P>
<P>
   Aikman sent to eight different receivers. None caught more than
three balls. Fullback Daryl Johnston had the only touchdown
reception.
</P>
<P>
   But the Cowboys were able to hit for big plays _ a 70-yard
completion to wide receiver Billy Davis, a 43-yarder to tight end
Eric Bjornson, a 33-yard shot to tight end David LaFleur and a
28-yarder to wideout Ernie Mills.
</P>
<P>
   Aikman said the Cardinals tried to take Irvin away, but it's
nothing new.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's kind of the way it came up,'' he said. ``We had some
things called to try to get Michael the ball. They rolled someone
over there to keep him from getting opportunities. He didn't even
get many balls thrown his way.
</P>
<P>
   ``But David LaFleur had a big ballgame, Ernie Mills and Billy
Davis made some big catches, and that's what we have to have if
they're going to do those types of things against Michael. Other
guys have to make plays, and they were able to do that.''
</P>
<P>
   Irvin didn't comment on the end of his streak, but Smith said
the Cowboys' star was deeply disappointed to see it stopped.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was very surprised (he didn't catch a pass),'' Smith said.
``But when you're double-covering a guy, it's hard to get the ball
to him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just feel for him because I know he's very frustrated. I
feel his pain. But he's got an opportunity to start a new streak.''
</P>
<P>
   So who would have expected the Cowboys to wrack up 35 points on
the day Irvin's streak died?
</P>
<P>
   ``I wouldn't,'' Smith said. ``We get 35 points, I expect Michael
Irvin to have at least eight catches. It wasn't that way, but it
says a lot for our offense that we were able to move the ball by
spreading it around.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
