<HEADLINE>
KEALY EXPECTED TO FACE UA  
 REDMOND STILL NOT 100 PERCENT, SNYDER CONCERNED 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By PAOLA BOIVIN  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   TEMPE, Ariz. - Quarterback  &UR; Ryan Kealy has recovered well from
arthroscopic knee surgery and is expected to play against Arizona
on Nov. 27, Arizona State Coach  &UR; Bruce Snyder said Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Kealy did not play in Saturday's 51-19 loss to Oregon.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's coming along real well,'' Snyder said. ``He has so much
competitiveness that he will be really anxious to play in the game
coming up. He'll be healthy.
</P>
<P>
   ``He had to stand on the sideline again and watch the game. I
think we'll find that he'll be highly motivated and ready to go.''
</P>
<P>
   Snyder is less confident about the status of tailback  &UR; J.R.
Redmond, who has a nagging ankle injury.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been close to a month,'' Snyder said. ``I know he ran
that (57-yard) touchdown (against Oregon), but that still wasn't
him. He's just not the same guy. God, I'm hopeful.''
</P>
<P>
   Redmond had 10 carries for 70 yards against the Ducks. He did
not return kickoff or punts. &QL; 
Secondary problems &QL; 
Just when Snyder thought it couldn't get worse, his secondary took
another hit.
</P>
<P>
   Redshirt freshman  &UR; Courtney Palmore suffered a dislocated
shoulder in Oregon and will miss the Arizona game.
</P>
<P>
   Palmore is the team's top reserve at safety and one of its top
special-teams players. ASU already was pretty depleted at defensive
back.
</P>
<P>
   ``Of all the places we were thinnest . . . we got it,' Snyder
said.
</P>
<P>
   Palmore's absence will complicate matters at practice. Starting
free safety  &UR; Mitchell Freedman has been unable to practice much of
the season because of injuries. Without Palmore to step in, the Sun
Devils will be walking through strategies much of the week.
</P>
<P>
   Cornerback  &UR; J'Juan Cherry also is limited because of injuries
and can't practice.
</P>
<P>
   ``On the defensive side of the ball, it's going to be stand
around and check assignments,'' Snyder said. ``I prefer not to do
that, I prefer execution . . . but if you can't run very well and
it aggravates (the injury) to run, the next best thing you can do
is walk through it.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Justin Taplin will get more work at cornerback this week.
</P>
<P>
   The depth problems at defensive back has limited ASU's ability
to use nickel and dime packages. That was evident against Oregon,
which often went with three wide receivers. To help with the
shortage, ASU drops back linebacker &UR; Eric Fields into coverage.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the right thing to do because of our personnel,'' Snyder
said. &QL; 
No average Smith &QL; 
After watching film of the Oregon game, Snyder was no less
impressed by the performance of Ducks quarterback  &UR; Akili Smith.
</P>
<P>
   And Oregon makes the most of his abilities, which makes life
miserable for every position on defense.
</P>
<P>
   Tackles have to watch for traps. Ends need to be aware of
sprint-outs. The Ducks can effectively run short routes and deep
routes.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you put a different quarterback in, all that doesn't
concern you,'' Snyder said. ``But because of who he is . . . He may
be the best option runner in the league and probably the best
passer.'' &QL; 
Briefly &QL; 
Snyder said he was pleased with the performance of quarterback
 &UR; Steve &UR; Campbell. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
