<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-CARDS-BICKLEY-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BLAME THE DEFENSE, NOT THE REFEREE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 RAW, UNEDITED VERSION  
 ATTN: Dallas Morning News  
 By DAN BICKLEY  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   TEMPE, Ariz. - Welcome to the great conspiracy.
</P>
<P>
   Time mysteriously disappears against the Raiders, and the
Cardinals lose. A flag remains in the pocket of an official, and
the Cardinals lose. One league referee is actually suspected of
having a personal vendetta against the Birds. And while we're not
sure of this, there are reports that Oliver Stone delivered the
post-game address when first place disappeared on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   You can blame the officials. You can whine about a flag that
could've been thrown. Should've been thrown. Would've been thrown
if they were playing anyone but the Cowboys.
</P>
<P>
   Or you can look at the scoreboard.
</P>
<P>
   Normally, you don't win when you give up 35 points.
</P>
<P>
   ``The big plays killed us,'' defensive coordinator Dave McGinnis
said.
</P>
<P>
   It is admirable that the lads didn't quit on Sunday, highly
encouraging that the offense is suddenly a juggernaut. And all this
talk about exacting revenge when these two teams meet again in the
playoffs was positively striking in its assumption.
</P>
<P>
   Anyone else concerned about how the offense is now compensating
for the defense? A defense that almost blew the game against the
Redskins and handed the Cowboys an insurmountable lead?
</P>
<P>
   Of course, some of this is attributed to the absence of Eric
Swann. Except Swann's temper got him bounced in the first quarter
of the first game in Dallas, a day when Andre Wadsworth took the
field without a single practice, and the Cardinals weren't pushed
around like this.
</P>
<P>
   And some of this is simply a talented offensive coordinator
turned head coach finding ways to exploit the Cardinals' defense.
</P>
<P>
   Jim Fassel did it. Chan Gailey did it. Who's next?
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a game where we'll have to look at the film,'' Corey
Chavous said. ``Anytime you get exploited, other teams will take
advantage of you. And it looks like we have some areas we need to
address.''
</P>
<P>
   When it was over, Simeon Rice and his one tackle put on a pair
of army fatigues and left. Andre Wadsworth and his three tackles
explained how the defensive line was ``pounding them up front``,
only to get burned when the Cowboys ``resorted to a little bit of
trickery to get us off balance.''
</P>
<P>
   Scoreboard, fellas. Scoreboard.
</P>
<P>
   On the first series of the game, a blitzing Tommy Bennett
flattened Troy Aikman. He was rarely touched again the rest of the
afternoon. And only once were the Cowboys handed a three-and-out.
It occurred with under five minutes left in the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``We couldn't get them into third down,'' Cardinals coach Vince
Tobin said. ``We didn't play as well defensively as I would have
liked.''
</P>
<P>
   An understatement straight from the master.
</P>
<P>
   An awful play in the first quarter - a reverse that led to a
fumble, a reverse mysteriously called when the offense was just
starting to find its legs - didn't help. Neither did Deion Sanders'
obligatory impact play that directly led to a touchdown. But the
defense was a passenger on Sunday, from missed tackles to blown
assignments to an overwhelmed front four.
</P>
<P>
   Pat Tillman had another bad day. He made the wrong read and left
a receiver uncovered, leading to a 43-yard gain and, one play
later, a Dallas touchdown. But aside from Aeneas Williams, the odor
was a team effort.
</P>
<P>
   Snapshot for the afternoon: Trailing 35-21 in the fourth
quarter, Jamir Miller was nailed for defensive holding, nullifying
an Emmitt Smith fumble that could've changed the outcome. On an
ensuing 3rd-and-6, the Cowboys converted. And after Ronald McKinnon
missed a tackle, Smith turned a flare pass into a 24-yard gain.
</P>
<P>
   ``Anytime you give a running back 100 yards at home, even one
like Emmitt Smith, that's a concern,'' Chavous said. ``And in
critical situations, we have to get off the field.''
</P>
<P>
   For all the bravado, know that Swann will miss at least another
week and the Cardinals could easily lose their next three games.
And before they teed off on Sunday, Cris Collinsworth called the
Cardinals the ``worst 5-4 team in football.''
</P>
<P>
   Now, they're just another team mired in mediocrity. And until
the defense rediscovers its roar, they're headed in one direction.
The wrong way. &QL; 
Dan Bickley can be reached at 602-444-8253 or at
dan.bickley(at)pni.com.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
