</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-PHOENIX-OPEN-PURSE-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
3 MILLION GREEN REASONS TO PLAY IN PHOENIX OPEN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 ATTN EDITORS: CORRECTION, STORY EMBARGOED UNTIL PMs  
 By BILL HUFFMAN  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - Sometimes the only way to lure a Tiger or a Shark or a
Freddie into the fray is to show them the money.
</P>
<P>
   So goes the logic behind the Phoenix Thunderbirds' decision to
up the ante to $3 million for the 1999 Phoenix Open. The $500,000
increase will boost the champion's share to $540,000 _ more money
than three of the four major championships paid in 1998. The
increase will be announced today at the Phoenix Open Tee-Off
Luncheon.
</P>
<P>
   ``(The increase) shows our commitment to the tour and its
players,'' said Ray Artigue, the tournament chairman. ``We're
trying to keep the money that we pay out in healthy relation to
what other professional sports are paying out to their players.
</P>
<P>
   ``At the same time, it's very important to us that we provide
our community with the best tournament we possibly can. By
increasing our payout to $3 million, we feel we're insuring our
place as one of the best events in professional golf.''
</P>
<P>
   But will it be enough to gain commitments from Tiger Woods, Greg
Norman and Fred Couples?
</P>
<P>
   ``If they have designs on the money title (for 1999), it will be
pretty hard for them to look past Phoenix,'' Artigue argued.
</P>
<P>
   But golf's three marquee names have not necessarily based their
schedules on potential purses. None of them was present at last
year's Phoenix Open, although Woods played here to record crowds in
1997.
</P>
<P>
   According to Tim Grant, the Big Chief of the Thunderbirds, the
chances of landing the Great White Shark and Tiger appear to be
reasonably good. Couples is more of a ``wait-and-see deal'' for the
Jan. 25-31 event at the TPC of Scottsdale.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've heard that Norman plans to play on the West Coast (for
the first time in seven years),'' Grant said. Norman missed most of
the 1998 season with a shoulder injury.
</P>
<P>
   ``Norman's also building a course here in the Valley (Stonehaven
in Scottsdale). So maybe both of those factors, plus our increased
payout, will help get a commitment from him.''
</P>
<P>
   Grant said that negotiations with Woods' camp have been ongoing
for some time.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ray (Artigue) has put together a great proposal for Tiger to
do a clinic here, and we're just waiting to hear back from his
people,'' Grant said.
</P>
<P>
   Couples hasn't played in Phoenix since 1989.
</P>
<P>
   ``Freddie is Freddie,'' Grant said. ``The more you press him,
the less likely you'll get him. We've got to play that one
low-profile and just hope he comes. He has said several times that
he would like to come back. You just never know.''
</P>
<P>
   If Norman, Woods and Couples do pass up Phoenix, it won't be
because of the money. Only the Masters ($3.2 million), TOUR
Championship ($4 million) and PLAYERS Championship ($4 million)
paid out more money among the 43 tour events this past season.
</P>
<P>
   Most tournaments are expected to announce increases for 1999,
and the newly created World Tour is offering three $5 million
events to a selected field. Still, none of the regular tour stops
will pay more than Phoenix, although the Bob Hope Classic, Doral
Ryder Open and the Byron Nelson Classic also are expected to be at
$3 million.
</P>
<P>
   What makes the Thunderbirds' move particularly gutsy is that the
Phoenix Open has no presenting sponsor for 2000, as a result of
Motorola's recent decision to pull out of the final year of its
three-year contract with the Thunderbirds.
</P>
<P>
   No need to panic, Artigue said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We just feel like the Phoenix Open property is one of the most
attractive on tour, and we're confident that (a future sponsor)
will recognize that,'' said Artigue.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sure, we're saddened that our run with Motorola only lasted
two years. At the same time, we've got some exciting opportunities
on the table. I truly believe that we're worth more, especially
with our new link with CBS Sports and the purse increase.''
</P>
<P>
   It seems almost unfathomable, but in 1986, the last year the
Phoenix Open was held at Phoenix Country Club, the total purse was
$500,000. And just two years ago, the payout was $1.5 million.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now in just the past two years, we've doubled the money,''
Artigue said. ``It just shows that we're a committed partner in
growing the tour, especially on the West Coast. And by staying on
top, we're giving our fans the best tournament we can possibly give
them.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-15-98 2310EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
