u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-OBIT-PENN-NYT     11-15 0140
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OBIT-PENN-NYT </SLUG>
 
MILES PENNYBACKER, 97 A FOUNDER Of RAYTHEON 
 (ms) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Miles Pennybacker, who helped start the Raytheon Co. 1925, died
Nov. 9 at the Watrous Nursing Home in Madison, Conn. Pennybacker,
who lived in Westport, Conn., was 97.
</P>
<P>
   He started Voltarc Tubes in 1927 to make neon tubes for electric
sign companies. He was able to fight off an infringement suit by
Claude Neon, who held the neon patent, because of a singular design
for an electrode that heated the helium gas in the neon tubes. He
sold the company and retired in 1967. It was renamed Voltarc
Technologies in 1989.
</P>
<P>
   He is survived by his wife, Jean; two daughters, Anne Watts of
Rockville, Md., and Claire Wilson of Putney, Vt.; a son, Bruce, of
Chapel Hill, N.C.; six grandchildren, and four great-grandchildren.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-15-98 2314EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981115.0242 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-15 23:15 </DATE_TIME>
