<SLUG> BC-OBIT-SHAPIRO-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IVAN SHAPIRO, 69, ADVOCATE ON SOCIAL ISSUES
</HEADLINE>
  (ms) 
 By NOAM S. COHEN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Ivan Shapiro, a real estate lawyer and former
president of the Ethical Culture Society, who was also a leader in
organizations concerned with civil liberties and the homeless, died
Nov. 5. He was 69 and lived in Manhattan.
</P>
<P>
   The cause was complications from Alzheimer's disease and cancer,
his wife, Maria, said.
</P>
<P>
   Shapiro was born in New York City in 1928. He graduated from
City College in 1948, and from Harvard Law School in 1951,
specializing in real estate law. He became a partner at the law
firms of Wein, Lane &AMP; Malkin and Greenbaum, Wolff &AMP; Ernst before
joining Willkie, Farr &AMP; Gallagher in 1981 as a specialist in large
commercial real estate transactions.
</P>
<P>
   Parallel to his legal career, Shapiro became a leader of the
Ethical Culture Society; he was its president from 1972 to 1978 and
chairman of its schools from 1977 to 1982.
</P>
<P>
   Shapiro also became a member of the New York Civil Liberties
Union, joining its board in 1966 and later becoming its treasurer.
There, he focused on abortion rights and on the separation of
church and state, a topic he often addressed in speeches broadcast
from the Ethical Cultural Society's Sunday meetings.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was someone who didn't get the visibility, but he was a
pillar of the development of the modern-day civil liberties
union,'' said Norman Siegel, executive director of the New York
Civil Liberties Union. ``He helped frame some of the most important
civil liberty issues of the late 20th century, and he did it in a
humanistic way.''
</P>
<P>
   More recently, Shapiro was the president of Urban Pathways, a
nonprofit agency that serves the homeless population of New York
City. During his time as president, the agency acquired an empty
plot in Hell's Kitchen and built a residence for 55 formerly
homeless men and women who are mentally ill. In 1996, the six-story
building on West 46th Street, with individual studio apartments and
supervised treatment, was named Ivan Shapiro House.
</P>
<P>
   Shapiro's first marriage, to Florence Goodstein, ended in
divorce. In addition to his wife, Shapiro is survived by two
daughters, Alexandra Shapiro of Malibu, Calif., and Lisa J. Kubiske
of Annandale, Va., and two grandsons. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
