<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GEN-POLO-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REASONS TO CELEBRATE FOR TOP-RANKED USC
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By HEATHER GRIPP  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Beating UCLA was even sweeter than usual for the USC men's water
polo team Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   USC's 9-6 victory over No. 2 UCLA clinched the Mountain Pacific
Sports Federation regular-season championship for the No. 1 Trojans
and almost assured them of a berth in the NCAA tournament.
</P>
<P>
   ``This game was huge first of all to beat the Bruins,'' said
goalie Richard McEvoy, who had 10 saves in the Trojans' ninth
straight win, ``but also because it puts us in a good spot for
NCAAs. Our goal is to go undefeated the rest of the season.''
</P>
<P>
   Host USC improved to 20-1 overall and 7-0 in conference play,
with two games remaining. One of those games is against the Bruins
(15-4, 6-2) _ whom the Trojans have now beat twice this year _ in
the season finale Saturday at the Rose Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   ``When it's SC-UCLA, it's all emotion,'' Trojans coach John
Williams said. ``This game was in the top two or three of the
season.''
</P>
<P>
   A steal by USC's Allen Basso set up a pass to wide-open Peter
Janov at the other end of the pool midway through the fourth
quarter. Janov went one-on-one with Bruins goalie Parsa Bonderson
and used a soft toss into the corner of the net to give the Trojans
their biggest lead of the day, 9-5.
</P>
<P>
   The junior 2-meter man led USC with four goals. Marko Pintaric,
James Castle, Adam Guerro and Basso scored one each.
</P>
<P>
   Pintaric made a two-point shot with 5:29 left in the first
quarter to give the Trojans the initial lead. Castle's back-handed
spin shot a little more than a minute later provided a 3-0 cushion.
The Bruins twice drew within one, but USC's superior defense
controlled the game. Even with a two-man disadvantage late in the
fourth quarter, the Trojans shut down UCLA.
</P>
<P>
   ``We played our worst game of the year,'' Bruins coach Guy Baker
said. ``We played scared. We weren't even close to what we wanted
to do.''
</P>
<P>
   Sean Kern led UCLA with three goals and Bonderson provided 10
saves.
</P>
<P>
   The Trojans won't savor the victory long, though.
</P>
<P>
   They witnessed first hand the struggles of last year's
regular-season champs. Pepperdine didn't even make the final of
last year's MPSF championships following a season much like the
Trojans are experiencing this year. USC entered the tournament as
the No. 4 seed and won the title. The Trojans then gave the Waves a
scare before falling in overtime in the NCAA final.
</P>
<P>
   ``The game was important,'' Williams said. ``But you can't say
this is the game. We still play UCLA again this week and probably
in MPSF. We didn't rest for the game, we didn't prepare any
differently.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
