<SLUG> BC-FBN-CARDS-CASSTEVENS-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CARDINALS ARE ALMOST-READY-FOR-PRIME-TIME PLAYERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 EDITORS: RAW, Unedited version 
 ATTN: Dallas Morning News 
 By DAVID CASSTEVENS  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   TEMPE, Ariz. - The plan was sound.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our goal on offense,'' Vince Tobin revealed during the week,
``is to score more points than they do.''
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, the Dallas Cowboys somehow got wind of this
strategy and adopted it themselves. Late in the second quarter
Sunday, the Cowboys had 28 points; the Cardinals zero.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was 28-0?'' Jake Plummer said.
</P>
<P>
   Jake didn't remember. ``I just knew it was bad.''
</P>
<P>
   It was worse than bad. This had the look and feel of one of
those Grade AA eggs the Cardinals usually lay in big games and this
was their biggest game in a long long time.
</P>
<P>
   The Cards were playing to a full house for a share of the NFC
East lead. Mercy, what if they won? Would players suffer vertigo?
The last time a Cardinals team was so high in the standings it got
a nosebleed.
</P>
<P>
   The Arizona Cardinals talked about playing in a game like this
back in training camp. Now they had the opportunity to prove to
everyone, and themselves, they are ready for prime time.
</P>
<P>
   Prime time as in national TV. Prime Time as in Deion Sanders who
picked off a Plummer pass and ran to the Arizona two-yard line to
set up Dallas' fourth score.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was 28-0?'' Jake said.
</P>
<P>
   Yes it was.
</P>
<P>
   But no one will remember 28-0. What we will remember is Jake
Plummer skittering around in the backfield and rolling out under
pressure and throwing on the run and leading a Cardinals
second-half comeback against odds longer than Deion's limousine.
</P>
<P>
   We will remember Plummer's three touchdown passes against a
Dallas secondary that suddenly appeared defenseless.
</P>
<P>
   We will remember Cowboys owner Jerry Jones pacing the sideline
for the benefit of TV cameras and glancing up at the ticking clock
and holding his breath _ as we all did _ when No. 16 softly lofted
ball one last time, the final play.
</P>
<P>
   A fade route in the corner of the endzone. Rob Moore was there.
So was the Cowboys' Kevin Smith.
</P>
<P>
   Jump ball. Contact. Incomplete.
</P>
<P>
   No flag.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to thank my Lord and Savior Jesus Christ,'' Deion said
after the Cowboys' 35-28 victory. Dressed in an electric blue suit,
red lizard shoes and a Dick Tracy fedora to match, Sanders also
might want to thank Troy Aikman and Emmitt Smith and the wisdom of
the side judge who reached for the hankie in his hip pocket, as if
he felt a sneeze coming on, but then took his hand away.
</P>
<P>
   No whining, please. The officials didn't beat the Cardinals.
Aikman and Smith and Billy Davis and David LaFleur did. The Cowboys
scored five touchdowns. Five touchdowns against a defense that gave
too much ground and left too many receivers uncovered.
</P>
<P>
   Five TDs will beat the Arizona Cardinals almost every time.
</P>
<P>
   Please, no talk of moral victory either. Losing is losing.
Plummer waved off those who recited his statistics _ 465 yards
passing, the most ever by an NFL player in Sun Devil Stadium. ``I'd
rather win,'' he said, quietly, ``and throw for 10.''
</P>
<P>
   But the Cardinals should be heartened. They turned certain
embarrassment into an afternoon to remember and a performance they
can build upon.
</P>
<P>
   They outplayed the Cowboys in the second half and when it was
over and the division leaders found their pulse they sounded more
like survivors than winners.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was 28-0?'' Jake asked.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't think they could come back,'' admitted Chan Gailey, a
better and classier coach than Barry Switzer.
</P>
<P>
   Chad Hennings, the Cowboys defensive tackle, talked about the
Cardinals fight and heart. Dale Hellestrae, a Valley resident in
the off-season, spoke the unvarnished truth when he said the
Cardinals ``are a step below us'' _ but not a giant step.
</P>
<P>
   The Cowboys have beaten every NFC East opponent. The Cards
twice. But this wasn't the same Arizona team Dallas rolled over in
the season opener. These are the new Cardinals, the young and the
restless. They have talent, and promise.
</P>
<P>
   And a future. Gailey said, ``I can't put into words the
improvement they've made.''
</P>
<P>
   It's easy to be gracious in victory. But the winners' remarks
had a ring of sincerity. Dallas lost here a year ago _ the day the
goalposts came down. And Sunday the Cowboys very nearly were pushed
into overtime by the heroics of a quarterback who said his team
````never'' quits, as you can tell.'' &QL; 
David Casstevens can be reached at 602-444-8635 or at
david.casstevens(at)pni.com via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
