<HEADLINE>
CARDINALS CONVINCED THEY WERE ROBBED 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 EDITORS: Raw, unedited version 
 ATTN: Dallas Morning News 
 By STEVE SCHOENFELD, LEE SHAPPELL and BOB YOUNG  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   TEMPE, Ariz. - Cardinals quarterback Jake Plummer was the first
to reach side judge Nate Jones and lashed out at him
</P>
<P>
   ``I told him, `Step up and make the call,''' Plummer said.
</P>
<P>
   Plummer was more polite than some of his teammates in discussing
the final play of the game, an incomplete pass to wide receiver Rob
Moore in the right corner of the end zone that preserved the Dallas
Cowboys' 35-28 victory over the Cardinals Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   The Cardinals were convinced that Cowboys cornerback Kevin Smith
had roughed up Moore and should have been called for pass
interference..
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm very upset,'' linebacker Jamir Miller said. ``The
officials threw the game. That's B.S. ... They must be on the
Cowboys' payroll.''
</P>
<P>
   Kevin Smith acknowledged that he ``thought it was a flag'' the
way the Cardnals responded. ``But it is over with, we won the game
and that's all that matters,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Cardinals Coach Vince Tobin, who rarely criticizes officials,
was incensed by interference not being called, especially after
Moore told him that one official had reached for a flag in his back
pocket.
</P>
<P>
   ``It looked to me like there were an awful lot of people pushing
and shoving,'' Tobin said. ``I didn't see a lot of looking back for
the ball. What I saw was Rob Moore go up for the ball, and guy come
into him. He (Moore) has to reach all the way over the top of
(Smith), and (Smith's) got his helmet buried in Rob's stomach.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know one thing: the Cardinals have had a lot of
controversial calls, and it seems most of them have gone against
us. That bothers me a lot. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Crybabies?
</P>
<P>
   Miller said he got tired of the Cowboys trying to influence the
officials' calls.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are like a bunch of little girls crying,'' Miller said.
``That's not how you play football.'' &QL; 
Moore speed
</P>
<P>
   Rob Moore thought he was gone, otherwise he would have run out
of bounds to sto p the clock.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't see the guy until the last second,'' Moore said of
Kevin Smith, the Dallas Cowboys cornerback who would become a
menace more than once in the closing seconds Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   With 36 seconds to go and the Cardinals 62 yards away from
sending the game to overtime, quarterback Jake Plummer hit Moore
deep over the middle. Moore spun away from Smith and broke away
toward the goalline. But Kenny Wheaton dove and got just enough of
Moore's shoe to trip him. Inbounds at the Dallas 5.
</P>
<P>
   By the time the Cardinals, who were out of timeouts, could get
set up for Plummer to spike the ball to stop the clock, only 9
seconds rema ined. It was a 57-yard play that used 27 precious
seconds.
</P>
<P>
   Had Moore taken a flatter path to the sideline, he would have
been able to get out of bounds an d save roughly 20 seconds.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really thought I would be able to get in (the end zone),''
Moore said. ``I was just living for the moment at the time. He s
urprised me. He got just enough of my legs.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're 5-5 now but there's no question we're still in the
playoff race. The challenge for us emotionally is to get back for
the next game. Games like this take a lot out of you.''
</P>
<P>
   Smit h was involved in controversial coverage on Moore on the
final play of the game. The Cardinals claimed Smith interfered with
Moore in the end zone. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Dropping an opportunity &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Cardinals have run the reverse to Frank Sanders dozens of
times on the prac tice field without a snafu. When they tried it in
the first quarter shortly aft er Dallas had taken a 7-0 lead,
though, it was a disaster.
</P>
<P>
   Sanders came aro und from the left side and fumbled the handoff
from Jake Plummer. Hurvin McCorm ack of the Cowboys recovered at
the Cardinals 32. Four plays later, it was 14-0 in a deficit that
would reach 28-0.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was too early to affect the gam e much,'' Sanders said.
``It gave them seven points, but there was a lot of tim e left.
We've shown that we can come back, it doesn't matter if it's Dallas
or whomever. That is just one of those plays that you run one time
in a game and h ope to catch the defense out of position. I
attribute the fumble to me. I just dropped the ball.''
</P>
<P>
   Sanders atoned to some degree with several big plays in a
second-half rally, finishing with 11 catches for 190 yards. &QL; 
Cowboys impressed &QL; 
Plummer threw for 465 yards and three touchdowns _ 123 yards more
than the second-best performance in the NFL Sunday (San Francisco's
Steve Young passed for 342 in a loss). And Dallas cornerback Deion
Sanders came away impressed.
</P>
<P>
   ``The guy's going to be special. You keep the right personnel
around him, he's a special quarterback. He looked like a young Fran
Tarkenton out there. I've seen him on film, week in and week out,
trying to make plays.
</P>
<P>
   ``He made some tremendous plays. There are not many quarterbacks
in the NFL who can make those plays.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the kind of quarterback you don't want to see in the
fourth quarter to tell you the truth. Because he finds a way to get
the job done. He did an exceptional job.''
</P>
<P>
   Dallas quarterback Troy Aikman agreed.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought he had an excellent ballgame,'' Aikman said. ``I've
been a fan of his. I enjoy watching him play, and I knew he was
going to continue to compete. They've got a good one in him. He's
going to win a lot of football games for them over the course of
his career.'' &QL;
</P>
