<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-15 23:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2082 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-COWBOYS-HNS &LR;      11-15 0893
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-COWBOYS-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ALAN TRUEX  
 c. 1998, Houston Chronicle  
TEMPE, Ariz. _ The way the Dallas Cowboys and Arizona Cardinals
played football Sunday, who needs the NBA?
<TEXT>
<P>
   If the pro basketballers don't settle their labor problems,
sports fans searching for high-scoring games might want to tune
into Jake ``The Snake'' Plummer and his Cardinals. They scored 28
points in a stretch of 27 minutes Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Throwing on the run and usually off-balance, Plummer brought the
Cardinals back from a 28-0 deficit, only to see his team lose 35-28
when his final pass, from the Cowboys' five-yard line, bounced off
cornerback Kevin Smith and eluded intended receiver Rob Moore.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I would have thrown the ball a foot higher, Rob, being the
athlete he is, comes down with the ball,'' Plummer said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We survived,'' a relieved Cowboys safety, Darren Woodson, said
in the visitors' locker room at Sun Devil Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   Said fellow safety Omar Stoutmire: ``In the second half, we
didn't come out ready to play, but we get to go home happy.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, they survived the challenge to their leadership of the
NFC East. By beating the Cardinals, however narrowly, the Cowboys
advanced their record to 7-3, giving them a two-game lead over
Arizona.
</P>
<P>
   Offensively, there was little to fault with the Cowboys, who had
no turnovers and no sacks. Emmitt Smith rushed for 118 yards and
had the sixth three-touchdown day of his career.
</P>
<P>
   Smith set up the first score by running 14 yards after taking a
pitch from a wide receiver, Ernie Mills, on a highly unusual option
play. On the next snap, Chris Warren, giving Smith a breather, used
a block from left guard Nate Newton to run three yards into the end
zone.
</P>
<P>
   The Cardinals tried a trick of their own on the ensuing
possession, but their end-around backfired. Dallas had the play
diagnosed and tackled Frank Sanders for a 13-yard loss. Sanders
fumbled, and Hurvin McCormack recovered on the Arizona 32.
</P>
<P>
   Cowboys coach Chan Gailey rarely uses a tight end for receiving,
but David LaFleur made a key play _ 18 yards to the one-yard line _
when he outfought safety Tommy Bennett for a pass from Troy Aikman.
A touchdown followed on a pass to fullback Daryl Johnston as the
Cowboys took a 14-0 lead.
</P>
<P>
   Early in the second quarter, Aikman again called on the tight
end. This time it was Eric Bjornson, who with no one within 10
yards of him, caught what turned into a 43-yarder to set up a
one-yard TD run by Smith.
</P>
<P>
   Said Cardinals defensive end Andre Wadsworth: ``They caught us
off-balance with passes to all those players. The option play was a
little bit of trickery, and it worked.''
</P>
<P>
   Deion Sanders gave the Cowboys another scoring opportunity in
the second quarter when he intercepted his fifth pass of the
season. Though hobbled by a sprained big toe on his left foot,
Sanders returned the ball 22 yards to the Arizona two, and Smith
plunged the ball over the goal line on his third try.
</P>
<P>
   Now it was 28-0, and the game appeared to be over.
</P>
<P>
   ``They had every right in the world to quit,'' said Cowboys
defensive end Greg Ellis. ``But we couldn't keep Plummer contained.
One time I hit him, and he got up and said, `I don't know how I got
that pass off.'''
</P>
<P>
   The Cardinals never thought of quitting against a Dallas team
that was physically damaged and emotionally flat.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can't sit there and get lulled to sleep and let a team come
back,'' said Cowboys receiver Billy Davis. ``But we had injuries
and situations we hadn't been in before. We can learn from this
experience.''
</P>
<P>
   With Sanders limping off the field, Plummer (31-of-56 for 465
yards) knew he could exploit a defense that was also missing nickel
back Kevin Mathis, who suffered a broken forearm last week against
the Giants.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I left the game, they went to that corner,'' Sanders
said. ``They had the freedom to do some things. Let's be honest _
the first half wasn't like the second half.''
</P>
<P>
   The Cowboys' other starting cornerback, Kevin Smith, was
impaired by a slight separation of the left shoulder, suffered in
the second quarter. He had to abandon his bump-and-run style of
play.
</P>
<P>
   ``With Deion hurt and Mathis down, it was a scramble for us,''
Cowboys defensive coordinator Dave Campo said. ``We had to use some
inexperienced guys.''
</P>
<P>
   Sanders was sidelined for the entire third quarter and most of
the fourth. Using a no-huddle offense, Jake the Snake struck again
and again, working over such nonentities as Charlie Williams, Kenny
Wheaton and Singor Mobley.
</P>
<P>
   Down by a touchdown with 36 seconds left in the game, Plummer
threw 57 yards to Moore, who caught the ball after Wheaton slipped.
Wheaton recovered to trip up Moore on the five-yard line.
</P>
<P>
   On the final play, Plummer tried to throw a fade over Kevin
Smith's head and into Moore's hands. But the ball bounced off
Smith's back, and Moore couldn't pull it in.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I jumped up and tried to go over his back to get the
ball, I got both hands on it,'' Moore said. ``I don't know what
happened then.''
</P>
<P>
   The Cardinals cried pass interference, but there was no call as
the ball landed in the painted grass of the end zone, game over.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was a great football game,'' Gailey said, ``for those who
like scoring.''
</P>
<P>
   And for those who miss the NBA.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-15-98 2343EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981115.0259 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-15 23:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2084 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBA-CLEMENS-HNS &LR;      11-15 1070
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-CLEMENS-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOSEPH DUARTE  
 c. 1998, Houston Chronicle  
The silver plaques hang on the wall, too heavy _ at least for the
time being _ for their owners to hold.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Kacy Clemens knows exactly which one belongs to him.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's mine,'' says Kacy, 4-year-old son of Toronto Blue Jays
righthander Roger Clemens, as he points to one of four Cy Young
Awards that occupy a space in the family's Houston home.
</P>
<P>
   How many 4-year-olds own a Cy Young, let alone know what the
award, given annually to each major league's top pitcher,
represents?
</P>
<P>
   ``He won those because he strikes out a lot of guys,'' Kacy said
of his father.
</P>
<P>
   With four Cy Youngs and four sons _ Koby, 11, Kory, 10, Kacy, 4,
and Kody, 2 (that's K as in strikeout) _ the math couldn't be more
perfect for Clemens, who has spent the past 15 years building a
baseball legacy to pass on to his family.
</P>
<P>
   Today, the Clemens household is expecting a new arrival. Only
this one's for Dad.
</P>
<P>
   Clemens is the odds-on favorite to become the first pitcher in
major-league history to be named a five-time Cy Young winner when
results of ballots cast by the Baseball Writers' Association of
America are released today. Clemens heads a list of American League
candidates that includes Boston's Pedro Martinez and the Yankees
duo of David Cone and David Wells.
</P>
<P>
   With an unprecedented fifth Cy Young, Clemens would move out of
a tie with Greg Maddux and Steve Carlton as the only pitchers to
win the award four times.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maddux and Carlton are great names,'' said Clemens, who won
the AL's Cy Young in 1986, 1987 and 1991 while with the Red Sox and
in 1997 with the Blue Jays. ``I think I enjoy it most when people
call me a power pitcher, because I was first a pitcher, and I
developed the power later.''
</P>
<P>
   At 36, Clemens showed no signs this past season of losing any of
the velocity that earned him the nickname ``Rocket.'' For the
second year in a row, the Spring Woods product claimed an AL
pitching triple crown by combining the most wins (20, tying with
Cone) and strikeouts (271) with the lowest ERA (2.65). Clemens is
just the fourth pitcher in baseball history to have pulled off the
feat in consecutive seasons.
</P>
<P>
   Clemens, who has 233 wins and 3,153 strikeouts for his career,
reflected Sunday on the path his big-league career has taken.
</P>
<P>
   ``To win the triple crown again was mind-boggling,'' said
Clemens, who in 1998 became just the 11th pitcher to reach 3,000
strikeouts. ``I never thought about it 15 years ago when I first
started. As I'm getting older, I'm getting a little better. Last
season, I was clocked seven or eight times at over 100 mph. I'm
usually at 95, and that's because of my conditioning and leg
strength. I've always had a good work regimen, and that's what has
kept me healthy.''
</P>
<P>
   Clemens, who joined Toronto in 1997 after 13 seasons in Boston,
is a devoted family man. His own father died when he was 9, and
because of his hectic schedule during the season, Clemens finds
time with his boys to be precious.
</P>
<P>
   ``That void was there when my father passed away, so I really
didn't have that father figure,'' Clemens said. ``I tell these guys
that are hanging around the clubhouse that do have fathers that
they are fortunate they've had their fathers this long.''
</P>
<P>
   Clemens said that ideally he would like to end his career
playing for either of the two major-league teams in Texas _ the
Astros or the Rangers. But his first commitment is to fulfill the
remaining two years of a four-year contract with Toronto and
hopefully return to the postseason. Clemens has an escape clause
that allows him to force a trade if he believes the Blue Jays are
not making an effort to upgrade their chances at a pennant.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, Clemens raised a number of questions and complaints
on his personal Web site (www.rocketroger.com), ranging from the
state of Toronto's ownership to his displeasure with the way the
Blue Jays are handling contract talks with his buddy, free agent
Jose Canseco.
</P>
<P>
   ``Both (Texas and the Astros) are in contention and are
playoff-caliber teams,'' Clemens said. ``That makes it even more
enticing. Right now, I want to win as a Toronto Blue Jay. That's
why I signed a four-year deal with them. They have given me an
opportunity and paid me very well to come up there and perform for
them. But I just don't want to go out there and perform. This isn't
like a Broadway show, even though I try to make it exciting for the
fans. I want to win.''
</P>
<P>
   Before acquiring Randy Johnson in late July from the Seattle
Mariners, the Astros inquired about Clemens but backed off because
of Toronto's steep asking price. Talks concerning Clemens and
prospective teams are expected to heat up at next month's winter
meetings in Nashville, Tenn. The Blue Jays have reportedly asked at
times for two position players and a quality pitcher in return for
Clemens.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're trying to keep an open mind,'' Toronto general manager
Gord Ash said. ``If we were actively trying to deal Roger Clemens,
we could have done the deal already. We haven't been overwhelmed
yet, but a couple of clubs have stepped up to the interesting
stage.''
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, Clemens is spending his offseason working in
the community. He held his annual celebrity softball game to
benefit local charities Sunday at Rice Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   Former President George Bush participated in the event, which
also featured Canseco, Ken Caminiti, Shane Reynolds and Mike
Hampton, and had nothing but praise for Clemens' work _ on and off
the field.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like it when people help the community,'' Bush said. ``He's
a big-name guy that has everything going for him and is one of the
most well-respected athletes. That's what I call one of my thousand
points of light.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wish he were playing for the Astros. We would love to have
him in Texas. Wherever he is, he's a credit to the game.''
</P>
<P>
   Whether he is able to fulfill his dream and play in front of the
hometown crowd in Houston is buried in the back of his mind _ but
not forgotten. Clemens knows it would be a grand finish to a Hall
of Fame career.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever he decides, his family will play a big part in the
decision.
</P>
<P>
   ``My two oldest boys always ask, `When are you coming home?'''
Clemens said. ``The next week it's, `Dad, are you going to chase
300 wins?' We're going to have to wait and see.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
