<DOCNO> NYT19981115.0260 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-15 23:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2085 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-FALCONS-NINERS-HN     11-15 1012
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-FALCONS-NINERS-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOHN McCLAIN  
 c. 1998, Houston Chronicle  
ATLANTA _ The next time The Star-Spangled Banner is played in
Atlanta, the last four words will no longer be ``home of the
Braves.''
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Falcons officially shoved the Braves into the background
Sunday and became the toast of Atlanta by beating San Francisco
31-19 before 69,828, the first sellout in the Georgia Dome since
1995.
</P>
<P>
   The Falcons (8-2) broke a first-place tie with the 49ers (7-3)
in the NFC West and ended a five-game losing streak in a series
that had been dominated by San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been looking up at them for a long time, and the view
from here sure looks good,'' said Falcons linebacker Jessie Tuggle,
a 12-year veteran who set an NFL record Sunday by scoring his fifth
career touchdown on a fumble recovery. ``It took a lot of blood,
sweat and tears to get where we are. We'd been manhandled by the
49ers, and to beat them in a game of this magnitude shows we're for
real.''
</P>
<P>
   No one in Atlanta will argue that point, not after the Falcons
built a 24-6 lead in the fourth quarter and survived a furious
rally by the 49ers when quarterback Chris Chandler completed a
78-yard touchdown pass to Terance Mathis with 2:51 remaining.
</P>
<P>
   In less than two seasons, coach Dan Reeves has restored pride in
a franchise whose one and only division title was in 1980. The
Falcons know that if they want to win a second NFC West
championship, they had to beat San Francisco. Over their last 18
games, the Falcons are 14-4 compared to the 49ers' 13-5.
</P>
<P>
   ``The 49ers have dominated us, and they've pretty much had their
way in this division,'' Reeves said. ``We've arrived for one day,
but tomorrow, we have to come back down to earth.
</P>
<P>
   ``We worked very hard to get to this point, and we want to
advance beyond this point by doing the same things that got us
here.''
</P>
<P>
   Unless they collapse, the Falcons have a chance to earn
home-field advantage. Of their last six opponents, the only team
with a winning record is Miami, which visits the Georgia Dome in
the regular-season finale.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've put ourselves in a position where we're in control, but
it won't mean anything if we don't finish it,'' Reeves said.
``Every team on our schedule's capable of beating us.''
</P>
<P>
   And now is appears that Atlanta is capable of beating any team.
The Falcons withstood quarterback Steve Young's 342 yards passing
and Jerry Rice's 169 yards receiving on 10 catches. They now have
won six of seven games, and in each of those victories, they have
scored at least 31 points.
</P>
<P>
   ``Atlanta defensed us very well, almost to the point of
frustration,'' Young said. ``Every game's like a car wreck, and I'm
surprised at our inability to do things. We put ourselves in a jam.
Now some pressing and urgency are needed.''
</P>
<P>
   The Falcons, who entered the weekend leading the NFL in average
time of possession, controlled the ball for 34 minutes, 30 seconds.
</P>
<P>
   Chandler, who was 12-of-21 for 198 yards, one touchdown and no
interceptions, is playing better than any time during his 11-year
career.
</P>
<P>
   Running back Jamal Anderson carried 31 times for 100 yards and
scored two touchdowns on runs of 10 and two yards. He has rushed
for 1,066 yards and scored 10 touchdowns. It is the third
consecutive season Anderson has passed the 1,000-yard mark. He also
tied William Andrews' club record of seven 100-yard games in a
season.
</P>
<P>
   ``The 49ers are the barometer in the NFC West,'' Anderson said.
``If you want to win the division, you have to go through San
Francisco.''
</P>
<P>
   The Falcons went through San Francisco on Sunday, but it took a
while. Atlanta led 7-3 at halftime and 10-6 after three quarters.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were kind of feeling each other out and playing a game of
field position,'' Anderson said. ``Then, we just kind of
exploded.''
</P>
<P>
   Late in the third quarter, Falcons cornerback Ray Buchanan
intercepted Young and returned it 34 yards to the San Francisco
one. On the first play of the fourth quarter, Anderson scored on a
two-yard run.
</P>
<P>
   ``We needed a confidence boost, and that play (his interception)
gave it to us,'' Buchanan said. ``After that, it was like, `Hey, we
can play with those guys. Let's smack them in the mouth. Let's take
their respect.'''
</P>
<P>
   On the 49ers' next series, Young was sacked by tackle Shane
Dronett, who forced a fumble that Tuggle recovered at the one and
rolled into the end zone for the touchdown. Morten Andersen's extra
point gave Atlanta a 24-6 lead with 14 minutes remaining.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of our goals was to not let them score quick at the start
of the second half,'' Buchanan said. ``We didn't. But we let them
score quick at the start of the fourth quarter, and it almost cost
us the game.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, Young on consecutive series threw touchdown passes of 54
yards to Terrell Owens and 65 yards to Rice, who had dropped an
easy pass in the end zone in the second quarter. Wade Ritchey's
extra point left the 49ers behind 24-19 with 3:09 left.
</P>
<P>
   ``After they scored those two quick touchdowns, our backs were
against the wall,'' Reeves said. ``I felt like we had to score a
touchdown on our next series.''
</P>
<P>
   On second down from Atlanta's 22, Mathis was supposed to run a
short sideline route, but the 49ers were in bump-and-run coverage.
Rookie cornerback R.W. McQuarters was pressing Mathis at the line
of scrimmage. Mathis adjusted his route, and Chandler saw the
adjustment.
</P>
<P>
   ``When the guy came up to bump Terance, I just decided to take a
shot,'' Chandler said. ``It was a high-percentage pass. Terance ran
a great route and made a great catch.''
</P>
<P>
   Chandler, who throws one of the best deep balls in the league,
made a perfect pass.
</P>
<P>
   ``When their corner got in my face, I converted my assignment to
a fade route,'' Mathis said. ``I got a good release, took off and
Chris' pass was perfect. I pride myself in making big plays, and I
was fortunate to have that opportunity.''
</P>
<P>
   The 49ers got the ball back one more time but ran out of downs
at their 48.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
