<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-15 23:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2086 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBC-ROBERTSONCOLUMN-H     11-15 0829
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-ROBERTSONCOLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   DaleRobertson
</P>
<P>
   &UR; c. 1998, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
BCS! BCS! BCS! Rah! Rah! Rah!
</P>
<P>
   I love it, the BCS. College football has never been more
exciting because of the BCS.
</P>
<P>
   It's hip, it's hot, it's happening. As I sit here typing, I
realize I'm not going to sleep a wink Sunday night, so extreme is
my anticipation to see how the computers will digest Saturday's
spate of gridiron craziness and spit out the Chosen Two.
</P>
<P>
   The polls are blah, predictable and boooring. But the Bowl
Championship Series rankings, with its witch's brew of human
prejudices and obscure statistical data, is pure pins-and-needles
stuff.
</P>
<P>
   How much, if any, will Tennessee be punished for winning a game
it fully deserved to lose?
</P>
<P>
   Will Kansas State, despite having ended 30 years of subjugation
at the hands of Nebraska's bullies, get kicked in its purple fanny
yet again for feasting on Indiana State, Northern Illinois and
Northeast Louisiana early in the year?
</P>
<P>
   Will the man-made brains overlook the fact that UCLA, for all of
its offensive might, is a hair short on defensive muscle?
</P>
<P>
   Does Florida stay as dead as dead can be for having lost to
Tennessee in overtime by the margin of a missed chip-shot field
goal in the third week of the season?
</P>
<P>
   Regarding the last, the answer is a resounding ``yes!'' unless
the three unbeatens all tumble. The BCS is completely intolerant of
defeats and does not want to hear excuses.
</P>
<P>
   In short, the BCS is quite the farce regarding its intended
purpose. It has no more of a chance of delivering an undisputed
national champion than throwing darts at a dart board would. But
what it has done is take the ``who's No. 1?'' debate to an
infinitely more convoluted level.
</P>
<P>
   That's BCS, as in big mess. And if it doesn't lead to a real
playoff involving at least eight teams, nothing will. In the
interim, though, I suggest we enjoy ourselves. I certainly am.
</P>
<P>
   There's a pretty good chance the BCS mainframe will whir and
burp a couple of times, then duly inform us that Tennessee and UCLA
are now fast-tracking to the Fiesta Bowl for the national title.
Imagine. K-State ends a three-decade losing streak against the
'Huskers, and their reward could be the brink of oblivion.
</P>
<P>
   If the 'Kats do suddenly find themselves on the outside looking
in, they will be screaming their fool heads off about the gross
injustices of what was intended to be a better mousetrap. Alas,
should the Vols and the Bruins win out, a likely scenario, K-State
could have 10 cows plus a conniption fit and it still wouldn't be
going to Tempe _ never mind that Bill Snyder's lads may finish No.
1 in the coaches' poll.
</P>
<P>
   See, the computer won't know squat about how Arkansas
quarterback Clint Stoerner fumbled away a sure victory for the
Razorbacks. All the computer will know is that the Vols defeated
the now-ninth-ranked team in the country to stay unbeaten, whereas
K-State was having to fight for its very life against the, ahem,
lowly 'Huskers, who tumbled to 17th after their 40-30 defeat.
</P>
<P>
   UCLA has surrendered more than 23 points to all except two of
its nine victims, but said scalps, according to Jeff Sagarin's
computer, constitute the 10th-toughest gantlet in the country. The
murdered row of Wildcats foes, in contrast, is way, way down there
at 74th, another 50 spots below Tennessee's 24th, too.
</P>
<P>
   As for Florida State and Texas A&AMP;M, both presumably fatally
tarnished at 10-1 (the latter courtesy of the former), they are
virtually certain to stay also-rans in the BCS pecking order.
</P>
<P>
   Unless the Aggies whip Texas and then knock off Kansas State in
the Big 12 Championship Game, they could be relegated to the Alamo
Bowl with 11 victories, since the Holiday Bowl would surely favor
Nebraska over them, even with the 'Huskers' three defeats.
</P>
<P>
   The Cotton Bowl, with the first choice among the bowls tied to
the Big 12, desperately desires a Texas-Arkansas matchup and, the
Texas Tech loss notwithstanding, is expected to force the issue
anyway with the Longhorns unless the Aggies utterly humiliate them.
</P>
<P>
   In which case Nebraska would get the invite. A&AMP;M was in Dallas
last year, and the Cotton pickers are high on fresh faces.
</P>
<P>
   The Razorbacks, however, may have played themselves out of the
Cotton's now-humble reach by nearly blindsiding the Vols. And the
Hogs do figure to get another shot at Tennessee on the SEC's
championship weekend.
</P>
<P>
   The Rose Bowl could be back in a deep funk as well, if UCLA
leapfrogs to second in the BCS. The unbeaten Bruins vs. either
Michigan or Ohio State is far more appealing than inserting
Arizona, another 10-1 afterthought, into the mix. No bowl has ever
been more of a stumbling block to proposed playoff plans than the
Rose. Perhaps losing UCLA would be painful enough to get
Granddaddy's attention.
</P>
<P>
   Hey, what time is it, anyway? Those BCS rankings out yet? The
suspense is killing me.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
