<SLUG> BC-FBN-CARDS-COWBOYS-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FURIOUS FINISH  
 COMEBACK ENDS IN CONTROVERSY AND FRUSTRATION  
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVE SCHOENFELD  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   TEMPE, Ariz. - The clock didn't lie, but the Cardinals still
couldn't believe their biggest game in the franchise's Arizona
history ended in such a foul manner.
</P>
<P>
   Make that a non-foul manner.
</P>
<P>
   An official reached into his back pocket _ press box observers
said it was side judge Nate Jones _ to grab a flag and call pass
interference on Dallas Cowboys cornerback Kevin Smith in the right
corner of the end zone.
</P>
<P>
   But the official stopped himself and instead signaled that
quarterback Jake Plummer's pass to wide receiver Rob Moore was
incomplete, preserving the Cowboys' 35-28 victory over the
Cardinals Sunday before 71,670 fans at Sun Devil Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told the team I wish there was something I could tell them
that would make them feel better,'' Cardinals Coach Vince Tobin
said. ``They should have had a chance to go into overtime. We were
denied that chance, and that's extremely disappointing.''
</P>
<P>
   The Cardinals had driven from their 22-yard line to the Dallas 5
in the final 52 seconds. Then, Plummer tried to loft the ball on a
fade route to Moore, who had Smith draped over him.
</P>
<P>
   ``The referees deserve to be under investigation for that (non)
call,'' Cardinals linebacker Jamir Miller said.
</P>
<P>
   But the Cardinals also know they lost the game much earlier.
They fell behind, 28-0, in the second quarter and never got closer
than seven points the rest of the way.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't spot a team like that 28 points,'' Cardinals wide
receiver Eric Metcalf said. ``They're too good.''
</P>
<P>
   The Cowboys' defense wasn't good _ Plummer's 465 passing yards
was the second-most allowed by them in 29 seasons _ but they
managed to hold on and beat the Cardinals for the 16th time in 17
games.
</P>
<P>
   A two-game sweep over the Cardinals this season all but clinches
the NFC East title for the Cowboys (7-3). They have a two-game lead
over the Cardinals (5-5) and hold the first tiebreaker against
them.
</P>
<P>
   The Cardinals are tied with New Orleans for the third and final
wild-card spot in the NFC playoffs. But if the season were to end
today, they would win the tiebreaker over the Saints because of a
better NFC record.
</P>
<P>
   They were lucky to be in Sunday's game considering the way they
played defensively the first three quarters.
</P>
<P>
   The Cowboys moved the ball at will. Running back Emmitt Smith
had 71 of his 118 yards at halftime and quarterback Troy Aikman had
13 consecutive completions in one stretch.
</P>
<P>
   Dallas' offense did it without wasting any energy; none of its
first four scoring drives took longer than five plays.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everything they got, we gave them,'' Miller said. '`When we
decided they weren't getting anything else, they didn't get any.''
</P>
<P>
   The Cowboys also took advantage of two costly Cardinals'
turnovers, scoring after wide receiver Frank Sanders lost a fumble
at the Arizona 32 on a reverse and when Plummer was intercepted by
All-Pro cornerback Deion Sanders, who returned the ball 22 yards to
the Cardinals 2.
</P>
<P>
   Plummer said Deion Sanders baited him into throwing his way.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was so far off,'' Plummer said of Sanders. ``I tried to
look up the field. As I threw it . . . he was Deion, a quick burst
to the ball.''
</P>
<P>
   Once it reached 28-0, the Cardinals finally got moving. Using
the no-huddle offense for one of the few times this season, they
scored on a 2-yard scoring pass from Plummer to Sanders in the
closing seconds of the first half and then cut the margin to 28-14
on a 15-play, 60-yard drive to open the third quarter.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt by doing the no huddle, we were putting pressure on
their defense to get their calls made,'' Tobin said. ``It looked
like they were lagging coming out of the huddle, and we felt that
was the best way to score quickly. We needed points.''
</P>
<P>
   Trailing 35-14 late in the third quarter, Plummer marched the
Cardinals 73 yards in seven plays, capping the drive with a 4-yard
scoring pass to Moore.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jake played an absolutely phenomenal game,'' said Tobin of
Plummer, who threw for 305 yards in the second half, more than his
total in any game this season.
</P>
<P>
   A Cardinals' drive ended at Dallas 16 midway through the fourth
quarter, but they got the ball back with 4:39 left and went 70
yards in eight plays. A 7-yard pass from Plummer to running back
Adrian Murrell cut the lead to 35-28.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes you come to the bench (after scoring) and feel
invincible,'' center Aaron Graham said. ``We felt that way in the
second half. That no-huddle stuff is for real.''
</P>
<P>
   The Cardinals' defense forced Dallas to punt in the final minute
and took over on their 22.
</P>
<P>
   After a 16-yard completion to Metcalf, Plummer found Moore wide
open over the middle. Moore, taking advantage of the absence of
Deion Sanders (bruised toe), went 57 yards before being caught from
behind by Kevin Smith at the Dallas 5.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought I might score,'' Moore said. ``I saw Eric (Metcalf)
making a block and thought that was it. Then, at the last second, I
saw the guy flash and make a play on my leg.''
</P>
<P>
   The Cardinals, out of timeouts, scrambled to spike the ball with
11 seconds left.
</P>
<P>
   Plummer threw too low for Sanders on second down, leaving three
seconds on the clock and time for a final pass to Moore.
</P>
<P>
   ``I gave Rob the fade signal, but I left it short,'' Plummer
said. ``It's obviously a route I need to work on in practice. If I
threw the ball a foot higher, with Rob's height and leaping
ability, even with the pass interference, there's no question it
would have been a touchdown.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
