<HEADLINE>
LOS ANGELES WOMAN CALLS FOR HELP FROM CAR TRUNK AT NEVADA CASINO
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY DAVID R. BAKER and DEBORAH SULLIVAN  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ A woman who told police she was kidnapped as she
left her church Saturday night was found alive in Nevada after she
used her cellular phone to call for help from the trunk of her car.
</P>
<P>
   Laura Dekkers, 44, was found Sunday still locked in the trunk of
her BMW convertible in the parking garage of Whiskey Pete's Hotel
Casino in Primm, Nev., said Los Angeles Police Department Sgt. Paul
Sciarrillo.
</P>
<P>
   The 44-year-old stockbroker from suburban Encino showed no
visible injuries, but was treated for shock and dehydration at a
hospital and released. She was expected to return home late Sunday,
Sciarrillo said.
</P>
<P>
   Police had tracked her through the day as Dekkers called 911
from the trunk.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were able to trace her through her cell phone,'' said
Officer Eddy Zelaya.
</P>
<P>
   Police had no suspects or known motive for the kidnapping,
Sciarrillo said. The investigation is continuing, with assistance
from the Federal Bureau of Investigation.
</P>
<P>
   Dekker's call for help sparked a furious search lasting much of
Sunday, with several police agencies from the two states trying to
locate the missing woman's BMW.
</P>
<P>
   The abduction apparently happened around 10 p.m. Saturday as
Dekkers was leaving Bel Air Presbyterian Church, officials said.
The pastor, Jim Lee, said Dekkers is a volunteer who works with
children at the church, which overlooks the San Fernando Valley
from Mulholland Drive.
</P>
<P>
   Lee wasn't sure why she was there so late in the evening.
``There was a couples class last night, but they were saying she
wasn't there,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   In her cell phone calls, Dekkers said she had been abducted by a
gunman wearing a ski mask, police said. Officers at the church
Sunday morning said a janitor saw her leave the building and head
downhill toward a parking lot but had not witnessed a kidnapping.
</P>
<P>
   Then, at about 7:25 a.m. Sunday, Dekkers called her husband,
Hendricus, from her cell phone. He alerted the police.
</P>
<P>
   Later in the morning, she called 911. Those calls were picked up
by the California Highway Patrol's Barstow office, indicating that
she was somewhere in the area.
</P>
<P>
   Neighbors, who learned of the abduction as police cordoned off
their Encino street, described Dekkers as friendly woman and mother
of one who used to arrange Christmas caroling parties.
</P>
<P>
   ``She's very amiable, she'll always say hello,'' said Lou
Marino, who lives nearby.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-15-98 2355EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
